<SLUG> BC-LABOR-WITNESSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYEES HAVE RIGHT TO WITNESSES FOR MEETINGS WITH BOSSES, LABOR
BOARD SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARY WILLIAMS WALSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal agency's ruling this week that any employee summoned
into a boss's office can take a fellow employee as a witness is
being derided by management lawyers and praised by labor advocates.
But both sides say the decision is unlikely to alter the dynamics
of the workplace immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1975, any union member called into a disciplinary meeting
has had the right to be accompanied by a co-worker. On Monday, the
National Labor Relations Board extended that right to all workers.
And the initial reaction from management ranks was dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, where the rights were limited to 10 percent
of the work force, now they're 100 percent of the work force,''
said Randel Johnson, vice president for labor policy at the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce. Some employment lawyers say the ruling
represents a new tripwire for managers as they conduct the routine
business of running offices and factories: disciplining employees,
handing out performance evaluations, sorting out misunderstandings
and, of course, firing employees. Supervisors generally prefer to
handle such matters privately, but under the new ruling, any
employee who anticipates trouble is entitled to take along a
co-worker of his choice as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very unworkable if every time you wanted to talk
to one of your employees, you had to get somebody to come into the
room and get involved in the conversation,'' said Thomas Walsh, a
partner at the law firm of Jackson Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   There are also concerns that the ruling could hamper employers
as they try to investigate embezzlement, sexual harassment and
other wrongdoing at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the hallmarks of a good investigation is whether the
company is able to keep it confidential,'' said Paul Salvatore, a
partner at the law firm of Proskauer Rose, which represents
managers in employment disputes. If the witness ``spreads the word
that they're investigating everybody in the department for theft,
that compromises the employer's investigation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, management lawyers have been counseling employers
to investigate sexual harassment assertions privately, to avoid
compounding such matters with accusations of managerial
insensitivity. Now, the lawyers are wondering how their clients
will be able to hold such discreet, one-on-one interviews if
accused gropers, say, are allowed to bring colleagues into the
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   They are also wondering about the practicalities of choosing
witnesses. In unionized workplaces, workers take their union
steward along when they expect a confrontation with a supervisor.
``Shop stewards can't object like a lawyer would, but they're able
to add some guidance because a unionized workplace is covered by
the collective bargaining agreement,'' Salvatore said. He added
that it was unclear who would fill this role in a nonunion
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the concerns of management, advocates for workers say
the new ruling could be a plus for both sides. Steven Platt,
president of the National Employment Lawyers Association, whose
members represent employees, said the presence of a co-worker
during a dismissal might defuse some of the tension and rage that
now prompt some fired employees to come back with guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we see workplace violence, it usually happens because
people feel like they have no recourse,'' Platt said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for both sides said there would not be a wave of demands
for witnesses any time soon. Even under the ruling, employers will
not have to invite witnesses to meetings unless the employees ask
them to. And nonunion workers are not likely to be aware of their
right to do so. But if an employee does ask for a witness in a
meeting, the supervisor must agree.
</P>
<P>
   The case promting the labor board's decision involved the
Epilepsy Foundation of Northeast Ohio and two employees, Arnis
Borgs and Ashraful Hasan. Borgs and Hasan had a falling- out with
their supervisor and sent memorandums complaining about him to the
executive director of the nonprofit foundation. The executive
director was furious and demanded that Borgs meet with her and the
supervisor. Borgs, knowing that a reprimand was on the way, said he
wanted to take Hasan along. The director refused and later fired
Borgs, who then took the matter to the labor relations board.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time that the agency had been asked to
consider the issue. In 1982, it ruled essentially the same way it
ruled this week, that nonunion workers could take co-workers to
disciplinary meetings. But the composition of the board changed
over the course of the Reagan and Bush administrations, and the
board began to rule in subsequent cases that the right to a witness
was limited to union workers.
</P>
<P>
   Platt said the new ruling reflected the waning influence of two
Republican administrations and a shift in philosophy resulting from
eight years of Democratic appointments and financing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland, Steven Moss, a lawyer who represented the Epilepsy
Foundation, said he would appeal the ruling to federal circuit
court. Although the labor board ordered the foundation to give
Borgs and Hasan their jobs back, Moss said his client would not do
so until all legal remedies had been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Because the board was divided, with a three-member majority and
two strong dissents, the law is likely to change again, Moss said,
depending on which party wins the presidential election this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
