<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND N.Y. SENATE CANDIDATE LAZIO APPEAR TOGETHER, CALL FOR
MISSILE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas flew to New York Friday
to offer his support for Rep. Rick Lazio's bid for the U.S. Senate,
belittling Hillary Rodham Clinton with a familiar critique before
an audience of Conservative Party donors in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, he's from here,'' Bush said of Lazio, a sarcastic
edge to his voice. ``This is his state. He knows New York well. He
also doesn't have to wear a Yankee cap to play like he's a Yankee
fan.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that Bush, the likely Republican
presidential candidate, had campaigned along side Lazio since Lazio
was chosen to run against Clinton. Lazio, a Suffolk County
Republican, and Bush used their back-to-back appearances to praise
each other's records and credentials, and Lazio used his first
joint appearance with his party's presumed presidential nominee to
state his support for an anti-missile defense shield that Bush
backs.
</P>
<P>
   In another speech, New York Gov. George Pataki praised Bush's
conservative ideals.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lazio and Bush were restrained in their comments about
Clinton and the Senate race in New York, in what appeared to be an
attempt not to draw too much attention to their joint appearance
before a Conservative Party fund-raiser. The event posed a
complication to Lazio's candidacy because Clinton has recently
sought to tie Lazio to Bush, and repeatedly challenged Lazio's
attempt to portray himself as a moderate Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even before Lazio followed Bush into the ballroom at the
Sheraton New York Hotel in Midtown, Clinton, at an early-morning
news conference on Long Island, was assailing Lazio for taking
Conservative Party support and appearing at its fund-raising
luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to its Web site, Clinton ran through the party's
positions on several issues, including school vouchers and abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent has some questions to answer about his being a
Republican-Conservative candidate, about his commitment to issues
that he claims to support and about his record,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The joint appearance of Bush and Lazio came during one of Bush's
rare trips to New York. Although Bush said Friday that he believed
he can win New York state against Vice President Al Gore in
November, many Republicans and Democrats in the state have said
they consider that unlikely, given the Democratic registration edge
in New York. For the same reason, Lazio probably does not stand to
gain much politically by campaigning with Bush, who he addressed as
Buddy in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's remarks about Clinton's residency may be the latest
indication of the extent to which her opponents believe a
carpetbagger attack is effective against her. The host of the
luncheon, Michael Long, the chairman of the state Conservative
Party, drew laughs and cheers when he said, ``I admit sometimes
when I hear people arguing about the horrible foreign menace that
has suddenly appeared in New York, I don't know if they're talking
about the West Nile virus or Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio returned to the same theme, if in a more subtle way, with
his own speech a few moments later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make this promise to you: I will be a senator from New York
and for New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio devoted most of his speech to talking, not about Clinton,
but about the need for an missile defense shield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a dangerous world, ladies and gentlemen,'' Lazio
said. ``We have enemies. And the technology for mass destruction is
spreading. My friends, I'm proud to announce today that I will be
working with Gov. Bush to make sure that we implement an effective
missile defense system for America.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bush devoted only a small part of his speech to Lazio and
his race with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about Rick is that he is a decisive person,''
Bush said. ``When he made up his mind to run, he entered the race.
He didn't need a listening tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had deferred his campaign for Senate last year at the
request of party leaders who wanted Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to be
their candidate. When Giuliani abruptly withdrew in the spring
because of health reasons, Lazio eagerly hopped into the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
