<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUF-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-BUF15-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MUTINY AT BOOT CAMP FOR KIDS RAISES QUESTIONS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DENNIS WAGNER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your story goes here.
</P>
<P>
   Did some troubled kids mutiny at a juvenile boot camp on the
White Mountain Apache Reservation or were they victims of abuse?
</P>
<P>
   Criminal investigators, tribal authorities, social workers and
families are still trying to sort out the mess in Whiteriver, where
a group known as America's Buffalo Soldiers Re-enactors Association
conducts a camp for wayward youths.
</P>
<P>
   This much is undisputed: The Phoenix-based organization runs a
strict program for children ages 7 to 17, most of whom were
enrolled by their parents. The Summer Endurance Youth Camp regimen
includes forced marches, black uniforms, in-your-face discipline
and a daily diet limited to an apple for breakfast, a carrot for
lunch and a bowl of beans for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-three juveniles, about half of them Apaches, attended the
program. On Tuesday, some of the youths reported that they had been
kicked, choked and subjected to other cruelty by drill instructors.
They also told of being handcuffed together.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said no juveniles were injured, and no arrests have
been made.
</P>
<P>
   The White Mountain Tribal Council voted to close the operation
Tuesday, but rescinded that order a day later after hearing from
Buffalo Soldiers administrators and supporters. By Friday, nearly
half the boys and girls had left the program.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Charles Long II, founder and president of the Buffalo
Soldiers, has not responded to interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   Grateful Jones, a sergeant in the organization, said the
controversy was created by a group of boys who made death threats
against camp leaders and concocted stories of mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no abuse going on up there,'' Jones said. ``These kids
all plotted to get their stories together. (They) have their own
rap sheets. It's not as if they're angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones emphasized that the program deals with hard-core kids who
benefit from a ``no-nonsense'' approach. In addition to exercise,
camp leaders use drama therapy, history lessons and bonding
methods. Parents, who pay $4,250 for the 35-day camp, sign papers
consenting to the methods.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph on the Buffalo Soldiers Web site shows boys bound
together and being led on a march with their hands tied and with
bags over their heads. The exercise, according to the Web site, is
designed to ``discourage runaways and deepen the group cohesion and
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said one boy was punished beneath a legendary hanging tree
where a rope dangled from a branch, but she denied a report that
the noose was around the youth's neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid spit in the colonel's face and called him a (racial
epithet),'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said a few boys started the trouble by persuading Apache
children to run away and make claims of mistreatment. More than
half the youngsters remain in the camp, and some parents lend vocal
support for the Buffalo Soldiers and Long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program has kept many children out of jail, and my son is
one of them,'' said Harriet Fontenot, a Glendale teacher whose
16-year-old twins have participated for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Silver, who also put two children through Long's camps,
said, ``He's tough as nails with them, but he's fair. It's tough
love.''
</P>
<P>
   Long founded the Buffalo Soldiers 10 years ago as a historical
re-enactment group based on African-American cavalrymen who served
in the Army 120 years ago, mostly as Indian fighters. The
association initially focused on education and film productions,
but also developed a branch involved with youth rehabilitation. It
also conducts boot camps for Roosevelt School District and at a
camp near Cave Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at Dennis.Wagner(a)Arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or (602) 444-8874.s
</P>
</TEXT>
