A2958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-REPUB-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      07-15 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REPUB-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SOLID REPUBLICAN DRUG PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 15:
</P>
<P>
   William Roth, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, rattled
his fellow Republicans this week by offering a plan to add
prescription drugs to Medicare that resembles proposals by
congressional Democrats and the White House. The Roth plan
repudiates the ill-conceived Republican bill that passed the House
and provides a plausible platform for a bipartisan agreement _
though probably not before the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House bill, only private insurers would offer coverage
to the elderly. But even some private insurers regard the bill as
unworkable. Roth concedes as much by proposing instead a plan that
would have the government, as well as private plans, offer drug
coverage. Roth's bill goes far beyond offering a drug benefit,
however, embracing a reform for the entire Medicare program that
mirrors proposals by President Clinton, a majority of the
bipartisan congressional committee on Medicare reform and a wide
swath of health experts.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a drug benefit is only one of Medicare's
problems. In the last few weeks, for example, many private
managed-care plans have dropped out of the program in some regions,
leaving enrollees to scramble for new coverage. The reason, they
say, is that government reimbursement for covering the elderly is
too low for them to survive. The simple truth is that under the
current rules the government cannot possibly know how much it needs
to pay plans to keep them active participants.
</P>
<P>
   Roth proposes major revisions. The government would continue to
offer existing Medicare coverage, as well as offer a second option
that would be expanded to include coverage of drugs. Managed-care
plans would be invited as well to offer the same two options. For
each enrollee, the government would pay the managed-care plans an
amount approximately equal to the cost per person of its
fee-for-service coverage. Managed-care plans that could offer the
same benefits for less cost would be allowed to offer their
customers rebates.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to harness market-driven competition to force plans
to provide innovative care and hold down costs. Like the Clinton
plan, the Roth formulation would not need to raise premiums in the
government-run fee-for-service plan faster than planned under
current law except to cover the cost of additional drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   There are flaws in the Roth plan, but they are remediable.
Enrollees in the government plan who decide to buy the new drug
coverage would pay more for home health care and some other
benefits. That threatens to fragment the insurance market, driving
people into or out of drug coverage based on their expected needs
for home health care and other benefits. Also, the drug policy that
Roth appears to have in mind would be far less generous than what
Democrats have proposed and what the elderly need. But to correct
these and the other flaws requires only the commitment to spend
more money. No structural redesign is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats attribute Roth's decision to side with them to
his need to firm up support for his re-election bid in Delaware.
Perhaps. But whatever the motive, Roth has offered an attractive
plan for giving reliable, affordable drug coverage to the elderly
as part of a vastly improved overall Medicare program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2960 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-TAX-SENATE-SFCHRON &LR;      07-15 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-SENATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SENATE VOTES TO ABOLISH TAX ON INHERITANCES  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With support from key Democrats _ including
California's Dianne Feinstein _ the Senate voted to repeal the
inheritance tax Friday, signaling a seismic shift in political
attitudes about wealth in America.
</P>
<P>
   Although President Clinton again promised to veto the measure
Friday, the 59-to-31 vote for repeal included backing from nine
Democrats. A similar measure, which was passed overwhelmingly by
the House last month, picked up support from nearly half of
California's Democratic delegation, including Walnut Creek's Ellen
Tauscher and Silicon Valley's Anna Eshoo and Zoe Lofgren.
</P>
<P>
   The repeal would phase out the current inheritance tax, which
applies to estates of more than $675,000, over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton veto would make the inheritance tax an instant
election year issue. Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
Democratic nominee, opposes repeal, while George W. Bush, his
Republican challenger, favors it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denounced the repeal as irresponsible, calling it ``a
budget-busting bill that provides a huge tax cut for the most
well-off Americans at the expense of working families.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of how far sentiment has swung against the estate
tax _ derided by opponents as the ``death tax'' _ Clinton and other
Democrats scrambled to propose their own relief plan, offering rate
reductions and exemptions for the farmers and small business people
who have been the biggest opponents of the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans rebuffed Clinton's alternatives, declaring that
nothing but repeal will do.
</P>
<P>
   Americans ``know double taxation when they see it,'' said Rep.
Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark. ``They know that if they've paid income tax,
they've paid capital gains tax, they've paid sales tax, that it's
absolutely fundamentally, inherently wrong to make death another
taxable event.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insisted that even though only about 2 percent of
Americans who die each year leave an estate large enough to be
taxed, the tax is inherently unjust.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a very basic and fundamental level, I believe that the
estate tax is unfair,'' Feinstein said in a statement. ``It amounts
to double taxation, taxing _ at times at a confiscatory rate in
excess of 50 percent _ assets that were already taxed when the
income was earned.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein is among the wealthiest members of the Senate. She and
her husband, Richard Blum, reported assets of at least $27 million
in her most recent financial disclosure statement. But she said it
was constituents who convinced her to support repeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a family works for years to establish and grow a business
or farm, an heir should not be forced to sell the business or farm
simply to pay taxes on it,'' she said. ``That is not fair, not
right and not what the American dream is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing soaring California real estate prices, Feinstein said the
tax is threatening many middle class people who were never intended
as its targets. She warned that her vote signals ``that the ball is
now in the administration's court'' to come up with a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The estate tax, first enacted in 1916 during the Progressive
Party era, now tops out at 55 percent, with a 5 percent surcharge
on especially large estates. The tax exempts the first $675,000 of
an inheritance per person, or $1.35 million for a couple, with that
exemption set to rise to $1 million per person and $2 million per
couple in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Becker, who with his wife owns Beckers' by the Beach, a
grocery store in Stinson Beach, said the combination of a home and
a small business in high-priced real estate markets such as the Bay
Area can easily force heirs to sell the property to pay the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about the Bill Gateses of the world,''
Becker said. ``If you come to Stinson Beach and you walk down the
main street, you'll see a surf shop, a real estate company, a
restaurant or two. You'll see my grocery store, a video store _
these are all operated by the people who own them. These are their
livelihoods.''
</P>
<P>
   The estate tax was long been supported on fairness grounds, as a
way to prevent an aristocracy of inherited wealth. Democrats have
traditionally denounced efforts to reduce it as a GOP giveaway to
the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it that Republicans are so prepared to protect the
financial interests of the wealthiest individuals?'' asked Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of the growing shift against the tax, Kennedy was
careful to acknowledge ``the legitimate concerns'' of small
businesspeople and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, California Democratic Sen. Barbara Boxer said, ``There
are some inequities we can fix and that we should fix, that deal
with family farms and smaller businesses and individuals. But to
repeal the entire estate tax is helping those at the very top of
the ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have proposed estate tax reductions that would have
been unthinkable for the party just two years ago and that some tax
experts say would provide faster and more certain relief than the
GOP's 10-year phase-in of repeal.
</P>
<P>
   The House Democratic version would have quickly slashed rates by
20 percent, and the Senate version would have raised the personal
exemption to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rising sentiment against the tax has been fueled by
small-business lobbies that have assiduously broadened their
coalition, attracting the National Association of Women Business
Owners, the National Black Chamber of Commerce and the U.S.
Hispanic Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, increasing stock ownership and soaring real estate
prices have made people wealthier and their assets more likely to
fall under the inheritance tax, especially as the parents of the
vast Baby Boom generation begin to die.
</P>
<P>
   Estate tax repeal is part of this year's GOP strategy of passing
the most popular elements of the $792 billion tax package that
Clinton vetoed last year.
</P>
<P>
   With the Treasury awash in surplus revenue _ projected now at
$1.87 trillion by 2010, not counting excess Social Security payroll
taxes _ Republicans argue that the time is ripe for tax cuts, and
they are finding significant Democratic support.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than simply opposing GOP tax cuts, the White House is
countering with offers to accept ``reasonable'' tax cuts if
Republicans support some of Clinton's key proposals, like a
Medicare drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   But the political dynamics of the approaching election undermine
the chances for any such grand compromise. With both the White
House and the House up for grabs, both parties are concentrating
more on collecting political ammunition for November than enacting
legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
