A2961 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-DIAMONDS-NYT &LR;      07-15 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DIAMONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CRUELTY-FREE DIAMONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, July 15:
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in Antwerp, the World Diamond Congress will meet to write
new rules for the treatment of diamonds from war zones. Diamond
traders and manufacturers are reacting to public concern about
diamonds mined illicitly by warlords in Angola, Sierra Leone and
Congo to finance wars fought largely for control of their country's
mineral wealth. The industry, realizing that bad publicity could
devalue a product whose only worth comes from consumer perception,
is eager to certify that it sells only clean stones.
</P>
<P>
   An effective certification system, however, requires independent
monitoring, which the industry has so far resisted.
</P>
<P>
   The diamond controversy began in Angola. When the United States
cut off its Cold War aid to the rebel leader Jonas Savimbi, he
turned to diamonds. Since 1992 at least $2.5 billion in diamonds
have emerged from territory Savimbi controlled, the majority
purchased eventually by De Beers, the diamond giant, which had a
policy of buying and hoarding excess diamonds to keep the price up.
De Beers denies that it bought diamonds from the rebels knowingly,
but few experts believe this.
</P>
<P>
   Angola's diamonds have extended a war that has killed half a
million people in the last decade and made the country one of the
world's most miserable. Diamonds also finance a vicious rebel
movement in Sierra Leone and a war in Congo that has drawn in
countries from across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has led an international effort to curtail
the trade in diamonds from areas convulsed by war. In 1998, the
Security Council banned the purchase of Savimbi's diamonds,
although the embargo was widely violated. Last March, the Security
Council published a surprisingly strong report that accused several
African leaders of sanctions-busting and said that the central
diamond clearinghouse in Antwerp _ the world's largest market for
rough diamonds _ had ``extremely lax controls.'' Recently, the
Security Council banned the purchase of diamonds from Sierra Leone.
Global Witness, a London nongovernment group, has also been
important in raising public concern about conflict diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   In March, De Beers said it would guarantee that its diamonds did
not originate in war zones. This week it told its 125 major trading
partners that they had to do the same, or lose De Beers' business.
This shift is part of De Beers' overall attempt to rescue its
sinking profits. Its diamond stockpile is now seen as a drain of
its capital, and De Beers faces increased competition. It will stop
hoarding diamonds and try to become known as a brand name for clean
diamonds. The announcement will also keep trading partners from
working with the competition.
</P>
<P>
   The diamond industry plans to follow De Beers' lead, setting
rules that would establish a paper trail accompanying diamonds from
the mine onward. Legitimate exporters like South Africa and
Botswana are particularly enthusiastic about reform.
</P>
<P>
   But a certification system will not be effective unless
governments pass the necessary laws, prosecute sanctions-busters
and solve technical challenges like preventing certificate forgery.
This is likely to happen, but the industry so far has resisted the
important step of having independent experts monitor the
certification process.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other industries accused of bad global citizenship, the
diamond trade has been quick to decide that reform can serve its
members' interest. But the industry is secretive and insular, and
members have lied in the past about traffic in diamonds from war
zones. Their embrace of new rules is welcome, but should not be
trusted without verification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
