<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2963 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-GAYS-SCOUTS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-15 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-SCOUTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ELEVEN LEGISLATORS ASK CLINTON TO QUIT BOY SCOUTS POST  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eleven members of Congress have signed a letter
asking President Clinton to resign as the honorary head of the Boy
Scouts of America now that the Supreme Court has upheld the
organization's legal right to ban homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The request, supported by several Bay Area Democrats, puts
Clinton in the prickly political position of either renouncing an
organization that has symbolized patriotism and wholesomeness for
nearly a century or turning his back on allies in the fight against
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had no immediate response to the letter Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton does not agree with the Boy Scouts' practice
of excluding what the group calls ``avowed homosexuals.'' At the
same time, they provided no indication that he is giving serious
thought to abdicating his honorary title, which has been granted to
every president since William Howard Taft.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to Clinton Thursday, Petaluma Democrat Lynn
Woolsey called the Boy Scouts' policy on gays ``unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to disavow this policy of intolerance, as well as to
clarify any misperception of implicit presidential approval, we
urge you, the leader of our nation, to resign as the honorary head
of the BSA (Boy Scouts of America),'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   It was signed by Woolsey and 10 other Democrats who have worked
closely with Clinton in the past, including Reps. Nancy Pelosi of
San Francisco, Barbara Lee of Oakland and George Miller of
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Few organizations are held in higher political regard than the
Boy Scouts, a group that boasts 6.2 million members and 100 million
alumni. Among their alumni are 66 U.S. senators and 209 members of
the House of Representatives. In fact, three of those who signed
the letter _ Miller, and Reps. Barney Frank, D-Mass., and Bob
Filner, D-Calif. _ were Boy Scouts in their youth.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Supreme Court struck down a New Jersey law
that required the Scouts to include gays as leaders and members. In
a 5-to-4 decision, the court ruled that such a law violates the
group's First Amendment rights of ``expressive association,'' the
right of a group to choose members who share an ideology or a set
of values.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GAYS14 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The Scouts had testified, during the years of litigation that led
to the decision, that being an ``avowed homosexual'' is
inconsistent with the Scout Oath, which requires members to strive
to be ``morally straight.''
</P>
<P>
   The House members did not take issue with the court decision,
but noted that ``we still believe intolerance is unacceptable and
that the federal government should not condone, play a role in or
be a partner to this policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's role with the Boy Scouts is largely symbolic. His
signature appears on certificates given to boys when they qualify
as Eagle Scouts, and he is invited to speak at the group's
quadrennial ``jamboree.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton last addressed the Boy Scouts in 1997 in Bowling Green,
Va., noting that since 1910, ``every president has proudly served
as your honorary president.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every president has recognized what a great contribution
Scouting has made and is making to the character of our young
people, and therefore to the character and future of the United
States of America,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that such statements are inconsistent with
Clinton's opposition to discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to associate himself with the Scouts really
contradicts everything he has ever stood for,'' said Scott Cozza, a
former Petaluma troop master.
</P>
<P>
   Cozza _ who said he was ousted as a troop leader after his
position on accepting gays became known _ and his teenage son
founded an organization known as Scouting for All, which is
dedicated to getting the Boy Scouts to rescind its policies on
gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the Boy Scouts have been outed as a bigoted
organization,'' Cozza said, ``Clinton definitely has to relinquish
his honorary postion. He's supposed to be a voice for human rights
and people who have been discriminated against.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House referred reporters to comments made by Clinton
shortly after the Supreme Court decision two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of GAYS14 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Asked during a news conference how he could justify his role as
honorary president of the Scouts, Clinton said, ``I'm generally
against discrimination against gays.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say that he is proud of the nation's efforts to
end discrimination in other areas, adding: ``The Boy Scouts still
are _ they're a great group, they do a lot of good.''
</P>
<P>
   Boy Scout officials say the controversy has had little effect on
their organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had tremendous support both before and after the
decision,'' said Boy Scouts' spokesman Greg Shields from the
group's headquarters in Texas. ``Boy Scouts is a voluntary
organization. We respect everyone's opinion and right to hold an
opinion. We simply ask other people to respect our right to hold
opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts do not inquire as to their members' sexuality, nor do
they automatically dismiss gays. However they reserve that right,
stating in their organization's Web page: ``We believe an avowed
homosexual is not a role model for the values espoused in the Scout
Oath and Law.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to calling on the Clinton to abdicate his honorary
title, Woolsey plans to introduce legislation next week that would
revoke the organization's 84-year-old congressional charter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scouting should help boys grow and learn how to be leaders and
good citizens,'' said Woolsey. ``But intolerance is not a value we
want our children to learn, and it's not a value that the president
of the United States should support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
