u s BC-BBO-YANKS-MARLINS-NYT     07-15 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW CLOSE BRUSHES, BUT CLEMENS KEEPS HIS COOL INTACT
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Preston Wilson flung both hands into the air, raised
onto his toes and jumped back from a fastball thrown by Roger
Clemens in the first inning Friday night, and there must have been
a sense of relief in the Yankees' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clemens' first start since he beaned the Mets' Mike
Piazza and was accused of doing so intentionally, and some of his
teammates _ and manager Joe Torre _ were not sure how he would
react, if Clemens would become tentative, for fear that he might
hit somebody again and raise more allegations.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens brushed back Wilson in the first inning, pitched
inside a few more times and pitched effectively, allowing only two
runs over seven innings and earning his third victory in his last
three starts as the New York Yankees dumped the Florida Marlins,
6-2, before 35,332 fans at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw a few inside,'' Torre said. ``I'm not sure he was as
aggressive as he was, or wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams and David Justice slammed back-to-back home runs
in the first inning, and in the fourth, Ryan Thompson ripped a
three-run homer, extending his audition to become the Yankees'
regular left fielder, at least for another day or two.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens strolled into the Yankees' clubhouse about two hours
before Friday night's game dressed in black slacks, one of his
primary wardrobe colors, with a Western-style belt, a dark blue
shirt and a beard one or two days' old, a major league pitcher
disguised as John Wayne. He is not the type to reveal his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre indicated obliquely that he sensed Clemens was hurt by
the fallout of the pitch he threw to Piazza _ the direct
accusations made by Piazza and some of the other Mets, as well as
some reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the reaction, on Sunday night at Shea Stadium,
Torre saw Clemens sitting in the Yankees' training room and asked
him how he was holding up, and Clemens answered that he was OK
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was no way of knowing how Clemens would react until
he pitched again. Torre and the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre had
encouraged him for more than a year, since he joined the Yankees,
to be more aggressive pitching inside, and Clemens had done so in
his first two starts in July and won.
</P>
<P>
   That was before the Piazza fallout, though. Clemens went to the
bullpen about 15 minutes sooner than he normally does, before
pitching against the Marlins Friday night _ he was anxious, Torre
thought _ and immediately was in trouble. The Marlins had a runner
at second and Clemens needed 10 pitches to strike out Cliff Floyd.
Wilson, who had a couple of hits Thursday, leaned across the plate
on a 1-1 pitch, and then Clemens threw inside, driving Wilson back.
It was a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens needed 33 pitches to get through the first inning, but
after the Yankees scored three runs in the bottom of the first, he
could be more aggressive with his fastball _ ``more efficient,'' he
called it. The Marlins scored twice in the third, when Wilson drove
a low fastball to the opposite field, to the right-field stands,
but Thompson hammered a hanging slider from Florida's Ryan Dempster
(9-6) for a three-run shot in the fourth. Clemens was more
comfortable thereafter, his fastball consistently reaching 95 mph,
and he shut out the Marlins in his last four innings.
</P>
<P>
   His beard had been shaved into a goatee after the game, the same
hard face. But Clemens' voice seemed to sink a bit when asked about
the reaction to Piazza's beaning. Clemens reiterated that he would
never say exactly what his plan was in pitching to Piazza that
night, but he indicated that he did have a plan _ to pitch inside,
surely _ that went awry. Others in the organization believe Clemens
meant to knock down Piazza, who had seven hits in 12 at-bats
against Clemens, but not hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt awful about it when everything went down,'' Clemens
said Friday night. ``I'm not going to tell you how I'm going to
pitch to you or try to get him out, but obviously with the game
plan, we had to do something different. But it obviously wasn't to
that extreme. It looked awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said he was told about the adverse reaction from family
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it bothered them as much, because they know me
personally as an individual,'' he said. ``Some guys that don't know
me write about it, and portray you in the media as someone you're
not when they don't really know me personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens said the only reactions he really cares about are in
this clubhouse. He added: ``Each man, to a man, said `We've got
your back and continue to be aggressive and do what you have to
do.' It's great to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   For his teammates, it was great to see him pitching inside
again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
