<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-VACCINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLU VACCINE TO BE LATE, MAY BE RATIONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Flu vaccine will be late this fall and possibly in
short supply because of production problems at four pharmaceutical
companies across the country, federal health officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention are
recommending that the most vulnerable get flu shots first and that
public health agencies delay drives - from October to November -
for others to get shots. The CDC also advised health agencies to
create contingency plans for vaccine shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's primarily a matter of delay, and if people are able to
follow recommendations, things should go well,'' said Dr. Keiji
Fukuda, chief of the influenza branch of the CDC's epidemiology
section.
</P>
<P>
   In California, where the flu season usually doesn't peak until
late December and early January, a month's delay is not expected to
cause a major problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about a two- to three-week delay in our flu clinics, and
that's about the biggest thing,'' said Gary Wong, regional
coordinator of preventive care for Kaiser Permanente Southern
California, which gave more than 600,000 flu shots to members last
year and will begin its anti-flu campaign Nov. 1. ``Fortunately,
California generally has a later flu season anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the Los Angeles County Department of Health
Services plan to postpone vaccinations scheduled in the latter half
of October. They plan to give the vaccine first to people 65 and
older who have heart disease or other conditions that make them
especially vulnerable to flu complications, according to an
internal department memo released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Maria Iacobo said, however, that the CDC has sent
out contradictory information in recent weeks about how long public
health agencies should wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still awaiting news from (the CDC), so we'd prefer to
wait to have something clearer to impart to the general public,''
Iacobo said.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies are expected to be late because the producers, which
last year made about 85 million doses, have not been able to make
enough of the vaccine, reformulated to fight a new flu strain
expected to circulate this season. In addition, two of the
companies, Parke-Davis and Wyeth-Ayerst, are experiencing
unspecified production problems under review by the Food and Drug
Administration, Fukuda said.
</P>
<P>
   Wyeth-Ayerst spokesman Doug Petkus said delays in reproducing
cultures of the virus will set delivery of the vaccine back about
four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The news comes even as the CDC is recommending that more
Americans than ever should get flu shots. In years past, the agency
had limited the recommendation to people 65 and older and to others
with certain health problems, but this year recommended shots for
all people over 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is no vaccine shortage, it shouldn't be a big
complication,'' Fukuda said. ``If there is a vaccination shortage -
and that's a big if - then what we're suggesting is that it's
appropriate to focus on people within that group who have high-risk
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fukuda said the vaccine will include killed forms of the
B/Yamanashi and A/New Caledonia strains, as in last year's batches.
But the drug manufacturers did not produce a hoped-for yield of a
third vaccine, known as A/Panama H3N2, he said. Drug manufacturers
told CDC officials they would need more time to make supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC is issuing no new recommendations about the use of new
antiviral drugs, such as Tamiflu and Relenza. Health authorities
said the drugs, taken at the first sign of flu, should not be
regarded as substitutes for the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the flu kills about 20,000 people and hospitalizes
110,000 across the country.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
