<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2972 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO--BECKETT-HNS &LR;      07-15 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO--BECKETT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Spring's Beckett shrugs off injury, turns heads with gifted arm
<TEXT>
<P>
   By RICHARD JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Josh Beckett runs a finger over the top of his right shoulder
and points to the spot where the pain began. Three months have
passed since then, and Beckett can afford to call it a learning
experience.
</P>
<P>
   He was sidelined for 44 days _ he counted all of them _ but this
day he's once more healthy and trading playful barbs with Sean
Burroughs, Josh Hamilton and many of baseball's other best
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so frightened I couldn't sleep,'' he said. ``I thought I
was going to have to have surgery. I really did. It hurt that
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   He's standing outside the clubhouse used for last weekend's
Futures Game. It's an hour or so before game time, and before the
afternoon is over, Beckett will take the mound and show dozens of
scouts and general managers why they loved him so much last year
when the Florida Marlins made the former Spring High School star
the second overall pick of the summer baseball draft.
</P>
<P>
   There's the 97-mph fastball that overpowered even some
major-league hitters this spring. There's the Bert Blyleven
curveball that will lock your knees and freeze your bat. And
there's the 6-4 frame and the confidence and the maturity that go
way beyond his 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, a few weeks ago, there was that terrifying stabbing
pain in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls no sign of trouble during a spring training in which
he spent 24 days in the big-league camp and was thrilled just to
share a clubhouse with Alex Fernandez, Cliff Floyd and others. The
Marlins sent him to the mound twice, against the Royals and Braves,
and Beckett more than held his own, compiling a 1.80 ERA while
striking out four and walking none in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   After watching him throw two perfect innings against the Royals,
Marlins manager John Boles gushed: ``That's big-time stuff. They
were late with their swings. He had composure. You don't want to go
crazy with your praise, but my goodness gracious.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett looked so good and so poised that some wondered if the
Marlins might not change their mind about sending him to the
minors. They didn't. Because he'd never had a full season of
professional baseball and because the roadside is littered with
young flameouts like David Clyde and others, they saw the risk as
too high.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's clear he might not be in the minors long. The
Marlins might have promoted him from a low Class A league to Class
AA by the end of the summer, with a big-league debut projected for
around 2002. For now, he's pitching for Kane County, Ill., in the
Class A Midwest League. He's on a 75-pitch limit. And he's being
told again and again to enjoy the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last year has just been awesome,'' he said. ``It's been
the most unbelievable experience. I went to big-league camp, and
there's no feeling like it. I learned why people spent 12 years in
the minor leagues to get there. It was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   He also learned a lesson about how fragile it all is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down to the minor-league camp, and that might have been
where I overdid it,'' he said. ``I was trying to prove too much.
When you think about the outcome, you corrupt the whole process. I
know it's a cliche, but you've got to take it one pitch at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows everywhere he goes baseball people nod at one another
and whisper that this guy can't miss, that he's the best pitching
prospect in the minors. In the next breath, they almost always
compare him to some other Texas legend _ to Nolan Ryan or Roger
Clemens or Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts who have seen both pitchers said Beckett throws harder
and has more polish than Wood at a similar age. So with that kind
of billing, Beckett did the only thing he could do. He kept
throwing hard and ignored the fact his right shoulder was on fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning of his first start, when the discomfort
worsened, Beckett's only thought was: ``Maybe it'll go away. Maybe
it's just some soreness.''
</P>
<P>
   He never had experienced anything similar at Spring, so he had
nothing to measure it against. He went back to the mound a few days
later and pitched the final four innings of a five-inning start
with the shoulder ``killing me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally told my trainer how bad it was,'' he said. ``I tried
to go out and throw the next day, and it was just so tight I
couldn't throw. It was scary because I didn't know what was going
on with my body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you learn a lot about what happens with your body
during your first pro season. It's such a long season and you start
to learn the things you need to do before a start, the day after
you start, stuff like that. You've got to take it in stride. You
can't rush it. You've got to take that first year to learn all that
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins, as worried as Beckett, sent him to Chicago for one
exam and then to Fort Lauderdale for another.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me nothing was torn, so I kind of relaxed,'' he
said. ``I was pretty stressed out about it. I got the MRI and all
the tests. They told me I had some inflammation of the biceps
tendon. That was causing the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   He was told to take two weeks away before throwing again, but
ended up on the sideline for more than six.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was still bothering me a little bit when I came back,'' he
said. ``After about four days of long toss, it was great. It's back
to normal now. I don't think it's going to be a recurring thing. If
it does, I'll know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett has won just one of his eight starts, but his statistics
are those of someone special: a 2.12 ERA with 39 strikeouts and 11
walks in 34 innings. Opponents are hitting .210 against him. In
short, he has been every bit as good as advertised. His fastball
and curveball are big-league-caliber pitches even as he struggles
with a changeup and the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Jeff Andrews wants about 10 of his 75 pitches to
be changeups. Beckett said he's trying even though ``there are
times you get so mad you want to give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews didn't know what to expect when he was assigned to care
for Florida's top prospect. He's as much a father figure as a
pitching coach, so along with teaching Beckett simple things like
holding on runners, he watches the overall development.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask about his personality,'' Andrews said. ``Well, it's
still developing. He's changing a little bit every day. He's got a
good work ethic and is very single-minded in what he wants to
accomplish. He's got All-Star-caliber stuff, but really, he just
needs to pitch. That's what this season is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's life has been lived at a fast pace since last summer
when he signed a four-year, $7 million contract that included a
$3.62 million signing bonus. He's using some of that money to build
a home in Spring and donated $100,000 to help Marlins owner John
Henry fund a baseball tournament for 500 South Florida children. He
invested most of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   If he has had trouble adjusting to life away from home, he
hasn't shown it. He has dedicated himself to a weightlifting
program that has added 20 pounds and has tried to soak up as much
knowledge from as many different sources as possible.
</P>
<P>
   During spring training, Beckett refined his pre-game routine by
watching Fernandez. And he has learned again and again the
importance of throwing that first pitch in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get behind in the count at this level, you're going to
get hit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Chipper Jones reminded Beckett of that lesson with a
scalding line drive off the wall in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just needs to keep going out there,'' Andrews said.
``People associate his draft status with his experience. He's a
high school kid 40 innings deep into his pro career. People want a
rush to judgment. They want to know why he doesn't strike out 20
every game. Why does he give up home runs? Those things are unfair
to ask of anyone starting his career in a new environment. He's
just getting started.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Spring, his parents, John and Lynn, listen to
Josh's games via the Internet or on a 50-cents-per-minute telephone
line. They have seen him pitch once in Kane County and for an
inning during the Futures Game. They've visited him during spring
training and saw him when he returned home for his girlfriend's
high school graduation and his brother's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a whirlwind and it's still a whirlwind,'' his
mother, Lynn, said. ``If you'd told me two years ago, I'd be doing
interviews I wouldn't have believed it. But you prepare for things
as they come along, and we've tried to prepare for the next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a good learning experience for him. He complains
about the travel every once in a while, but he loves baseball. He'd
do anything to play baseball. We're so proud of him, and he has
handled this year excellently.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
