u s BC-BBO-METS-BOSOX-NYT &LR;      07-15 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA ERASES ANY DOUBTS WITH 2 HOMERS
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New York Mets came back to beat the Boston Red Sox
Friday night, but a more significant comeback took place. Mike
Piazza, it turns out, is just fine.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Mets' catcher played for the first time after
suffering a concussion from a Roger Clemens fastball to the head
last Saturday. He went 1 for 4, and answered countless questions
about whether he had feared anything or felt awkward in the
batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   He answered no on Thursday, and his bat talked for him Friday
night. Piazza blasted two home runs, the second one a game-winner,
as the New York Mets came from behind to beat the Boston Red Sox,
6-4, in a game delayed 62 minutes at the start because of a power
outage at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's the MVP,'' said Mets catcher Todd Pratt. ``I don't know
how far we're going to go, but right now, he's doing everything
we've always known he could do. It's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   After blowing the lead to the Boston Red Sox in an ugly seventh
inning, the Mets needed a jolt in the eighth. Red Sox reliever
Hipolito Pichardo had retired all eight batters he faced, but with
two outs in the eighth, Red Sox manager Jimy Williams called on
Derek Lowe, his all-star closer, to face the Mets' two offensive
all-stars.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo singled, and Piazza _ who missed the All-Star
Game because of the concussion _ came to the plate. He drove a 1-1
curveball from Lowe off a giant cola bottle mounted on the light
tower above the high left field wall, giving the Mets a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``For myself personally, I didn't really worry about any sort of
questions,'' Piazza said. ``I was happy about myself, health-wise,
that I'm OK That sort of has a way of mediating my expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer earned a victory for Pat Mahomes, who got the last out
in a seventh inning in which the Red Sox took the lead with two
runs off three Mets relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' starter, Glendon Rusch, has not walked a batter in his
last 33 2/3 innings. But as soon as he was removed from the game,
the Red Sox drew their first walk, by Jose Offerman off Turk
Wendell to lead off the seventh. After a sacrifice, Dennis Cook
relieved and faced Brain Daubach, who won Thursday's game with a
two-out, two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Cook had fanned Daubach on a nasty slider on Thursday, and
Williams _ a former Atlanta Braves coach _ had the ball checked
before Cook's first pitch. Cook got ahead in the count, 0-2, and
Williams came onto the field to complain about the way Cook was
rubbing the baseball with his hands between pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been checked probably 50 times between these guys and the
Braves, and every time I get the ball back,'' said Cook. ``I've
been rubbing the ball up for 15 years the same way, and the only
teams that seem to have a problem with it are the Braves and Red
Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook stepped off the rubber and backed away from the mound, then
got back on and stared in for several seconds. It was gamesmanship,
and Daubach did not like it. Annoyed, he stepped out of the
batter's box and walked away from catcher Todd Pratt, who became
irate and confronted Daubach, with umpire Marty Foster coming
between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to `Save it,''' Pratt said. ``I just said, `Who are
you to tell me to save it?' I couldn't believe a guy who's got one
year in is telling me to save it. I told him how I felt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The benches and bullpens emptied, but no punches were thrown and
several Red Sox and Mets players joked with each other. Foster
still warned both benches, and on the next pitch, Daubach lined a
single to right, scoring Offerman to tie the score, 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Cook then walked Nomar Garciaparra, and two pitches later, he
hit Carl Everett in the back of the shoulder. Foster ejected Cook,
who was livid and stalked to the plate pointing, claiming Everett
was crowding the plate.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse one pitch later. Left-hander Rich Rodriguez came
in, and in his first game back from a five-game assignment to
Triple-A Norfolk, Rodriguez allowed a bloop single to Troy O'Leary
that scored Garciaparra to put the Red Sox ahead, 4-3. It was the
third time in the game that O'Leary singled home Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra had kept Rusch in trouble for much of his six
innings. The Red Sox shortstop entered the game with a major
league-leading .391 average, and he was 4 for 4 in the game,
pulling his average to .400 as he chases his second batting title
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch had left with a 3-2 lead, courtesy of Piazza's first homer
_ which he sent onto Landsdowne St. beyond the left field wall _
and a two-run shot by Mora.
</P>
<P>
   Mora's error on Thursday prolonged the ninth inning and made
possible the Red Sox's comeback victory. Mora was shaky at
shortstop again Friday night, losing the ball on a transfer from
his glove to his hand as he tried to throw to first on a potential
double-play grounder in the second.
</P>
<P>
   But his obvious advantage over his predecessor, Rey Ordonez, is
his offensive ability. Mora bashed one high into the netting above
the Green Monster in left field. It was his sixth homer _ Ordonez
had none _ and it gave the Mets a 3-1 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
