r a BC-STABBING-DEATH-SPI &LR;      07-15 1568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STABBING-DEATH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STABBING DEATH RAISES QUESTIONS OF RACISM IN RESORT TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HECTOR CASTRO  
 and ROBERT L. JAMIESON Jr.  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEAN SHORES, Wash. _ In a flash it was over: One man was dying,
three men were fleeing a bloodied parking lot in fear, and this
quiet beach community, where residents don't lock their bicycles,
was left struggling for words.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the July 4 stabbing death of Christopher Kinison, a
20-year-old white man _ allegedly at the hands of two Asian men _
has attracted attention aside from the tourists who flock here in
the summer. White supremacist groups have lined up on one side,
human rights organizations on the other, and townspeople, caught
uncomfortably in between, insist their community is not racist.
</P>
<P>
   But Kinison's death has done more than spark civic
soul-searching. Only the second homicide in the Ocean Shore's 30
years, the case has forced the small police department to juggle
detective work with media scrutiny. Just three days before the
killing, authorities learned that Kinison had joined friends at a
mall, allegedly taunting Asian visitors.
</P>
<P>
   County prosecutors, in the face of criticism, stand by their
decision to charge Minh Duc Hong, the 26-year-old man accused of
killing Kinison, with first-degree manslaughter, not murder.
Prosecutors did not charge Hong's brother, Hung Duc Hong, who
allegedly held Kinison during the attack, or De Qiang Chen, their
friend. Minh Duc Hong is free on $20,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, police shed light on the events of July 4 by releasing a
911 dispatch tape; terror resonates in the voice of Hung Duc Hong
who fled with his brother and friend to a hotel after the fight at
a Texaco gas station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to try to get something to eat and we were getting
harassed by some American kids, '' Hung Duc Hong told the
dispatcher. ``They were like racist stuff. Calling us gooks and
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the group was ``yelling white power and punched me in
the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinison's death perplexes some in his town. They are trying to
balance the Hongs' claims of self defense with Kinison's 22 stab
wounds _ balance memories of their friend who had a wild side and a
tender soul.
</P>
<P>
   Kinison once bought long-stemmed roses for a good friend's wife,
and could be counted on if a friend needed to move furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``His reward was just a smile and a thank you. He was content
with that, never asking for money or saying, `you owe me one' ''
said Jenni Helm, a friend.
</P>
<P>
   One friend said he wasn't surprised Kinison might have started
the fight, or even that he used racist jibes to do it. He was
surprised Kinison was killed. ``I did not think he would ever go
down,'' said James Bohrn. ``I've seen him take down 40-year-old
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never anybody else after them,'' said Randy Deibel,
a friend who witnessed the fight. ``There was just two people
against their three. They could easily have beat him up, got in
their car and left.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monte Hester, the defense attorney for Minh Duc Hong, said
the young Asian men faced a rapidly escalating situation of ``sheer
terror.''
</P>
<P>
   And even Kinison's friends say other factors could have made the
threat appear greater than it was intended. For one, Kinison waved
a Confederate flag _ viewed by some people as a symbol of racism.
And Kinison showered the Asian men with sharp taunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not know him,'' Deibel said. ``They did not know
Chris was just a small town, local boy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kinison also had a rap sheet. In October 1997, he was
convicted of possession of marijuana and of having a dangerous
weapon _ a butterfly knife. Also in 1997, he was investigated for
racially harassing a group of African American youths; no charges
were filed. In 1999, Ocean Shores police said, he and a friend were
arrested for using a gun to shoot out street lights.
</P>
<P>
   White supremacist groups said Kinison's history of trouble _ and
even his taunting of the Hongs _ was no reason for getting stabbed
22 times; they lambasted the Hong brothers claim of self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have a situation where if you are a minority you can
murder a European American and walk free,'' said David Jensen,
spokesman for the Western Washington chapter of the National
Organization for European American Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The local chapter, which claims more than 200 paid members, is
part of the national group started by David Duke, a former Ku Klux
Klanman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what's right and what's wrong, and so far I have seen a
violation of (Kinison's) rights,'' said Jensen, who plans to attend
the trial this fall. If need be, he said, Duke could come to
Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   However, Eric Ward of the Northwest Coalition for Human Dignity
said the group is exploiting bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their goal. Our best defense is to demand that our
community, our public officials, deal fairly and honestly with the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Grays Harbor Prosecutor H. Steward Menefee said Friday night
that the charges filed were appropriate. ``I don't think it is
appropriate for any group to try to use this situation to inflame
racial tensions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here do not see a broad-based racial problem. ``We
are a small town. We'd see signs of something if it was building
up,'' said detective Sgt. Dave McManus. ``Everybody knows
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is not universal. Kinison's tauntings of the Hongs,
witnesses said, were steeped in ignorance and post-adolescent
brashness.
</P>
<P>
   Kinison, friends said, did not mind a fight _ and sometimes used
his mouth to start one. ``They didn't believe what they said,''
Deibel said of Kinison and his friends. ``They would say anything
to start a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Around town, Kinison and his friends were part of crew that
frequented local establishments _ to drink and have fun. Other
options for young people, they said, are few.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a young person what it is like in Ocean Shores past midnight
most evenings. ``Dead,'' said 18-year-old James Troyell, as he hung
out with friends by the closed bowling alley late one recent
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The main drag, Chance ala Mer, begins at the Pacific Ocean and
rolls into the heart of the town. Most business along it are in the
first half-mile, beginning with the massive Shilo Inn, and ending
at Point Brown Avenue, where the 24-hour Texaco gas station and
market sits.
</P>
<P>
   In between are shops selling kites, renting scooters, and
catering to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The street most nights is quiet until 1:30 a.m. _ until last
call arrives at The Legend Inn, a bar on Chance ala Mer. Then, the
rush is on. Bar patrons make a quick dash to the Texaco for beer
before sales end at 1:45 a.m. ``The only thing going on is the
24-hour Texaco,'' said 18-year-old Philip Tanguy, a friend of
Kinison's.
</P>
<P>
   But, several locals said, the nights leading up to the Fourth of
July tend to be different; Ocean Shores becomes a party town.
``It's always a local's worst nightmare,'' one resident said.
Authorities said the town's population swells during the holiday to
80,000.
</P>
<P>
   This last holiday was no different.
</P>
<P>
   Deibel, a 27-year-old construction worker, was out that night to
retrieve his truck, which had broken down at the Texaco when his
wife went there to get something to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Walking to the gas station, he ran into Kinison and three of
Kinison's friends; Kinison had a Confederate flag draped around
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why those guys had that flag,'' Deibel said.
</P>
<P>
   Deibel went to The Legend, a tavern, to get a relative to help
him get the truck. Then he went to the Texaco, where Kinison was
with perhaps 20 people, all mingling in a holiday party atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Kinison soon stood apart from the crowd, witnesses said _ and
that's when Minh Duc Hong, his brother and a friend drove up in
their gold Honda.
</P>
<P>
   Kinison began to taunt the trio, even when friends told him to
stop because a police officer had passed by moments earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But to the Hongs, their defense attorneys say, the taunts were
threats.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said inside the market, Minh Duc Hong grabbed a pair
of 4-inch kitchen knives, packaged for sale and hooked on a peg
board near a kite display.
</P>
<P>
   Hong, his brother and friend left the store and got into the
car. Hong's defense attorney Monte Hester said three wanted to
leave, but Kinison blocked the car's path.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Kinison stepped close to the car and waved his
flag, but did not block it. The taunts continued, and witnesses
said the men stepped out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hear Chris say, `I'll take both of you on,' '' Deibel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the main crowd, one of Kinison's friends fought Chen;
meanwhile Kinison allegedly fought with the two brothers. Many of
Kinison's friends, who were several dozen feet away, were unaware
of the severity of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   It was soon clear Kinison was losing the fight, and Deibel
thought his friend had ``had enough'' so he walked toward him. At
the same time, Kinison broke free and ran toward Deibel's truck,
less than 50 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   The Hongs stared at Deibel and, with Chen, ran to their car.
</P>
<P>
   Only then did people realize Kinison was hurt. Some girls
screamed. Friends took off their shirts to stop bleeding from
Kinison's wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Kinison then leaned over the bed of his truck, and uttered what
were among his last words: ``It hurts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
