<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUMMER-MOSS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSS COMPLETES THREE-GAME SHOT AT BASKETBALL 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH _ Randy Moss became bored this summer. So the
Minnesota Vikings' wide receiver decided to evaluate his basketball
abilities against the professional talent at the Southern
California Summer Pro League.
</P>
<P>
   Without any preparation, Moss threw on his Michael Jordan
sneakers for three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out here, just (on) straight talent,'' Moss said.
</P>
<P>
   The talent didn't really show through until Friday when Moss
finished up his three-day basketball run. In front of Vikings coach
Dennis Green and a smattering of Viking fans at the Long Beach
State Pyramid, Moss scored 18 points, including four 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I just wanted to see where my talents were,''
said Moss, who broke a two-day silence on his basketball
intentions. ``I just wanted to come out here and play and give
myself a good look.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss didn't rule out a future attempt at the NBA but he didn't
think he was ready to make the jump yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that (I'm ready),'' Moss said. ``It's still a
lot &QL;
</P>
<P>
   of work. I just wanted to play out here against some guys that
are capable of going to the NBA. I already have a job, to have a
second job would be nice. I'm not going out here trying to make
myself become a basketball player knowing that I'm a football
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss, playing for the Magic Johnson All Stars, entered the game
against Play 2 Win and hit his first shot, a 3-pointer, almost
right in front of Green's seat. The Viking coach let out a large
grin after the shot went in.
</P>
<P>
   Green, in town after vacationing in San Diego, told Moss' agent
that he would catch a game if he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy made the decision a long time ago to play football,''
Green said. ``If he wanted to go play basketball he could have done
that. He chose not to. So I don't have any problems with him going
out there and having fun and competing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get afraid of injuries any time he goes on the football
field but you can't operate from fear. You have to remember players
get hurt all the time in sports. It's not because he's out here
playing basketball. It's because freak accidents happen. That did
not make me hesitate supporting him in his decision to compete and
have some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss played high school basketball in West Virginia with
Sacramento point guard Jason Williams. The two won a state title
together.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Moss said that he would be interested in playing with
the Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are two things that Randy is focused on now:
having a great year and getting a great contract,'' Green said. ``I
think anything about the Timberwolves is going to be down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Viking training camp opens on July 23. Moss has spent much of
his summer in preparation for the football season, working out with
quarterback Daunte Culpepper and wide receiver Cris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Moss followed his first 3-pointer with a second 3. Then he
floated in for a finger roll on a fast break. It was a far cry from
his previous performance, in which he scored 9 points on 4-of-13
shooting and even airballed a free throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all right,'' Moss said of his performance. ``I needed
to come out here and do something. The first two games I came out
here and was really not too hot. I just wanted to come out here and
do a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss was tied for high-point honors in leading his team, owned
by Magic Johnson, to a 88-75 win.
</P>
<P>
   For his three games, Moss averaged 13.3 points and impressed
players and scouts with his athleticism. Scouts agreed that Moss is
not ready to play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pro Bowler was noticed for his work on the football
field.
</P>
<P>
   When Moss entered Friday's game, teammate Wilson Stevens
remarked, ``Let's go get a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Former UCLA guard Kris Johnson covered Moss for much of Friday's
game. Johnson is a big Moss fan and while lining up defensively
made a point of telling him so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you're the man in football,'' Johnson told Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who played in the CBA last season, was surprised how
well Moss shot the ball but said that he needed to improve his ball
handling. Overall, he said Moss was an OK basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are incredible athletes,'' Johnson said of football
players. ``That's why a guy like Randy Moss can come out here and
look more than halfway decent. ... I'm sure if this was his main
thing from day one he would probably be in the NBA right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss clearly hasn't given up the dream and even said that a goal
of his would be to play in the summer league on a more full-time
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, throughout the years,'' Moss said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
