<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-U.S.-TRACK-NYT &LR;      07-15 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-U.S.-TRACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARION JONES CRUISES AT OLYMPIC TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ It is a long process that will not be
resolved for two and a half months, but Marion Jones took her first
fleet steps on the long journey toward five gold medals Friday
night, cruising through the 100-meter preliminaries in 10.92
seconds at the U.S. Olympic track and field trials.
</P>
<P>
   Later Friday night she qualified in her weakest event, finishing
fifth in the preliminary round of the long jump with a leap of 21
feet 6} inches. Jackie Joyner-Kersee came out of retirement and
also qualified for Sunday's final by jumping 21}, her first attempt
in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long jump, it's all about making the final,'' said
Jones, who added about the 100: ``I think I can run faster than I
ever have before.''
</P>
<P>
   The world's fastest man, Maurice Greene, ran this year's
second-fastest time of 9.93 seconds in his 100-meter preliminary.
Michael Johnson ran the opening round of the 400 meters winning his
heat in 45.16 seconds as he seeks to repeat his Olympic double with
gold medals at 200 meters and the quarter-mile. But the focus of
this meet is on Jones and her attempt to do what no female athlete
has ever done _ win five gold medals in track and field at the same
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking to win silver or bronze,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   And the more people tell Jones that she cannot win five golds at
the Summer Games in Sydney, Australia, the more convinced she is
that she can. She has been accomplishing the extraordinary all of
her life: nine state high school championships in California, a
collegiate basketball title at North Carolina as a freshman point
guard, a pair of world championships at 100 meters, 36 consecutive
victories running and jumping in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, going for five golds is continuing to achieve what
doesn't seem reasonable to some or what people told her she
couldn't do,'' said Ron Rapoport, who wrote Jones' biography, ``See
How She Runs.'' ``This is one more. When people say, `You can't do
that,' she puts it to the farthest reach. I think it helps her with
the events that she's been able to dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has not lost a foot race since the end of the 1997 season.
And she is not likely to lose at 100 meters at the Olympic trials.
Her personal best of 10.65 seconds is the fastest time run by any
woman except Florence Griffith-Joyner, whose world record of 10.49
seconds was allowed to stand at the 1988 Olympic trials despite the
widespread belief that a strong tail wind was not properly recorded
by a faulty wind gauge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm ready to run my personal best at any time,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anyone who can beat her at 100 meters? Inger Miller,
the 1999 world champion at 200 meters and Jones' chief sprinting
rival, struggled recently in the 100 in Europe, finishing fifth at
a meet in Athens and sixth in Rome. Friday night, she ran her
seasonal best of 11.04 seconds, while the two-time Olympic champion
Gail Devers ran a 10.99. Both will compete in Saturday's
semifinals; the final is also Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just training,'' Miller said of her mediocre
performances overseas. ``I was trying to see what I could do when I
was tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by her world 200 title in 21.77 seconds last year at
the world championships in Seville, Spain, Miller has been saying
that women's sprinting ``is no longer a one-woman show.'' Jones
pulled up with back spasms at the event.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of Lennox Miller, a two-time Olympic sprint
medalist from Jamaica, Inger Miller has a beautifully fluid stride.
This technical proficiency aids her significantly in maintaining
her form through the grind of running rounds. But one of her
training partners, Ato Boldon, the 1996 Olympic bronze medalist at
100 and 200 meters, believes that she has become distracted by her
fixation on beating Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has shown me yet that they are ready to run with Marion
in the latter half of the 100 meters,'' said Boldon, who trains
with Miller under the sprint coach John Smith in Los Angeles and
who is considered one of the more astute students of sprinting. ``I
think Inger has to have more vision than, `I just want to beat
Marion here.' I think her focus should be on `getting my act
together, and qualifying, then dealing with Marion.' She'll face
Marion a lot in Europe. That's when you work your magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' form in the 100 suggests the rawness of power and speed
more than the silky grace, say, of Carl Lewis, but there is a
tremendous resolve and control evident in the way she runs. Unlike
most women, Johnson noted, Jones does not cross her chest with her
arms as she sprints but is strong enough to keep them
piston-pumping straight up and down in rhythm with her legs.
</P>
<P>
   Boldon said: ``Technically, she's not as good as she was in the
past, but she's gotten stronger so it doesn't matter. People who
know the sport do not use Marion as the textbook example of
technique. You look at Marion as an athlete, her ability to
compete, how she focuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Her form in the long jump is more troubling, and, some believe,
more susceptible to injury. She has decided to let speed carry her
to great distances, rather than to rely on any intricate technique.
Her best jump this season is 22 feet 10{ inches, fifth on the world
list. But she is erratic and prone to fouls. Many experts,
including Mike Powell, the men's world record holder at 29-4{,
believe that Jones should be jumping 24 feet regularly and
threatening 25 feet, which is four inches beyond the women's world
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``She may be jumping badly, then she can put a far jump out
there if she does something right,'' Powell said. ``She can jump 23
feet by accident, she's so talented. But she shouldn't have to rely
on accident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
