<P>
   BRAZIL-POLITICS (Rio de Janeiro) _ President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso is facing a political crisis as a corruption scandal grows.
By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-TAPE-BEATINGS (Undated) _ In the nine years since George
Holliday, a plumber standing on the balcony of his Los Angeles
apartment, videotaped the vicious beating of Rodney King by police,
tapes made by onlookers have become a potent legal and political
tool. This week, with two more beatings by police videotaped by
news helicopters in Philadelphia and Lawrenceville, Ga., the images
are as powerful as ever _ even though, like most bystander videos,
they do not present a full or clear picture of precisely what
happened. That is usually the main issue when cases involving
videotaped evidence come to trial: defense lawyers argue, as they
did successfully in the first prosecution growing out of the Rodney
King beatings, that because the video recorded only the tail end of
the interaction, it leaves out the behavior that led to the
beating. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-KARSKI (Undated) _ Jan Karski, a liaison officer of the
Polish underground who infiltrated both the Warsaw Ghetto and a
German concentration camp and then carried the first eyewitness
accounts of the Holocaust to a mostly disbelieving West, died on
Thursday in Washington. Karski, a retired professor of history at
Georgetown University, was 86. By Michael T. Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MISSILE-TEST (Undated) _ Experts say the recent failures in
the U.S. anti-missile defense system are growing pains typical of
ambitious rocket projects and do not mean that it cannot be fixed
to meet the testing goals. Whether it will work as a real missile
defense is another question. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-LAB-SECURITY (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ It is one of the historic
relationships in science. The University of California, since the
very beginning, has run Los Alamos Nuclear Laboratory. Now with
security lapses the tight relationship between the Los Alamos
Nuclear Laboratory and the University of California is straining.
The Energy Department has taken security away from them. And Bill
Richardson, the energy secretary, is whacking away at them. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN-BISHOP (Cincinnati) _ On the Rev. Vashti Murphy McKenzie,
the first woman elected bishop of the African Methodist Episcopal
church. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DOTCOM-ENTREPRENEURS (Beijing) _ Hundreds of millions of
American investment dollars have fattened the bank accounts of
China's young Internet entrepreneurs over the last year, making
dot-com companies the most vibrant part of the country's fledgling
but still struggling private sector. And despite the
high-technology stock slump in the United States, as much as $1
billion more in venture capital, most of it from America, is
waiting to dive into China's fast-developing Internet industry,
venture capitalists say. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
