<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-GRANT-NYT &LR;      07-15 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-GRANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT SAVORS A TASTE OF NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
  By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ On Wednesday afternoon, Brian Grant and his wife,
Gina, arrived at Newark International Airport like other harried
tourists, setting their itinerary for New York City. But between
the usual attractions, Grant found himself being courted by the New
York Knicks. By the time he was eating a final piece of New York
cheesecake as he waited for his flight home to Portland, Ore., he
was ready to turn the two-night vacation into a permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out, I was all Portland,'' Grant said as he signed
autographs from fans who lined up to tell him to stay. ``But coming
back, it's a toss-up, 50-50. I could come to New York or I could
stay in Portland. New York sold me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they work something out, then I will come to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   More difficult than the recruiting process for the Knicks is
actually figuring out a deal to get Grant to New York. Although he
opted out of his contract with the Portland Trail Blazers, the
Knicks are over the salary cap and can only offer him a $2.25
million midlevel exception. The way the deal can be done is through
a sign-and-trade agreement between the Blazers and the Knicks. But
until the Knicks can figure out a package that will appease the
Blazers, the pursuit of Grant is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we may say, `Yeah, we want to come to New York,'
they don't have to trade me,'' Grant said of the Trail Blazers.
``It's up in the air. Just because I say I want to be in New York,
doesn't mean necessarily that they would bring me to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   He also cited speaking with Charlie Ward and Allan Houston, who
share his religious beliefs, as a key selling point.
</P>
<P>
   Grant's agent, Mark Bartelstein, said his client would not try
to pressure Portland into making any trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian is not one to go around issuing ultimatums,''
Bartelstein said. ``He just doesn't work that way. The Blazers are
a great opportunity for Brian, and the Knicks are a great
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the teams' general managers, Bartelstein said,
``Scott Layden and Bob Whitsett are going to talk, and they'll see
if they have something to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant did see some of the typical attractions, like the Statue
of Liberty, during his New York stay, but unlike the tourists who
crowd onto the Circle Line, he saw it from the deck of the yacht of
James L. Dolan, the president of Cablevision. Rather than taking in
a show, he was solicited by the stars of the shows. But it was the
pastoral country homes of Westchester County and Connecticut and
the promise of a vital role on a contending team that convinced
Grant that he could adjust to life in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say I'm scared of living in the city, I don't mean I'm
scared of the people,'' Grant said. ``I just mean that I'm from a
small town of 2,500 people. Portland is a smaller city and it's
easier to get adjusted to, so I never thought I'd be able to adjust
to living in New York City. Actually, you don't have to live in New
York City, but yet you still can travel in and out of New York City
being a part of the Knicks.''
</P>
<P>
   He had praise for the Knicks' management and its impression of
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything they've said has been right on time as far as
factual stuff,'' Grant said. ``It's not like they're just blowing
me up. It's things you can look at and say, `You're right, you're
right.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I would make a great fit here as far as adding to the
great team that they already have here. Do I make this team that
much better? Who knows? But I'm a similar-type player as far as
what they bring to the table. They're a very hard-nosed defensive
team that plays well together.''
</P>
<P>
   While the NBA rules prohibit teams from actually negotiating
until Aug. 1, the Knicks accomplished their goal of proving to
Grant that he could be a vital piece of the team and town. ``It's a
recruiting process and I know that,'' he added. ``But it just feels
good to have all that going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
