<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON DOESN'T PLAN TO CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dodgers manager Davey Johnson understands the
pressure is mounting to have a strong second half and make a push
for the playoffs, but that doesn't mean he's going to do anything
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job doesn't change from day to day. I try to do what's best
for today as well as tomorrow,'' Johnson said. ``Whatever comes
down, you try to solve the problems you have on a daily basis. The
bottom line is to give us a chance to be in position to win the
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I do, and I've been successful at it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 days it's become clear that changes could be
coming if the Dodgers don't improve on their 44-42 mark they had at
the All-Star break. Before the break, managing general partner and
CEO Bob Daly traveled to San Diego and spoke with Johnson. Daly
said the Dodgers need to play with more fire and urgency.
</P>
<P>
   During the All-Star break, general manager Kevin Malone said
everyone in the organization had to improve, starting with
management, Johnson and the coaching staff. On the field, Malone
said the Dodgers need to hit behind runners more often, manufacture
runs and do the little things to win ballgames instead of relying
on the home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's injuries, or suspensions or poor performance or
whatever, you have all those things in the course of a season,''
Johnson said. ``Having injuries that cut into your depth, that's
when you need to be able to do things within the system, and I feel
like we've come a long way. We're better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we have a chance? Yeah, we have a chance. You say, 'Can you
do things better?' Well, you can always do things better. We have
young players who are learning who they are (Adrian) Beltre, (Alex)
Cora. You have some veterans who have struggled at times, that's
part of the game. Getting past this short-handed period (with Todd
Hundley and Mark Grudzielanek hurt), to me, this is probably the
toughest part of our season.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek better: The Dodgers' plans to put second baseman
Mark Grudzielanek on the disabled list went awry, particularly
because of an oversight and partly because Grudzielanek's condition
improved enough that he believes he'll be able to play Sunday or
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek missed the last five games due to a viral
infection, and though his condition improved he's only hopeful for
the series with Pittsburgh. But keeping the Dodgers from placing
Grudzielanek on the disabled list is circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   The team had planned on recalling infielder Mike Metcalfe from
Triple-A Albuquerque, and Grudzielanek's move was going to be
retroactive to last Friday. However, since Metcalfe wasn't sent
back to the minors until after Sunday's game in Seattle,
Grudzielanek would have to be placed on the disabled list
retroactive to Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, since Grudzielanek believes he'll be ready by the end
of the weekend, the Dodgers elected not to put him on the disabled
list and lose him for an additional week.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Grudzielanek's injury, shortstop Alex Cora made his
second start of the season at second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize you have more time over there so you take
more time,'' Johnson said. ``I feel safer with (Cora) over there
than Elster, than teaching a new dog, new tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring training decision: An announcement about an agreement
that would keep the Dodgers in Vero Beach, Fla., for the next 20
years was delayed until next week because of a snag. The Dodgers
weren't sure whether the designs of the new stadium were compliant
with the Americans with Disabilities Act, so research had to be
done, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were slated to announce an agreement with Vero Beach
and Indian River County (Fla.), but it was put off until the
stadium questions could be answered. However, that should be taken
care of and an announcement is likely within a week, a source said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield appeal: Jim Naeder, the agent for Gary Sheffield, said
his client plans to go through with the appeal of his five-game
suspension, though the commissioner's office hasn't set a date for
the hearing. Dodgers officials believe commissioner Bud Selig will
hear the appeal when the club is in Philadelphia July 28-30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
