<HEADLINE>
STONEMAN WELCOMES MORE REVENUE SHARING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bill Stoneman, the Angels' general manager, said
Friday night at Dodger Stadium he's not opposed at all to a
revision in Major League Baseball's revenue-sharing plan.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said he's all for it, and added that he needs to
look only as far as his former team, the Montreal Expos, for a
reason why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a team with little or no money coming in from (English)
radio-TV, so where's the money going to come from without shared
revenue?'' wondered Stoneman, who pitched five years for the Expos
(1969-73) and was a member of the club's front office for the past
17 years until joining the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman played for the Expos when their home was cozy and
intimate Jarry Park, not the vast Olympic Stadium where they play
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olympic Stadium hasn't worked out the way they thought it
would,'' conceded Stoneman, noting the Expos' are averaging a
National League-low 7,444 fans for their 85 home games.
</P>
<P>
   Freeway Series SigAlert?
</P>
<P>
   So far, the interleague Freeway Series between the Angels and
Dodgers has had nowhere near the impact at the turnstiles as
interleague series between the Mets and Yankees in New York and the
Cubs and White Sox in Chicago, where packed houses are the norm.
</P>
<P>
   The three games between the Angels and Dodgers last month in
Anaheim averaged a shade under 40,000. The first game of the
current series at Dodger Stadium Thursday night was played before
35,456, meaning more than 20,000 seats went unused.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of dynamics go into attendance . . . why and why not
fans come out,'' said Angels manager Mike Scioscia, wisely taking a
diplomatic stance inasmuch as the question had to do with his
current employer as well as his former.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern California is a baseball hotbed, I know that,'' he
said. ``I've seen it. With the Dodgers we'd always get our 3
million (annual attendance), and I remember going to Anaheim for
the (exhibition) Freeway Series and there'd be 60,000 fans out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why there aren't more now, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's Dodger Stadium crowd --- 53,115 --- was the
biggest yet for this year's Angels-Dodgers Freeway Series, although
it was lured in part by a giveaway. It was Sports Watch Night.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even with smart new timepieces the fans were late in
arriving.
</P>
<P>
   Angels left-hander Scott Schoeneweis, on a minor league rehab
assignment, hurled 4 fr 2/3 innings Friday night for Lake Elsinore
in a Class-A California League game at San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis, disabled since June 27 because of a strained muscle
in his right rib cage, gave up just one run on three hits. He
struck out three and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   He'll likely make one more minor league start before he's
activated. Before he was hurt Schoeneweis was 5-5 with a 5.08
earned run average in 14 starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
