<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG NAMES STAND OUT AT TRIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino Sun 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO -- Maurice Greene made a statement in 9.93 seconds,
Michael Johnson answered with the greatest of ease, and Marion
Jones and Jackie Joyner-Kersee set up a May-December women's
long-jump final.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's biggest names made the biggest waves Friday in Day 1
of the U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials at Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   Greene clocked a quick, 9.93-second time in the first round of
100-meter qualifying, and he did it despite glancing back at
pursuers at the 70-meter mark, and practically jogging the final
five meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people thought I came in here not ready to
run,'' Greene said. ``I ran a couple of bad races (in Europe), but
those were practice. This is serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not completely. Had Greene run full speed through his race
Friday he might have threatened his own world record of 9.79
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot left,'' he said. ``My coach (John Smith) thinks
I can run a 9.6. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene's 9.93 was the 27th sub-10-second clocking in his career,
extending his own record, and was the second-fastest in the world
this year to his 9.91.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, Greene's rival for alpha male in the world of
sprinters, practically coasted to a day's-best clocking of 45.18
seconds in the first round of the 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supposed to feel as smooth and easy as it looks,'' said
Johnson , who wore a pair of ``chameleon green'' shoes. ``At this
point, I don't think I need to work on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene and Johnson have the 100 and 400, respectively, to take
care of first, but each already seems to be looking forward to a
showdown in the 200-meter final on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he hopes to accomplish here, Greene said, ``Get
Michael Johnson, that's what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee and Jones, divas of American women's track past
and present, each qualified for Sunday's long-jump final, but
neither overawed the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' best jump was 21 feet, 6 3/4 inches, more than 2 feet shy
of her personal best, and put her fifth in the qualifying field of
12.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee, competing for the first time since 1998, was
eighth in 21-0 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I here? Because I want to try to make my fifth Olympic
team,'' said Joyner-Kersee, heptathlon world-record holder. ``I
want to go to one and just have fun. All the other times, it was
`Get off your feet and rest' during the heptathlon, and the next
thing I knew I was on the plane home.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is 24 and headed for her first Olympics, where she hopes
to win five gold medals. Joyner-Kersee is 38, and resumed training
in earnest only a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a chance to compete against her, my hero, is
wonderful,'' Jones said of Joyner-Kersee.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was the top qualifier in the women's 100, at 10.92
seconds. She believes she could approach her personal best of 10.65
in today's semifinals and finals.
</P>
<P>
   In other competition Friday:
</P>
<P>
   -- American-record holder Jeff Hartwig became the first victim
of the top-three-or-else nature of the U.S. trials, no-heighting in
pole-vault qualifying. He set the U.S. record of 19-9 1/2 exactly
one month before he failed to clear 18-2 at Hornet Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   -- Marla Runyan, the legally blind middle-distance runner,
overcame a knee injury to finish second in her heat and qualify for
the women's 1,500-meter final Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   -- DeDee Nathan leads the heptathlon after four events, with
3,747 points, narrowly ahead of Tracye Lawyer with 3,723 points.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mebrahtom Keflezighi of UCLA, a native of Eritrea, won the
men's 10 ,000-meter qualifying in an Olympic-qualifying time of 28
minutes, 3.32 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   -- In the day's other final, Deena Drossin won the women's
10,000 in 3 1:51.06.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
