<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE GAME, POSSIBLY BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gary Sheffield continued his assault on the
Dodgers' home run record and Darin Erstad assaulted the Dodgers
with a two-run homer in the seventh inning. But much of that was
lost in Anaheim's 5-3 win Friday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, everyone associated with the Dodgers had a sleepless
night wondering how badly staff ace Kevin Brown's right shoulder is
strained.
</P>
<P>
   Brown left the game after throwing his first pitch in the top of
the eighth inning. The preliminary diagnosed was a mildly strained
right shoulder. However, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said the
extent to which Brown injured his shoulder won't be known until
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shoulder really has been out of whack since San Diego,''
Brown said. ``I was sliding around on the mound, kind of strained
it a little bit. Thought there was nothing to it and I felt a lot
better the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in the second year of a seven-year, $105 million
contract, told pitching coach Claude Osteen he experienced
discomfort in his right shoulder during his July 6 start in San
Diego. But Johnson said he wasn't alerted to it.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who allowed nine hits and four runs and fell to 8-3, is
listed as day to day. He will be re-evaluated today, but his start
Wednesday against Colorado is in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first I heard of it (the injury),'' Johnson said.
``Normally, I would hear something about that. He didn't say
anything during the ballgame about it. I don't know why I didn't
know about it. I'm going to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'Why am I hearing it after the fact?' Sometimes they
don't want to say something about it, but I wish I would have know
that was bothering him going into the All-Star Game. I wouldn't
have let him throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield hit a pair of solo homers to give the Dodgers leads of
1-0 and 2-1, and in doing so, became the second-fastest Dodger to
reach the 30-homer mark. He did it in 88 games while Duke Snider
did it in 87 games in 1955 when the Dodgers were in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheffield's offensive exploits were of little consequence,
especially given what happened with Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him wince and at first I thought it might just be a
blister,'' Sheffield said. ``Then I thought about the All-Star
Game, and how they rushed him in and there was no real chance for
him to get ready. I just hope it's not serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who walked three and gave up a run during his one shaky
inning at Tuesday's All-Star Game, missed two weeks in April when
he broke his right pinkie attempting to bunt against the Mets. He
was pitching Friday instead of Thursday because Johnson wanted to
give him an extra day to rest after the All-Star appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He remarked in the San Diego game, after he a threw a pitch
and slipped a little bit, but I don't think it was to the point
where he couldn't pitch or anything like that,'' Osteen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anything warming up where he was restricted or
anything. All the pitches were going for him in the bullpen, and he
had them all in the game until the fifth or sixth inning. We
thought we saw a pitch in the sixth inning that looked out of sync,
that didn't look like a normal delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus started the Angels' three-run seventh inning with a
homer into the left-field bleachers. Adam Kennedy lined out to Eric
Karros at first and Matt Walbeck grounded to short, but pitcher
Kent Bottenfield got his second hit, a single to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad continued to pound the ball, hitting a 1-1 pitch deep
into the Angels bullpen in right field to give them a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad also made a diving catch for the first out in the ninth
inning with Alex Cora on first and Sheffield on deck. Angels closer
Troy Percival then walked Sheffield but got Shawn Green to ground
into a game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Erstad) has to be close to the MVP in the league,'' said
Bottenfield, who improved to 6-7 after allowing three hits in seven
innings. ``He gets us started, he has great clutch RBI, he's all
over the field doing everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
