<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS RALLY TO BEAT COMETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The Sparks showed just how bad they can play and how
good they could play Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the biggest game of the season, a possible preview to the
WNBA Championship, No. 2 vs. No. 1, the Sparks and three-time
defending champions and the Sparks didn't appear ready for prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they seemingly had the advantage when Houston's star
Cynthia Cooper was advised by the Comets trainer less than an hour
before the game not to play on a severely sprained right ankle she
suffered in Wednesday's game against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it look as if the Sparks' hopes were dashed, the
team which had one 12 consecutive games at one point, resurfaced
and reversed the roles of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks turned up their defense with seven minutes remaining
to erase a 15-point deficit and send a season-high Forum crowd of
11,378 into a frenzy with an amazing 63-58 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players just decided they wanted to start playing,''
Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. ``I got kind of verbal with them
at half time, but still that didn't work. It was just that they had
been pushed around and slammed and Houston was beginning to stick
their chest out and they just started to play. Maybe fatigue caught
up to Houston because their two big players were playing a lot of
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson, alone, were giving the Sparks
all kinds of fits and the Sparks had no solution until late in the
game. Swoopes had 17 of her 26 points in the first half, and
Thompson had 11 of her 17. At one point, those two had more points
(35) than the Sparks total (32) with 11:42 to remaining as the
Sparks trailed 47-32.
</P>
<P>
   But it was just around that time when the momentum shifted from
the Comets to the Sparks, who went on a 26-10 run to take a 59-57
with 1:06 to play.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference came when Tamecka Dixon switched with Mwadi
Mabika to play defense on Swoopes and the change made a big
difference. Dixon came up with a couple of big steals and Mabika
made some big offensive plays. She scored eight her team-high 15
points during the spree, including a three-pointer to tie the game
at 55-55 with 3:04 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie, who struggled with the physical play of the game
and was benched much of the second half for lack of defensive
effort, assisted DeLisha Milton for a layup to give the Sparks the
lead for good (57-55) at the 2:15 mark. Dixon stole the ball from
Swoopes and DeLisha Milton knocked down a 18-foot jumper to make it
a four-point game and the eventual Sparks victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give L.A. credit, they did a great job,'' Houston coach Van
Chancellor said. ``The game got physical They just stepped it up a
notch. The crowd got into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory pulls the Sparks (17-3) within a game of the
first-place Comets (19-3), whose 10-game win streak was snapped. It
could have been a game to give the Sparks the Western Conference
lead, but the Sparks 12-game win streak was snapped Tuesday by
Portland. Nonetheless, it gives the Sparks a possible home-court
advantage in the playoffs and their first real shot at the WNBA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they had no idea it would take this type of unusual
game to reach this point.
</P>
<P>
   SPARKS NOTES: The Sparks plays host to Minnesota Lynx today at
7:30 p.m. They defeated the Lynx, 82-75, in their second game of
the season. Minnesota lost Portland Friday 65-54.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
