<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-SIDEBAR-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER APPLAUDS MOVE BY SCIOSCIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For just an instant the other night Orel Hershiser
admitted he shed his tried-and-true Dodger Blue for a swatch ---
albeit a small one --- of Angels periwinkle.
</P>
<P>
   It was Thursday night, in the bottom of the 10th inning, when
Mike Scioscia, Hershiser's old batterymate with the Dodgers and now
the Angels' manager, employed the six-man infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he did that I said, Yes! Way to go Sosh,''' Hershiser was
saying Friday night at Dodger Stadium before the second game of the
interleague Freeway Series between the Angels and Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to try that,'' Hershiser said, smiling. ``I'm
a ground-ball pitcher. I wanted to do that. But we (the Dodgers)
never did.''
</P>
<P>
   To recap, the Dodgers had the winning run on third base in the
bottom of the 10th inning of a 3-3 tie, only one out and Kevin
Elster at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia brought in his left-handed-throwing left fielder, Darin
Erstad, and stationed him behind the pitcher, just to the shortstop
side of second base.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, of course, from Scioscia's perspective, was not to
lose the game on a roller getting through the infield. Elster
played right into Scioscia's hands when he grounded to Erstad, who
threw out Elster, with an assist from first baseman Mo Vaughn, who
dug Erstad's throw out of the dirt. Score it 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can even play shortstop,'' Scioscia said of Erstad, of whom
he said recently, ``He can do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't go entirely the way Scioscia envisioned; the next
batter, Jim Leyritz, drove a ball to right-center and the Angels
lost anyway, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   But the move, admittedly a daring one inasmuch as it left the
Angels with only two outfielders, only confirmed what Hershiser
already knew: Scioscia is already one heckuva manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very intelligent guy, and someone with great people
skills,'' Hershiser said of Scioscia. I always thought he'd be a
terrific manager . . . if he wanted to. Even when he was playing he
was like a manager on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   What Hershiser --- now retired and awaiting word on just where
he's going to fit into the Dodgers' coaching and instructing scheme
--- meant was that Scioscia routinely called the defensive plays
with runners on base, even occasionally working a hit-and-run on
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, when the Angels evened the current series at a
game apiece, 5-3, Scioscia was again at the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   First, he left his pitcher, Kent Bottenfield, in the game to bat
in the top of the seventh inning even if he hadn't been to the
plate all season and even if the Dodgers were leading at the time,
3-2. Maybe it was Bottenfield's fifth-inning single that swayed the
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was,'' said hitting coach Mickey Hatcher.
``I had 14 guys ready to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. Bottenfield singled. And Darin Erstad followed with the
decisive blow, a two-run homer into the right field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his job,'' Erstad said of Scioscia, when asked if he
was surprised Bottenfield was allowed to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia had one more ringer. When Garret Anderson tweaked his
right knee running in the eighth inning, Scioscia replaced him the
next inning in center field with Erstad, and he stationed Orlando
Palmeiro in Erstad's spot in left.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dodgers' ninth, with a runner on first, Erstad made a
remarkable diving catch of a drive to right center by Paul LoDuca.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a putout at shortstop, he's made a game-saving catch
in center, he plays left field better than anyone in our league,''
Scioscia of Erstad. ``There's nothing this guy hasn't done this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia paused, then smiled and said, ``We could use another
lefty in the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Hershiser wouldn't be surprised if Scioscia tried that
one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
