<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLERUD DELIVERS A `DO-OVER' AGAINST PADRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Jose Paniagua winced.
</P>
<P>
   He'd been warming up, throwing a ball against a wall in the
bullpen during the top of the sixth inning Friday night at Qualcomm
Stadium, when a throw went awry. The ball flew over his head and
rolled onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Umpire Jim Wolf saw the loose ball rolling around in right
field, just as San Diego pitcher Brian Weathers prepared to pitch
to John Olerud with one out and two on. Olerud doubled off the
left-field wall and would have driven in the tying run, but Wolf
said his timeout call came first.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua saw the double and figured he'd be the goat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a big hit like that,'' Paniagua said, ``it's not
that easy to get another one.''
</P>
<P>
   It was for Olerud. Told that he had to hit again, he did. He got
in the batter's box and hit Meadows' first pitch, a fastball, hard.
Not for a double this time, and not to left field. Olerud pulled
the ball and jacked it deep into the seats in right-center.
</P>
<P>
   The three-run homer, Olerud's ninth of the year, gave the
Mariners a 4-2 lead and put Seattle ahead to stay. The Mariners won
7-5 and, coupled with Oakland's 4-2 loss to San Francisco, moved
four games ahead of the Athletics in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes Paniagua the MVP of the game,'' closer Kazuhiro
Sasaki said. ``Olerud's really the MVP, but Paniagua is, too.''
</P>
<P>
   What Paniagua mostly is is relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get the ball back before anything happened,''
Paniagua said. ``But I didn't and he (Wolf) called time out. And
then we lost the double. After the home run, I was the happiest
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   No happier than Olerud, who would wind up matching his career
high with five RBIs. And certainly no happier than manager Lou
Piniella, who was so upset by Wolf's call that he came close to
getting thrown out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The game was held up for about five minutes while the Mariners,
in the person of Piniella, protested the call. Short of offense
with four regulars not in the lineup, Piniella wanted that run
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been scrambling for runs,'' Piniella said. ``I wanted
that one.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud, however, did his manager three better, hitting the next
pitch from Meadows into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was standing at second base (after the double), I
didn't know what had happened,'' Olerud said. ``I thought maybe
there'd been some kind of interference or something. I never saw
the umpire call time out, never heard him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, it's disappointing to lose a big hit,
especially for us with hits tough to get lately. I wasn't happy,
but there's really nothing you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes there is. You can hit the ball higher and farther and
out of the park, which is the course Olerud ultimately took.
</P>
<P>
   The three-run shot was notable in that it gave the Mariners more
than two runs for the first time in three games. With Alex
Rodriguez, Edgar Martinez, Rickey Henderson and Dan Wilson all out
of the lineup, runs have been exceedingly difficult to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud added a second homer in the eighth inning, going
back-to-back with Mike Cameron as part of a three-run Seattle
uprising. And it had been Olerud who'd started the game's scoring
with a first-inning RBI double _ one that actually counted. It was
his 33rd double, tops in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The win went to starter Jamie Moyer (9-3), who is 5-0 when
starting a game after a Mariners loss. Moyer went six innings and
pitched out of a couple of jams to keep the Mariners closer until
Olerud could offer the only antidote that would take the pain out
of Wolf's bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what was going on,'' Moyer said. Told that
Paniagua was the culprit, Moyer broke into a half-grin,
half-grimace. ``I'm glad that things went in our favor. It (the
loose ball) was unfortunate, but to turn out the way things did was
very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella was fortunate to be around to see the play.
</P>
<P>
   Denied the tying run and, possibly, the chance for a big inning,
Piniella went nuts. He got in Wolf's face, and when the other three
umps tried to run interference, Piniella did the Seattle sidestep
and went after Wolf again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf wouldn't change his call, but neither did he throw Piniella
out. It was fortunate for both Piniella and Paniagua that Olerud,
who spent the entire Piniella Pirouette standing on second base,
took the news much more calmly. And it was fortunate for the
Mariners that Wolf didn't start throwing people out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard him call time, and I saw him raise his hands,''
pitching coach Bryan Price said. ``He made the right call.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Paniagua made the wrong call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow, Olerud has to buy me dinner,'' Paniagua said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it should be the other way around. One suspects that
Olerud wouldn't mind paying, even so.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Oakland manager Art Howe said that when he set his
rotation to pitch Kevin Appier Friday and Gil Heredia Saturday, it
was so that Appier and Heredia would face the Mariners when Seattle
visits Oakland next Wednesday and Thursday. That should come as no
surprise, since the Mariners' best bets to win, Jamie Moyer Aaron
Sele, are poised to face the A's in those games, which will match
the first- and second-place teams in the West. ... After batting
cleanup Thursday and third Friday, center fielder Mike Cameron now
has started in every spot in the batting order except eighth.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
