<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUMMER-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS MAKING AN IMPACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE WERSTINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH _ Shammond Williams made a name for himself in the
NBA last season - with his hair.
</P>
<P>
   Over the first week of the 2000 Summer Pro League, the Seattle
SuperSonics guard is again making a name for himself - but this
time with his prowess on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who averaged just 5.2 points in 43 games for the
Sonics last season, has been arguably the best player at the SPL so
far, scoring nearly 27 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to show the people what I am capable of doing,''
said Williams, whose hairstyles - pin curls, corn rolls and Afro -
gave him some notoriety while playing behind the likes of Gary
Payton and Brent Barry. ``I'm just trying to make a name for
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's doing just that as teams are beginning to key on him,
like Dallas did Friday afternoon in a 105-104 victory over Seattle.
The Mavericks' double-teams held Williams, the North Carolina
record-holder in 3-point shooting, to just 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no surprise that he's scoring,'' Seattle head coach Paul
Westphal said. ``If he even gets a little look, he can put the ball
in the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who played the entire 48 minutes because of assorted
Sonic injuries, scored 19 points in the first half, then was forced
into passing off the rest of the game, recording most of his six
assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They double-teamed him, trying to take him out of the game,''
Westphal said. ``But he was able to get other guys involved.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of on-the-floor leadership the Sonics want to
see from Williams, who is shooting 62 percent from the field and 86
percent from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play with some of the best players in the game and I'm not
the No. 1 option offensively, so I have to show my offense and that
I can run the team,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal, as many others, have been impressed, saying, ``When he
gets his chance (in the NBA), we will do well.''
</P>
<P>
   West end?
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of NBA kinds at the SPL with some kind of link
to Lakers GM - or is that ex-GM? - Jerry West. And most of them
find it hard to believe that West is finally hanging up his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Jerry since he was a player, watched his whole
career,'' said Lakers longtime assistant coach Bill Bertka. ``Over
the last three years, there have been rumors that he might retire,
and here we are again. It's just a rumor right now and we will have
to wait and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a close relationship over the years and it's too bad
... a loss for the game if it happens,'' said Portland Trail
Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy, whom West gave his first pro head
coaching job in 1990. ``That's his choice, and I support whatever
is best for him. I'm sure he will still be with organization in
some way. They will take care of him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been at it for 40 years,'' said Del Harris, who coached
the Lakers from 1994 to 1998. ``Everybody has to have some time off
and certainly he deserves it. Maybe he will take some time off and
decide to come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 0308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3006 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ILLEGAL-AZR &LR;      07-15 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLEGAL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BORDERCrossing death leaves woman in despair &HT;    BORDERCrossing
 &HT;    over from
 &HT;    hope to
 &HT;    desolation
 &HT;    BC-ILLEGAL15-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    BORDER CROSSING TURNS TO DESOLATION(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By TESSIE BORDEN AND LAYRA TRUJILLO(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alone and heavy-hearted, Ana Maria Ordaz Gonzalez on Friday
prepared for the 27-hour bus trip back to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The death in the desert of her boyfriend, Roberto Arturo Olvera
Morales, had ended her hopes of a better life and decent care for
her sick child.
</P>
<P>
   The two had wandered in the killing heat for two days without
water or clear directions. Olvera Morales became the 73rd person
this year known to have died crossing the Arizona-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had so many plans, so many illusions,'' Ordaz Gonzalez said
hours before she was to bid farewell to Olvera Morales at a Douglas
funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to get ahead, he wanted to have his own home and a
job,'' she said. ``More than anything, he was thinking of my son.''
</P>
<P>
   The two set off Monday on the last leg of a border crossing they
hoped would eventually take them to jobs in Baltimore. But after
shuffling disoriented in the desert for two days, Olvera Morales,
38, collapsed near Arizona80 just west of Douglas and later died of
heat exposure at a Bisbee hospital.
</P>
<P>
   They were less than five miles north of the barbed-wire fence
that marks the U.S.-Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never told me that he was feeling badly,'' Ordaz Gonzalez
said. ``He simply fell, and I couldn't get him to respond. He never
woke up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordaz Gonzalez said the two had been planning the trip north
from their hometown of Toluca, near Mexico City, for at least a
month. She said Olvera Morales was hoping to make enough money to
get adequate medical treatment for her 3-year-old son, Jonathan,
who is paralyzed because of a brain hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had plans to try to make things better for my boy,'' she
said. ``He wanted to give him better medicine and a better
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordaz Gonzalez left the boy with relatives. The two took a bus
to Agua Prieta, across the border from Douglas. A man told them how
to get across the border and assured them he would meet them by
Arizona80 near the town.
</P>
<P>
   They started walking but didn't know the way, according to
Mexican Consul Miguel Escobar Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were duped,'' Escobar Valdez said. ``There is so
much naivete. They didn't know the directions. They just started
walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordaz Gonzalez said they took nothing with them, not even water.
They weren't worried because they thought the walk wouldn't be
long.
</P>
<P>
   But after two days of wandering, Olvera Morales fell ill. Then,
he couldn't breathe. Ordaz Gonzalez tried to revive him. She ran to
the road trying to flag people down, but the cars whisked by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running along the highway,'' she said. ``No one wanted
to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a Border Patrol agent stopped and returned to where
Olvera Morales lay unconscious. Rob Daniels, Tucson sector
spokesman, said the agent and his partner used water to cool Olvera
Morales off and succeeded in getting a pulse. But 10 minutes later,
the man stopped breathing again. The agents began CPR, continuing
as an ambulance came and drove Olvera Morales to Copper Queen
Hospital in Bisbee. He was pronounced dead minutes after his
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol officials say 239 people have died this year
trying to cross the U.S.-Mexican border. California's El Centro and
Arizona's Tucson sectors tied for the lead this week, which reached
53 when Olvera Morales died. Daniels said deaths like this are why
the agency has poured planes, helicopters and personnel into the
area in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, we keep hearing about people who are without
food or water at a fairly close proximity to the border,'' Daniels
said. ``That gives an indication that they have probably traveled
from the interior without any provisions. And they're already in
pretty bad shape when they get to the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the deaths keep happening, they're something that
Escobar Valdez never gets used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming more common, more typical,'' he says. ``But we
will never get used to human tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, deaths of border crossers in the Arizona sectors have
risen steeply in the past two years. In 1998, 19 border crossers
died in Arizona. In 1999, the figure was 39. Rescues have become a
daily occurrence. Since October1999, agents have rescued almost
1,000 people, up from 600 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, Olvera Morales worked as a bar manager, one of
several jobs he worked to get ahead, Ordaz Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked at everything,'' she said, sobbing. ``He supported
me so much with my son. He was my support and my all.''
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporters at Tessie.Borden(a) ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-4783, or Laura.Trujillo(a)Arizona
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or (602)444-8891.
</P>
</TEXT>
