<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, July 16:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ While it is impossible to know what
is going on at the negotiating tables at Camp David, the
delegations themselves offer a road map to the process. Israelis,
Palestinians and Americans, their political, military and
diplomatic careers have been interwoven and, in some cases, steered
exclusively toward this goal: the supposed endgame of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace effort and the resolution of 52 years of
conflict. By Deborah Sontag and Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-WEAPONS (Nizhny Tagil, Russia) _ Stung by meager defense
orders from an impoverished army at home, Russia's military
industrial establishment is engaged in a major effort to increase
arms sales to Asia, the Middle East and Africa and is expanding its
share of the lucrative global arms market. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS-ASSESS (Durban, South Africa) _ When the former
South African president Nelson Mandela issued his forceful call for
action to stop the AIDS epidemic that is ravaging his country and
much of the continent, it was a great relief to the 12,500
participants at the 13th international AIDS conference, which ended
here on Friday. They were bitterly disappointed when the current
South African president, Thabo Mbeki, did not acknowledge
forthrightly that HIV causes AIDS, emphasizing instead social
factors like poverty as a major force behind the epidemic. In a
way, however, Mandela's call for immediate action and Mbeki's
emphasis on poverty were making similar points. A news analysis. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-ELECTION (Port-au-Prince, Haiti) _ Haitian officials
continued to insist on the legitimacy of their recent parliamentary
and local elections despite warnings from the international
community that foreign aid would be suspended if the Haitian
government installs a new legislature whose members won their seats
through a vote-counting method that has been deemed unfair and
unacceptable. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-SRILANKA (Toronto) _ Fund-raising for the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the guerrillas embroiled in the bloody
secessionist war in Sri Lanka, is illegal in the United States. But
Canada has no such prohibition, and Canadian intelligence officials
and Sri Lankan diplomats say it has become an increasingly
important source of support for the Tigers, who are seeking to
carve a Tamil homeland out of Sri Lanka, an island nation off the
southern tip of India. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-ABORTION (Yellowknife, Northwest Territories) _ Canada,
traditionally North America's liberal bastion in abortion wars, is
suddenly gripped by a polarizing debate that has gone beyond
ideology to an array of violent attacks and threats. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-BLACK-SOLDIERS (Sommocolonia, Italy) _ The tiny Tuscan
town of Sommocolonia is honoring black American World War II
veterans who heroically defended the town from the Nazis in 1944.
By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-POLLSTER (Hong Kong) _ In a case that has stoked fears
about academic freedom in this former British colony, a prominent
pollster said on Friday he was warned by the head of Hong Kong
University not to publish surveys critical of the Beijing-appointed
chief executive of Hong Kong. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CLINTON (Washington) _ At a time when polls show Vice
President Al Gore trailing his Republican rival, Gov. George W.
Bush, in several battleground states, a rising tide of Democrats
contend President Clinton should play a prominent role stumping for
Gore this fall _ even if it reminds voters that he, and not his
protege, remains the party's pre-eminent performer. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-DLC (Baltimore) _ Gore addresses the Democratic Leadership
Council; speech scheduled for 1:30 p.m. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-DELAYS (Undated) _ Last summer was the worst on record
for airline delays, prompting the airlines and the Federal Aviation
Administration to swing into action to try to ease the burden on
weary passengers. Yet despite those efforts, this summer is turning
out to be even worse. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   LABS-ASIAN-SCIENTISTS (Undated) _ Asian and Asian-American
scientists are staying away from jobs at national weapons
laboratories, particularly Los Alamos, saying that researchers of
Asian descent are systematically harassed and denied advancement
because of their race. The issue has long simmered at the
laboratories, but it came to a boil last year with the arrest of
Dr. Wen Ho Lee, who is accused of mishandling nuclear secrets at
Los Alamos. Though officials vehemently deny it, many
Asian-Americans said Lee, a naturalized citizen born in Taiwan, was
singled out because of his ethnicity. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-TOBACCO (Undated) _ Even if cigarette makers succeed in
getting the $145 billion award handed down Friday in Miami sharply
reduced or even thrown out, as many experts expect, the staggering
size of the damage figure _ nearly 30 times higher than the
previous record _ stunned some industry observers. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-CONVENTION (Philadelphia) _ Before its current downtown
revival and upbeat remake as a major convention site, this city
spent some years indulging the advertising of self-abnegation.
``Philadelphia isn't as bad as Philadelphians say it is,'' went the
slogan, followed by a variety of punch lines about local
attractions. There is soon to be a great test in the form of the
Republican National Convention of whether this city is safely
beyond such gloomy habits of self-promotion. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DOTCOM-RUSH (Nevada City, Calif.) _ In sleepy places like
Sonoma and Nevada City, an old gold rush town in the Sierras, towns
are meeting up uneasily with dotcomers who are moving in. Sonoma
County is struggling with this new trend, and so is Salinas, a farm
town that has seen some explosive growth. Basically, the towns are
being jolted awake and caught off-guard about how to deal with the
dotcomers. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
