<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA PUSHES TO INCREASE SHARE IN WEAPONS TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIZHNY TAGIL, Russia _ Stung by meager defense orders from an
impoverished army at home, Russia's military industrial
establishment is engaged in a major effort to increase arms sales
to Asia, the Middle East and Africa and is expanding its share of
the lucrative global arms market.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and western Europe dominate the international
weapons bazaar. But last week, on a once-secret test range in the
Ural mountains, the men who fashioned the formidable arsenal that
once made NATO anxious and was paraded with pride by the Kremlin
each May Day showed that they could attract plenty of customers _
and had plenty to sell, too.
</P>
<P>
   Defense officials from India and China _ Russia's major
customers for weapons _ Kuwait, North Korea, South Korea and dozens
of other nations watched attentively as a T-90 tank, one of
Russia's newest weapons, sent a laser-guided missile streaking
toward a target more than two miles away. South Korean officials
kept a watchful eye on any weapons that piqued North Korean
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Baton-twirling majorettes paraded along the range's esplanade as
Russian officials toasted their guests from vodka bottles bearing
the imprint of a Russian tank. And Mikhail Kalashnikov, the
80-year-old designer of the AK-47, strolled through the crowd,
posing for pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from General Dynamics, the American defense
contractor, were also there, scrutinizing the Russian tanks.
Russian officials say that General Dynamics is discussing the
purchase of a revolutionary Russian system to protect tanks from
missile and grenade attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exports are the most important thing for us because they bring
in real money,'' said Viktor Yamov, the chief of advertising for
Uralvagonzavod, manufacturer of the T-90 tank. ``We don't see much
real money from the Russian army.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to calculate arms sales: agreements made and
actual deliveries. In terms of deliveries last year, the real money
from the rest of the world totaled $2.8 billion, putting Russia
fourth, behind the United States, France and Britain, in weapons
sales. Russian weapons accounted for 6 percent of all arms
delivered _ compared with 49 percent for the United States _ but
Terence Taylor, assistant director of the Institute of Strategic
Studies in London, says that Russia is now expanding that share
toward 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   During Soviet times, the military sector had first claim on
resources here and defense plants churned out thousands of tanks,
artillery pieces and air defense missiles. Weapons production was
surrounded by intense secrecy, and, although the Soviets dispatched
tons of weaponry to friendly nations, a fair to sell arms to the
world was unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   With the Soviet collapse, Russia's defense complex plunged into
depression. Defense orders dried up. Debts to suppliers and
utilities mounted. Conversion to civilian production remained
largely a pipe dream. Exports became a vital, if tenuous, lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the Russian armed forces are buying very
little,'' Taylor said in a telephone interview. ``Virtually all of
the production is going for export.''
</P>
<P>
   Yamov's factory, a sprawling complex near this test range that
used to employ 45,000 people, is a case in point. It produced all
of the Soviet tanks, from the legendary T-34 of World War II to its
T-72, operating under the cover story that it turned out mere
railroad cars. Now, it lives for exports.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is on the verge of announcing a major arms deal with
India under which it would buy about 300 T-90 tanks. One hundred of
them would be manufactured at the Uralvagonzavod plant, with some
200 assembled in India. Russian press reports estimate the deal is
worth some $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Russian Army has just two T-90 tanks in the
European part of its territory, according to data Moscow supplied
in January under the treaty limiting conventional forces in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   And despite President Vladimir Putin's pledge to boost weapons
procurement, the Russian Army is scheduled to receive only 30 T-90
tanks this year. That is a small fraction of the 350 new tanks Col.
Gen. Anatoly Sitnov, the weapons chief for the Russian armed
forces, says are needed each year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Russian air force is buying just 12 SU-30 fighter
and attack planes, although with exports in mind, about 50 are
being produced. In 1998, the air force did not acquire a single new
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   While exports are vital to Russia's military complex,
competition is stiff. Western nations can offer more generous
financing, have long-standing customers and better maintenance and
spare parts service after sale. And former Soviet states like
Ukraine, which also inherited Soviet defense plants, compete for
orders Russia covets.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Russian military has fielded so few new
weapons does not help either; many customers like only to buy
systems that have been put to the test.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Russians have some advantages. Low labor costs make
their weapons cheaper than those of Western counterparts. They also
have a reputation for producing high-quality armored systems,
anti-tactical missile systems and artillery.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's weapons trade has consequences for its foreign policy,
according to some experts here. The defense establishment is still
dominated by men reared in Cold War enmity; the competition for
sales has reinforced the notion that America is an unfriendly rival
whose success comes at Russia's expense, particularly since NATO
has expanded its membership and hence its arms clientele into the
former Soviet bastion of Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the defense establishment even more anti-American,''
said Dmitri Trenin, the deputy director of the Moscow Carnegie
Center. ``This is not just the abstract notion of competition. It
is a confrontation over money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of Russia's arms exports go to two nations,
China and India. Their primary interest is in acquiring the means
to make weapons, not just to buy the weapons systems themselves, a
development that contributes to the spread of advanced military
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's major deals with China include a licensing agreement
permitting Beijing to help produce SU-27 aircraft and the sale of
two destroyers. In addition to the pending tank contract with
India, another deal under discussion would provide the Indians with
the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Gorshkov and the MIG-29 planes
that would be on it.
</P>
<P>
   Measured in terms of agreements, Russia counted for 40 percent
of weapons sales to Asia between 1995 and 1998, according to
Richard F. Grimmett of the Congressional Research Service in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are highly dependent on arms contracts with those
two countries,'' Grimmett said. ``China and India have tremendous
leverage in terms of getting the advanced equipment they are
seeking.''
</P>
<P>
   With a younger, more dynamic president now in the Kremlin and
sales at stake, the Russians appeared to go all out to make this
week's arms fair in the Urals _ the second annual event here _ a
prestigious occasion. Putin himself showed up.
</P>
<P>
   And there were several new pieces of weaponry. One notable new
item was a tank support vehicle, which has a crew of five. It has
the protection of a tank but is outfitted with a unique set of
weapons, including grenade launchers, a 30-millimeter cannon and
four anti-tank missiles. The Russians appear to have designed the
weapon with an insurgency like the one in Chechnya in mind, but it
was a big hit with the Chinese, who clustered around it.
</P>
<P>
   Another novel system that attracted attention was Nakidka,
basically a tarpaulin that is draped over equipment to foil weapons
guided by radar and heat-seeking devices that create images from
the heat of objects.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign military officials also seemed impressed by the Iskander
surface-to-surface missile, which was shown for the first time, and
the S-300 system, which is designed to shoot down Scud-type
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hits of the arms fair were the T-80 and T-90 jumping
tanks, which zoomed up a ramp and leaped through the air.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of foreigners who identified themselves only as defense
attaches, intelligence experts or trade officials but often
declined to give their names, prowled among the exhibits. Many
carried sophisticated cameras and snapped detailed pictures of
firing mechanisms, artillery tubes and weapons chassis.
</P>
<P>
   While Kuwait may owe its freedom from Iraqi occupation to the
coalition of troops the United States assembled to fight the war in
the Persian Gulf, Kuwaiti military officials eagerly talked with
the Russians about their tanks.
</P>
<P>
   An Iranian delegation wanted to see executives at
Uralvagonzavod. Iran has a fleet of T-72 tanks and is interested in
upgrades, said Yamov, the advertising director.
</P>
<P>
   General Dynamics, for its part, has been exploring the idea of
acquiring Russia's Arena system, which uses a radar to detect
anti-tank missiles or grenades and destroys them by firing
munitions, according to Alexander Kobin, the general director of
Rosvooruzheniye, the Russian arms sales agency. He indicated that
Putin would have to decide whether the system could be provided to
the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the American corporation, based in Falls Church,
Va., declined to discuss their interest in Arena, but they were
certainly taking a close look at the Russian tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one country has the corner on good ideas,'' said Philip W.
Lett, the former program manager for the U.S. Army's M-1 tank
program and a General Dynamics consultant.
</P>
<P>
   And despite their long alliance with Washington, the South
Koreans expressed interest in exploring production with the
Russians. As a South Korean defense attache put it, ``Business is
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
