<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAB-ISRAELI TALKS TURN ON CHEMISTRY OF CENTRAL PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG and JANE PERLEZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Given the total seclusion of the Camp David peace
talks, photographs issued by the White House offer the only glimpse
inside the presidential retreat. They present frozen images of men
in shirtsleeves, pens poised over note pads, their faces absorbed
in thought.
</P>
<P>
   While it is impossible to know what is going on at those
negotiating tables, the delegations themselves offer a road map to
the process. Israelis, Palestinians and Americans, their political,
military and diplomatic careers have been interwoven and, in some
cases, steered exclusively toward this goal: the supposed endgame
of the Israeli-Palestinian peace effort and the resolution of 52
years of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   For the three members of the U.S. peace team, for instance, this
summit meeting marks the culmination of a professional life spent
shuttling between Israelis and Arabs, a career that became a
personal mission.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations that will surely go right to the wire, and then
trip it, everything will eventually come down to the leaders
themselves. But the fabric of relations is knitted by the
negotiators, by, say, the interaction between Shlomo Ben Ami, the
popular Labor Party politician who is a potential future challenger
to Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel, and Abu Ala, the
Palestinian parliament speaker, who is a potential future heir to
Yasser Arafat, president of the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, leader of the Labor Party and a general turned
peacemaker, brought the smallest delegation, a relatively lean,
mean team of mostly military men and center-left politicians like
himself. This fighting trim was not intentional; it reflects the
defection of the rightist parties in his government on the eve of
his departure. But it could serve to streamline his approach, since
he will not have to answer to the deep-seated reluctance of those
ministers who would otherwise have come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak is so intent he is like a horse with blinders, and this
will make it simpler here, although harder when he returns home,''
an adviser to the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Arafat traveled to the United States not only with
his senior negotiators, security professionals and economic
advisers but with some opposition party leaders and with a vocal
critic as the appointed spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Barak, a democratic leader, Arafat, who is often
considered to be an authoritarian, has surrounded himself with a
consensus-building organism. The opposition leaders are not inside
Camp David _ in fact, the Americans would not admit them when they
banged at the gate last week _ but even within the group inside,
there is a spectrum ranging from the more pragmatic to the more
cynical, from money men to ideologues.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. and Israeli officials think Arafat would not have made
the journey in such complete Palestinian company if he were not
intent on reaching some kind of deal.
</P>
<P>
   But an adviser to Arafat cautioned that the Palestinian leader
has always ``tried to bring people inside his tent'' _ and that has
been a strength and a weakness. Sometimes, hard-liners have kept
him ``too pure,'' an Israeli official said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the main opposition leaders, like Sheik Ahmed Yassin of
the radical Islamic group Hamas, did not accept his call for unity
behind the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time,'' a former diplomat said, ``Arafat will only make a
deal when it is to his advantage, and he won't let artificial
deadlines force him into something he doesn't want to do.'' The
artificial deadline that the former diplomat is citing is President
Clinton's scheduled departure for Okinawa on Wednesday for the
meeting of major industrial nations.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Clinton at Camp David, there is a triptych of diplomats
who _ sometimes symbiotically, sometimes competitively _ have
devoted themselves to the Middle East since the 1980s: Dennis Ross,
52, chief Middle East peace envoy; his deputy, Aaron D. Miller, 51;
and Martin Indyk, 49, who is now on his second tour as ambassador
to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For all three men, their formative experience was the 1973
Arab-Israeli war. Miller and Indyk were graduate students in
Israel; Ross had just left. And as young Jewish intellectuals,
colleagues say, they came away believing that Israel needed peace
with its neighbors as badly as it needed to be protected from
another devastating war.
</P>
<P>
   From that conviction, their concept of Israel grew, fortified by
a strong security relationship with the United States, making peace
with its neighbors through incremental steps. These ideas were
developed by Indyk, who became the first director of the Washington
Institute for Near East Policy, an offshoot of the American Israel
Public Affairs Committee, and by Ross, who perched there briefly in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton became president, he gave the three men a chance
to turn position papers into policy. Indyk, an Australian, became a
U.S. citizen to seize the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The three began with the 1993 Oslo interim peace accord. Miller
cultivated relations with Arafat, whom he had first met in Tunis,
and his key aides. Ross and Indyk concentrated on the Israelis. And
when Barak was elected prime minister last year, the three made
little secret of their pleasure at having an Israeli leader whose
peacemaking platform matched theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, who think U.S. policy has long been skewed toward
Israel, frequently note quietly that all three U.S. negotiators are
Jewish. But over the course of their repeated trekking to Gaza and
Ramallah to visit Arafat, the three have come to be seen as fair _
although this judgment could fray in the heat of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for the summit meeting, one of the three said
that it was the most ``extraordinary development'' he had
experienced in 20 years. ``The stakes are incredibly high,'' he
said _ and it was clear he was talking both personally and
diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   Stakes are high, of course, for all present.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There is not a single Palestinian official with the stature of
Arafat. But in the speculation about who will succeed the
70-year-old leader, his long-time deputies, Abu Ala and Abu Mazen,
are the top contenders. They are formally positioned to split his
two roles: Abu Ala to succeed him as president of the Palestinian
National Authority and Abu Mazen as chairman of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
   As such, they have an investment in negotiating a final peace
accord that could stand the test of time. And yet, while they are
both relative moderates within the Palestinian world, the
delegation's official position is that the summit meeting is being
held too soon, without the proper groundwork laid for a full or
even partial resolution of outstanding problems.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Camp David, Abu Ala, 63, a gritty pragmatist and strong
strategist, is certain to be playing the visible lead role.
Although Arafat occasionally considers him a bit too independent,
he has relied on Abu Ala for the hands-on part of all key
negotiations. Abu Mazen, 65, who was the godfather of the
breakthrough Oslo talks in 1993, is more the overseer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
