<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3033 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-2NDTAKE     07-15 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the overseer.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians think of Abu Ala, a forceful white-haired
politician who comes from the town of Abu Dis, adjacent to
Jerusalem, as a businessman for his role overseeing PLO
investments, and consider that the key to his negotiating skill. He
negotiated the 1995 interim peace agreement, Oslo II. But, on the
plane ride to Washington for the signing ceremony, Arafat informed
him that Abu Mazen would sign the agreement and deliver the speech.
Abu Ala was crestfallen, and withdrew to the sidelines of the
negotiation process for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Abu Ala was accorded no official role in the present
final-status peace negotiations. But he played the more important
unofficial part in back-channel talks that eventually moved to
Stockholm this spring and then materialized into the main channel.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Abu Mazen, whose West Bank villa in Ramallah has
been the site for late-night meetings of Israeli and Palestinian
leaders, was in charge of the Israeli file of secret contacts
between the PLO and progressive Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the relationships he nurtured, Israeli doves and
U.S. peace negotiators regarded him as the most flexible
Palestinian official. This made it difficult for him to play a
central role, because it discredited him on the Palestinian street.
But Abu Mazen, anyway, prefers to be behind the scenes, thinking
the big thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Saeb Erekat, a political scientist who is almost 20 years
younger, has been most visible to the Americans, since he makes
media appearances and whispers English translations into Arafat's
ears. He was not an original member of the PLO, never lived in
exile and is thus considered to be in better touch with popular
sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat made his diplomatic entrance by defying his superiors'
orders in the Madrid peace talks in 1991, when the Palestinians
were trying to keep a low profile. He walked into the talks with a
kaffiyeh draped over his shoulder. Arafat scolded him later, but
Erekat disarmed him by saying, ``Mr. Chairman, I felt I was
carrying a piece of you inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is also accompanied by his senior security chief,
Mohammed Dahlan;his information minister, Yasser Abed Rabbo, who
plays the role of house skeptic; and his senior economic adviser,
Mohammed Rachid, who is an Iraqi-born Kurd.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rachid is the most pragmatic and the least ideological of the
delegation, and Arafat is said to feel indebted to him for creating
the monopoly businesses that generated the first income for the
Palestinian Authority _ along with allegations of cronyism and
corruption. Before the summit meeting, Rachid was preparing the
Palestinians' compensation demands _ $40 billion, mostly for
refugees _ and making clear that if he had sufficient influence, he
would steer Arafat toward the practical.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli delegation is not a well-oiled peace team, like the
Americans and the Palestinians, but a disparate, experienced group
of politicians, lawyers and generals. At the last minute, after the
summit meeting had already begun, Barak summoned Dan Meridor, a
right-leaning legislator, to round out the center-left delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Elyakim Rubinstein, a religious Jew and the attorney general,
was reportedly reluctant to come. But he is there as the
government's lawyer, and as the only delegate who participated in
the original Camp David in 1978, bringing with him the accumulated
experience of all the peace agreements from then on. Insiders say
that he also tells the jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The two central negotiators are Ben Ami and Gilad Sher, a
private lawyer who used to be a lawyer for the military. Barak
trusts Sher, who negotiated the most recent interim agreement last
September, precisely because he is apolitical.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Ami, on the other hand, is a Moroccan-born Israeli. He rose
from humble beginnings to become an Oxford-educated historian and
Israeli diplomat who, in the most recent Labor Party primary, shot
up from political obscurity to the top spot behind Barak. Insiders
say that it signals Barak's keen desire for an agreement that he is
willing to use him as a resource, to tolerate his meetings with
Clinton on the back porch of the Aspen Cabin, which surely raise
Ben Ami's political capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, as Barak sees it, the team is not essential,'' said an
Israeli Cabinet minister. ``They fill the chairs, make the
atmosphere. He's so sure of himself. At Camp David, Barak is
everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
