<SLUG> BC-MASRY-TVSHOW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASRY RETURNS TO PRACTICE - ON TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECILIA CHAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Westlake Village attorney Edward Masry sat
patiently as the makeup artist at Empire Studios dabbed on
foundation and powder and trimmed his gray eyebrows and sideburns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want you to be confused,'' said Masry, known to
moviegoers as the real-life boss in the recent film ``Erin
Brockovich.''
</P>
<P>
   ``About?'' the woman asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That I'm Tom Cruise,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Portrayed by actor Albert Finney in this year's Julia Roberts
blockbuster, Masry is now starring in his own courtroom drama.
``Power of Attorney'' - sort of a cross between ``Judge Judy'' and
``L.A. Law'' - debuts Aug. 28, featuring Gloria Allred, Christopher
Darden and other high-profile attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   For Masry, 67, it was the first time in a decade that he was
back in the courtroom. After suffering a heart attack while arguing
a 1990 case in federal court, his wife made him promise to leave
the trial work to others.
</P>
<P>
   But in his new half-hour show, Masry and a corps of 22 other
attorneys will represent clients in misdemeanor and civil cases
heard by former New Jersey Judge Andrew P. Napolitano, who will
issue binding decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am doing this because people don't understand the role we
attorneys play in life,'' said Masry, of Thousand Oaks. ``I think
it's good for them to have a program like this. This is as close to
realism as they can get here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way I miss the courtroom. I am looking forward to it.
It's a challenge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Masry was selected for the show from a pool of 40 attorneys,
most of whom were chosen after a test shot. The partner in Masry &AMP;
Vittitoe, however, didn't have to go through a tryout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed was one of the few people we did not test,'' said John
Rizzotti, a spokesman for Twentieth Century Television, a division
of Fox, which is producing the show. ``We felt confident enough he
could handle himself in front of the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``After `Erin Brockovich,' he was bombarded by the press and he
handled himself well in interviews, travel and speaking
abilities,'' Rizzotti said.
</P>
<P>
   During a taping early Friday, Masry went head-to-head against
Boston attorney Wendy Murphy in a civil dispute between two
sisters. A session scheduled for today pits him against Darden, one
of the prosecutors in the O.J. Simpson criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris has been up against the best, so Chris is a very good
lawyer,'' Masry said. ``But I'm more concerned with Wendy because I
am dealing with an unknown. I've seen Darden in court and can
pretty much predict what he will do. I don't know if Wendy is
laid-back or aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Masry said in his typical pit bull style, ``I'm
looking forward to totally destroying that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   During his first taping, Masry represented Jessica, who was
suing her sister for $5,000 for damage to her truck. Murphy
represented Rachel, the defendant, who admitted she accidentally
crashed the truck, but didn't think she should have to pay because
the vehicle was uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   After some feisty exchanges, tears and objections raised by both
sides, Napolitano awarded $5,000 to Masry's client.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the studio's Green Room, Masry critically assessed his
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really rusty,'' he said. ``It's been 10 years since I've
been in a courtroom. I felt it. It took me awhile to start to get
back into it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murphy gave high praise to Masry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt he did a great job,'' she said. ``Obviously, he is
experienced and he is someone I admire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an icon in the legal community and a hero. I've always
admired him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, of course, I loved `Erin Brockovich.'''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which has grossed more than $120 million, starred
Roberts as Brockovich, a fledging file clerk who with Masry, waged
a legal battle against Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. The duo won a
record $333 million settlement for residents in the High Desert
town of Hinkley, Calif., after determining the utility had
contaminated the water supply.
</P>
<P>
   ```Erin Brockovich' made him,'' Rizzotti said. ``I mean, taking
into consideration that Ed is an exceptional lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In law circles he was fairly well known, but the nation did
not know him until `Erin Brockovich' came out,'' Rizzotti said.
``We are putting him back in front of the camera so his 15 minutes
of fame is not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And although his face has been plastered all over television,
newspapers and magazines such as ``People,'' the notoriety hasn't
gone to his head, said Joey Masry, who accompanied her husband of
10 years to the first taping.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the same,'' she said. ``He's a workaholic. In the car
he's on the phone, in the house he's on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1975, I've gone with him and have seen him in papers and
on TV,'' she said. ``This is a little more publicity, but I am used
to him being a public figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Masry also said fame hasn't changed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still that good-looking, attractive, handsome young man,''
he said with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
