<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3040 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CANCERKIDS-GAMES-LADN     07-15 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCERKIDS-GAMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEUKEMIA VICTIM HELPS SICK KIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN MAESHIRO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Calif. _ Eleven-year-old Brittany McDaniels is a
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   When she was diagnosed with leukemia two years ago, Brittany
vowed to battle the disease and has since expended her formidable
energies on raising thousands of dollars to find a cure and helping
others like her who are afflicted with illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her outlook is, `I want to live, I don't want to die.' That's
what it was from day one: `cancer is not going to beat me,''' said
Brittany's mother, Barbara McDaniels.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany's latest crusade is to raise money to buy Nintendo 64
video games to replace the ones stolen from the pediatric oncology
clinic at the Kaiser Permanente Hospital in Woodland Hills, where
she receives chemotherapy treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The games provide a vital diversion for young cancer patients,
who at times spend up to eight hours a day at the clinic getting
blood drawn, waiting for lab results, and undergoing treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are there for a long time, and you are very bored. It
helps to have something to do,'' said Brittany, whose hair started
growing back four months ago. ``I was really mad (about the theft)
because I couldn't think why somebody would take our things.''
</P>
<P>
   The theft of the five games a couple weeks ago was not the first
time the pediatric oncology clinic has been hit. A donated Nintendo
game system was stolen a while back and was replaced by the
volunteer department, according to staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``That people would steal from children is unthinkable,
especially children who are fighting for their lives,'' said Alicia
DeGroff, a registered nurse at the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   To raise money, Brittany and her friends in her west Palmdale
neighborhood are having a bake sale. They've made cookies,
cupcakes, brownies, breads, cakes and candy. So far they've raised
$100.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and my friends were selling lemonade. I was thinking we
could use money for the video games. Then we were like, `Let's have
a bake sale,''' Brittany said.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany's efforts are typical of her generosity and warm
spirit, said her mother and staff members at the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   She raises money for the Leukemia Society, including $3,000 last
year on a fund-raising walk. She gives talks to local schools as
part of the society's ``Pasta for Pennies'' campaign: the class
that collects the most change wins a free outing to the local Olive
Garden restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   She's raised money for the Ronald McDonald's camp, appeared on
the Donny and Marie Show to publicize her cause, and made a
commercial for the Make-a-Wish Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   On a more personal level, she wrote to and got tickets from
Legoland theme park for a 3-year-old boy who is a fellow patient at
the clinic, and recently donated a chest of her own toys to be
given to children who undergo particularly difficult procedures,
such as having bone marrow samples taken or spinal taps.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very special and warm-hearted child. She's made little
things for the staff,'' DeGroff said.
</P>
<P>
   DeGroff recalled Brittany having a painful experience when she
had to have an IV needle stuck in her hand. ``It was very
traumatic, and yet the next day, she left a bookmark for me that
said, `Love comes from the heart.' The child had a traumatic event
and she brings you something,'' DeGroff said.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Mendoza, a campaign manager for the greater Los Angeles
chapter of the Leukemia Society, describes Brittany as a ``little
angel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a little fighter,'' Mendoza said. ``It's amazing that
even after chemotherapy and debilitating drugs she has to take that
she finds the time and energy to do stuff for other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara McDaniels said Brittany, the third of her four children,
is her hero. Brittany is not bitter despite having to endure
numerous hospitalizations and exhibits incredible spirit and
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so proud of her. It really comes from her heart. She never
asks for anything for herself. She's the biggest trooper and
doesn't really complain,'' the mother said. ``That's what inspires
me.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
