Analysis, a conservative research group. The ranks of the worried
are swelling along with real estate prices in prosperous suburbs
and urban neighborhoods from Florida to Boston to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nydia Velazquez, a liberal New York Democrat who might have
been expected to oppose repeal, instead embraces it. ``Maybe five
and 10 years ago it didn't make sense, but it does make sense
today, given the reality of the real estate market and the
fast-growing values of small business,'' she said. ``This
represents a real financial burden on a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   It is another measure of how popular the issue has become that
the Democrats felt compelled to offer a compromise, which would
have reduced the tax, not abolished it. That was voted down on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, estates are generally exempt from federal
taxation up to $675,000, an amount scheduled to climb to $1 million
by 2006. Family-owned businesses and farms are exempt up to $1.3
million. The tax, which hit 47,596 estates in 1997 (out of the 2.3
million Americans who died), starts at 37 percent and climbs to a
maximum of 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the tax see it as a tool for raising revenues and,
more fundamentally, for narrowing the nation's economic inequities.
To hear them talk, the only people who pay it are billionaires like
Warren Buffett and Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists for repeal, however, condemn what they see as a death
tax that socks mostly farmers and small businesses, hard-working
people who have pulled themselves up, creating wealth and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought government was supposed to protect our property, not
confiscate it, not penalize someone because they've been
successful,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the tax point out that estate tax payments by
farmers represent only 1 percent of the taxes paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side has done a pretty good job of selling it, in
pretending that it's the little guys who pay it,'' said Robert
McIntyre, executive director of Citizens for Tax Justice, a
Washington-based advocacy group that wants to retain the tax.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Davenport, a tax expert at Rutgers University in Newark,
N.J., said that repealing the tax would mean a $7 million tax cut
for the top 0.1 percent of families. ``Why is it that the people
who have enjoyed the greatest run-up in wealth in the last decade
deserve a tax break now of this amount?'' he said. ``There's no
compelling argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of repeal make their own arguments about fairness.
They charge unfair double taxation, noting that much of the wealth
hit by the inheritance tax has already been subject to income tax
and capital gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   More ingeniously, repealers make what might be called a
stupidity argument. They claim the tax is unfair because, as the
economists Henry Aaron and Alicia Munnell once wrote, it is
``imposed on those who neglect to plan ahead or retain unskilled
estate planners.'' Bartlett, the tax expert, said, ``It's a tax on
ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, according to many analysts, it is no coincidence that
the push to abolish the tax has picked up steam at the same time
that millionaires are playing an increasingly dominant role in
financing campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Edward McCaffery, a law professor at the University of Southern
California who favors eliminating the tax, said that the mere
threat of repeal is good for Republicans and Democrats alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps the campaign contributions coming in,'' he said.
``You don't need a lot of people who care about this issue, because
the people who care about it have a lot of money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3043 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GORE-THESIS-REVIEW-2T     07-15 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-THESIS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORD FOR WORD: AL GORE'S SENIOR THESIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(Eds: Words in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets.) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices. Phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44. 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, the lessons learned in youth. About love, faith, family and
yes, the power of television to define the modern presidency. This
last issue weighed especially heavily on at least one young person,
Albert Gore Jr., as revealed in the topic he chose for his senior
thesis for the history department at Harvard in 1969. Its title:
``The Impact of Television on the Conduct of the Presidency,
1947-1969.''
</P>
<P>
   The 84-page paper sheds light on an aspect of political life
that would preoccupy Gore in his career in public office and into
the current presidential campaign. Often perceived by voters as
stiff and overrehearsed, the vice president has sought advice from
image-makers conventional (the media consultant Carter Eskew) and
not so (the feminist author Naomi Wolf) for ways to improve his
image before the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he was a senator's son probably didn't hurt the
research process: Those who granted him interviews included Arthur
Schlesinger Jr., who served as special assistant to President John
F. Kennedy; Bill Moyers, a former press secretary to President
Lyndon B. Johnson; and James Reston, a columnist and senior
executive at The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   _ PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shades of earth-tone suits: Every president since Harry Truman,
Gore writes, has had to adjust his image to the demands of the
television screen, even those with a special distaste for the
process, like Dwight D. Eisenhower: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He was even persuaded against his will to change to a different
style of glasses so that he would come across better, and before
long he was using the TelePrompTer to be what he hated most _
artificially sincere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For Gore, John F. Kennedy was the closest thing to a political
TV star: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the credit for Kennedy's success on television
was due to his personality. Not everything can be explained in
terms of formats and camera work; there is no objective proof but
it is generally agreed that President Kennedy was simply better on
television than most. He was equipped with an understanding of the
medium and its exigencies, and he knew how to use the visual
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If Kennedy had the small-screen wattage of George Clooney, his
successor, Lyndon B. Johnson, was more akin to Drew Carey. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   President Johnson, according to Bill Moyers, often rehearsed TV
appearances and watched them on videotape, and after one such tape
had run for two minutes, ``the president jumped out of his seat,
turned off the monitor and exclaimed, `God damn, even I can't stand
that.''' He often said, ``I was born with these ears, these eyes,
this nose, this drawl; what can I do about it?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Even if he couldn't fix the ears, Gore observes, President
Johnson was determined to influence the filming of them. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tried to control as many of the mechanics of the
broadcasts as he could. He began by advising television cameramen
that his best side is his left and he prefers to be photographed on
that side at angles of no less than 45 degrees. Stewart Alsop ((a
journalist)) commented that ``anybody but Johnson would have known
in advance that the photographers would vie with each other to get
pictures on his right side, preferably in the act of stroking his
long nose or pulling his ear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Johnson's efforts to bend television news to his will clearly
fascinated Gore. The president's failure to grasp the subtleties of
the task is a recurring theme of the paper, as Gore illustrates in
an anecdote about Johnson's building of a television studio in the
basement of the White House. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Once this studio was set up, it presented irresistible
possibilities to Johnson. He began to use it ``at any moment,'' not
only for major speeches but for all manner of minor announcements.
Many of his appearances didn't even carry a bulletin slug on the
wire service reports. This practice had unfortunate consequences:
it overexposed the president, it produced friction with the
networks and it conflicted with the established expectations of the
viewing audience.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gore also analyzes the decision by Richard M. Nixon, who had
taken office just two months before Gore submitted his thesis, to
forgo giving a State of the Union address just after his
inauguration. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon may be quite correct and quite sophisticated. The State of
the Union address is not good television; it draws a large audience
because it pre-empts all three networks, but it is a dull show.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Of the changes wrought by the televised news conference, he
writes: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Before the advent of television, the president was much less
guarded in his statements. He had the prerogative of giving
background and going off the record completely. If he made a
mistake, he could correct it before it got into print; and if a
mistake was printed, it was still attributed to a ``White House
spokesman,'' or some such euphemism. ...
</P>
<P>
   Because there is no longer a margin for error, the president is
forced to view the conference much more seriously, and to prepare
himself more adequately. Luckily, it is easy to anticipate
questions .... But in order to do so, the president must prepare
for 10 times as many questions as are asked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Which leads Gore to this observation: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The result of this for the president is that he is able to get
away with pre-polished answers lacking any depth. It has stripped
the press conference of any value it might have once had for
putting the president on the spot and probing his thoughts. He now
tells the press only what he wants to.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5762 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GORE-THESIS-REVIEW-2T     07-15 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-THESIS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORD FOR WORD: AL GORE'S SENIOR THESIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(Eds: Words in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets.) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices. Phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44. 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, the lessons learned in youth. About love, faith, family and
yes, the power of television to define the modern presidency. This
last issue weighed especially heavily on at least one young person,
Albert Gore Jr., as revealed in the topic he chose for his senior
