<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, July 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The slow-moving low pressure system that has brought flooding
rains to parts of the Middle Atlantic and Northeastern states
during the past two days will continue to meander near the
Northeast coast. The steadiest, heaviest rain is expected to shift
into the central and northern New England where a flow of moist air
from the Atlantic will be strong. Elsewhere in the Northeast,
scattered showers will linger in the unseasonably cool air.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler air will spread south across the northern parts of the
Rockies and Plains in the wake of a cold front. Ahead of the front,
scattered thunderstorms will develop from the central Rockies to
the lower Missouri Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Heat will persist across the Southern tier of states. Sunshine
will be plentiful from the southern Plains to the Gulf Coast states
while scattered afternoon thunderstorms will develop in the deserts
of the Southwest.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HEAT INDEX
</P>
<P>
   The heat index, a warm season analog to wind chill, is an
attempt to quantify the effects on humans of the combination of
warmth and high humidity. In the Northern states, a heat warning is
usually issued when the heat index is forecast to rise above 100 on
consecutive days. When the air has a high moisture content, cooling
by evaporation from the skin is reduced and the stress on the human
body is increased. However, the heat index does not account for
variables such as wind or sunshine, which can contribute to heat
stress. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3056 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-RADIO-REFORM-FCC-REVI     07-15 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-REFORM-FCC-REVIEW-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET A THOUSAND VOICES BLOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices. Phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44. 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the beginning of this year, the Federal Communications
Commission announced that it was setting up hundreds of free,
low-power radio stations for nonprofit groups across the United
States, in an attempt to increase the diversity of voices on the
airwaves. People were invited to submit requests for a license.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radio is our most ubiquitous mass medium,'' said the FCC
chairman, William E. Kennard, who championed the program. ``People
don't feel they have a local voice'' on the airwaves anymore, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The response exceeded almost everyone's expectations. Thousands
of groups wrote to the commission expressing interest, and some 750
applied for the 200 or so licenses in the first 10 eligible states.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC envisions as many as a thousand microstations, each with
a broadcast range of 7 miles, and with a combined audience of
millions for an entirely new group of broadcasters. Analysts called
the program potentially the biggest change in the radio industry
since the growth of FM in the 1960s. Perhaps for that very reason,
it has touched off a huge battle in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress, most of them Republican, say that Kennard
is arrogantly trying to create a personal legacy, and they are
seeking a way to block the plan.
</P>
<P>
   They have been joined by the nation's large broadcasters,
including National Public Radio and the National Religious
Broadcasters Association, who claim the new stations would
interfere with the signals of existing stations. Kennard has called
the opposition's arguments a smoke screen designed to shield the
broadcasters from competition.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the fight is the fact that AM and FM radio lack
the variety they had two decades ago, in part because stations
today are likely to be owned by corporations that are located far
away and are relatively indifferent to local issues.
</P>
<P>
   To Gary Williams, the director of music and technical services
at the Good News Church in Augusta, Ga., which has applied for a
license, radio has become nothing but the same ``handful of people
who have a great voice all over our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The applicants for low-power licenses, who want to restore a
local and regional element to the airwaves, are a diverse lot.
Nearly half are churches, and most of those are the kind of
fundamentalist groups often active in conservative politics.
Schools make up about 10 percent of the list, according to Media
Access Project, a Washington law firm. Other applicants include
immigrants' rights groups and a few jazz societies.
</P>
<P>
   Their collective frustration at not hearing their interests and
values on the air is hardly limited to radio; people often tell
pollsters that they feel prosperous but not particularly connected
to their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a parallel phenomenon to the political one, in which
people don't feel the parties represent them,'' said Michael
Janeway, a Columbia Journalism School professor and the author of
``Republic of Denial'' (Yale University Press, 1999). ``It may take
a populist left turn or a populist right turn, but it's rooted in
the vast distancing that people feel from the mainstream
institutions that used to represent them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Microradio _ a term popularized by operators of unlicensed,
``pirate'' radio stations and picked up by Kennard, whose agency
had spent years prosecuting them _ offers a chance for people to
set up community broadcast institutions, something that has become
increasingly hard to come by in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Telecommunications Act relaxed ownership rules in
1996, more than half of all radio stations in the United States
have changed hands, said Reed E. Hundt, the FCC's former chairman.
The number of station owners has declined by about 1,000 over the
same period. Last year the largest owner of stations, Clear Channel
Communications, agreed to buy its nearest rival, AMFM Inc., which
will create an 800-station giant.
</P>
<P>
   The companies' new size has given them truly mass audiences for
the first time, making them much more attractive to advertisers.
Deregulation, in turn, has loosened the rules about advertising,
and some stations, having added 10 extra minutes per hour, now
spend almost half of their time broadcasting advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, community groups say, they have a much harder time
getting on the air. ``There are a lot of needs that fall through
the cracks of your commercial radio stations,'' said the Rev. James
A. Burkett of the ChristLife Community Church in Athens, Ga.,
another license applicant.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Puesan, the founding director of a jazz and blues
organization in Washington that is another microradio hopeful,
wants to broadcast jazz 24 hours a day and also help aspiring
musicians in the city raise money and gain exposure. No commercial
radio station in Washington does either now, he said. ``It's
important that we as American citizens get a chance to put
information out there,'' Puesan added.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is particularly important, low-power advocates say,
because of radio's historical mission. When the government first
established rules for television and radio broadcasters earlier in
the century, it limited the number of national networks in order to
set aside a large part of the spectrum for local broadcasters. That
decision, said Akhil Reed Amar, a professor at Yale Law School, had
its roots in the founders' desire to stitch a number of smaller
democracies into a large one.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently the FCC even required stations seeking a renewal
of their licenses to explain how they were filling a need in their
community, noted Ben H. Bagdikian, a prominent critic of media
consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is a chance that low-power radio will quickly
become a moot issue. As more people get access to the Internet and
broadband connections allow for rapid transmission of video and
speech, people seeking a platform for their views will not need a
government license.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, posting a message in a chat room remains a
poor substitute for broadcasting onto a device that the average
American owns five of.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a radio in every car in the United States,'' said
Hundt, now a consultant at McKinsey &AMP; Co. ``There isn't the
Internet in every car.''
</P>
<P>
   That suggests that even if the opponents of low-power radio win
the current argument over technical problems, the larger question
of who gets to have a voice in a democracy will not go away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-RADIO-REFORM-FCC-REVI     07-15 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-REFORM-FCC-REVIEW-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET A THOUSAND VOICES BLOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices. Phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44. 
