Communications, agreed to buy its nearest rival, AMFM Inc., which
will create an 800-station giant.
</P>
<P>
   The companies' new size has given them truly mass audiences for
the first time, making them much more attractive to advertisers.
Deregulation, in turn, has loosened the rules about advertising,
and some stations, having added 10 extra minutes per hour, now
spend almost half of their time broadcasting advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, community groups say, they have a much harder time
getting on the air. ``There are a lot of needs that fall through
the cracks of your commercial radio stations,'' said the Rev. James
A. Burkett of the ChristLife Community Church in Athens, Ga.,
another license applicant.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Puesan, the founding director of a jazz and blues
organization in Washington that is another microradio hopeful,
wants to broadcast jazz 24 hours a day and also help aspiring
musicians in the city raise money and gain exposure. No commercial
radio station in Washington does either now, he said. ``It's
important that we as American citizens get a chance to put
information out there,'' Puesan added.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is particularly important, low-power advocates say,
because of radio's historical mission. When the government first
established rules for television and radio broadcasters earlier in
the century, it limited the number of national networks in order to
set aside a large part of the spectrum for local broadcasters. That
decision, said Akhil Reed Amar, a professor at Yale Law School, had
its roots in the founders' desire to stitch a number of smaller
democracies into a large one.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently the FCC even required stations seeking a renewal
of their licenses to explain how they were filling a need in their
community, noted Ben H. Bagdikian, a prominent critic of media
consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is a chance that low-power radio will quickly
become a moot issue. As more people get access to the Internet and
broadband connections allow for rapid transmission of video and
speech, people seeking a platform for their views will not need a
government license.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, posting a message in a chat room remains a
poor substitute for broadcasting onto a device that the average
American owns five of.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a radio in every car in the United States,'' said
Hundt, now a consultant at McKinsey &AMP; Co. ``There isn't the
Internet in every car.''
</P>
<P>
   That suggests that even if the opponents of low-power radio win
the current argument over technical problems, the larger question
of who gets to have a voice in a democracy will not go away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3062 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-OPEC-REVIEW-955&AMP;ADD-N     07-15 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-REVIEW-955&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CARTEL OF CONFLICTING AGENDAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices. Phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44. 
 By NEELA BANNERJEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They mislead each other, although they are supposedly on the
same side. They make decisions that shape the economies of the
world based on disturbingly imperfect information. If they were a
U.S. conglomerate, they would be market pariahs and serious
candidates for Chapter 11.
</P>
<P>
   The subject under discussion is not a failing Eastern European
car manufacturer, but the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, the group that controls the global supply of crude oil,
the commodity that runs the world.
</P>
<P>
   As gasoline prices rose this summer, along with predictions of
how high heating-oil costs would rise this winter, OPEC became a
convenient focus for consumer anger and political point scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas complains that the Clinton
administration has failed to persuade OPEC to ``open the spigots,''
while in Congress lawmakers propose legislation to allow the
Justice Department to investigate the cartel for antitrust
violations. Vice President Al Gore, meanwhile, suggests that Bush
is a tool of the oil industry, which, he says, is gouging
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the angry words, however, the price of oil is
notoriously difficult to micromanage. Controlling oil prices is
``like trying to fly a jumbo jet across the ocean without any
instruments,'' said Leonidas Drollas, chief economist for the
Center for Global Energy Studies, a London research center. ``You
just look out the window and hope for land. You can do it, but it's
rather hazardous.''
</P>
<P>
   OPEC nations have 75 percent of the globe's known oil reserves
and are responsible for 60 percent of the world oil trade.
Nonetheless, OPEC is a fractious and fallible operation, composed
of 12 sovereign states with varied national interests.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has been rife with intrigue and conflict. Nor
does it control the psychology of the world's commodities markets,
a motley community of play-it-safe refineries and airlines and
bet-it-all hedge funds that has a notoriously unpredictable mind of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC has stumbled many times because the markets weren't willing
to follow its lead. This occurred most recently after OPEC's June
decision to raise output. Contrary to the laws of supply and
demand, raising production actually caused crude oil prices to
increase because the market expected more oil than it got.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price judgments are more an art than a science,'' said Gary N.
Ross, chief executive of PIRA Energy Group, a New York consulting
firm. ``It's a leap to go from the data to the price outlook. You
look not just at inventories, but at market psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest hopes that OPEC might help ease high fuel prices were
stirred two weeks ago when Saudi Arabia, the de facto leader of the
cartel, said that it would begin producing an additional 500,000
barrels a day. The rest of OPEC balked, and hurried negotiations
yielded a statement from OPEC and the Saudis that was worded with
the ambiguity of a fortune-cookie message.
</P>
<P>
   As with most OPEC-related decisions in the past, few besides the
Saudis themselves know how they arrived at the
500,000-barrels-a-day calculation. And perhaps no one is certain
how that increase will be reflected in the price of crude oil,
other than the consensus that prices will decline.
</P>
<P>
   When OPEC nations mull over changes in production, they don't
rely on one another for information, because cartel members,
anxious to protect their standing, do not provide reliable
statistics about output and capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want anyone to know that you are at full capacity,
because without excess production you are not a player in OPEC,''
explained Ross. ``You can't threaten anyone. You can't hurt the
price with more production. So what kind of say can you have?''
</P>
<P>
   Even if a member nation is caught cheating, there is no
enforcement mechanism to bring it back into line. For example, in
1997, Venezuela claimed to be producing its allotted 2.3 million
barrels of oil a day, but independent firms had evidence that
Venezuela actually was pumping closer to 3.2 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Saudi oil minister isn't going to publicly call the
Venezuelans a bunch of liars,'' said one European oil economist,
who spoke on the condition of anonymity. Instead, OPEC raised
Venezuela's overall output, a bit of sleight of hand that allowed
the cartel to save face.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the OPEC nations have attempted to act in a more
consultative, cohesive manner, but it remains difficult for the
group to manage the oil market, or even measure it accurately.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much oil is produced in the world? No one knows for
sure,'' said a senior economist with a Western oil company, who
also spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``It's like asking how
many cabbages are sold in New York every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Many oil-producing nations are in the developing world, and they
lack the interest and resources to gauge oil production accurately.
They report data months, if not years, late. Private companies
track exports by following how much crude oil is bought from
producing nations by major oil companies, or by following the
tanker traffic in major ports. All have secret industry sources as
well, but the resulting figures are merely estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The industrialized nations, too, must regularly revise their
data for production, demand and inventories of crude and refined
fuels, a critical indicator of the balance between supply and
demand.
</P>
<P>
   Daily inventory figures may be off by 1.6 million barrels a day,
according to David Knapp, head of the oil division at the
Paris-based International Energy Association. It's a troubling
discrepancy ``when the markets are swinging based on decisions to
increase output by a few hundred thousand,'' Knapp said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, no one ever has perfect information about any market;
guessing is part of the game. But since oil is so important and the
price so volatile, the price of guessing wrong can be enormous. For
example, OPEC increased production in late 1998, just days before
the Asian financial crisis. As Asian demand for oil dried up, the
production increase flooded the world with crude and prices went
into a free fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought Asia would always stay a dynamo,'' said Falah
Aljibury, a California-based oil analyst close to OPEC. ``They
didn't ask the right questions. If they had had more timely
information, it might have made a difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
