<HEADER>
A3068 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-QUANTAM-PHYSICS-REVIE     07-15 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUANTAM-PHYSICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFINING THE CAT'S-EYE VIEW OF THE COSMOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(Eds: Boldface `it' in 9th graf should be set in italics.) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44.) 
 By GEORGE JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Startling as life in the subatomic realm can seem, with
particles existing both here and there or darting to and fro at the
same time, people have been able to take some small comfort in
knowing that the ``real'' world doesn't work that way. Though made
of the very same stuff that marches to the dictates of quantum
theory _ the laws that explain how particles behave _ solid objects
obediently occupy one place at a time and are never seen moving in
two directions at once. It may be hard to tell whether a torpid
cat, barely blinking its eyes, remains among the living. But that
is a far cry from the mythical cat in the physicist Erwin
Schroedinger's oft-recited thought experiment, which is placed in a
state of being dead and alive at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   When quantum rules are applied to the domain of creatures and
things, the result is nonsense. ``When I hear about Schroedinger's
Cat,'' Stephen Hawking once grumpily declared, ``I reach for my
gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the taunting feline (along with the image of Hawking
pulling a revolver from a holster on his wheelchair and blasting
the poor kitty to bits) was evoked once again. Experimenters at the
State University of New York at Stony Brook showed more decisively
than ever that quantum effects can indeed exist in the larger world
_ you just have to know how to look for them.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most pressing questions in science is why the
universe seems to operate according to two sets of laws. If
scientists are so sure of quantum theory, one of their proudest
creations, then why is it so flagrantly spurned here in the
ordinary world? The new experiment may nudge theorists closer to an
answer.
</P>
<P>
   While physicists have yet to produce a quantum cat or even a
quantum microbe, the Stony Brook team showed that a tiny wire loop
a little wider than a human hair _ but monstrous by subatomic
standards _ can indeed hover in the kind of ambiguous state
Schroedinger puzzled over. As reported in the British journal
Nature, the researchers cooled the ring to near absolute zero and
showed that a current consisting of billions of electrons could be
coaxed to spin around it in two directions at once, clockwise and
counterclockwise.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists had already demonstrated that single atoms or
molecules could be placed in the catlike condition known as quantum
superposition. By achieving what is known in the trade as a
macroscopic quantum state, the Stony Brook researchers have raised
the bar much higher. As a headline in Nature put it,
``Schroedinger's cat is now fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Most physicists, in fact, are surer than ever that everything,
no matter how portly, is quantum at heart. Why then don't we see
these weird juxtapositions?
</P>
<P>
   In Schroedinger's fantasy, a cat is placed in a box with a vial
of deadly hydrogen cyanide gas and a lump of some radioactive
substance like uranium. If the uranium decays, it will shoot out a
piece of nuclear shrapnel, triggering a Rube Goldberg device that
smashes the vial and releases the poison. With a 50-50 chance that
this reaction will occur, Schroedinger proposed, the cat could be
thought of as being simultaneously dead and alive.
</P>
<P>
   Schroedinger was perfectly aware that when he opened the box and
peered inside, the cat would have to be one way or the other. Some
physicists have proposed that it is the very act of observation
that conjures up the hard edges of the familiar world. Most
theorists insist that the observation need not be made by a
conscious being _ an insentient measuring device will do. Hook an
electroencephalograph to the cat to monitor its brainwaves and the
continuous act of measurement would keep it from slipping into
quantum limbo. Or would the EEG itself fall into an ambiguous
state, its needle twitching out ``dead'' and ``alive'' at the same
time? Then something would have to observe  &UR; it &LR; . Dr. Hawking, get
your gun.
</P>
<P>
   It has been tempting to think that as things get bigger, quantum
effects somehow disappear on their own. But that begs the question
of where nature draws the line. With more and more evidence that
size doesn't matter, other ideas are gaining ground. Maybe the
quantum fuzz snaps into focus when a collection of particles passes
some threshold of complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Most bets now are being laid on a different possibility: that it
is simply the interaction with an environment that solidifies the
macroscopic world. The particles that make up the cat are
constantly jostling each other and being bombarded with air
molecules and photons of light. These tiny ``measurements'' may be
all that's needed to keep Schroedinger's Cat at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The feline would be in good company, with everything in the
universe _ stars and trees as well as scientists _ engaged in a
buzzing orgy of mutual measurement, keeping the cosmos in line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
