<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS OF THE PAST WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices. Phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44. 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Enormous Award for Smoking Damages
</P>
<P>
   After a two-year trial, a six-member jury in a state circuit
court in Miami ordered the tobacco industry to pay $145 billion in
punitive damages to Florida smokers who have become ill. The award
shattered previous records for the size of a punitive damages
verdict, and a lawyer for the plaintiffs in the class-action suit
called it a ``day of reckoning'' for Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   But spokesmen for the tobacco companies quickly predicted that
the sheer size of the award, which they said they could not pay,
would make it untenable. Philip Morris Inc. was ordered to pay the
largest amount, $73.96 billion; the other defendants were Lorillard
Tobacco Co., Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co.,
Liggett Group Inc. and the industry's defunct Council for Tobacco
Research and Tobacco Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam and U.S. Move Toward Normal Trade
</P>
<P>
   The last time the United States and Vietnam spent five years
arguing over the details of a major accord, they cleared the way
for America to withdraw from Vietnam. This time, Hanoi is hoping
for an invasion _ of American business. The two nations signed a
sweeping agreement that commits Vietnam to observing open trade and
investment rules that most of its Asian neighbors follow. Hanoi
hopes the agreement will lift its stagnant economy and allow the
communist bureaucracy to develop a more investor-friendly image.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOSEPH KAHN
</P>
<P>
   Still Hangin' On
</P>
<P>
   Concert promoters had high hopes for what was billed as the
first reunion of the Motown group the Supremes in three decades.
They paid the former Supreme Diana Ross a guarantee reported to be
between $15 million and $20 million and set a top ticket price
around $250.
</P>
<P>
   But none of Ross' surviving former bandmates deigned to join her
on the tour, claiming that their pay was too minuscule compared
with hers.
</P>
<P>
   Though a date at Madison Square Garden on July 8 sold out, other
arenas have been half or even three-quarters empty. Last week, Ross
issued a press release stating that the tour had been canceled
against her will. But SFX, the tour's promoter, despite calling off
almost every concert at the last minute since then, claims that the
tour is still happening, leaving ticket-holders grumbling, ``You
Keep Me Hangin' On.''
</P>
<P>
   _ NEIL STRAUSS
</P>
<P>
   A New Old Building
</P>
<P>
   Seventy years after it was built in New York as the tallest
building in the world (a title it held only briefly), the 77-story
art deco masterpiece known as the Chrysler Building may get a
chance to reclaim proper title to its name.
</P>
<P>
   The skyscraper was built by Walter P. Chrysler, founder of
Chrysler Corp., who once had offices and a private dining room
there. But after he died in 1940 the company's use of the building
fell off and it was sold. Now, DaimlerChrysler AG, the
predominantly German-managed company into which Chrysler Corp. was
merged in 1988, said it was hoping to rent and renovate space in
the building as a ``virtual headquarters'' where its board would
meet and investor and public relations staffs would work.
</P>
<P>
   A Woman as AME Bishop
</P>
<P>
   Black women are some of the United States' most powerful
preachers. But it took until now for one of them, Vashti Murphy
McKenzie, to be elected a bishop of the African Methodist Episcopal
Church, the nation's oldest black denomination and now the first to
have a woman bishop. As one of 20 AME bishops, she will have a
prestigious post that she will likely hold until mandatory
retirement in 20 years. She will spend her first four years
supervising AME churches in southern Africa. Triumphant after the
election at the church's quadrennial convention in Cincinnati, she
said from the podium, ``The stained glass ceiling has been
pierced.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE GOODSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   Look. Up in the Sky ...
</P>
<P>
   The stalled effort to build the International Space Station
lurched ahead with the launching of the Russian Zvezda service
module. The 20-ton craft, which is to serve as the orbital
outpost's crucial command and living section during early stages of
construction, began a series of maneuvers and tests aimed at having
it dock with the nascent station on July 25.
</P>
<P>
   With Zvezda in place, the United States and 15 partner nations
can end an 18-month building hiatus primarily caused by Russia's
not having the money to finish and fly their segment. Saying they
had traveled a very long road to get Zvezda launched, Yuri Koptev,
head of the Russian Space Agency, thanked project partners for
their patience and support. ``We wish this road had been a highway,
but a highway it was not,'' he said. ``It was oftentimes closed for
repairs. We have experienced detours, bumps and holes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ WARREN E. LEARY
</P>
<P>
   Israel Stops a Sale to China
</P>
<P>
   In a precisely timed decision, the Israeli government announced
the cancellation of a $250 million sale of a sophisticated airborne
radar system, after protests from the Clinton administration and
members of Congress. Prime Minister Ehud Barak told President
Clinton of his decision on the first night of the Camp David
summit. The next morning, congressional critics praised Barak. The
issue had become so heated that military aid to Israel was
threatened in the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _ JANE PERLEZ
</P>
<P>
   A Grim AIDS Conference
</P>
<P>
   Dashing the hopes of thousands of scientists gathered in Durban,
South Africa, for the 13th International Aids Conference, President
Thabo Mbeki singled out extreme poverty, rather than AIDS, as the
biggest killer in Africa. Mbeki has stirred a furor by entertaining
the theory that poverty, not the HIV virus, causes AIDS _ an
argument that most scientists say was debunked years ago.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes the link between poverty and AIDS. But many
scientists fear that Mbeki's comments will fuel confusion among
ordinary people who may assume they can continue risky sexual
behavior because the president has questioned whether HIV causes
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   _ RACHEL L. SWARNS
</P>
<P>
   Go Play With Your Food, Dear
</P>
<P>
   Some child-development theory has long held that children's play
is their work and their food is their play. So when executives at
H.J. Heinz wanted to sell more ketchup, they zeroed in on its
potential entertainment value. They came up with not just a bottle
that is easier to squeeze (and draw pictures with), but also
another color _ leafy green.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America being what it is, the subject of playing with
one's food was presented not very playfully at all. ``Kids had a
particular need at mealtime that wasn't being met,'' said Deb
Magness, a spokeswoman for Heinz. ``It was about having better
control and more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one more sign of how children are driving decisions large
and small, from the purchase of the family car to the packaging of
food. But at Heinz, the ketchup (which is still made from tomatoes)
seemed to have some appeal to grown-ups, too. A board meeting last
week featured a few bottles of green ketchup, all of which seem to
have gone home with the directors. ``I never saw a product
disappear out of a boardroom so fast,'' said Ted Smyth, a
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Not far off: a rainbow of ketchup. ``We felt green had a little
more kitchen logic to it,'' said Casey Keller, Heinz's managing
director for ketchup, ``but the idea is to keep it fresh. Over
time, we'll look at other colors.''
</P>
<P>
   _ CONSTANCE L. HAYS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
