<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3078 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ULSTER-REVIEW     07-15 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ULSTER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER AND ISRAEL LOOK IN A MIRROR AT EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ David Trimble, the leader of Northern Ireland's new
power-sharing government, paid a brief visit here recently, shortly
before Ulster re-erupted into flames last week and Middle East
negotiators hunkered down for endgame peace talks in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As one veteran peacemaker to another, he held a comradely chat
with Yossi Beilin, the Israeli justice minister who helped lay the
groundwork for the Camp David summit, and another with Oded Eran,
who ran Israel's preliminary negotiations with the Palestinians.
Earlier, in Gaza, he met with Yasser Arafat and other senior
Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli reporter buttonholed him and asked him to contrast
the parties in conflict here with the two sides of the Ulster
dispute. Trimble refused. ``There is no room for comparison,'' he
said flatly. ``The Israeli-Palestinian conflict is much more
complex than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The disappointed Israeli pressed on: Isn't the Irish problem far
more entrenched, with enmities dating back 500 or 600 years?
</P>
<P>
   Trimble wasn't buying it. The present Irish troubles began
barely three decades ago, he replied, while ``your conflict is
3,000 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. From Ulster or from here, peace seekers tend to see the
other conflict as one inherited from the past, and their own as one
based in the more manageable present.
</P>
<P>
   Returning home, Trimble was quickly pulled into the peculiar
dynamics of the Ulster ``marching season,'' which celebrates the
defeat of the Catholic King James II by the Protestant King William
III 310 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians and Israelis, meanwhile, were ensconced in the
Catoctin hills, confronting seemingly intractable issues _
refugees, borders, the ownership of Jerusalem _ which are rooted
not in ancient history but in Israel's victory over Arab forces
here just half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh wounds, however, are the most painful, noted Meron
Benvenisti, one of Israel's leading social commentators. ``The
conflict here is much more raw, and even among intellectuals there
is less understanding of the other side's position and history than
you would find in Northern Ireland,'' said Benvenisti, who wrote
his Harvard doctoral thesis on Ulster politics 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Israelis who have compared the conflicts, Benvenisti
agrees with Trimble that the dispute between Israelis and Arabs _
whatever its timeline _ is inherently more difficult. The religious
and ethnic division and distrust is more profound, the economic and
political disparities are far greater, and at the explosive heart
of the conflict are mutually exclusive territorial claims, he
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all those reasons, he and others here say, Israelis and
Palestinians should look at Northern Ireland for instructive
parallels, warning signs and, more recently, practical lessons in
how to resolve conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the lessons are encouraging. The riots that raged
through Northern Ireland last week could be seen as a foreshadowing
of the internal problems many expect Israel and the Palestinians
will confront after a settlement. With the staunchly loyalist Royal
Ulster Constabulary faced off against Orange Order marchers, the
parades that had long been a flashpoint for friction with Catholics
instead exposed deep rifts within the Protestant community.
Similarly, Israeli troops are braced to confront militant Jewish
settlers, while Palestinian police are prepared to battle radical
Islamist opponents of a peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   The bloody terrorist bombings by breakaway Irish Republican
factions after the Good Friday agreement was reached in 1988 offer
another object lesson for the future here, some observers believe.
And the fierce resistance within the Irish Republican Army to
unequivocal disarmament is likely to have its parallels in the
Fatah movement and other armed Palestinian factions after an
accord, Beilin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the two longest-running conflicts since the Second
World War,'' said Beilin, who visited Belfast in January. ``In both
cases we now seem close to a solution, but in Northern Ireland this
week we saw the fragility of the process. Good Friday can be
followed by Bad Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, Beilin convened a workshop here where Israeli and
Palestinian officials traded insights with Irish and British
experts in the Ulster conflict. What struck him most forcefully, he
said, is the need for peace agreements to reflect the power of
``symbols and rituals,'' along with more tangible things like
political institutions and economic benefits. An example: Beilin
believes Israel should let a Palestinian flag fly over the Dome of
the Rock, the crowning monument of Jerusalem's Old City _ an image
shocking to many Israelis, but to Palestinians a powerful statement
of their national identity.
</P>
<P>
   Beilin particularly admires the artful blurring of sovereignty
lines in the Good Friday accord. The Republic of Ireland now has a
formal consultative role in the Northern Irish government, a
concession that for many Protestant loyalists struck at the core of
their British identity. Yet in return the Republic withdrew its
historic claim on the province and formally recognized the United
Kingdom's rule there for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has also repeatedly drawn comparisons. In
speeches in Northern Ireland he pointed to the Oslo accord as a
sign of the possibility of cooperation between once-bitter enemies,
and when visiting Israel and the Palestinian territories, he cited
the Good Friday accord as an example of what he hoped negotiators
could achieve in final-status talks here.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant parallel is the critical mediation of
Clinton himself, said David Scannell, a veteran Irish diplomat, who
worked on the Northern Ireland settlement before being sent to
Israel as Dublin's ambassador four years ago. But when looking at
the political backdrop to both negotiations, Scannell is
discouraged about Clinton's chances for securing a settlement here.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli polls still show a solid 40-percent-plus opposition to a
peace accord, he noted. In the referendum approving the Good Friday
pact, support was overwhelming in the Irish Republic _ it passed 94
percent to 6 percent _ and still resounding in the predominately
Protestant North, where it carried by 71 percent to 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Benvenisti is similarly pessimistic, saying that in the critical
``emotional aspects of the conflict,'' Israelis and Palestinians do
not appear ready for a lasting, binding compromise. Yet he adds
that the increasing normalization of life in Belfast, with its two
long-warring communities, may offer hope for a resolution of the
dispute over ethnically divided Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be said that if you know the solution to the Irish
question, you don't know the question,'' Benvenisti said. ``The
same could still be said here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
