<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-POLLSTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG UNIVERSITY WARNINGS THREATEN ACADEMIC FREEDOM, POLLSTER
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In a case that has stoked fears about academic
freedom in this former British colony, a prominent pollster said on
Friday he was warned by the head of Hong Kong University not to
publish surveys critical of the Beijing-appointed chief executive
of Hong Kong, Tung Chee-hwa.
</P>
<P>
   The pollster, Robert Chung, said the university's
vice-chancellor, Cheng Yiu-chung, told him through a deputy that
the university would ``dry up'' the financial support for his work
if he did not stop conducting polls on the popularity of Tung or
the post-colonial government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was a very clear message,'' said Chung, at an
emotional news conference in which he broke down twice.
</P>
<P>
   Chung's disclosure capped a week of bitter accusations and
denials that began on July 7, when he wrote a column for the South
China Morning Post describing how he was pressured.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than once, I was given a clear message from Tung via a
special channel that my polling activities were not welcomed,'' he
wrote. `` Tung did not like me polling his popularity, or the
government's credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   A government spokesman, Stephen Lam, said Saturday that neither
Tung nor anybody on his staff had instructed the university to stop
polling.
</P>
<P>
   With Chung's decision to name names, a personal dispute has
escalated into a furious debate over whether Hong Kong is stifling
academic freedom. Such questions have been raised about press
freedom and the legal system since Hong Kong reverted to Chinese
rule in 1997. But its eight publicly funded universities have been
generally untouched by political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is potentially more serious than those other disputes,
because Hong Kong's future depends on the free flow of
information,'' said Michael DeGolyer, a professor at Baptist
University who also conducts polls about the government. ``If Hong
Kong gains a reputation for limiting or restricting its news flow,
any hope of making this the financial center of Asia are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung's surveys have revealed a marked deterioration in the
popularity of Tung _ a trend that DeGolyer's polls also show.
Although Hong Kong has rebounded from the Asian financial crisis,
this normally tranquil city has been disrupted by protests over
falling real estate prices and the lack of government reform.
</P>
<P>
   DeGolyer said Chung's polling methods were sound. But he noted
that the professor brought a ``pro-democracy'' perspective to his
work. Chung did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is a keen embarrassment for Hong Kong University,
one of the most highly regarded institutions in Asia. The
university said it would set up a commission to investigate Chung's
allegations. But student groups marched on the hilly campus,
calling for the vice-chancellor to resign.
</P>
<P>
   As chief executive of Hong Kong, Tung is the chancellor of the
university. But it is a ceremonial job, and the vice-chancellor
runs things.
</P>
<P>
   Academic freedom is not the only civil liberty in question here.
In April, a senior mainland Chinese official urged the local news
media not to report about the independence movement in Taiwan.
Another official said Hong Kong companies should not get involved
with pro-independence Taiwanese companies.
</P>
<P>
   For some here, the dispute is fresh evidence that Hong Kong is
adopting a Chinese-style political culture, where threats to civil
liberties are rarely made openly. They say that university
officials, knowing of Tung's unhappiness with the polls, may have
taken matters into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a new culture in Hong Kong of second-guessing the
boss,'' said Martin Lee, a pro-democracy leader. ``That's what Tung
has been doing with the bosses in Beijing. And now we have the
practice here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
