<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: DUSTY BAKER'S SECRET; REDS GIVE UP; POOR YEAR
FOR ASTROS; ISRINGHAUSEN HAVING FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second month of the season had not ended, and the San
Francisco Giants were nine games from first place. Is that any way
to maintain a reputation for always being in the race? No, but look
again. The Giants are very much in the National League West race.
</P>
<P>
   It's the old Dusty Baker hocus-pocus. It is becoming a cliche
that Baker always has his team in contention, that he gets more out
of his players than most managers do out of theirs. But it is all
true. And now Barry Bonds has unveiled Baker's secret: It's the
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always brings food in every day,'' Bonds said. ``I got to
have my greens, macaroni and cheese. He always brings something. He
takes care of everybody. When he knows you're down and out, he does
something to perk you up. When you're struggling, he'll say: `Here,
I brought you lunch. You're looking a little weak. I want you to
get strong. You need to eat better.' He takes care of you.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing fancy about the food Baker provides his players,
Bonds said. ``Latin food, soul food, regular food. Dusty knows
every restaurant in every city, and he can get you whatever you
want in any city. I know that for a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   When Baker was informed that Bonds had blown his secret, he
readily acknowledged his nutrition contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started when I was in Atlanta and Los Angeles,'' Baker
said, referring to his playing days. ``I learned it from Hank.''
That would be Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hank would get on me about eating better, more
nutritionally,'' Baker said. ``I learned from him, especially about
breakfast time before day games. In the seventh inning you wondered
why your legs were wobbly after a triple. You got to stay strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said when he began coaching, ``I'd see guys coming in with
a bag from McDonald's or Arby's or Taco Bell, and they'd wonder why
they were tired late in the game. I believe in the guys eating
right. Especially on the road. It's more important on the road
because guys don't eat right on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he offered the players a variety of food, mentioning
collard greens, black-eyed peas, macaroni and cheese, grits, hash
browns, bacon, eggs, sausages. He estimated that he spends $50 or
$60 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The manager has another reason for bringing food to the
clubhouse for his players. ``I don't like to share my food with
anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bonds' claim that Baker knows every restaurant in every
city, he said: ``That's close. They're not all the prettiest, but
they serve the best food.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the job,'' he said of his one-man food delivery
service. ``You've got to be nutritionally strong. In the end only
the strong survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants survive nicely under Baker. This season is an
example.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-game losing streak in April? A seven-game winning streak
the first eight days of May. An eight-game losing streak in May? An
eight-game winning the first eight days of July. The Giants have a
way of canceling out their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just steady,'' said Bonds, who in the first two games
after the All-Star Game hit his 29th and 30th home runs, giving him
475 for his career. ``We're a 200,000-mile car. We're a team that
just keeps going. We'll always be in the yard. Do we get through
the door? I don't know, but we're going to be in your yard.''
</P>
<P>
   And where there's a yard, there's a house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have guys who like to play every day,'' Bonds said. ``We
don't have the best talent on the field. We don't have the best
team. We don't care that we don't. We care that when you come into
our house or we go into your house, you got a fight; you got a
game. You got to play. Then whatever comes, comes.''
</P>
<P>
   SLUMPING REDS CONCEDE
</P>
<P>
   When the Reds acquired Ken Griffey Jr. last February, they and
their fans figuratively (maybe some literally) danced in the
streets. Next stop, the World Series. Or at least the first round
of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Proving once again that there is no sure thing and that no one
player can single-handedly produce a division championship, the
Reds conceded their playoff chances last week by trading their best
pitcher to the Yankees. They kept their best hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics might place some of the blame on Griffey for the
disappointing season. He had difficulty getting out of the low
.200s the first two months of the season, and began post-All-Star
Game play hitting only .238. But he also was tied for second in
home runs and tied for fourth in runs batted in among National
League batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's complaining, saying I'm having the worst year of
my career,'' Griffey said. ``But if you look at my numbers, the
only thing that's down is my batting average.''
</P>
<P>
   A .299 career hitter, Griffey hit .300 or better in seven of his
11 seasons with the Mariners. Two of his sub-.300 seasons came the
last two years when he hit .284 and .285. Why has he struggled with
his average this season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just trying to do too much,'' he said. And why would that be?
``That's how it works. You want to get off to a good start in a new
atmosphere. You want to go out there and do some things. Sometimes
it works, sometimes it doesn't and you find yourself in a situation
you don't want to be in. You go out and work hard and do things to
try to get yourself better. That's all I can do. That's what I've
been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But even a .300 Griffey average would most likely not have been
able to overcome the Reds' pitching deficiencies. Except for Denny
Neagle, now at a new address in New York, the Reds' starters have
struggled. The earned run averages tell the tale: Pete Harnisch
7.52, Ron Villone 5.98, Steve Parris 5.26. The staff ERA, 4.81,
placed the Reds halfway between the NL's lowest (Arizona's 4.21)
and highest (Houston's 5.41).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   REVERSAL FOR ASTROS
</P>
<P>
   They trade their 22-game winner, and the pitching staff falls
apart: Cause and effect?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hambone definitely had a great year,'' Shane Reynolds of
Houston said, speaking of Mike Hampton, now with the Mets. ``He was
our leader last year. Losing him definitely made a difference. But
to say that was the problem this year, I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds cited Enron Field, the Astros' new home, as the primary
culprit. ``We went to a new stadium that was hitter friendly,'' he
said. ``It took a little time to get adjusted to it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the All-Star Game break the Astros had a 30-57 record. They
played the same number of games before the All-Star Game last year
and had a 50-37 record. This season and last, Jose Lima pitched the
last game before the break. Last year he emerged from the game with
his 13th victory against four defeats en route to a 21-victory
season; this time he gained only his second victory against 13
defeats.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers attached to Lima's name this season are eye-opening.
Besides having the most losses in the league, he has allowed the
most runs, earned runs and home runs. His 7.36 ERA is more than
twice his season's 3.58 last year. The 29 home runs he gave up in
18 starts and 106 1/3 innings before the break were one shy of his
1999 total of 30 in 35 starts and 246 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no physical problems, no mental problems,'' Reynolds
said. ``He still has the confidence. He got on a bad streak and
couldn't get off. He pitched seven good innings for us Sunday and
got a win. He said the second half is going to be different. He's
going to start over. He hasn't changed at all. I think that's
great, especially for a guy who goes from 21 wins to having a year
like this. He's still Jose Lima.''
</P>
<P>
   AN `AMAZING' EX-MET
</P>
<P>
   No player at the All-Star Game last week was more excited about
being there or more unlikely to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how it's possible that I'm here, especially all
the stuff I've been through,'' Jason Isringhausen said. ``I'm
pretty excited about this. It's an amazing feeling. I didn't know
if this day would ever come.''
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen once upon a time was part of the foundation of the
Mets' future. He was a starting pitcher then. Now, one shoulder
operation and two elbow operations later, he is a relief pitcher
and the Oakland Athletics closer. Nineteen saves earned him a spot
on the American League All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' Isringhausen said of his new job. ``I blew three
saves in a row, but it was still fun. That's part of the game. The
failure and the success all come together. I'm really enjoying this
role. I like it better than starting. I enjoy going out there for
one inning. I'm either going to succeed or fail. There are no
no-decisions out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It would seem to have been a master stroke by the Athletics to
have traded for Isringhausen last season with the idea of making
him their closer, but the Mets also had thought about the
possibility, even though they had John Franco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had talked about it in the minor leagues,'' the 27-year-old
right-hander said. ``They thought I had the right makeup for it.
But with the guys in the big leagues at the time, there was no
sense in even fathoming it then because the guy with 400 saves is
ahead of you and it's hard to sneak in when you've never even
proven yourself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
