<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEMOCRATS EYE PENNSYLVANIA   SEAT; ILLINOIS PAPER CLIP
TRAIL; UTAH'S CONCERNED REPUBLICANS; A FLOOD OF BALLOT INITIATIVES
IN OREGON 
BY B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill., Utah, Ore.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrats looking to regain control of the U.S. Senate this fall
had high hopes in the spring that they could deny a second term to
Rick Santorum, a Republican freshman from Pennsylvania. He squeaked
into office in 1994 with 49 percent of the vote, and the
conventional wisdom was that he was too conservative for a state
with more Democrats than Republicans and had done little since his
election to improve his standing with voters.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton flew into Philadelphia on Monday to campaign
for the Democratic challenger, Rep. Ron Klink, a moderate from
suburban Pittsburgh. He raised some money for him, roughly
$200,000, and gave Democratic hopes an extra boost when he labeled
the Santorum seat ``worth fighting for.''
</P>
<P>
   But those hopes slumped on Wednesday with the release of a poll
that showed Santorum with a 2-to-1 lead over Klink. And they sagged
even lower on Thursday with the release of a campaign finance
report that showed Santorum with nearly an 8-to-1 lead in campaign
funds, $4.3 million to $564,500.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the best face possible on the new reports, Democratic
leaders noted that the finance report did not include the
just-raised $200,000, and they pointed out that the poll found
almost a third of all voters still undecided _ many because they
knew little or nothing about Klink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are right on track,'' Mary Keirnan, Klink's campaign
manager, declared.
</P>
<P>
   John Brabender, one of Santorum's political advisers, countered
that the poll and finance report showed that Klink ``has minimal
support from within his own party.''
</P>
<P>
   TALE OF A PAPER CLIP HAUNTS A CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1980, when he was one of the newer members of the
Illinois House, state Rep. Timothy V. Johnson, a Republican from
the Champaign-Urbana area, rigged a paper clip so that it held the
``Yes'' voting button on his desk in the down position. When a
picture of the clip hit the newspapers, he first denied installing
it but later backtracked, saying such rigs were ``accepted
practice'' in the legislature and enabled members to vote on
legislation even when absent from the House chamber, especially at
times when votes were called while members were meeting with
constituents or working on other pressing matters.
</P>
<P>
   That explanation apparently satisfied voters in Johnson's
district. He still represents it 20 years later.
</P>
<P>
   But now he has his eye on a larger district, the 15th
Congressional, which has an open seat this year, and the photo of
the paper clip has come back to haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic rival, Mike Kelleher, has dredged up the shot and
contends it says much about Johnson's worthiness to serve. He has
posted newspaper articles about it on the Web _ timspaperclip.com _
and is running ads about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a pattern of behavior by Tim Johnson to avoid his
responsibilities and violate the trust his constituents placed in
him,'' Kelleher said last week. ``Voting is the reason you are
elected, and he delegated that responsibility to a piece of office
supply. This goes to character.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says he is guilty of no wrongdoing and calls the
resurrected picture and stories ``a silly little red herring''
raised by ``a desperate candidate who is far behind.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP IS CONCERNED AT A CHANGE OF HEART
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Merrill Cook, a two-term Salt Lake City Republican, is
about as outspoken and unpredictable and controversial as any
legislator in Washington _ so outspoken and unpredictable and
controversial that even in a year when his party desperately needs
to re-elect every House incumbent, he was denied re-nomination in
last month's primary. His angry response to rejection: He just
might run in the fall as a write-in independent.
</P>
<P>
   That threat left Republican leaders deeply concerned. They
reasoned that while Cook had paid a high political price for loudly
and publicly feuding with them, members of his office staff and
even his campaign manager, he still had a following and just might
win running as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Equally bad, they figured, if he did not win in his own right,
he might draw away enough votes to assure the defeat of the new
Republican nominee, Derek W. Smith, a little-known businessman up
against a formidable Democratic nominee, Jim Matheson, son of
former Gov. Scott M. Matheson.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Cook announced last week that he wanted to remain a member of
the Utah Republican Party. In fact, he said, he wanted to be
chairman of the Utah Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could help expand its base, bring peace to the party,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of the Utah House, Marty Stephens, one of the
state's leading Republicans, was left all but speechless by Cook's
change of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' he told The Deseret News of Salt
Lake.
</P>
<P>
   But after a moment of reflection on a fellow politician he knows
well, he offered this: ``I would counsel Merrill to take his time.
He's had a bitter, bitter defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook's response: He remains prepared to jump in the House
contest as an independent should Smith falter.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOT INITIATIVES HIT NEW HIGH IN OREGON
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half of the states authorize citizen ballot initiatives,
and more and more are showing up every election day as frustrated
voters and advocacy groups become more and more adept at gathering
the petition signatures required for ballot access.
</P>
<P>
   Debate is building around the country about whether initiatives
are being overused, or whether they are a reasonable substitute for
too little or too much legislative action. But in the absence of
any consensus on that, the petition process continues to pick up
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is there more petitioning under way than in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, election officials say, Oregonians will be asked to
vote on at least 25 ballot measures. The issues include huge tax
cuts, forbidding teachers to speak favorably of homosexuality,
repealing the death penalty, banning animal trapping, requiring
background checks to buy firearms at gun shows and limiting the
amount of money spent on political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the initiatives are the work of perhaps the most
accomplished ballot petitioner in the country, Bill Sizemore,
director of Oregon Taxpayers United, a conservative group that sees
government, especially the Oregon Legislature, as a money
squanderer unresponsive to normal citizen complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Does Sizemore worry that he and his group are perhaps overdoing
the petition process by submitting half a dozen initiatives for a
single election?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's counting?'' he replied the other day as he turned in
another batch of signatures.
</P>
<P>
   One person who was counting was Oregon's top elections official,
Secretary of State Bill Bradbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll have the largest voters' pamphlet in history,''
Bradbury said. ``It'll be huge, like a phone book. I'm afraid that
voters will look at it as overwhelming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
