<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL A BIG CONCERN FOR MOSS
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the time of year in the NFL when many players pack their
bags, kiss their wives and kids goodbye, give up their luxury homes
and move into a dormitory for a month. Oh, do players hate training
camp! The constant pounding, the bad food and the twice-a-day
practices in 100 percent humidity with coaches screaming at them.
Lovely.
</P>
<P>
   That may be why Minnesota Vikings wide receiver Randy Moss is
seemingly trying to delay the inevitable. With the Vikings' camp to
start next Sunday, Moss on Friday played the last of a handful of
basketball games in the Southern California Summer Pro League.
While most players try to get their last full nights of sleep, Moss
was working on his jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who played high school basketball in West Virginia, has
never hidden his desire to play the sport professionally one day.
Surprisingly, the Vikings took a laid-back approach to their star's
participating in the summer hoops league. That attitude is
different from the one most organizations would take. Many coaches
would stay awake at night sweating out nightmares that Moss, the
best wideout in the game, was twisting an ankle or blowing out a
knee on the court.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a great personal risk for Moss. He is looking for
a contract extension worth more than the $56 million Keyshawn
Johnson received from the Tampa Bay Buccaneers in April. Nothing
like a torn knee ligament after a dunk to ruin contract
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   As training camps begin in earnest this week, Moss and the
Vikings are among a number of interesting stories coming into the
summer practices. Minnesota has handed the reigns of its offense to
the second-year quarterback Daunte Culpepper. A risk, to be sure,
but Coach Dennis Green has taken risks before, and most have paid
off. After all, he drafted Moss, who was considered a risk because
of his off-the-field problems in high school and college. But Moss
has been a solid citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 things to watch as camps open (sweat not included):
</P>
<P>
   1. THE BALTIMORE RAVENS
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Art Modell, is excited about his team, saying, ``This
is the most optimistic I have felt going into a training camp in
years.'' He should be thrilled. The team already has one of the top
defenses in the league, so the Ravens spent the off-season
upgrading the offense by adding the free agent tight end Shannon
Sharpe and by drafting Tennessee running back Jamal Lewis and
Florida wideout Travis Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore might be the surprise of the league this season, but
only if quarterback Tony Banks becomes a consistent leader.
</P>
<P>
   2. CHEMISTRY IN BUFFALO
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Rob Johnson took Doug Flutie's job at the end of
last season, and make no mistake, Flutie wants it back, and he is
not one to stay quiet if Johnson struggles. That situation could be
a running soap opera for much of the season.
</P>
<P>
   3. GIANTS MOVES
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, General Manager Ernie Accorsi had a tremendous
off-season. He has gotten the team's salary cap complications under
control, while completely revamping the offensive line and drafting
Ron Dayne. He also added Michael Barrow to pair with his pal Jessie
Armstead at linebacker. The Giants have more of an edge now, and if
they win, which will depend largely on the play of quarterback
Kerry Collins, Accorsi should be strongly considered for executive
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE DEFENDING CHAMPIONS
</P>
<P>
   With so much attention focused on the spending by the Washington
Redskins, it is easy to forget that St. Louis is still the Super
Bowl champ. The Rams' only significant change was drafting the
burner Trung Candidate, a wide receiver out of Arizona, giving them
even more speed. The challenge for the Rams is that the team will
surprise no one, and toward the end of last season, defenses had
begun to decipher quarterback Kurt Warner.
</P>
<P>
   5. TOM COUGHLIN'S LAST STAND?
</P>
<P>
   The Jacksonville Jaguars have been one of the more successful
franchises of the last few years, but Tennessee has outclassed them
in the playoffs. Time is short for the head coach, Tom Coughlin,
and the quarterback, Mark Brunell, who has not played a full season
since 1996 because of injury. If the Jaguars do not advance deep
into the playoffs, look for those rumors about Coughlin going to
Notre Dame to start yet again.
</P>
<P>
   6. BRAIN DRAIN
</P>
<P>
   The league lost quarterbacks Dan Marino and Steve Young to
retirement, and John Elway left the year before, but there is still
plenty of talent at the position. Troy Aikman, Drew Bledsoe and
Brett Favre will look to rebound from average seasons. Then there
is Peyton Manning, considered the best quarterback in the game.
</P>
<P>
   7. STAR RUNNERS
</P>
<P>
   The keys to two franchises are coming off devastating knee
injuries. The knee of Denver's Terrell Davis seems to be doing
fine, while Atlanta's Jamal Anderson is having some problems after
his reconstructive surgery. Both players must be completely healthy
if their teams are to make it back to the postseason. Meanwhile,
Atlanta coach Dan Reeves said he planned to run a more physical
training camp than last season. Reeves did the same thing on
occasion when he was in New York, to mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE WORST FRANCHISE
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland was the only team in the league not to score a
touchdown on an interception, kick, punt or fumble return last
season. But the Browns had an excuse. They are an expansion team.
Cincinnati, perhaps the worst franchise in sports, has no such
excuse. Wide receiver Carl Pickens wants out of town, and running
back Corey Dillon hates the team so much he has vowed to play only
six games next year, the minimum required to earn his fourth year
of eligibility and thus become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   9. MERRY-GO-ROUND
</P>
<P>
   Seven teams changed coaches, but the coach with the toughest job
may be the Jets' Al Groh, who is following Bill Parcells. Coach Jim
Haslett in New Orleans also has a difficult task. He must get
inside the head of Ricky Williams, the space cadet running back who
has managed to alienate most of his teammates. If Williams starts
to run and stops complaining, the Saints could do some damage in
the average NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE BUCCANEER
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the single best free-agent acquisition was Tampa Bay's
signing of wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson. When their training camp
begins next Sunday, the team will see that Johnson is brilliant,
selfish and tough. Most of all, he's a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Agreement by Redskins
</P>
<P>
   Washington is closing in on signing its top two picks,
linebacker LaVar Arrington and offensive tackle Chris Samuels. The
team has basically agreed on the signing bonus language, which
would pay Arrington about $10.5 million and Samuels about $500,000
less.
</P>
<P>
   There is still work to be done, but agreeing on the bonus is
half the battle. Getting their two draft picks in camp would be a
major coup for the Redskins, a team many believe will make a run at
the Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
