<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE OLYMPICS: SHATTERING BARRIERS FOR WOMEN IN TRACK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Netherlands)  By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A half-century before Marion Jones, the greatest female
track-and-field athlete was Fanny Blankers-Koen of the Netherlands,
whose four gold medals at the 1948 London Olympics set a record
that Jones will try to break with five at the 2000 Summer Games in
Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Just as significant as Blankers-Koen's medals were the cultural
barriers she hurdled, the barriers that said women should not
compete in anything as vigorous and sweaty as track and field, that
they were unwomanly if they did, that they would not be able to
have children or would not succeed in sports as mothers, that their
careers would be or should be washed up long before the age of 30.
</P>
<P>
   She would not consider herself a feminist _ she admitted to
crying and wanting to leave the London Games because she missed her
two young children so fiercely _ but Blankers-Koen stood as an
important bulwark against the capsizing discrimination female
athletes experienced then, and to a lesser agree, today.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she was named by track and field's world governing
body as the sport's top female athlete of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 30 in London, and people said I was too old, that it was
not good to be running if you had a baby, that you should do the
housekeeping rather than running in shorts in a stadium,''
Blankers-Koen, now 82, said last week from her home in Hoofddorp,
the Netherlands, outside of Amsterdam. ``They were not used to it,
but I was not listening to them. I did what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Her Olympic career actually began as an 18-year-old at the 1936
Berlin Games, when the unmarried Fanny Koen finished tied for sixth
place in the high jump and participated on a Dutch relay team that
took fifth. She did meet Jesse Owens in Berlin, marveled at his
four gold medals, got his autograph and even had a drink with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it must be nice to have just one medal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   World War II intervened, however, and the Summer Games were
shelved for 12 years. She remained in the Netherlands during the
war, Blankers-Koen said, obtaining food from an uncle who had a
farm, thankful just for surviving, never thinking about training
for the Olympics. Finally, the Summer Games were renewed in London
in 1948. By then, she had married her coach, Jan Blankers, and was
the mother of a 7-year-old boy, Jan, and a 2-year-old daughter,
Fanny.
</P>
<P>
   Societal bias against female athletes was withering. Babe
Didrikson and other track athletes had been allowed to enter only
three events at the 1932 Los Angeles Games. Officials were so
alarmed by the exhausted conclusion of the 800-meter race at the
1928 Amsterdam Olympics that women would not be permitted to run
longer than 200 meters again until the 1960 Rome Olympics. Not
until 1984 would a women's marathon be added to the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes who were mothers faced the accusation that they were
unfit parents whose place was in the home, not the homestretch.
Blankers-Koen ignored the complaints. She began competing again
when her daughter was 6 months old, taking her to meets around
Europe, carrying her in a little basket, breast-feeding in the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my doctor about taking up sport and he said, `You are
breast-feeding, but try it,''' Blankers-Koen recalled. ``I had more
and more food for the girl than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine track and field events held for women at the London
Games, she won four _ the 100 meters, 200 meters, 80-meter hurdles
and the 400-meter relay. Her time in the hurdles, which have since
been extended to 100 meters, was an Olympic-record 11.9 seconds.
Before the 200 meters, she said she began crying, telling her
coach/husband that she wanted to return home to see their children,
who were staying with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not necessary for me that you are running,'' she said he
told her. ``But if you don't run, I'm sure you will be sorry for it
later on.''
</P>
<P>
   She remained in London, set an Olympic record of 24.3 seconds in
the 200-meter semifinal, won the final in 24.4, then anchored the
Dutch relay to her fourth gold medal, taking the baton in fourth
place and crossing the finish line first. She would undoubtedly
have won a fifth gold medal, considering that the winning distance
in the long jump was 22 inches shorter than her world record of
20-feet 6\ inches, but Blankers-Koen skipped the event because it
conflicted with the 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband said it was better to win one gold medal than two
silvers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Blankers-Koen's long-jumping ability was so extraordinary that
Jones' first attempt this season _ 52 years later _ was only
three-quarters of an inch farther at 20-7. The two have met once,
and will undoubtedly meet again when Blankers-Koen travels to
Sydney to watch Jones try to eclipse her record for gold medals.
``I told her she should win more medals than I did,'' Blankers-Koen
said. ``She can do so many things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
