<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CLERGY0716-COX     07-15 2195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLERGY0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As church memberships grow, numbers of clergy decline
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAYLOR, Texas _ Nobody sneaks in late for Sunday service at St.
James Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   The pews creak loudly when congregation members take their
seats, a sign that the centuries-old country church with its
missing shingles and interior tiles needs a facelift.
</P>
<P>
   Repairs will come slowly as St. James' physical problems mask a
deeper wound that is cutting a wide swath through rural Central
Texas and the nation: A shortage of clergy in mainline
denominations, the lack of financial resources and the fact that
most seminary-trained ministers do not want to serve rural areas
have left many small-town congregations without full-time pastors
and declining membership.
</P>
<P>
   Presbyterians, Lutherans, Methodists and Episcopalians are
looking for solutions to the growing problem that is overshadowed
by the publicity surrounding the priest shortage in the Roman
Catholic Church. Without their female clergy and ecumenical deals
to share pastors, the pulpits in these denominations could be even
harder to fill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a huge shortage in the Presbyterian Church,'' noted
the Rev. E. Quinn Fox, vocation and admissions director at Austin
Presbyterian Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like being in a hot real estate market,'' he
added. ``People are not having difficulty finding positions who are
graduating from seminary, and that's a bit of an understatement.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition for clergy has left small churches in a bind.
Less than a fourth of the Presbyterian Church (USA) churches with
under 50 members have full-time pastors, according to statistics
provided by the denomination, which is affiliated with the Austin
seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Auxiliary Bishop Gregory Aymond of New Orleans, who has been
named the next bishop for the Roman Catholic Diocese of Austin,
said the decline in rural membership came as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We build churches and we use the demographics of the time and
the rest of it is a guess,'' he said. ``You can have a thriving
parish in the 1950s and all of a sudden in the 1990s, no one is
living out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It is part of vicious circle with no easy solutions. Rural
congregations that lose full-time pastors usually experience a
membership decline. The fewer the congregation members, the less
likely it is the church will ever see a full-time pastor again.
Meanwhile, the number of rural congregations with fewer than 50
members is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Aymond, who until recently headed a New Orleans seminary, was in
Canada in June to attend a meeting of the Association of
Theological Schools, which includes Protestant, Catholic and Jewish
institutions. One of the things they all talked about during
informal discussions was their dwindling clergy, Aymond added.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all denominations there is a smaller number of people who
are willing to give a number of years to study and then to serve in
general and particularly in rural areas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The median salary range for Protestant pastors is around
$36,000, but rural ministers usually make less. If the church
provides a housing allowance, reimbursement for the pastor's
expenses, medical insurance and a retirement package it is not
unusual for a church to need more than $40,000 to $50,000 for a
full-time pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Claude Payne of the Episcopal Diocese of Texas, which
includes the Hill Country, said no diocese is immune from the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in the survival-nature culture for years and
years,'' he added. ``The same reason that a young person moves away
from a rural area for greater opportunities, so would clergy not
want to serve a rural area.''
</P>
<P>
   RURAL CHURCHES STRUGGLING
</P>
<P>
   A century ago in Texas, 90 percent of the population lived in
rural areas. Today, that number is less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some young families living on the outskirts of urban areas, such
as Austin, drive to city churches that offer large, vibrant
congregations. As a result, mainline denominations struggle to keep
rural churches operating.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, members of the Dessau Cemetery Association, whose
ancestors are buried next to what was Dessau Lutheran Church, are
opposing a proposed sale of the church, which was built by German
settlers in 1876.
</P>
<P>
   Dessau Lutheran Church members voted to disband in 1994 because
they could not afford a full-time pastor and regular church
attendance had plummeted from a high of 130 five years earlier to
around 15. Today, the church is rented to a Baptist congregation
and the Southwestern Texas Synod of the Evangelical Lutheran Church
in America wants to sell the building and more than eight acres
surrounding the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``My great-great grandparents are the ones that sold the
property for $1 an acre to begin with,'' said Charles Mueller, the
cemetery association president. It was the home church for both
sets of his grandparents and his mother and father, all of whom
were buried in the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional pain felt by those whose heritage is tied to a
dying church is devastating, and can tamper with their faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``A church building is sacred space and has special
significance,'' Aymond said. ``It's small communities that have
developed not only in familiarity and family but in terms of their
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainline denominations are doing everything they can to hold
onto their small churches, even if it means sharing social
ministries, clergy and the buildings themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At the triennial Convention Episcopal Church this month in
Denver, delegates passed a unity agreement that was approved last
year by the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America. It means, for
instance, that a Lutheran pastor in a rural area also could serve
as the pastor for the local Episcopal Church, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Hammering out the details, though, will take time _ a commodity
many small-town churches don't have.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Chrisman, 54, who runs a public relations firm in Austin,
is the lay vicar for St. James and plans to bypass seminary to
become a priest. He will be the first person in the diocese
ordained under a little-used church law, Canon 7, that will put him
on equal footing with seminary-trained priests.
</P>
<P>
   Chrisman will attend a new two-year academy developed by Payne
that will offer occasional weekend study for Canon 7 candidates who
will be able to pastor at more than one rural parish.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Payne began making priests out of lay vicars
under another church law that restricts those ordained from working
for any parish other than the one they are assigned.
</P>
<P>
   Prebyterians and United Methodist have similar rules that permit
them to install pastors who can serve only a particular rural
church.
</P>
<P>
   Mainline denominations also rely on seminary students to fill
the pastor role in rural churches. ``We have several in small
congregations serving within 45 miles of Austin in all
directions,'' said Douglas Cannon, spokesman for the Southwestern
Texas Conference of the United Methodist Church. Many of the
conference's seminarians attend Austin Presbyterian Theological
Seminary. About 25 percent of the Presbyterian seminary's students
are Methodists.
</P>
<P>
   In one very basic example of a denominational agreement, the
Southern Baptist Church and the United Methodist Church in
Driftwood, in northern Hays County, worship together as one
congregation. Eighty-three years ago, the Baptist church was blown
away in a storm and the United Methodists invited them in. The
Baptists never left.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joe Trull of Wimberley, a retired Southern Baptist
ethics professor and the editor of Christian Ethics Today magazine,
and the Rev. Floyd Vick of Austin, a retired United Methodist
minister, perform the service on alternate Sundays for the
congregation that numbers less than 50 people.
</P>
<P>
   The pastors' combined annual salary is $13,200.
</P>
<P>
   SEMINARY COSTS PROHIBITIVE
</P>
<P>
   The cost of becoming a minister also makes it harder for
small-town churches to find and keep pastors.
</P>
<P>
   While Austin's Presbyterian and Episcopalian seminaries try to
help students graduate without racking up big debts, that education
on top of what a student may owe for undergraduate school is
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, a seminary education is four years of college and
four years of seminary,'' said Vick. ``There are ministers going
out into ministry $70,000 to $80,000 in debt.''
</P>
<P>
   The dropout rate for newly ordained Protestant clergy is high in
their first year, even among those who secure positions in big-city
churches. Low salaries make it almost impossible to meet their
financial obligations, Vick added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say what you want about a matter of faith, but the reality is
you have to pay your debt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting salary for seminary graduates is usually less than
$30,000 a year, and many rural churches cannot afford to pay even
that, Vick said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one mainline denomination, the Lutheran church, is
looking into the possibility of buying student seminary loans that
can be repaid at low or no interest if the pastor will take a rural
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not a profession that gives you monetary
rewards and it's not as secure as it used to be,'' Trull said.
</P>
<P>
   There are some financial bright spots. The average age of those
entering seminary is around 38, meaning they are second-career
people and do not have the burden of an undergraduate debt. And
alternative programs, like the Episcopalians' lay vicars, do not
drain the financial resources of small congregations or dioceses.
Lay vicars work for free.
</P>
<P>
   However, as in the huge Roman Catholic Church, the average age
of mainline clergy is graying. Besides older seminary graduates,
many denominations have tapped their retirees to help take the
burden off rural congregations.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of growth in the Southwest and the South has
further burdened the clergy load. New and growing churches create a
bigger need for ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Without female clergy, mainline denominations would be
experiencing a clergy crisis similar to the one in the Roman
Catholic Church. Today, there are fewer than 50,000 priests serving
the nation's 62 million Catholics _ and their average age is 58.
</P>
<P>
   The number of men entering seminary has significantly declined
in other mainline denominations as well. For instance, the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in American has seen a 25 percent drop
in male seminarians. Many seminaries _ including the Episcopal
Theological Seminary of the Southwest and the Austin Presbyterian
Theological Seminary _ have as many or more female seminarians as
they do males.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major reasons Methodists, Lutherans and
Episcopalians allow women pastors is because they can't get enough
men to answer the call to pastor,'' said the Rev. Harold O'Chester,
pastor of Great Hills Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Great Hills is part of the nation's largest Protestant
denomination, the Southern Baptist Convention, which in June barred
ffemale pastors. O'Chester believes the Bible makes it clear women
do not have the authority to teach over men, excluding them from
the role as pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in mainline denominations disagree, saying they believe
women and men are equally called by God to ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists do not require ministers to have seminary
training. Any Southern Baptist pastor or congregation can ordain a
minister into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was pastoring in Dripping Springs, we ordained a young
man who is right now going to some correspondence theological
courses in San Antonio,'' said David Smith, the executive director
of the Austin Baptist Association. However, he added, it is not
unusual for a rural Baptist pastor to also have a full-time secular
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to or he'd starve to death,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, parishioners can expect to see more small
congregations merge, more itinerate clergy serving rural
congregations and more non-seminary-trained ministers pastoring
country churches.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with most congregation members as long as they can
keep their doors open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down to very few people here,'' said Becky Kelley, a
parishioner at St. James in Taylor. ``We were worried it would
close.'' Since Chrisman came to the church, Kelley said, she has
not missed a Sunday except because of illness or vacation. Under
Chrisman's leadership, the church has more than doubled its
congregation to 50, Payne said. But it isn't just numbers that
count, he added.
</P>
<P>
   St. James now has a vibrant social ministry and Bible discussion
group. Congregation members said after years of worrying about
their future, they now look forward to Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale's being here is an experiment and it's worked,'' said
parishioner Bob Lindquist. ``He's doing a fantastic job here.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, an acolyte pulled the rope of the
high-pitched bell that has rung out at St. James since 1885.
Chrisman processed to the altar and said, ``Good morning and
welcome to St. James on another beautiful day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
