<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CREMATION0716-COX     07-15 2108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREMATION0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More families are choosing cremation when looking for a
meaningful way to say goodbye
 &HT;    By Julie Ardery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``It's an irreversible decision,'' Chet Robbins
advises me.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. To stretch this body out and bake it for two hours at
1,600 degrees reduces my decision-making powers, and me, to about 4
pounds of crumbled bone. There goes the figure-skating career. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   At the subject of cremation even Robbins, who as executive
director of the Texas Funeral Service Commission should be used to
this type of thing by now, clicks off the joviality and turns a
dour, professional gray. It wasn't so long ago, he says, ``People
would have asked, `What's cremation?' '' Traditional funerals, with
embalming, caskets, religious services and ground burial in a
family plot, weren't really matters of choice. They were the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Not so today. More and more people are choosing to be cremated.
The state's Bureau of Vital Statistics reports that in Texas the
rate of cremation almost doubled between 1989 and 1998, rising from
7 percent to nearly 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Funerals, too, are changing. Grieving families, rather than
turning to church liturgy, increasingly want to design rituals all
their own, eccentric ceremonies that find mourners perched on bar
stools or gathered at the pole of Enchanted Rock. Says Lamar
Hankins, president of the Austin Memorial and Burial Information
Society, ``People have learned that there's no correct way to do
it, that you can do many, many things to help family and friends
work through the grief process, so a lot of creativity has begun to
enter into this.''
</P>
<P>
   As the final acts of our just-lost lives, funeral practices have
been bound by iron traditions. The fear and permanence of death
tended to drive even the most freewheeling survivors back to ``the
green, green grass of home,'' to religious sacraments and to a
funeral parlor in the old neighborhood. Bigger than the senior
prom, sadder than a wedding _ or most weddings, anyway _ funerals
have resisted vagaries of fashion, taste, even price. Death has
never been when we've exercised what Hankins calls ``creativity'' _
at least never before. But now the goopy organ music is fading and
the stolid oak coffin is giving way. The rising incidence of
cremation glows as proof. We are special, and we want special ways
to be dead.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Deckert a native of San Antonio, died two years ago. His son
Bryan, who manages Mezzaluna restaurant in Austin, said his father
had made known to the family his wish to be cremated. ``He'd had a
love affair with the Bay Area, with all the sports teams out there.
And he knew he was dying,'' Bryan Deckert says. ``He asked if when
he died he could be cremated and left in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulfilling these wishes was awkward for some family members
``who have strong religious ties,'' Bryan Deckert admits. More in
keeping with custom, a small ceremony was arranged in San Antonio,
at the graveside of Ron's parents. And then Bryan flew to San
Francisco, meeting his mother and brother to carry out his father's
request. ``We took him to Candlestick Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan explains, ``In the south end zone at Candlestick, Dwight
Clark caught a touchdown pass that's kind of lore.'' In the last
minute of the NFC Championship game, Jan. 10, 1982, Clark leapt up
and into the history books, making what fans ever since just call
``The Catch.'' With that miracle snag, the 49ers beat the Dallas
Cowboys by one point. Deckert calls it ``one of the great comebacks
of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly modern mourners, the Deckerts did what pilgrims do.
They traveled to a ``sacred'' place to pay their respects. And
while Bryan Deckert didn't talk about theology or faith in
recounting this story, isn't some inkling of the afterlife really
``the great comeback of all time''?
</P>
<P>
   Many cemeteries and some local churches have special niches or
gardens for the committal of funeral urns. But, like the Deckerts,
a lot of families today want utterly personal ceremonies in quirky,
unchurchy places. Cremation makes these one-of-a-kind rites
possible. In and around Austin, such unconventional services happen
all the time as ashes, more properly called cremains, are scattered
at the Umlauf Sculpture Garden, the Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower
Center, the Zilker Botanical Gardens _ really, anywhere that
survivors find fitting.
</P>
<P>
   Texas does not clearly regulate the scattering of cremains.
``Apparently the laws about ashes are pretty broad,'' says Janet
Maykus director of spiritual care and bereavement services at
Hospice Austin. ``The only thing you can't do with ashes is harass
someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hankins, of the burial information society, adds that cremains
are ``nontoxic, so there really are no environmental issues to be
concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   Scattering ashes IS illegal in national parks, according to Rob
Trippet park manager at the Enchanted Rock State Natural Area.
``You basically have to sneak in and do it without telling anybody.
And if it's happening out here, then that's probably what they're
doing.'' In the year and a half since Trippet became supervisor of
the big, mystic purple outcropping in Llano County, only one park
visitor has ``actually called up and said, `Is it OK if we come and
bring Uncle Jim out and sling him out over the back side of the
rock?' Most of it is `Don't ask, don't tell,' on a lot of this kind
of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Peel, director of Austin-Peel and Son Funeral Home, says
he often hears about memorials at ``Town Lake, the river, Mount
Bonnell, or like up on Lake Travis, somewhere up in that area where
maybe the old gentleman that's cremated has been fishing a lot.''
Peel knew a UT science professor who asked that his ashes be
scattered around the biology building and another friend whose
widow surreptitiously sprinkled his remains over a local golf
course. ``We've had 'em take 'em to Hawaii, we've had 'em take 'em
down to the coast. It kind of goes back to the person and what they
enjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Enjoyed? Whatever happened to dirges, to pulling over as a
hearse, two limousines and a line of cars, lights beaming at
midday, roll past? What happened to Jackie Kennedy, looking blank
beneath a sheer black veil? Today's bereaved seem to want something
else, an upbeat occasion that deflects sorrow and dwells on ``the
good times.''
</P>
<P>
   Hankins respects, even advocates, these new funeral rites.
``Most people who have memorial services find them to be far more
important ways to remember the life of someone who has died. The
focus of the memorial service is more on the life of the deceased
rather than on the dead body.'' From this perspective, the
vanishing act of cremation makes sense. It takes the corpse out of
the picture and frees survivors to carry out any kind of memorial
in any place, or places, they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone shares this view.
</P>
<P>
   ``This society is a death-denying society,'' says Barry J.W.
Franklin manager of King-Tears Mortuary. Franklin contends that
it's important for mourners to view the deceased: ``It helps set in
the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Peel agrees. ``Part of the grief process is to view. I've
had people come in here where we've even had a closed casket, and
they leave and they've said, `Well, I didn't know if that was my
friend Joe in that casket or just a casket sitting there,' because
they didn't get to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Among African-Americans and Hispanics, cremation has never been
popular. The Cremation Society of North America, reported that of
cremations in 1996-97, 88 percent of the decedents were white, 6
percent were African-Americans, 3 percent were Asians and 3 percent
were Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   In part, these are religious differences. The Roman Catholic
Church forbade cremation until 1962, in keeping with its creed of
the body's resurrection. Under Vatican II, the church approved a
new Canon Law lifting the ban but still recommends burial of the
dead. Even under the revised canon, the Catholic Church does not
condone the scattering of ashes; cremains are to be buried intact.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Charles Villasenor II director of Mission Funeral Home
in Austin, says his largely Hispanic clientele continues to prefer
traditional burial. He estimates that less than 10 percent of his
customers choose cremation and says that the practice is even rarer
south of the border; Villasenor adds that families may choose to
precede cremation with more familiar rites _ embalming, viewing and
visitation _ and many families do.
</P>
<P>
   At Franklin's funeral home, with its majority African-American
clientele, the number of cremations has ``about stayed the same if
not gone down.'' Of 325 decedents at King-Tears Mortuary last year,
``we probably had about 12 cremations,'' he says. ``A lot of my
cremations are Anglo.''
</P>
<P>
   Among blacks, too, there are religious reasons why people choose
caskets and ground burial. According to Franklin, ``There are some
churches in the African-American community that say cremation is
contradictory to the Bible. A lot of preachers put that out, saying
that if you're cremated, you're going to hell.'' Yet, he says, the
preference for traditional funeral services is even more a matter
of social custom and cultural importance.
</P>
<P>
   African Americans tend to go all out for weddings and funerals,
Franklin says. ``They have that support from family, friends and
especially churches.'' He says that the black community pulls
together in force for people in bereavement. ``Some churches have
benevolent committees that come to the house, clean up. They answer
the phone, do the chores,'' sitting with the family ``all the way
until the day after the funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremation has always been a far less expensive means of
disposition than conventional burial practices. According to
Hankins, three companies in Austin offer direct cremation for about
$800, while a full-service funeral with embalming and a casket plus
gravesite expenses costs thousands more. And now, funeral directors
say, clients are more cost-conscious than ever. ays Peel, ``To
call funeral homes and find out prices _ people didn't do that.
They just had a particular traditional funeral home they used, and
they went to it. But now there's hardly a day goes by we don't have
people call and ask'' about costs.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, though, it's the more affluent person who tends to
choose cremation. ``The more highly educated people are, the more
cremation is done,'' says Peel. It takes more than thrift to
disrupt formidable burial rituals. Forces other than price are
obviously driving the change.
</P>
<P>
   Maykus, of Hospice Austin, thinks dwindling church membership
has had a dramatic effect on funeral rites. ``For people who are
involved in a religious body, to veer from the tradition would be
difficult. This is what happened with your ancestors. This is what
you hope will happen with your children. It's this real binding
experience.'' But, she says, ``For people who aren't
tradition-bound and that's not their worshipping community, I think
that oftentimes very liturgical ceremonies are empty. That's when
it becomes important to personalize your services.''
</P>
<P>
   Hankins notes, too, that ``The baby boom generation is getting
into their 50s now, and they're beginning to think about traditions
with respect to their own parents. They're used to not necessarily
doing things the way that was expected just a few years ago.''
Others choose cremation, he says, as the ``environmentally sound
thing to do'' and ``for the simplicity of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But as California and Florida tellingly lead the nation, it
seems cremation is here to stay, a drastic but logical solution to
the problem of last rites in a mobile society. In former
generations, relatives visited and tidied up the family plot every
other week or so. In these times, who recognizes Decoration Day?
</P>
<P>
   With cremation, Maykus says, unless religious beliefs proscribe
otherwise, the ashes can be split among survivors and left at
several meaningful places: Austin, Boston, the Biltmore Hotel and
Hamilton, Ohio, too. For the loss of handkerchiefs and solidarity,
creativity is rushing in with condolence in a thousand forms.
</P>
<P>
   For highly religious people, these roll-your-own rituals may
seem trivializations of death. Others may find the end-zone funeral
a complete and satisfying form of mourning. Most of us, Maykus
says, ``are a little bit in both worlds,'' both reaching back to
custom and tinkering to ``find out what is it that is comforting
and binding and grounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
