<HEADER>
A3145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOYS-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-N     07-15 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLING FOR BOYHOOD IN THE LEAGUES OF ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Mass.)  By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The escalating scuffle that left one suburban hockey dad dead
and another charged with manslaughter last week was no isolated
incident of rink rage gone mad. It was one of the more violent
skirmishes in a battle for boyhood that is spreading across the
fields of play.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when male adolescents have become a hot
psychopolitical topic among feminists and antifeminists, it might
be more useful to examine jock culture's role in boys' lives. The
two fathers, acting out of their own ideas of how best to raise a
boy, probably saw each other as threats not only to their sons but
to images of manhood formed in their own boyhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The last time we looked in on the impact of jock culture on
young people was right after the shooting deaths at Columbine High
School last year. In an earlier version of &UR;  &LR; thelipsite(at)aol.com,
readers were invited to comment on the prevailing wisdom that the
arrogant, entitled behavior of high school athletes, as encouraged
by the parents, teachers and coaches who vicariously live through
their overhyped deeds, created an everlasting divide; we identify
ourselves as jocks (or their camp-followers) and outsiders (geeks,
nerds, greasers, burnouts, etc.)
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail response was overwhelming, thoughtful and sometimes
emotional, mostly from middle-aged men who remembered high school
with still smoldering resentment against jocks. But former athletes
wrote as well. Some of them remembered those years with guilt for
bullying and hazing weaker kids, and with some shame for the way
they had been humiliated by coaches. High school was too late to
begin changing the pattern of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think peewee leagues,'' says Dr. Michael Miletic, a
Detroit-area psychiatrist who played hockey as a teen-ager in
Canada and now watches his 12-year-old play. ``And it's not just
the elite traveling teams. Even the house league teams become
parents' teams. There are no easy solutions. These psychologists
who tell you to monitor the coaches or pull the kids out are not
realistic. They're certainly not at the rink.''
</P>
<P>
   They are in the bookstores, however, and on the lecture circuit
in a somewhat simplistic frenzy of boy-watching that seems like a
weak imitation of the ground-breaking books of a few years ago on
adolescent females. The most popular is William Pollack's 1998
``Real Boys,'' which describes its subjects as trapped against
their will in the oppression of traditional masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   Of sports, Pollack writes: ``Sheer competition among boys rarely
builds character and does little to bring boys closer to one
another. But sports, when they are play, can be a tremendously good
thing for boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack's chief rival, Christina Hoff Sommers, offers even less
in this year's ``The War Against Boys,'' which basically describes
them as under siege by feminists who would unman them. Sommers
manages to misinterpret the Glen Ridge (N.J.) rape case; what her
agenda would list as suburban liberal permissiveness was actually
the traditional deification of smalltown football players who were
hollowed out by burdens they couldn't carry.
</P>
<P>
   Adults may be able to escape jock culture if they work at home
or in the arts and avoid television and newspaper sports sections,
but for most adults the harm or the health has already been
bestowed. For boys, however, there is no escaping jock culture. And
the potential for harm may be greater for young athletes.
</P>
<P>
   In Miletic's son's league, as he tells it, there is ``an
overweight, not overbright coach who over and over sends out the
dirtiest teams and no one does anything about it. For the same
reasons the nonabusive spouse allows the kids to be abused. People
are passive and they rationalize. They're in denial, they say:
`It'll stop. It's not so bad. It's a tough world out there and
maybe this will make the boys ready for it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the background details are known of the incident in
suburban Boston other than that the father who killed was demanding
that the other father stop encouraging rough play among the boys.
</P>
<P>
   From a distance, Miletic can spin a sadly common scenario. A
father-coach sends children out to be rough; he stirs their rage,
establishes an opposing team as an enemy and provokes his boys not
just to beat them but to dominate them. How much, asks Miletic, has
this to do with strategy and how much to do with the coach's own
feelings of smallness and submissiveness? How much has this to do
with the way he was traumatized in childhood? And he is
traumatizing another generation who will take it out in bullying
other kids and eventually their own sons and players.
</P>
<P>
   Among Miletic's patients, who include professional athletes, is
a 14-year-old boy who came to him suffering from depression. In the
course of therapy, Miletic learned that the boy had been on a
championship peewee football team in which the boys were abused
after a loss or even a poor practice. Garbage pails were set out on
the field and the boys were made to run around them until they were
hanging over them, vomiting. The boy eventually quit the team, to
his parents' anger and disappointment, but joined his high school
team, where the abuse was somewhat less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he broke his arm in practice,'' Miletic said. ``How
convenient. And what relief he felt.''
</P>
<P>
   In the battle for boyhood, the broken arm was a real war's
equivalent of the so-called million-dollar wound that sends you
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1449EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
