<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-REYNOLDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: REYNOLDS MAKES STARS FLY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ga., Australia)  By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this quadrennial year of elections and an Olympiad, there are
constants in the air. Politicians and athletes alike will chase
long-held dreams of cheers and glory. Great swatches of television
time will be devoted to outcomes both foregone and unpredictable.
And, for the fourth consecutive running of the Summer Olympics, the
Star class sailor Mark Reynolds will be prospecting for gold.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Stars, literally and figuratively, the
44-year-old Reynolds knows the ropes. To the native of San Diego,
Star boats have been a common thread in the fabric of his
existence. His father, Jim, who crewed for local Star legends like
Malin Burnham and Dennis Conner, dragged his son to his first
regatta, up the road off Newport Beach, when he was 4. Jim Reynolds
was a fine sailor, but his boy would be the one to make history.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Reynolds grew up with a tiller in one hand, a mainsheet in
the other. He started like many junior sailors, with a string of
one-design sailboats: Sabots, Lasers, a Flying Dutchman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, in the early '80s,'' he said in an interview last week,
``I got serious with Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he ever. In the years that followed, Reynolds roamed the
world collecting passport stamps and Star class sailing medals. He
nabbed a gold medal at the Goodwill Games in Estonia in 1986, and
followed that up with a silver at the Olympics in Pusan, South
Korea, in 1988. Then, in Barcelona, Spain, in 1992, Reynolds won
Olympic gold.
</P>
<P>
   In Savannah, Ga., the Olympic sailing venue in 1996, Reynolds
posted a rare, substandard performance, and finished eighth. But
now he's back, with a new crewman _ 46-year-old Magnus Liljedahl, a
native Swede who gained his American citizenship in the early '90s,
and who has replaced Reynolds' longtime partner, Hal Haenel _ and
he appears stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Reynolds and Liljedahl breezed to victory in the
Olympic trials off San Francisco, winning nine of 14 races. The
pair followed that up with a resounding triumph while vanquishing
111 other crews in the Star World Championships, in May, on the
Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it worked out we had a little extra speed edge on
everybody,'' Reynolds said. ``It's been a really good year so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   The Star, a hard-chined, 22-foot-8-inch keel boat, has an all-up
weight of just under 1,500 pounds _ 900 of which are stashed low in
its ballast bulb. It also features a massive mainsail that propels
it beautifully in light wind, which is one of the reasons the boat
has been so popular in San Diego, where other Star luminaries such
as Lowell North, Gerry Driscoll, and Vince Brun have also reigned.
But with its size, the mainsail can be a handful in heavier air.
</P>
<P>
   To counterbalance that big main requires beef, and the
relatively compact, circular Liljedahl, at 6-foot-1 and 255 pounds,
fills the bill. He is also the perfect complement to the more
angular, 6-foot-3, 200-pound Reynolds. In silhouette, the pair
could be mistaken for the wide receiver Jerry Rice and the nose
tackle Jerry Ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a big guy hanging out and getting his weight out as far
as he physically can will help keep the boat more upright and going
fast through the water,'' Reynolds said. ``The harder you hike, the
faster you go.''
</P>
<P>
   If Reynolds is the current embodiment of the quintessential Star
sailor, it's also because, by profession, he's a sailmaker whose
business is crafting the aerodynamic wings on which the fastest
Stars fly. But that also means he is sometimes in the unenviable
position of sharing the equivalent of state secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you find a little edge you don't want to tell people
about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one reason people buy my sails is because they get my
advice on how to set them up,'' he continued. ``The only way I can
afford to keep sailing is by selling good sails. If I started
hiding stuff, it'd shut me down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the coming Olympics in Sydney, Australia, Reynolds will not
be contending with a 100-plus-boat fleet, as he did at the world
championships. The Olympic Star class quota is only 18 boats, but
it is a highly competitive field that includes the Canadian Ross
MacDonald; the hometown favorite, Australia's own, Colin Beashel;
and the Brazilian Torben Grael, back to Stars after his stint
aboard Prada in the last America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of depth there,'' Reynolds said. ``Beashel's
been consistent for years and he came real close to winning the
gold last time. MacDonald's a great sailor, and Grael has a new
boat with a little different hull shape so it's possible that could
give him a little edge.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reynolds, on his accustomed mission in an Olympic year,
likes his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been going well,'' he said. ``Barring any catastrophes I
think we have a good shot at winning an Olympic medal. We're aiming
for the gold one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
