<HEADER>
A3159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      07-15 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTER FATIGUE AND A NEW CAST CREATE A LULL, AND NEITHER CAMPAIGN
MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last year, perhaps the best place to measure
the frenzy that was the New York Senate race was in the cramped,
cluttered press office for Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign.
There, across the street from Madison Square Garden, Clinton's
aides fielded hundreds of inquiries from around the globe every
day, all the while directing assaults on Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and
responding to incoming attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But the other day, a hot and languid weekday July afternoon, the
scene on Seventh Avenue was almost tranquil. The phones were
relatively silent. Howard Wolfson, Clinton's driven press
secretary, who would normally be juggling at least two telephone
calls and three e-mail exchanges at once, even found a free moment
to search through baseball rotisserie-league sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, New York still has a Senate race, and it still features a
sitting first lady of the United States. But that has often become
increasingly difficult to detect on many days in recent weeks, as
aides to Clinton and her Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, have
come to discover.
</P>
<P>
   A fog has descended over this once highest of high-flying
campaigns, leaving the candidates' advisers discussing what to do
about it _ if anything, because it remains a matter of debate in
both campaigns whether all this attention was ever a good thing for
either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   If aides to Lazio and Clinton agree on anything, it is that
voters (and, not incidentally, other politicians and the news
media) have lost, at least for the time being, some of their
fascination with a contest that for so long had seemed the
political equivalent of the O.J. Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   And who can blame them?
</P>
<P>
   First, and most obviously, with Giuliani gone, this race is very
different from what it was just a few weeks ago. If Giuliani was
brash, cunning, sometimes intemperate and almost always
interesting, Lazio is cautious and tentative, heeding campaign
advisers who have urged that he learn the lay of the land and avoid
the provocative statements that Giuliani relished. That makes the
candidate Lazio less like Giuliani and more like _ well, Clinton,
with the not surprising result that comes from having two
candidates intent on avoiding controversy.
</P>
<P>
   But the new cast of this contest is only part of it. New Yorkers
have been drowning in politicking for what seems like years now.
Aides to Clinton and Lazio suspect that a fatigue has crept over an
electorate that can be forgiven for feeling oversaturated.
</P>
<P>
   This campaign for the Senate started almost as soon as the last
one ended, in November 1998, when Daniel Patrick Moynihan announced
he would not seek re-election. Clinton has been talking and
listening her way across New York since last July. Vice President
Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush have been making daily policy
pronouncements and attacks from the moment each emerged as his
party's presumptive presidential nominee last March. The Senate
race in New Jersey, one of that state's most combative and closely
watched campaigns in decades, has thrown a few more voices into the
political din, at least in the New York metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that there are only so many issues to go around,
and it does seem as if Clinton, Gore, Lazio and Bush are reading
off the findings of the same focus groups. Can anyone be faulted
for losing track of whether it is Clinton or Gore who is denouncing
the ``risky'' Republican Social Security or tax plan, or whether it
is Bush or Lazio blaming the Clinton administration for soaring
fuel costs or high taxes?
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the campaigns is that they started so long
ago,'' Steve Gold, 49, who was eating lunch outdoors at Bryant Park
the other afternoon, said dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Henri, a 24-year-old writer from Chelsea, put it a
little more pungently. ``The campaign,'' she said, ``is boring.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As Wolfson discovered, press phone calls to both campaigns are,
generally speaking, markedly down. So are the requests to the
campaigns for guests for the Sunday morning network talk shows,
which once paid nearly as much attention to the New York Senate
race as they did to the presidential contest. Clinton's campaign
events, while still unwieldy by the standards of a normal New York
state race, no longer have the overwhelming feeling of a full-scale
spectacle, with chattering television crews from across the world
competing with Washington-based network correspondents for a
question to the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Although the candidates have been talking _ Clinton has some
sort of event almost every day _ there is little evidence that the
voters are listening. In a poll by Quinnipiac University released
on June 7, Clinton and Lazio were tied, 44 percent to 44 percent.
Two weeks ago, after a month in which Clinton had been attacking
Lazio for one thing or another almost every day, in speeches and
with television advertisements, another Quinnipiac Poll was
released. The result? Clinton and Lazio are tied, 45 percent to 45
percent.
</P>
<P>
   At Jones Beach on Long Island the other day, the mere mention of
what was once viewed as the race of the century drew long stares
and yawns from people who had obviously found a better way to pass
a hot July afternoon. ``It's, like, summertime,'' said John Cooper,
23, of Wheatly Heights. ``People are not interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Up the beach, Colleen McGrath, 39, from Nesconset, seconded that
sentiment as she kept an eye on her two children. ``It gets played
out after a while,'' she said. ``After a while, you don't want to
hear it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   What has happened, really, is that the race for Senate in New
York is becoming normal. This is the way it is supposed to be.
Summer time is hibernation time in most campaigns, which candidates
use to raise money and try out their fall campaign themes,
preferably without too much attention.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for president, Bush and Gore both decided to
campaign as if Election Day were a week away as soon as each
effectively grasped the nomination, and not risk ceding the stage
to his opponent. But Clinton and Giuliani made no such choice: They
could not escape public attention if they tried, and they did try,
concerned from the start that too much attention was not good for
two candidates who were so polarizing.
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, the departure of Giuliani _ and the entrance
of what many Republicans have concluded is the more politically
conventional and less dynamic Lazio _ that more than anything
accounts for the quick and dramatic shift of tone.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this reflects what Lazio is. As a member of Congress
from Suffolk County, as opposed to the chief executive of the
nation's premier city, Lazio does not have the captive press corps
or City Hall platform that Giuliani used to drive coverage of the
Senate race. Lazio, by contrast, spent much of last week 300 miles
away from New York: in Washington, casting little-noticed votes in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But much of this change is a direct reflection of the style and
relative experience of the man who entered the race after
Giuliani's diagnosis of prostate cancer. One Republican leader,
after nervously commenting about Lazio's sometimes rocky entrance
onto the Senate campaign stage, suggested that Lazio, who has never
before run for statewide office, could benefit from a little more
practice and a little less attention.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's advisers disagree with that assessment of the
candidate's skills, though they do seem to be taking that advice.
Mike Murphy, Lazio's senior strategist, said that the lull played
to Lazio's benefit. ``The Lazio campaign is very happy with the
current tempo of the campaign,'' he said. ``Mrs. Clinton is slowly
sinking, and Lazio is slowly coming up. I don't think the media is
hyperventilating any more.''
</P>
<P>
   At Clinton's headquarters, even Wolfson sounded a bit relieved.
``I think it's fine that it no longer feels that the whole world is
watching,'' he said. ``It feels more like a normal Senate
campaign.'' After all, if Lazio and Clinton kept going at it the
way Clinton and Giuliani had, what on earth could be left to say
after Labor Day, once the campaign really starts?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
