<HEADER>
A3182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BRITISH-HOLE0716-COX     07-15 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-HOLE0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIVE HOLES WORTH WATCHING
 &HT;    by Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ There are two ways to play St. Andrews,
the way the pros play and the way golf writer Glenn Sheeley (9
handicap) played it.
</P>
<P>
   AT THE OLD COURSE, ST. ANDREWS:
</P>
<P>
   No. 1
</P>
<P>
   376 yards, par 4
</P>
<P>
   How the pros play it: Anybody who misses this fairway might not
be around for the weekend. Like the 18th, which runs beside it,
this hole is wide enough to catch even the most errant drive. A
fairway wood or long iron sets up the second shot, which is the
real key. The approach must carry the 6-foot wide Swilcan Burn,
which snakes in front of a green that slopes toward the water. When
the wind blows, which is almost always, shots with too much air
under them are knocked down easily. A pitch played too firmly can
bring an uneasy, downhill putt.
</P>
<P>
   How I played it: With the rain coming sideways and the wind
blowing hard, I semi-shanked a driver but got plenty of roll. My
7-iron second shot got caught in the wind and ended up on the right
fringe but stayed dry, except for the raindrops, of course. I
chipped up to 15 feet and two-putted for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   No. 8
</P>
<P>
   175 yards, par 3
</P>
<P>
   How the pros play it: Depending on the wind, this par 3, the
only one on the front side, to a giant shared green, can be
anything from a 9-iron to a 5-iron. The pin often is hidden by a
ridge of rough grass that runs across the face of the green,
allowing only the top half of the flag to be seen from the teebox.
</P>
<P>
   How I played it: With the hole playing 166 and the weather
suddenly dry and mild, I blocked a 7-iron so far right that I
actually was closer to the 10th green's flagstick, 108 feet away
from the correct one _ no joke; we walked it off. Wondering if
putter was enough club, I somehow hit the approach putt to eight
feet and sank the remainder for par, receiving a high-five as if I
had made birdie.
</P>
<P>
   No. 9
</P>
<P>
   352 yards, par 4
</P>
<P>
   How the pros play it: Definitely a reachable par 4 for many,
especially downwind, but two small bunkers must be avoided in the
final 70 yards to the hole. From the area in front of the green,
putting often is the best option.
</P>
<P>
   How I played it: With the hole listed at 307 yards and playing
shorter on firm and fast ground, my drive was about 15 yards off
the front of the green. Putting over the mounds and dips, I stroked
the ball against the flagstick and dropped it from about 45 feet
for eagle.
</P>
<P>
   No. 17
</P>
<P>
   455 yards, par 4
</P>
<P>
   How the pros play it: The ideal path on the famous Road Hole is
a blind driver over a corner of the Old Course Hotel, just over the
capital ``O,'' to hit the fairway and avoid the deep rough on the
left. The safe approach is to the right side of the green, avoiding
an area left that funnels into the steep-faced Road Bunker. Hit
right and onto the gravel road _ or worse, against the stone wall _
and anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   How I played it: Not my proudest moment. Going for the bold
route, I came out of my drive on the downswing and flared a ball
out of bounds right, hitting the Old Course Hotel. Fortunately,
it's still standing, and, actually, it happens all the time. After
a reload drive that wound up in the left rough, I hit 5-iron out to
the fairway. Pitching to 10 feet, I missed the putt and wrote down
a 7.
</P>
<P>
   No. 18
</P>
<P>
   357 yards, par 4
</P>
<P>
   How the pros play it: Facing another huge fairway that is hard
to miss, a driver here can reach the green, too, depending on the
wind and the firmness of the ground. It's out of bounds right if
someone really blocks one beyond the posts that separate the course
from the town. Key to the approach is avoiding the deep Valley of
Sin on the left of the green's front.
</P>
<P>
   How I played it: Decent drive up the middle with darkness
approaching. Hit an 8-iron and the ball trickled down toward the
Valley of Sin. With darkness approaching, I three-putted from about
45 feet for bogey, and I wasn't all that disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   TEE TO GREEN
</P>
<P>
   The repositioning of six championship tees at St. Andrews for
the 2000 Open has increased the overall yardage from 6,933 yards to
7,115.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
