<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-SIDE0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods approaching Grand Slam history
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ The odds are favorable for improvement
from Tigers Woods' last British Open at the Old Course in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, then a 19-year-old U.S. Amateur champion who had
immeasurable raw talent but little course management, tied for 68th
on rounds of 74-71-72-78. He was 13 shots behind winner John Daly.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods won by 13 shots this week, few people would be shocked.
Not after his mind-boggling 15-stroke win in the U.S. Open. Not
when, at 24, he is going for the career Grand Slam, poised to join
Jack Nicklaus, Gene Sarazen, Ben Hogan and Gary Player as winners
of all four major championships. Not when two of his three majors
wins, with the 12-shot blowout at Augusta in 1997, have been routs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, Woods has demonstrated a scary ability
to strike every possible type of shot he chooses. Once wild, Woods'
swing has become grooved and his distances controlled. The result
has been a staggering 15 wins in his last 26 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Pebble Beach was a familiar course that suited Woods well, and
St. Andrews, with its open property and his ability to blow the
ball over bunkers, is even more ideal. He shot 66 twice there in
the 1998 Dunhill Cup, when his game was not nearly this polished.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods' putter is on form, he should win.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Woods pillaged Pebble Beach, former Royal and
Ancient Golf Club secretary Michael Bonallack suggested ``a
steward's inquiry'' if he doesn't prevail at the Old Course.
</P>
<P>
   Keen on history and the place he quickly has taken in it, Woods
will be as motivated to make it happen this week as he seemed
uninterested two weeks ago in the Western Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person who has ever played the game of golf has wanted
to win an Open Championship (at St. Andrews),'' Woods said last
week in Ireland, where he won a charity event as a warmup for the
Old Course. ``It would mean everything to me, and I'd say I have a
good chance. To have the opportunity to complete the (career) Grand
Slam at the course where it all started is very symbolic.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods tied for third at Royal Birkdale in 1998, when his
tightened swing was still a work-in-progress, and he was 7th last
year at Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything depends on the weather,'' Woods said. ``I'm just
hoping the wind blows a little bit, to make it a test. Then the
person driving it well is going to have the greatest advantage. . .
. If it's calm and warm, like it was when Nick (Faldo) won in 1990,
then (the Old Course) is not very hard _ pretty easy, in fact. But
when it blows, it becomes brutally hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf has a habit of biting people when they least expect it,''
said Peter Dawson, the R&AMP;A secretary. ``Tiger is clearly the best
in the world, but it doesn't mean he's going to win every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
