<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BRITISH0716-COX     07-15 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A return to the Old Course
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ A year ago, the world's finest players
were ready to set fire to Carnoustie's knee-high rough and spit on
its narrowed fairways.
</P>
<P>
   This week, they come home to St. Andrews, and all is right with
the world. In comparison, the Old Course is an Old Friend.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a torture test to be forgotten. This is a history
lesson to savor. After the Shadow of Death, heck, what's a little
Valley of Sin?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even Jean Van de Velde, the tragic figure of Car-nasty,
can go a week without slipping off his cleats. Situated about 7,000
miles east of Pebble Beach, golf's third major of 2000 arrives at
the home of golf, St. Andrews, for the 129th British Open.
</P>
<P>
   A Hell Bunker and a heavenly scenario: Tiger Woods, 24, after
winning by 15 strokes in last month's U.S. Open, attempts to become
the youngest player in history to complete the career Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   As always in Scotland, the elements will play a large role. It
might have been a smile crossing Woods' face when he stepped out of
a helicopter last week in Limerick, Ireland, for a charity event
and noticed winds gusting as much as 40 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends if the wind blows or not,'' Woods said. ``If
the wind blows, I'll have a bigger advantage than when it doesn't
blow. If it's calm, anybody can go low there. That golf course is
going to be torn apart if it's calm.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's been mostly cold, windy and rainy for the last couple
of weeks in Scotland, the rough at the Old Course is plenty sparse
compared with Carnoustie. Perhaps only three inches deep, except
for a few places on the seaside links property, it is quite a
contrast from last year, when drives missing the fairway almost
eliminated pars.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Course is not about length. Several par 4s can be
reached from the teebox by many players, not just Woods. When the
most famous piece of land in golf is bordered by ocean and a town,
the course can be extended only so far.
</P>
<P>
   Some length has been added for the Open, with six tees
repositioned to increase the yardage from 6,933 yards to 7,115 and
to bring into play some old hazards and bunkers that have been
flown over by today's big hitters. But the Old Course's only
consistent defenses are weather, bunkers so deep that the only exit
is sometimes backwards and elevated greens with giant dips and
swales.
</P>
<P>
   To protect St. Andrews' precious sand-based turf, fans playing
there in recent months have been required to carry along a piece of
Astroturf to place on the fairway at their ball.
</P>
<P>
   Because the ground is so firm, the greens often must be reached
with the ground game. If the wind howls, you'll see balls scooting
across greens, in and out of swales, more like pingpong balls.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, course officials would want St. Andrews to
force shots such as some of the bounding beauties Sergio Garcia
made in the most recent Dunhill Cup, shots that bounced 80 to 100
yards to the putting surface.
</P>
<P>
   It's a course that the long hitters will overpower if enough
holes aren't against the wind. Woods could be facing frequent eagle
putts on a par 4.
</P>
<P>
   All 112 bunkers on the Old Course have been retooled for the
Open Championship. In an effort to protect the course's three
largest bunkers _ Cottage at the 4th, Shell at the 7th and Hell
Bunker at the 14th _ railroad ties have been set vertically in
concrete to form a face against which layers of turf are stacked.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Course is a bomber's paradise, provided you know which
spire to aim for in the distance, but it requires a bit of luck to
miss the key bunkers. Much of the trouble at St. Andrews is on the
right side, but often an approach from the safer left side presents
a poor angle to the green. Dead center drives, unless placed in
orbit, can find nasty pot bunkers unseen from the teebox.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to drive the ball well there,'' said Nick Price,
who won at Turnberry in 1994. ``St. Andrews is a good driving golf
course. People think it's wide open. It's not as wide open as you'd
think. . . . If you don't get the right line into the green, many
times you can't get even a pitching wedge closer than 30 feet from
the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Andrews can be far more unpredictable than Pebble Beach,
largely because of the uneven ground and the greens' funky nature.
</P>
<P>
   But it might be just wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think St. Andrews will help the rest of us,'' said Nick
Faldo, who won here in 1990 under warm, dry conditions. ``It's a
true links course, with big greens, and you can play it with no
real scare.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
