<HEADER>
A3186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OLY-TRACK-1500-(TRIMS     07-15 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-1500-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SEEKS COMEBACK AT MIDDLE DISTANCES
</HEADLINE>
  By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Although he ran no farther than one lap
around the track, Michael Johnson accounted for America's only
medal at any distance longer than a full-out sprint at the 1996
Olympics in Atlanta. There is renewed hope for the middle distances
at the 2000 Games in Sydney, Australia, where the United States
could not only win a medal in the women's 1,500 meters but also win
even a gold.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Jacobs, a two-time silver medalist at the world
championships, and Suzy Favor Hamilton, only the second U.S. woman
to breach four minutes in the 1,500, will face off Sunday at that
distance in the Olympic track and field trials. While championship
races are often tactical and slow, Tom Craig, who is Jacobs' coach
and husband, believes Mary Slaney's 17-year-old U.S. record of 3
minutes 57.12 seconds could be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Suzy takes it seriously and goes out like she did at
Prefontaine, it's going to be a very fast race,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   On June 24 at the Prefontaine Classic in Eugene, Ore., Favor
Hamilton ran a searing pace against Gabriela Szabo of Romania, the
1996 Olympic silver medalist, building a 20-meter lead only to be
caught at the tape as she stumbled to the track. Szabo's time of
4:00.73 is the fastest time in the world this year, and Favor
Hamilton's 4:00.79 is second fastest. Until Friday's victory in the
preliminaries in 4:06:16, Jacobs had not run a 1,500 meters
outdoors this season, but at the Prefontaine meet she set a
personal best of 1:58.08 at 800 meters.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. women have never won a medal at 1,500 meters since it was
added to the Olympic program at the 1972 Games in Munich, Germany.
The event has been dominated by runners from the former Soviet
Union, and the current Olympic champion, Svetlana Masterkova, is
also from Russia. However, Masterkova has undergone a pair of
surgeries on her Achilles' tendons and remains an unknown commodity
with the Olympics 2 1/2 months away. Previously she said she would
skip the European circuit before Sydney, although she will
apparently emerge at a meet in Oslo later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think they are having a real problem with her
coming back,'' Craig said recently of Masterkova. ``It wasn't one
Achilles, it was both.''
</P>
<P>
   Szabo will run the 5,000 in Sydney and may double in the 1,500.
But Jacobs and Favor Hamilton are clearly threats to win the gold
medal. Both are at the top of their games after suffering
career-altering traumas _ Jacobs overcoming a severe iron
deficiency and Favor Hamilton having gained a new resolve after the
suicide last year of her brother, who suffered from manic
depression.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Wisconsin, Favor Hamilton won nine
collegiate titles. She has made two previous Olympic teams and only
Slaney has surpassed her own personal best of 3:58.43 among U.S.
women. But Favor Hamilton, who is 31, has also had a reputation as
a soft, timid runner who was not fortified athletically or mentally
to contend in major races.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   She missed last season after undergoing surgery to repair a torn
Achilles' tendon, and on Sept. 9 her brother Dan, an artist who had
stopped taking his anti-depressant medication, killed himself. His
sister has begun using her maiden name again to honor Dan Favor,
and she has spoken frequently about her brother's death in hopes of
raising awareness about manic depression. She races now to honor
her brother, Favor Hamilton said, and she has developed a new
urgency and fearlessness in her running, as well as a new affinity
for distance training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel rejuvenated and motivated,'' Favor Hamilton said after
winning her preliminary heat in 4:10.29 Friday night. ``I'm a new
runner. Every race is a gift. I want to give it my all. People say
it's dangerous and you can overdo it. But I want to do something
amazing for my brother, myself, my family. My brother's death has
motivated me. It's funny how tragedy can turn a life around and
bring positives.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs will turn 37 before the Sydney Games begin and could
become one of the oldest Americans to win an Olympic gold medal.
She was born in Los Angeles on Aug. 28, 1963, the day that Martin
Luther King Jr. gave his ``I have a dream'' speech in Washington.
Her mother, Cecilia Pinkett, told The Sacramento Bee that King's
speech gave her the determination ``that my daughter's life was
going to count.''
</P>
<P>
   By age 17, Jacobs was participating in the 1980 Olympic trials
as an 800-meter runner. But she never won a collegiate title while
at Stanford, and it was not until the past three years that her
career has reached full flower. In 1993, Jacobs was diagnosed with
low levels of iron in her body, accounting for her wildly erratic
performances on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two weeks of hard training, I couldn't put together hard
workouts for another two weeks,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   She changed her diet, eating more vegetables and red meat, and
began taking iron supplements to boost the deficient levels in her
body and to increase her stamina. Now she has blood drawn weekly to
measure the lactic-acid levels in her system, and she monitors her
heart rate daily to keep from ``running past the warning signs'' in
training, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the 1997 and 1999 world championships, Jacobs lost to
Masterkova at 1,500 meters, the second time by less than a second
last August in Seville, Spain. Jacobs keeps a videotape collection
of Masterkova's races, exhaustively analyzing her style and trying
to develop ways to counter the Russian's furious kick. Masterkova,
who is also the reigning Olympic 800-meter champion, can run the
final 100 meters of a 1,500-meter race in 14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like looking in a rear-view mirror and seeing a Cadillac
coming,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs has worked hard this season to make her own stride more
sound, reaching less with her arms and striking the ground with her
feet under her hips for maximum efficiency. The greatest difference
between the Jacobs who finished 10th to Masterkova at the Atlanta
Olympics and the one who appears ready to challenge for a gold
medal in Sydney is confidence, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was nervous,'' Craig said of his wife. ``I don't
think she believed in herself. Now she's at the point where she's
realizing how well she can run. It's confidence, experience. You've
been there before. You're more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Olympics, of course, come the finals of the Olympic
trials and a riveting matchup with Favor Hamilton. The top three
finishers in the race will qualify for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the death of her brother, Suzy is different,'' Craig
said. ``She's not afraid of anything. Regina has the same sort of
attitude: `Who cares? Let's go.' It could be tactical or it could
be the American record. It's going to be fun. I'd love to see it be
the kind of race that can convert 10,000 girls who are playing
soccer back to track and field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
