<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-RUSSIA-     07-15 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: RUSSIA'S NEW PRESIDENT EYES AN UNRULY PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moscow's best journalists, never a particularly sunny lot, now
talk ominously about a return of Soviet-style controls on the
press. They fear, with some reason, that the Kremlin wants to
restore its choke hold on Russia, not simply by bringing order to
government and business, but by setting limits for the country's
struggling new media.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin has repeatedly promised that he intends
to make press freedom a cornerstone of Russia's infant democracy.
But in recent days, the former KGB agent has added some disturbing
new definitions for the word ``free.''
</P>
<P>
   During his first annual state of the nation address on July 8,
Putin talked about how ``freedom of journalism has become a juicy
morsel for politicians and major financial groups. ...'' He
criticized media owners who were trying ``to settle scores''
through their publications or were using their powerful voice as
``a tool for fighting government.'' Such tactics, the Russian
president said, create a ``phony freedom.'' What is needed, he
said, are the legal and economic conditions for a ``civilized
information business.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that one person's ``civilized information
business'' is another's censored media. If Putin imposes his
favored version of a ``free'' press, no matter how lofty he thinks
his aims, there will not be a free press in Russia. To gain this
most basic liberty for his country, Putin will need something that
may be hard for a former Soviet official to comprehend _ namely a
high tolerance for obstreperous and even offensive media.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage in its liberation from Soviet censors, Russian
journalism offers about as much variety and inconsistency as the
Internet. The same publication can print important news and barely
rewritten corporate press releases or pornography. Verified facts
are often coupled with rumors in an effort to sell more papers.
Still, this untidy mix is an important stage in the media's
transition. At its worst, the new Russian media are still vastly
better than in the old days when truth came only in state-approved
shadings.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of Russia's biggest media outlets have also used their
power unwisely, aiming at political enemies in a vengeful way that
is not unheard of in the West but which ultimately undermines their
own credibility. During the 1996 presidential race, for example,
Russia's new media barons commandeered the airwaves and headlines
on behalf of President Boris Yeltsin, either criticizing, mocking
or virtually ignoring his Communist opponent. The argument at the
time was that the press was fighting for its life against a return
of communism. When Putin complains that news organizations are
settling scores and fighting the government, he may be describing
this tendency, especially by the large media company run by
Vladimir Gusinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But trying to drive independent news organizations out of
business or into submission is not the answer, if Putin wants a
truly free press. The owner of some of the best and most
independent news publications in Russia, Gusinsky has become the
target of a series of investigations of alleged financial
improprieties. Gusinsky, who also runs the only national television
network in the country that is fully independent and steadfastly
critical of Putin, was jailed for a few days last month. Gusinsky's
many talented journalists fear he will be forced out as head of his
company, Media-Most, and be replaced with someone less willing to
challenge the new president.
</P>
<P>
   The warning flags in Russia have already drawn international
concern. A group of journalists, primarily from the World Press
Freedom Committee and the Committee to Protect Journalists, visited
Moscow last week, mainly to protest governmental threats to the
media. The Westerners also advised Russian journalists to improve
their standards of ethics and professionalism, to stop using their
voices as a political or public relations club if they want ``to
claim their vital place in building a free and democratic
society.'' But those problems should be fixed by the journalists
and media barons, not by the Kremlin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000715.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3188 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-ART-2T     07-15 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-DELAYS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE DELAYS ARE THREATENING LAST SUMMER'S RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
 
repeating to add photo note  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A collective groan rose up from the United Airlines check-in
line at La Guardia Airport at 8 a.m. Monday as the announcement
sounded from a loudspeaker. Because of heavy thunderstorms in
Chicago, the disembodied voice intoned, flights to O'Hare
International Airport would be delayed one to four hours.
</P>
<P>
   For Sharon Mantel, a drug saleswoman on her way to a meeting in
Chicago, the day had already had a bad start. She hit a deer on her
way to the airport from her home in Stamford, Conn., shattering her
car's windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days earlier, Jacqueline and Philip Clinton and their
daughters, Caitlyn, 2, and Victoria, 3 months, had arrived four
hours late _ without their luggage _ on their way to Long Island
from their home in Spokane, Wash. Now, rescheduled onto an
afternoon flight to Denver, they faced an even longer trip back.
</P>
<P>
   But for Cindy Miller, an advertising executive who has been
flying at least once a week for four years, it was business as
usual. ``It's just absolutely horrendous,'' she said. ``You just
get used to it after a while. What can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer was the worst on record for airline delays,
prompting the airlines and the Federal Aviation Administration to
swing into action to try to ease the burden on weary passengers.
Yet despite those efforts, this summer is turning out to be even
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Delays in June rose 16.5 percent from June 1999, according to
the FAA's latest statistics. So far this year they are up 12.7
percent. And with air traffic continuing to expand at a time when
few new airports or runways are on the drawing board, delays may be
a fact of life for years to come, airline executives and government
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   No group of passengers has suffered more of late than those
flying United, the world's largest airline. Just under 57 percent
of the carrier's flights arrived on time in May, far worse than the
performance of its closest competitors, according to the latest
figures compiled by the Department of Transportation. Of the 33
flights that were late more than 80 percent of the time in May, 27
were United's. And United canceled more flights in May _ nearly 9
percent of its schedule _ than any other airline.
</P>
<P>
   May was also the month that United agreed to buy US Airways, the
country's sixth-largest carrier, for $4.3 billion, a deal that
would make it responsible for carrying 25 percent of the country's
air passengers. Many politicians and consumer advocates oppose the
deal _ which has set off a frenzy of merger negotiations among the
other major airlines _ saying it will lead to a decline in both
competition and service.
</P>
<P>
   United blames a stretch of unusually bad weather and an outmoded
air traffic control system that it and other airlines complain is
not up to the task of managing an air transport network carrying
twice as many passengers as it did 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more at work, too _ United's deteriorating
relations with its employees, for example. Six years ago, the
airline's pilots led a group of employees that traded deep wage
cuts and other concessions for stock in United's parent company,
the UAL Corp., making UAL the world's largest employee-owned
company.
</P>
<P>
   Without a new contract since April, many of the pilots have
refused to fly overtime, forcing the airline to cancel thousands of
flights. Both sides say they want to reach an agreement, but the
labor picture could get worse before it gets better: On Wednesday,
the contract covering United's mechanics, gate agents and ramp
workers expired.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything our folks are doing is inconveniencing passengers,
I am truly sorry,'' said Herb Hunter, a 777 captain and spokesman
for the United branch of the Air Line Pilots Association. ``That
can all be fixed if the company would step up and try to take care
of its employees.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for United's difficulties, according to
conversations with dozens of employees and executives over the last
week, is that many of its internal systems, from its arrival and
departure information boards to its baggage handling operations,
have not kept pace with the airline's fast growth.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday was a typical example of United's travails. At 5:30
a.m., violent thunderstorms converged on O'Hare, and the FAA
quickly reduced the number of arrivals there to 40 an hour from the
normal 100.
</P>
<P>
   With that information in hand, under a new program that puts the
FAA and the airlines in closer contact, United began canceling
flights. Like other major airlines, it uses a sophisticated
computer program that determines which flights will cause the least
disruption to passengers and the system if they are grounded.
Ultimately, United canceled 354 of its 2,300 scheduled flights on
Monday, 231 because of weather and air traffic control delays and
the remainder for mechanical problems, unavailable flight crews and
other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   By acting early, said Peter D. McDonald, United's vice president
for operations, United can get word out to passengers about delays
and cancellations. But it does not always work out that way. The
Clintons _ she is a freelance artist, he is an Air Force pilot _
checked with the airline at 6 a.m. Monday before heading to La
Guardia from Wading River on Long Island, where they were staying,
and were told there were no delays. By then, of course, storms were
threatening Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can predict four hours into the future,'' asked
Clinton, ``why couldn't they tell us at 6 a.m.?''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said that even if United could have correctly forecast
the storms, it would not have been able to anticipate every delay.
``You can predict the weather and you can predict a thunderstorm,
but you can't predict what the FAA will do with the arrival rate,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Customer surveys conducted by United have found that the top
priority of passengers, after arriving safely on time, is getting
accurate information from the airline. Yet because many of United's
computer systems do not communicate with one another, its
front-line employees often are in the dark when flights are
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at 8:40 a.m. how long the Clintons' original 9 a.m. flight
would be delayed, Willy Pena, a United customer service
representative at La Guardia, looked at a computer screen and said
20 minutes _ despite the earlier warning of delays up to four
hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the flight took off more than two hours late, at
11:40 a.m. ``It is difficult to prove the point that we are not
lying,'' acknowledged Graham Atkinson, United's senior vice
president of marketing. ``But it may be that certain people at the
airline may not know what other people know.''
</P>
<P>
   United plans to introduce a system _ at O'Hare by the end of the
summer and systemwide next year _ that will link customer service
representatives, gate agents and arrival and departure monitors
directly to its main operations center in Chicago. Now, the
information they receive has to be updated manually _ which means
that visitors to United's Web site or customers who sign up for its
new paging service, both already connected to the new system,
receive more current information than United's own call center and
airport personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Antiquated systems are also the reason United loses more baggage
than any other airline. In May, it mishandled 6.71 bags per 1,000
passengers, more than twice the number lost by top-rated Alaska
Airlines, according to the government.
</P>
<P>
   John Johnson, who is in charge of deploying baggage handlers at
O'Hare and has worked at United for 31 years, recalled a big
celebration a few years ago when the airline handled a record
51,000 passengers at the airport in one day. Now United routinely
handles that many at O'Hare, its busiest hub, and 55,000 to 60,000
a day is common, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen it this bad before,'' Johnson added. ``This
year is incredible, and I said the same thing about last year.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In April, United began trying to hire another 600 baggage
handlers at O'Hare. Frontline workers there are being outfitted
with radios, and the company is installing scanners around its
system to let it more closely track bags. Also, a new baggage
connection center that is due to open at O'Hare early next year
will link baggage operations directly to customer service. The goal
is for bags to accompany passengers rerouted because of delays,
something that rarely happens now.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the Clintons. After their flight from Spokane to Denver
was delayed on July 1, the family was put on a later connecting
flight to La Guardia. But their luggage _ including car seats for
their daughters _ did not make it to the new flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't leave the airport,'' Clinton said. Not, at least,
until her parents arrived with car seats they purchased on the way
to La Guardia (which the Clintons returned to the store after their
luggage was delivered by United the following evening).
</P>
<P>
   Their trip home last Monday was even more harrowing. To avoid
the delays at O'Hare, they were taken off the 9 a.m. flight to
Chicago and rebooked on a 2:40 p.m. flight to Denver. After waiting
at La Guardia for nearly four hours, they were delayed more than
five hours more in Denver before taking off for Spokane. The family
finally landed _ with luggage, this time _ after midnight Tuesday
morning, more than 10 hours late.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the experience has not dimmed her husband's enthusiasm
for the skies; he hopes to work for an airline after he finishes
his service in the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't be flying with a 2-year-old and a baby,'' his wife
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Clinton said. ``That's why I might try to fly for
Fedex. No passengers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
