u a BC-NJ-WHITMAN-PHOTO-NYT &LR;      07-15 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-PHOTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TELLING SILENCE GREETS WHITMAN FRISKING PHOTO 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ If Gov. Christie Whitman's political future were
still as bright as it once was, the photo showing her grinning as
she frisked a young black man might have done some real damage.
</P>
<P>
   Black lawmakers and clergymen expressed outrage last week over
the photo, taken when Whitman accompanied state troopers on patrol
in Camden in 1996, and the Rev. Al Sharpton seized on it as proof
of the governor's racial insensitivity. But what was perhaps most
striking about the furor that followed its recent publication was
how little of an effect it was likely to have on Whitman's
political standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about it is, her term's almost over, and she's never
running for anything else again,'' predicted Charles E. Cook Jr.,
editor of the Cook Political Report, a Washington newsletter. ``So
what difference does it make?''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's allies, predictably, argued that Whitman would
emerge unscathed because she quickly admitted that her pat-down of
the man, who had already been searched by troopers, and who was not
arrested, had been a mistake _ though that argument seemed
unpersuasive as she resisted growing demands that she apologize to
the man.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who said through a spokeswoman that she frisked
the man because she wanted to experience what police officers face,
endured two days of criticism and even ridicule by television
commentators and late-night comedians. But the videotaped beating
of a carjacking suspect by 10 Philadelphia police officers on
Wednesday quickly shifted attention to a far uglier law enforcement
confrontation with its own racial overtones.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling commentary about the governor's gaffe, however,
may have been the silence of most New Jersey Democratic leaders,
who seemed to have nothing to say about it. No faxed attacks, no
breathless phone calls to reporters, no slogans shouted from the
State House steps.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton was hardly alone, of course, in suggesting that the
photograph was so problematic it could cost Whitman a spot on the
Republican ticket with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. ``They say a
picture is worth a thousand words,'' Sharpton said. ``It might be
worth a vice-presidential nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   But what the photo really brought into focus was how far
Whitman's political star had fallen since the picture was taken in
1996. Back then she was at the height of her celebrity, the best
known of the wave of moderate Republican governors elected in 1993
and 1994. A year earlier, she had been asked to deliver the
Republican response to the State of the Union address; in 1996 she
was on Bob Dole's short list of potential running mates, and she
was considered a likely presidential candidate in her own right in
2000 should he lose.
</P>
<P>
   Today, by contrast, with her party's convention coming to New
Jersey's backyard in two weeks, Whitman's horizons are generally
seen as limited to a Cabinet office at best, or even to an
ambassadorship, if Bush wins in November. ``By and large most
people are acknowledging that the vice presidency isn't ready to be
served up to her,'' said Tom Wilson, a former director of the state
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, many believe Whitman may have sacrificed any hope
of a spot on a national ticket in 1997, when she vetoed a ban on
the procedure known to opponents of abortion rights as
partial-birth abortion, and won the undying enmity of her party's
conservative wing.
</P>
<P>
   That fall, for all her popularity, she barely eked out a victory
against James E. McGreevey, then a little-known mayor from
Woodbridge.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen A. Salmore, a Republican campaign consultant often
critical of the governor, said her early exit from the Senate race
pointed up her steadily softening support, which he attributed to a
lack of an ideological or geographical political base.
</P>
<P>
   While Whitman's support for abortion rights and gay rights has
made her a favorite target for conservatives, he said, her
memorable stumbles on race _ from her 1995 remark about ``young
black males'' competing to see ``how many children you can sire
outside of wedlock,'' to the newly surfaced pat-down photo _ have
made her vulnerable to attack from the opposite direction. ``She's
found herself caught in a political no man's land, without support
from the left or the right,'' Salmore said.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman's spokesman, Pete McDonough, scoffed at past-tense
talk, even though by law she cannot run for governor again when her
term expires in 2001. ``She's 53 years old,'' he said. ``Deciding
to look back now, as if her political career has somehow drawn to a
close, I think is foolhardy. She was the first female governor in
the history of New Jersey. Will she be the first something else in
her life? Probably.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
