<SLUG> BC-NY-CLUB-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY PATRON KILLS CLUB OWNER OVER BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The owner of a Korean nightclub in Midtown Manhattan
was shot dead early Saturday by a customer enraged by his $980
bill, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The customer shot the owner, Sang Dal Choi, 43, several times in
the head inside the Club Nix, in the basement of 6 East 32nd
Street, about 4:25 a.m., said Lt. Stephen Biegel. The man, whom the
police described only as an Asian in his 20s, pulled out a pistol
as he argued with the owner over the check.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect had been in the club with as many as four friends,
said Biegel.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they thought the killer, who fled after the
shooting, had been a customer in the club in the past. But it was
unclear whether he had been identified by detective investigating
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Choi, who lived in Flushing, Queens, was taken to Bellevue
Hospital Center, where he was pronounced dead, police said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the shooting, the club was empty except for the
employees and the party with the suspect, the police said. After
the shooting, the people who had been with the gunman also fled,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Two men who work on the block said that the club was popular
with younger Koreans, with patrons primarily in their early to
mid-20s, and that it was often the scene of drunken brawls.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Delgado, who works as a security guard at the Avalon hotel
a few doors away and who has recently worked the night shift, said
the club usually heated up about 2 a.m. ``Every night there's
fights, people punching each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, Do Hyun Kim, 20, who works in Lee Wireless, a
cellular telephone store near the club, said he visited the night
spot every few weeks. He said security guards at the club frisked
all the male patrons for weapons before they were admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go there and fight all the time,'' he said. ``Come here
at 3 in the morning and you would see drunk people screaming and
staggering all along 32nd Street from one end of the block to
another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
