<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-15 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLS ARE ALIVE AGAIN WITH A STRONG KELME RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIANCON, France _ Although the Kelme team from Spain was a
wild-card choice for the Tour de France, one of three controversial
selections, it showed again Saturday that it belonged in the
20-team field.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in three mountain stages, a Kelme rider won
and captured the polka-dot jersey of the top-ranked climber. This
time the victor was Santiago Botero, a Colombian who has been
knocking on the door the last few days. He was second on a hilly
stage into Revel on Tuesday and fifth up Mont Ventoux on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Botero took advantage of a seven-man breakaway halfway along in
the 155-mile (249.5-kilometer) 14th stage to build an uncatchable
lead once he left his companions behind on the last of three
mountains in the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   He finished 2 minutes 30 seconds ahead in a total time of 7
hours 56 minutes 13 seconds, a speed of 19 mph on a sunny, cool day
with strong winds on all three climbs.
</P>
<P>
   Both the length of the stage and the winds were cited by Lance
Armstrong, who finished seventh in a group of his leading rivals
and retained his overall lead of nearly five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long day, a hard day,'' Armstrong, the leader of the
U.S. Postal Service team, said. ``Maybe too long a day. The racing
wasn't aggressive. People took it easy for the first three or four
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   After receiving another yellow jersey, Armstrong was relaxed and
joking at a news conference. Asked if this had been his worst day
in the first two weeks of the three-week Tour, he responded: ``Why?
Did I look bad?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact he looked good _ launching a strong attack on the final
climb and moving alone ahead of his rivals _ but isolated. Jan
Ullrich, in second place overall, had a Telekom teammate to help
him and Richard Virenque, now in fifth place, had a Polti teammate
to help him. Both benefited from the strong pace set by those
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong had nobody to help him once he sped away from the last
man to stay with him, Marco Pantani of the Mercatone Uno team, and
the winner on Mont Ventoux with Armstrong's gracious help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're using our riders a different way this year,'' said Dan
Osipow, the Postal Service team's director of operations. ``Last
year, when Lance won, we had men staying with him as long as
possible on the climbs. This year we're going harder earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   That results in a pace so fast that it leaves behind many men in
the 141-rider field. But it takes an early toll on Armstrong's
support system. So far he has been strong enough to carry on
single-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is proving that they're strong, very strong,''
Armstrong said before the stage. ``Did you see the bottom of the
Ventoux? There were 10 guys there and we had three.'' Although the
two others were gone quickly, they were, as he showed, unnecessary.
He seems confident that the strategy will continue to work in the
next two Alpine stages, Sunday and Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Armstrong praised Botero's winning ride and said the Colombian
might become a rival in what the Texan has referred to as ``this
three-stack we have here in the Alps.''
</P>
<P>
   Botero and the others in the breakaway were not chased
strenuously at first because all of them ranked low in the overall
standings _ Botero was highest placed at 19th overall, 13:11 behind
Armstrong. Now he is eighth, 10 minutes behind.
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Savodelli, an Italian with Saeco and another member of the
breakaway, was second in the stage, with Pantani third, 2:49 behind
when the main chasing group of 11 riders made it up a steep, long
ramp into Briancon, at 1,326 meters the highest city in Europe. The
stage began in Draguignan and headed north.
</P>
<P>
   Of the mountains traversed Saturday, the toughest was the last,
the Izoard, 14 kilometers (8.7 miles) long with a grade of 7.2
percent. It was followed by a 20-kilometer (12.4-mile) twisty
descent into Briancon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Virenque broke away on the descent, Armstrong decided it was
payback time for Pantani, whose victory on the Ventoux he did not
dispute. Seeking a pacesetter, he tapped Pantani on the back and
gestured ahead. The Italian, a master descender, nodded and zipped
off, quickly catching Virenque.
</P>
<P>
   No similar downhill will be available at the finish Sunday.
After climbing the Galibier and the Madeleine peaks, both rated
beyond category in toughness, the riders will face a 22-kilometer
(13.7-mile) slog up to Courchevel on a grade of 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tomorrow will be more difficult because today was long
and hard,'' Armstrong said. ``On paper, it looks like a very hard
day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
