<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TELECOM-COMMISH-AR     07-15 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TELECOM-COMMISH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE VIRTUAL WORLD, A REAL PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.Y., Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Allan H. Dobrin, the city's information technology
and telecommunications commissioner, is eminently at home in the
virtual world.
</P>
<P>
   He carries a Palm Pilot V, a Motorola alphanumeric pager, a
wireless IBM laptop, a Startac cell phone and a Nextel cell phone
that works like a walkie-talkie.
</P>
<P>
   It is the real world, with boundaries both physical and
bureaucratic, that sometimes gives him pause.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a state judge in Albany ruled in favor of Dobrin and
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, saying that they, and not the City Council,
had the power to negotiate franchise agreements with cable
television companies.
</P>
<P>
   While Dobrin spends much of his time in meetings or dealing with
matters like the court case, he says he would much rather spend his
time planning new Internet services and finding space for new
fiber-optic cables in in the Silicon Alley of Lower Manhattan. .
</P>
<P>
   ``The advent of the Internet is the opportunity of a lifetime to
fundamentally change the way New York City provides services to its
residents,'' Dobrin said. ``But the challenge is doing it in one of
the largest governments in the country, which has hundreds of
different missions.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobrin serves as the citywide technology officer, the liaison to
the Silicon Alley businesses and the mayor's chief adviser on
information technology. (The mayor has Internet access at his desk
and uses a Palm Pilot to go online while traveling.) Dobrin's
department is also responsible for the 911 system and for
regulating cable television franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Dobrin's aides say their boss recoils from the publicity and
perks other appointees thrive on. He is among the few commissioners
with neither a press secretary nor a driver. He is rarely seen at
fund-raisers or other political events.
</P>
<P>
   R. Ryan Nelson, the director of the Center for Management of
Information Technology at the University of Virginia, said, ``The
changing nature and needs of technology in the last decade have
made jobs like these, especially in complicated, large
bureaucracies like New York City, very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of his time, Dobrin said, is spent on dealing with new
legal or practical issues that arise because of advances in
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lhota, the deputy mayor for operations, said rapid
changes made Dobrin's job more difficult. ``His goals are a moving
target, because the life cycle in the world of the Internet is
moving so quickly that last year's idea is replaced by a better
structure, and you never know what type of problems you are going
to face.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, one primary concern centers on a lack of space
beneath Lower Manhattan's streets for new fiber-optic cables.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, we have been hearing that it is overcrowded
underneath that part of the city _ that when you dig into the
ground, there is no more room to put anything,'' Dobrin said.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers working for Dobrin came up with a solution ingenious
in its simplicity: using 175 miles of abandoned century-old water
pipes in Manhattan and Brooklyn as conduits for the cables. It is
unclear whether it will work.
</P>
<P>
   Dobrin started in city government in the 1980s as an
administrator at the Board of Education. He moved to the mayor's
office in the late 1980s and is among the few political appointees
who has served in the Koch, Dinkins and Giuliani administrations.
He left as chief of staff to former Deputy Mayor Ninfa Segarra in
1997 to become deputy executive administrator of Bellevue Hospital
Center, where he became more interested in technology. But Giuliani
was able to lure him back less than a year later.
</P>
<P>
   He is known for spending 70 hours a week working on technology
problems and preparing the government for one of his favorite
topics: what he calls ``the e-government revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobrin would like citizens to be able to go to one Web site to
fill out and pay for all the permits needed to, say, erect a
building, instead of having to visit a dozen agency offices.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, would reduce the need for city clerks and thus
provide more money for police officers, firefighters and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Within City Hall, Dobrin's name has been mentioned for several
higher positions. But he says he wants to stay in his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to create a reorganized virtual government, as
if you started the government in 2000 instead of 1898,'' Dobrin
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
