<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-McLAREN-RESURGENC     07-15 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-McLAREN-RESURGENCE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THE DRIVING FORCE BEHIND McLAREN'S RESURGENCE 
By BRAD SPURGEON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ron Dennis reached across the spotless table, picked up the
interviewer's pen and turned the exposed tip away from its
proximity to the interviewer's shirt-sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   Few habitues of Formula One would be surprised with this move by
the owner and director of the series' most successful team. By
caring for every detail of the team, car and working environment,
Dennis has brought 16 world titles to McLaren since he joined it in
1980.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, at the French Grand Prix, he renewed the contract
of his driver David Coulthard. And he confirmed that Mika Hakkinen,
who won the last two drivers' titles with the team, would also keep
his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think one of the most constructive things we can do to make
our task a little easier and to really get focused,'' Dennis said,
``is to make sure the drivers know where they stand for the balance
not only of this year, but next year. I think it will extract that
little bit more from both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Coulthard won the race and Hakkinen came in
second. As a result, Coulthard comes to the Austrian Grand Prix
near Zeltweg Sunday only 12 points behind Michael Schumacher, who
leads the drivers' series, after trailing by 22. And McLaren is
only six points behind Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   By the colorful standards of many of the team's competitors, the
sober silver-gray and black McLaren cars are cold looking. But by
most accounts, Dennis' capacity for caring makes McLaren a warm
place to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the impression one gets from the outside but once you
are one of his group, even if you have a bad day, he backs you up
and he stays behind you, whether it's mechanics, drivers or
engineers,'' said Gerhard Berger, who drove for McLaren from 1990
to 1992 alongside Ayrton Senna.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis cares so much about bringing success that he takes it
very hard when McLaren does not win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very painful experience to go back to your hometown,
there's nowhere to hide,'' Dennis said, noting that the failure is
seen by hundreds of millions of television viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis started as a teen-ager by serving coffee and cleaning the
garage for the Brabham team, working free. His first race was when
he was 18, and he went to the Mexican Grand Prix in 1966 as a
mechanic with the Cooper team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at least 10 years younger than anyone else in the pit
lane and probably closer to 20,'' he said. ``And that was a big
advantage when five, 10 years down the road I had all the
experience that would normally be attributable to someone who was
40, 50 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   He rose through the hierarchy to become chief mechanic, which
was like a team manager today. A turning point came when Jack
Brabham, then the team owner, chose Dennis to run his Formula Two
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we had Formula One competence that we applied to a
lower category, the team was very successful and it pretty much
rewrote the way that you went motor racing,'' Dennis said. ``We put
total emphasis on preparation. We had the most immaculate racing
cars and transporters and workshops. Dirt was something that we
just fought against. And it put us in a different league.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of the Dennis reputation for cleanliness in
a sport that is fundamentally about grease. His 350-member race
staff is issued McLaren clothes that members must wear even at the
spotless factory. The professionalism not only appeals to Dennis'
personal manias, it also impresses sponsors. In the late 1970s, the
Philip Morris Co., the main sponsor of the ailing McLaren team,
took notice and invited Dennis to join it. He merged his team,
Project Four, with McLaren to form McLaren International.
</P>
<P>
   The team had won three world championships since it entered
Formula One in 1966. But during the late 1970s it was overshadowed
by Lotus and Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   By 1984, however, McLaren won both the drivers' and
constructors' titles.Through the late 1980s, the team dominated the
sport with Alain Prost and Senna, who together won 15 of the 16
races in 1988. Prost left in 1990, and Senna left after the 1993
season, at the start of the most difficult period for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We essentially went into self-destruction mode,'' Dennis said.
``We had become so used to winning that it seemed there was nothing
we could do to not win. And we lost sense of things.''
</P>
<P>
   He hired Hakkinen in 1993 and Coulthard in 1996. But the
turnaround was when he took on Mercedes as an engine supplier in
1995. Coulthard's triumph in the 1997 season-opening Australian
Grand Prix ended McLaren's longest streak without a victory, three
years and 49 races. McLaren won both the constructors' and the
drivers' championships in 1998 and the drivers' championship in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, who has feuded with the International Automobile
Federation, said the team's goal is to win every race. Last year at
the Malaysian Grand Prix, McLaren lost the constructors' world
championship when the federation, on appeal, overturned a stewards'
decision that the Ferrari cars were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my more paranoid moments, I think they're out to get us,''
Dennis said. ``But all that means is that when we win, we really
have to win by all that much more.''
</P>
<P>
   He turned to his assistant a few steps away and said: ``Can you
get the air-conditioners down? It's too cold.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only about one degree too cold, but every detail counts. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
