<SLUG> BC-GORE-DLC-0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore Ridicules Bush Leadership in Texas
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Vice President Al Gore is testing a campaign
strategy against Texas Gov. George W. Bush that, ironically, comes
from Bush's father, former President George H.W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 the elder Bush, who was then vice-president, torpedoed
the presidential bid of Michael Dukakis by picking apart Dukakis'
record as governor of Massachusetts. If Dukakis can't run a state,
Bush told voters, how can you expect him to run a country.
</P>
<P>
   Now the roles have reversed with Vice President Gore needling
Gov. Bush about his record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Democratic Leadership Council (DLC) here
Saturday, Gore ridiculed the governor's record and painted an
unflattering statistical portrait of Texas, much as the elder Bush
once stood on the shore near polluted Boston Harbor to ridicule
Dukakis's environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of fish, Gore is focusing on children, specifically,
the welfare of low income children in Texas as way to counter the
``compassionate conservative'' core message of the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Noting on Saturday, for example, that Texas ranks 50th among the
states in providing health coverage to families, Gore sarcastically
questioned the governor's priorities in dealing with the budget
surplus in Texas last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might think that a governor whose state ranks dead last in
the entire nation for families with health coverage, who then gets
a surplus courtesy of the national economic boom, might turn his
attentions to moving from number 50 to, say, 45. Maybe even better.
But nooooo,''Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of taking up or proposing legislation to help them,
Governor Bush made a big tax break for the oil industry the very
first bill that he signed that year. Now, I don't really know how
many oil executives in Texas lack health insurance, but I can tell
you this: A lot of children in Texas do,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels to the 1988 presidential contest were apparent to
the members of the DLC, the centrist organization Gore helped found
in 1985 following the party's disastrous performance in the 1984
election with a liberal, Walter Mondale, at the head of the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope the results are the same (as in 1988),'' quipped
Al From, the DLC president and the founder of the ``new Democrat''
movement that led to the creation of the DLC.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his speech to the DLC, once again focused on Texas
newspaper accounts this week suggesting that:
</P>
<P>
   A $1.7 billion tax cut Bush pushed through the state legislature
last year has significantly reduced the state's anticipated budget
surplus this year.
</P>
<P>
   One million low income children in Texas are not being served
under a federally funded summer nutrition program because the state
government decided not to spend the $33 million the federal
government provided for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week, as Governor Bush was travelling from photo-op to
photo-op, trying to put the compassion into his conservatism, we
learned that he failed to use tens of millions of dollars budgeted
to feed poor and hungry children during the summer months,'' Gore
said. ``Just because school is out doesn't mean that hunger takes a
summer vacation - or that leadership can go on leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett said Bush had increased the number
of children served over the summer _ from 175,000 in 1996 to
259,000 this year _ and has already acted to spend $2 million more
on outreach to further bolster participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worse Al Gore does in the polls, the more he continues to
attack and that's why his credibility deficit continues to grow,''
Bartlett said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials have underestimated spending needs on Medicaid
and criminal justice programs by roughly $600 million this year,
eroding an estimated $1 billion budget. The Texas Legislature is
expected to approve a supplemental spending bill to cover the
Medicaid and criminal-justice costs when it convenes next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign arranged for House Budget Committee Chairman
John Kasich, R-Ohio, to respond to Gore's attacks on the Texas
budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich told reporters that the Clinton-Gore administration has
asked for 13 supplemental spending bills since 1993 and Gore
``never complained.'' Now, he added, ``Texas is facing a $600
million supplemental appropriation to meet unexpected needs and the
new Al Gore is on the attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore said Texas's budget surplus is ``rolling away like
tumbleweed,'' his attack was aimed more at Bush's budget cutting
priorities than the shrinking budget surplus in Texas, however.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1999 budget proposal, with Texas reaping a $6.4 billion
budget surplus, its largest ever, Bush suggested $2.6 billion in
tax cuts, including $2 billion to reduce property taxes that fund
public schools, $300 million for businesses and $300 million in
sales tax exemptions. The first bill Bush signed in the 1999 state
legislative session provided the oil industry a $45 million
``emergency'' tax break.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Bush defended signing the tax cuts into law,
saying, ``I did the right thing.'' He said that ``it is a little
too early to project'' how much money the Texas legislature will
need to make up for the shortfall. And, apparently in reference to
his bid to be elected president, he added, ``As you know, I hope
I'm not here to have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said on Saturday, ``With all due respect to Governor Bush,
America can't afford to deal with it, either.'' He suggested that
Bush's economic policies would return the country to ``the days of
deficits, debt and economic decline'' that he said marked the
administration of the governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's address is scotts(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www. dlc.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
