<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OPEN-CINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTING TOUGH: A SLICE OF LIFE IN LITTLE ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joe Ruggiero nodded at the two-bit tough guys
flickering on the south wall of the DeSalvio Playground. The
celluloid gangsters might as well have stepped out of his
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were guys like that everywhere,'' he said. ``The
so-called people in charge, they didn't do anything for the
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruggiero knew there was a time when mouthing off like that in
Little Italy could have gotten him a broken arm or a bullet in the
head. But these days, he was more likely to be bruised by tourists
jostling for cannoli. For a taste of the old neighborhood, he had
to walk over to the playground at Spring and Mulberry Streets to
watch films like ``Mean Streets,'' the 1973 Martin Scorsese opus in
which Harvey Keitel and Robert De Niro play small-time wise-guys in
Little Italy.
</P>
<P>
   It showed on Friday night, the fifth screening this year in the
free Open Cine film series started in 1996 by Luca Pizzaroni. The
movies run on most Friday nights throughout the summer. Pizzaroni,
a young filmmaker from Rome, had set out to recreate the open air
cinemas so popular in Italian cities. He shows mostly Italian
films, with exceptions like the work of Scorsese, who grew up in
the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   People find out about the screenings through fliers posted on
the park fence or Pizzaroni's Web site, www.nyopencine.com. Most
who go are cinephiles or Italian-Americans from around the corner.
The biggest screening this summer, ``La Dolce Vita,'' drew 200
people.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, the night got off to a slow start. Kids were
playing on the basketball court and slides well past 8:30. A friend
who was supposed to bring chairs didn't show up, so the two dozen
people in the audience plopped down on flattened cardboard boxes.
Pizzaroni set his 16-millimeter projector on a rickety wooden
ladder and ran an extension cord into the base of a lamp post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to blow up one of these days,'' he said as he
frantically plugged in the cord.
</P>
<P>
   But soon enough, a beam of light poured from the projector, and
the Ronettes' ``Be My Baby'' boomed across the playground during
the opening credits. Pizzaroni's friends had brought the speakers,
borrowed the ladder from a firehouse, paid for the film rental and
printed the fliers. His supporters were here, even if his e-mail
invitation to Scorsese remained unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   The projector was old, and the picture kept going in and out of
focus. But those in the audience who had grown up in Little Italy
watched the movie with smiles. Ruggiero, whose family emigrated
from southern Italy in 1963, told one spectator that while working
in a bakery he had sold bread to the film crew for a hallway scene.
(Most of the film was made in Los Angeles, but parts were shot in
New York.)
</P>
<P>
   When the film first opened at the now-defunct Fifth Avenue
Cinema, Ruggiero said, he walked into the theater and saw half the
neighborhood there.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, those guys used to live right down the block,'' he said,
pointing to two extras on the screen. ``I don't know their names,
but they must have been friends of the director.''
</P>
<P>
   One audience member, dressed sharply in a black suit and
narrow-brim hat, squinted at the screen. His name was Frank
Huaquilino, but everyone called him Butch the Hat. He had lived his
entire 54 years in the neighborhood, he said, and once ran with an
Italian gang that brawled with Jewish, Puerto Rican and Chinese
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Scorsese had cast him in small roles in several movies, he said,
and he was acting in a film Pizzaroni was making about
Italian-American extras. He told people of the days when De Niro
hung out on a bench in this playground and talked about getting
into acting.
</P>
<P>
   He waved at the screen as it showed a drunken man stumbling
around a bar and a hoodlum pulling a gun on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``See where he gets killed,'' Butch said to Pizzaroni and his
friends. ``That really happened. It was in the pocketbook store
right down the block. That was a social club in 1968. A guy was
carrying a gun and acting cocky, and those days when you carried a
gun, you had a problem. He was a nice kid, but what can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Butch's rapt audience leaned closer. He pointed to Mulberry
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where it happened,'' he said. ``Right there, during the
Feast of Saint Gennaro.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ruggiero, the feast was a thing of the past. These days, it
is no different from any other street festival in the city, he said
to Sam Rohn, one of Pizzaroni's friends. It had gone the way of
everything else in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought they should have kept this place the way it
was,'' he said. ``I don't want to sound nationalistic, but they
should have done it for history's sake. There's only tourists and
restaurants now. What is there to show in a restaurant?''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Italians assimilated,'' Rohn said. ``That's the way of
all immigrants here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' Ruggiero said. ``But if there were cultural
institutions like museums and good schools, people would have
stayed here.''
</P>
<P>
   His own parents had moved out to Long Island years ago. These
days, he said, there was too much noise, too much garbage. He shook
his head and stared up at the screen. A woman was walking into her
apartment building carrying groceries, a baguette sticking out of a
sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the bread,'' Ruggiero said. ``I'll never forget that
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Pizzaroni lit a cigarette and glanced at the audience. It had
dwindled to a dozen people. No matter. He had already changed the
reels twice, and the movie would end soon. It ended in blood, he
said with a grin. Lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   On the screen, De Niro leaned over the counter of a bar and
pointed his gun at a gangster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This scene is so true,'' Ruggiero said. ``If you went and
pulled a pistol on a gangster, it didn't matter who they were, you
were saying they were nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough movie,'' said Pizzaroni, ``with tough guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been tougher,'' Ruggiero said, ``if they had
picked the right guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
