<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3219 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHICAGO-MANSIONS-REAL     07-15 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-MANSIONS-REAL-1040(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GOLD COAST NEAR DOWNTOWN CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT SHAROFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a throwback to the early years of the 20th century
when wealthy Chicago families tended to live in such close-in
neighborhoods as Prairie Avenue and the Gold Coast, the city's
Lincoln Park area is experiencing a boom in mansion construction.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the neighborhood, about a mile and a
half north of the Loop, has seen construction of dozens of examples
of the kind of house that had not been built in any great numbers
in the inner city in many years. They are palatial residences of at
least 6,000 square feet that start at around $2.5 million and go
much higher.
</P>
<P>
   The number of such houses, like the official definition of what
constitutes a mansion, is difficult to ascertain. Most people seem
to know one when they see one, however. And the evidence of a
dramatic change in the neighborhood's fortunes is clear from a walk
down any of the long blocks of Howe or Mohawk or Burling streets
just north of Old Town.
</P>
<P>
   Looming over the remaining original housing _ mainly modestly
scaled clapboard cottages and brick three-flats that date from just
after the Chicago fire in 1871 _ are the elaborate limestone
facades of dozens of new three- and four-story houses.
</P>
<P>
   Who is buying them? Real estate agents and builders say the main
clients are couples and families in their mid-30s and early 40s who
have struck it rich in the booming economy of the last decade and
are choosing to stay in the city rather than move to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the new wave,'' said Sean Conlon, director of sales
and marketing for Sussex &AMP; Reilly, a leading North Side residential
brokerage firm. ``The last people to build houses this big downtown
were the great industrialists and robber barons of the 1890s. But
they built over on the Gold Coast. A new neighborhood is emerging
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Conlon, 31, recently moved into a new four-story,
6,000-square-foot house on Mohawk Street with a slate mansard roof,
arched windows and lavish detailing. ``They had homes like this in
Paris and London in the 1700s and 1800s,'' he said. ``It's an
exquisite, timeless style.''
</P>
<P>
   Conlon's house is typical of the prevailing look of the new
houses. The style, which leans heavily toward limestone columns,
balustrades and elaborate fruit and flower friezework, is usually
described as Georgian or classical or beaux-arts.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it is an unlikely look for the Chicago area, the
birthplace of modern architecture and the home of such modernist
giants as Frank Lloyd Wright and Mies van der Rohe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look like banks,'' said one top real estate agent who
requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   John Vinci of Vinci/Hamp Architects, a firm noted locally for
historic renovation, calls them fantasy houses. ``They're
emulations of turn-of-the-century Parisian or Belgian grand
houses,'' he said. ``It's just fantasy to build these houses now.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinci is also the architect _ along with the late Max Gordon, a
British architect _ of the house that many say was the beginning of
the whole downtown mansion trend. Nine years ago, Lewis Manilow, a
local investor and chairman of President Clinton's Illinois
fund-raising committee, went looking for what he called ``a country
house in the city.'' When he could not find one, he decided to
build a new house on four adjoining lots that he had acquired on
Howe Street.
</P>
<P>
   Howe Street at that time, Vinci said, was ``a street of small
houses'' in a neighborhood that had been steadily gentrifying since
the 1970s but had yet to see much new construction.
</P>
<P>
   The house Vinci designed is a modern, 10,000-square-foot tan
brick structure with a sizable garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to consolidate my life,'' Manilow said. ``I used to
have a condo as well as a loft where I had my office and part of my
art collection. Now everything is in one place.'' Why Lincoln Park?
``It's very urban,'' Manilow said. ``You can walk downtown, to the
lake, the park. There's lots of people on the street. It's just a
very friendly neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is the availability of land for
construction, free of landmark-district constraints. Traditionally,
the wealthy in Chicago have lived on the Gold Coast, a roughly
12-square-block area that includes Lake Shore Drive and Astor
Street and is just south and east of Lincoln Park.
</P>
<P>
   Developed around the turn of the century, the housing is a mix
of mainly co-op apartment buildings and historic mansions and row
houses, many of which are official landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only 80-some single-family houses on the Gold Coast,''
said James M. Kinney, president of Rubloff Residential Properties,
a leading downtown residential brokerage. ``And you have to get
neighborhood approval to tear anything down. Lincoln Park, however,
aside from a few areas, isn't landmarked. You can build what you
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what is happening. ``I get calls every day from
people who are looking to build in the neighborhood,'' said
Elizabeth Ballis, a saleswoman with Coldwell Banker's Lincoln Park
office.
</P>
<P>
   The new houses are a mix of build-to-suits and speculative
ventures by half a dozen custom builders. The two most influential
are Metzler Hull Development Corp. and BGD&AMP;C Corp. Both are local
companies that build four or five houses a year. The houses
generally take 12 to 14 months to complete.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jay Metzler, one of the principals of Metzler Hull,
the process begins with finding land, something that has become
more difficult in the last few years. Single 25-foot-by-125-foot
lots now sell for up to $700,000 or $800,000 and the ideal is two
or more contiguous lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building a $2.8 million spec house right now on a single
lot and the land is a quarter of the price,'' Metzler said. ``We
like doing specs. They give us a chance to exercise our creativity.
We've done 12 to 15 of them over the last few years and all but one
sold well before they were finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies stress that what sells is luxurious details and
craftsmanship. ``We spend a lot of time in Europe researching
moldings, door designs and other features that people seem to have
gotten away from over here,'' said Charles Grode, vice president of
BGD&AMP;C.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   u fxxnt06 nt22 nt26 nt11 nt33 &QL; 
ufxx &QL; 
 &UR; BC-CHICAGO-MANSIONS-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CHICAGO: of BGD&AMP;C. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He added that the company recently built an 8,500-square-foot
Venetian-style home on a double lot on Burling Street that is
authentic ``right down to the chimney caps.'' The roof, he added,
is made of ``100-year-old clay tiles from a building in
Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   His customers ``want the details to be rich,'' Metzler said.
This means, as a matter of course, mahogany paneling and window
frames throughout, marble and oak floors, grand curving staircases
and _ in some houses _ 20- and 25-foot-high ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   How do they differ from the grand houses of the past? ``They
don't have ballrooms,'' said Vinci, the architect.
</P>
<P>
   What they do have, however, are children. Both companies say
that children's rooms and activities have a new prominence in most
of their houses. Metzler said he was building a roller-hockey rink
in the basement of one house and was planning a basketball court in
the basement of another. The basketball court alone, he said, will
add more than $200,000 to the cost of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an absolute dream house,'' said Elizabeth Saltzman,
who along with her husband, Richard, the owner of Banner Wholesale
Grocers, recently bought a Metzler Hull house. ``We looked at some
older houses, but we have four kids and it can be tough to find
that many bedrooms in an older house. There's a very welcoming
feeling here. People sit on their porches and stoops. The kids have
a certain freedom that they probably wouldn't have in other
neighborhoods. They can walk to the park and do things by
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Her verdict? ``As long as we can afford it, we're staying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
