<HEADLINE>
PAUL HENRY MUSSEN, 78, CHILD PSYCHOLOGIST AND AUTHOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.J., Wis., Ohio)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Henry Mussen, a child psychologist who wrote a classic
textbook and taught for 30 years at the University of California at
Berkeley, died July 7 in Berkeley. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was prostate cancer, the university said.
</P>
<P>
   Mussen's books focus on interactions between parent and child,
an emerging concern in the 1950s when the first of them were
published; they were widely translated, and a number of them remain
in print.
</P>
<P>
   He was the principal author of the seminal ``Child Development
and Personality,'' first published in 1956. It was a standard for
30 years and made Mussen the best-selling author at Harper
Textbooks for years.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote ``The Psychological Development of the Child''
(Prentice-Hall, 1963), and was the co-author of ``Roots of Caring,
Sharing and Helping'' (W.H. Freeman, 1977), ``Psychological
Development: A Life-Span Approach'' (Harper, 1979), ``Essentials of
Child Development and Personality'' (Harper, 1980), and ``The Roots
of Prosocial Behavior in Children'' (Cambridge University Press,
1989), among others.
</P>
<P>
   Mussen was the main editor of the four-volume ``Handbook of
Child Psychology.'' Its fourth edition was published by Wiley in
1983. He also edited the Annual Review of Psychology from 1968 to
1973.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mussen was born in Paterson, N.J., and graduated in 1942
from Stanford University, where he received an M.A. degree in 1943.
He then served in the Navy until 1946.
</P>
<P>
   He completed his Ph.D. in psychology at Yale University in 1949
and taught at the University of Wisconsin and Ohio State University
before joining the Berkeley faculty in 1956. He was a past director
of the Institute of Human Development at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   He traveled as a lecturer and consultant to universities
throughout Europe, the Middle East, the Far East and Australia. He
was one of the first American professors to teach in China after
the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Mussen is survived by his wife of 46 years, Ethel Foladore
Mussen; a daughter, Michele, of Berkeley; a son, Jim, of New York;
a brother, Irwin, of Berkeley; and one grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
