<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DIERBECK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT DIERBECK, DOCUMENTARY FILMMAKER, DIES AT 71  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ill., Wis.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Dierbeck, a documentary filmmaker whose interest in
science and wildlife carried him around the world, died July 7 in
New York. He was 71 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was emphysema, said his wife, Janet.
</P>
<P>
   Dierbeck produced, wrote and directed films about a wide range
of subjects, from oceanography (``The Earth and the Sea'') to
anthropology (``Nomads of the Rain Forest''), often working with
grants from the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   His 1966 documentary, ``Flying at the Bottom of the Sea,'' about
oceanographic research, was awarded the Grand Prix de la Marine
Nationale in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his films have been presented at the Margaret Mead Film
Festival and at other festivals worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career Dierbeck, who was born in Urbana, Ill., was
associate curator of education at the Milwaukee Public Museum.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring, he served as a consultant for the anthropology
department of the American Museum of Natural History and
occasionally narrated documentary films.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a daughter, Lisa
Dierbeck, of Brooklyn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
