<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DALTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK DALTON, 92, AUTHORITY IN LIBRARY STUDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ala.)   By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Dalton, who was dean of Columbia University's School of
Library Services, died on July 7 at his home in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton headed the library services school from 1959 until 1970.
The school was closed in 1992. While dean, he was a teacher as well
as an administrator, and he introduced courses in information
science into the school's curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   James S. Healey, the former director of library schools at the
University of Oklahoma and at San Jose State University in
California, studied at Columbia while Dalton was the dean.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had assembled a truly outstanding faculty, some of the best
people in our field in the world,'' Healey said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, who was born in Holland, Va., received bachelor's and
master's degrees from the University of Virginia. He took courses
at the University of Michigan in 1935 and 1936. He later was
director of the American Library Association's international
relations office from 1956 to 1959.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from Columbia, Dalton directed the Library
Development Center, which advocates better library services for the
disabled and disadvantaged. He was also a consultant to the H.W.
Wilson publishing company.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife, Mary Gochnauer Dalton, died.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his second wife, Margaret Stieg Dalton; a son,
John Preston Dalton of Tuscaloosa, Ala.; a brother, Robert, of St.
Thomas, Virgin Islands; and a sister, Antoinette Nelson of
Lynchburg, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
