<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MOLINARO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URSULE MOLINARO, A WRITER OF NOVELS AND PLAYS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Va., Hawaii)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ursule Molinaro, a novelist and translator, died Monday at her
home in New York City. She was believed to have been in her 80s,
said McPherson &AMP; Co., her publishers.
</P>
<P>
   In a career that spanned five decades, she wrote 14 novels, four
collections of short fiction and 18 one-act plays. She also
translated books and was fluent in five languages.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Paris, Molinaro was educated at the Sorbonne and the
University of London, and studied medicine in Florence, Italy.
Jailed for harboring Jews in Paris during World War II, she escaped
and joined the Resistance. After the war she became a free-lance
journalist and soon published her first book, a collection of
fables.
</P>
<P>
   She came to New York in the 1950s as a simultaneous translator
at the United Nations and adopted English as her primary language.
Her first book published here was ``Mirrors for Small Beasts''
(Noonday Press) in 1960. That year she was also one of the founders
of Chelsea magazine, a literary journal.
</P>
<P>
   Molinaro's books include ``The Borrower,'' ``Green Lights Are
Blue'' and ``Sounds of a Drunken Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   During the '60s and '70s Molinaro wrote a series of one-act
plays and translated works by such authors as Hermann Hesse,
Nathalie Sarraute and Christa Wolf for publication in English. She
also taught at Virginia Polytechnic Institute, the University of
Hawaii and New York University.
</P>
<P>
   Her most recent book, a trio of short satirical novels under the
title ``Demons and Divas,'' was published this year.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by a daughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
