<HEADER>
A3232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SPECIAL-CAMP-NYT &LR;      07-15 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPECIAL-CAMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNS COLUMN: SUMMER CAMP LIKE ANY OTHER: ORDINARY PEOPLE, ORDINARY
FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTER, N.Y. _ ``What we're going to do today,'' the drama
counselor said to the girls of Bunk One, ``is we're going to be
models. We're going to put some makeup on. Do our hair. Put on some
clothes. And then we're going to have a fashion show.''
</P>
<P>
   Out came the eyeliner, the red lipstick, the sparkly nail
polish, the scarves and fancy dresses. A camper named Lauren
declared her done-up bunk mates gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   These campers are not models in the outside world. They are
exceptions, delicately and ambiguously called special.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Camp Loyaltown, in the shadow of Hunter Mountain, they
are ordinary _ the adults with Down syndrome, the autistic
children, the emotionally and mentally limited, the childlike
spirits frozen in wrinkled, stooped bodies. They swim and sing and
put on plays and shout silly cheers in the cafeteria and pump
themselves up for a softball game against a rival camp.
</P>
<P>
   Those who can talk, do, some engagingly. Those given to hugging,
hug indiscriminately. Some are sullen and moody. Many are silent
and smiling. They produce a newspaper, The Happy Camper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a dream,'' said Vanessa Radke, 30, a counselor from
London. ``You have to come back to make sure it's real.'' She's
returned nine summers, drawn by a camper with Down syndrome named
Patty. ``She's about my age and she's just amazing,'' Radke said.
``She has very little speech. She's just so lovely. She speaks to
me with her eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   People here often refer to a short essay called ``Welcome to
Holland.'' In it, a parent likens raising a disabled child to
planning a vacation to Italy, only to have the plane land in the
Netherlands. Sorely disappointed, you find the Netherlands slower
and more drab. But eventually you discover the windmills and the
tulips and the Rembrandts. ``It's just a different trip,'' a
camper's father said.
</P>
<P>
   Each summer more than 500 people attend the camp, run by the
Nassau County chapter of the Association for the Help of Retarded
Children. Paul H. Cullen, the camp director for 22 years, hires 150
counselors and strives for an environment where the disabled ``do
not experience their handicap as interfering with their enjoyment
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a respite for parents. ``These kids are
all-consuming,'' said Sloan Ettinger, visiting her 18-year-old
stepdaughter, Brandy, who is the size of a 4-year-old and rides in
a stroller. ``Imagine having a toddler in your house for 38
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The campers stay in bunks: summer societies of complex
characters. Bunk One has Gabbi, at 13 a social butterfly with Down
syndrome, as strong-willed as she is well spoken, depending on her
mood. There is Lauren, 19, an inveterate Islanders fan with a
revolving list of favorite counselors, mostly males.
</P>
<P>
   There is Brandy, her little hands forever reaching for someone
to touch, and Melissa, 18, always willing to hold them. Chrissy,
21, is silent, but meets everyone's eye with a smile. Katie, 20,
has Down syndrome, and sometimes surprises with her enthusiasm, as
when singing ``Happy Birthday'' to campers during lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, the six baked an apple crumble, dressed for their
fashion show and made witches out of pipe cleaners and fabric.
(``It's not a witch,'' Lauren insisted. ``It's my Islanders guy!'')
Lauren complained loudly at lunch that Gabbi's banging was giving
her a headache. Brandy told her visiting stepmother in a slow,
determined voice, ``I love you, too.'' The counselors recounted the
thrill of getting Gabbi out of bed in the morning or helping
Chrissy learn to shower herself.
</P>
<P>
   In the late morning, Julie Trimble, a counselor from Belfast,
Northern Ireland, announced it was time for cooking class. Gabbi
assumed her usual traveling position _ on Julie's back. Gabbi
pressed her freckled cheek against Julie's, and they laughed and
said together what Julie always teases in her Irish lilt, ``You're
a big, lazy lump.''
</P>
<P>
   The night before had been Karaoke Night. The girls in Bunk One
had performed ``Holiday'' by Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors and campers crowded the recreation hall. The music
deafened. A bubble machine belched bubbles. Lights flashed. The
wooden floor bounced. Campers and counselors moved to the same
music. On stage, Melissa grabbed the mike. Gabbi, refusing to sing
at first, came alive, screaming wildly, dancing with her head
thrown back. Even Brandy, in the arms of a counselor, bobbed up and
down. The room was in a roar. For a moment, ``special'' and
``normal'' didn't matter. It was just camp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 1728EDT &QL; 
