<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICKING-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW GAME AT ELEMENTARY SCHOOL: PICKING YOUR CHILD'S TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE GROSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELHAM, N.Y. _ There is a new kind of finagling afoot in the
land of overachieving parents and their prized children. The game
is as stylized as a Japanese tea ceremony but the goal is simple:
handpick a child's elementary school teacher while pretending not
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Once this was a bureaucratic routine, something parents didn't
know about or figured was somebody else's job. But that was before
suburbanites picked communities based on the number of Advanced
Placement classes, spent more on SAT tutors than on college tuition
and planned a child's summer to impress the Ivy League admissions
office.
</P>
<P>
   Like any new game, this one has a set of rules, laid down with
great precision in certain places, this community in southern
Westchester County being among them. There is a window of
opportunity each spring when parents are invited to write or call
their elementary school principal to discuss the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   The contact must be made in May, before May 26 to be exact, in
at least one of the four elementary schools here. The parents are
encouraged to discuss ``learning styles'' and ``teaching styles.''
They are forbidden to say which teacher they want.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody is fooled. Mothers acknowledge writing disingenuous
letters that avoid saying ``Mr. B stinks so give me Mr. A,'' even
though that is what they mean. The principals say that if the
desired match is made, it is because parents and school
professionals usually agree about what is best for the child.
</P>
<P>
   The results of all this conniving will be seen in official
notification letters later this month, when parents are told whose
class their child will be in.
</P>
<P>
   But meanwhile, at the village pool and the Metro-North platform,
the buzz these days is about the merits of one teacher over
another: Who is strict? Who is kind? Who is stimulating? Who is
over the hill? The information is passed along the grapevine. And
accurate or not, it leaves some parents with palpitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gets a lot of airplay, but unreasonably so,'' said Gerard
Finelli, principal of Colonial Elementary School. ``Why is it given
all this attention? Isn't it a distortion? And if it gets to a
certain degree, it comes back to hurt the children. But it's
endemic to our society today.''
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, parents would not have dreamed of trying to
influence the selection process. Linda Peters, the mother of two
children at Colonial and a product of parochial schools, recalls
arriving the first day and being directed to a classroom, with no
ifs, ands or buts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You showed up and they called your name,'' said Peters, who
sells advertising for Glamour magazine. ``And with the nuns, you
got mean, meaner or meanest.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was then and this is now. So Peters was not shy when
she thought her son Trevor, now entering fourth grade, had had one
too many novice teachers. Finelli deferred to her and assigned the
boy to a seasoned hand. It was a disaster, Peters said, and she had
no one to blame but herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know about teachers is what we've heard from our
friends, and it may not be a reality,'' she said. ``I don't think
parents should have a say.''
</P>
<P>
   But parents who have not been burned by their own intervention
either meddle, consider meddling or worry about not meddling. One
Pelham mother _ and according to the principal, all of the
lobbyists have been mothers _ is already plotting how to get the
teacher she wants for the 2001-02 school year.
</P>
<P>
   And the parents who do not know the rules of the game _ some
schools publish them in their handbooks while others do not _ are
furious when they discover they have been bested by somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mysterious process, like Kabuki theater,'' said one
mother, who like many others asked not to be identified, out of
fear of retaliation against her children. ``It all happens behind
the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Pamela Arsove, an emergency room doctor and mother of two,
who was told at a July 4 barbecue that another parent had gotten a
sneak preview of the class lists and knew what teacher her daughter
was getting in fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have leaked this closely held information, Arsove
wondered. Why did it go to another mother and not to her? Was she
at a disadvantage because she spent less time at school than the
stay-at-home mothers? And how could she have slipped up and not
been a proper advocate for her child?
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like an idiot,'' Arsove said recently, acknowledging
that the July 4 shocker had produced a migraine headache, weeks of
agitation and angry telephone calls to Colonial Elementary, where
Finelli said he made a thorough inquiry and was satisfied the class
lists had not left the building.
</P>
<P>
   Arsove is one of many working mothers who are sure they suffer
for not being regulars at school. Finelli said he had heard parents
express that, ``but it's not a perception I agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   But the perception, real or imagined, is a window into the gulf
between mothers who stand sentry in the playground and supervise
field trips and those who leave for work at dawn and do not return
until dark. And a handy place for an anxious mother to see
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Peters worries that she sees the principal only ``when I have a
bone to pick,'' not an ideal way to form a trusting relationship.
And Arsove wonders how she can compete with another mother who has
had lunch with the school psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Allen, a former accountant and now a stay-at-home mother,
is saddened to hear that others feel that way, but she sees their
point.
</P>
<P>
   She runs a publishing center at Colonial, where children produce
books of their own writings, and is thus in the building virtually
every day. That means easy chitchat with the teachers, a first-name
relationship with Finelli, knowledge of who pulls the levers of
power and a sense of humor about the process that the working
mothers envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't bother the principal with every nickel-and-dime
issue,'' Allen said. ``But the school secretary _ she's the key.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
