<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PROGRESS AND PAIN ON RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 16:
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a half-century ago, in his novel ``Invisible Man,'' Ralph
Ellison wrote of a society in which whites and blacks rarely
intersected in any meaningful way, in which black people simply did
not register in the majority consciousness, except as
one-dimensional stereotypes. Yet Ellison was both an optimist and
an integrationist, and he might have been pleased to see, in The
New York Times' six-week series on race in America, that this
nation is far removed from the separatist society that he recorded
in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   The 15th and final installment in that series is an
autobiographical narrative by Don Terry, a New York Times reporter,
which appears Sunday in an issue of the Sunday magazine devoted
entirely to race. The magazine uses the same journalistic technique
that marked the series as a whole _ inviting whites and blacks to
express their feelings about race in an uninhibited way. The
results are startling _ an outpouring of hopes and grievances that
add up to a sharp, contemporary picture of how whites and blacks
think about one another and themselves, and of how they actually
interact on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   These conversations would not have been possible, however, if
America had not advanced to a point where blacks and whites, unlike
the races in Ellison's day, could share the same spaces and many of
the same dreams and aspirations. America is now an inescapably
multiracial society in many of its schools, workplaces, churches,
cultural institutions and its military. In some articles in the
series, blacks and whites did not interact much at all, living
essentially parallel lives _ the white quarterback at the
predominantly black university, for example, or the two Cubans in
Miami, thrust into separate orbits by a racially divided city.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the pieces are rich with shared activity _ in the
public schools of Maplewood, N.J., in the Akron Beacon Journal
newsroom, on the set of an HBO series, in a tank battalion at Fort
Knox, at the Assembly of God Tabernacle in Atlanta. As a New York
Times poll on race suggested last week, these are not isolated
instances of social interaction. Though most Americans still do not
live or worship with those of other races, 76 percent of whites and
84 percent of blacks said they had close friends of another race,
and equally surprising numbers _ 43 percent of whites and 58
percent of blacks _ said people of a different race had visited
their homes socially in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also confirmed dispiriting aspects of the Times series.
Although whites seem more sensitive today to the realities of black
life than they were in Ellison's time, the two races seem to be
living on different planets on issues like fairness and equal
opportunity. By an overwhelming margin, for instance, blacks said
they were treated unfairly by the police, as opposed to only one in
four whites who thought blacks were treated unfairly. Four of 10
blacks thought they had the same economic opportunities as whites,
whereas 6 in 10 whites thought the playing field was now level.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike whites, blacks live with the consequences of America's
history of discrimination every day, which may help explain why
they seemed far more willing than whites to share their thoughts
with Times reporters. While many whites expressed fatigue with
racial issues, blacks like Charles Dutton, the angry director in
the story about the HBO series, seemed eager to discuss their
feelings with a liberating bluntness.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, President Clinton and both major presidential
candidates, George W. Bush and Al Gore, made pilgrimages to the
NAACP's annual meeting. Their appearances were a reminder that this
country's next leap forward in race relations must build upon but
also reach beyond the issues that moved America in the 1960s, when
bigotry was more nakedly expressed and civil rights advocates of
both races could focus their united energies on the legal barriers
to political and educational equality.
</P>
<P>
   Today's racial divide is more subtle, but it remains a
stubbornly persistent blend of remoteness, distrust and economic
inequality. Trust, perhaps, cannot be mandated. But as Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. observed decades ago, shared prosperity and caring
communities are essential components of a healthy multiracial
society. One of the lessons of The Times' series is that this
message is as relevant at the start of the new American century as
it was in the early days of the civil rights revolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
