<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-RATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RAT FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, July 16:
</P>
<P>
   When Joseph Mitchell wrote in 1944 that ``Rats are almost as
fecund as germs,'' he was getting at something profound about our
urban nightmares. We fear the creatures that proliferate wildly _
rats and cockroaches chiefly _ because to do so they must
proliferate unseen. No really hard numbers exist on the rat
population in New York City for that very reason. One of Mitchell's
sources, an exterminator, estimated that the number of rats in the
city had dropped from two per person around 1920 to one per person
in the early 1940s, largely because of a reduction in horses and
changes in construction. Since then, one rat per person in New York
has come to seem like gospel.
</P>
<P>
   A rat is a rumor until it is seen, and then it becomes a plague.
In the past few days, since the mayor proposed a rat task force
after rat sightings at Gracie Mansion, the number of eight or nine
rats per person has been batted around, without much foundation.
The higher estimate tells us nothing about the actual number of
rats in New York, but it does say something about the revulsion
rats cause. It also says something about the fear of what one might
call the unseen New York, the basements and tunnels, crawl spaces
and plumbing that abound in our built surroundings. The more you
live in the light, the more you fear the dark, though the opposite,
of course, is true of rats.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a shock from time to time, like seeing rats at Gracie
Mansion, to re-energize the task of rat control. From a low of
about 200 employees and a budget of $5 million in the early 1990s,
the Health Department's Pest Control Bureau has grown in size to
some 375 employees and a budget of about $13 million, closer to
what it was in the 1970s. Rats are supreme opportunists, and with
every slight change in the way humans handle garbage, there is a
change in the number of rats to handle it for us. Street collection
instead of incineration, plastic bags instead of garbage cans _
each of these changes has had an impact on the rat population.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that rats will always be with us does not mean we have
to like it. Although in the broader health picture they are a
nuisance, not a threat, their fleas carry the same diseases as they
always have, and rat bites are as dangerous as ever. But rats also
communicate something besides disease. ``Away from their nests,''
Mitchell wrote, rats ``are usually on the edge of hysteria,'' and
at the sight of them we tend to know just how they feel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
