<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-TIME PAYBACK: DAUBACH PACES BOSTON
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Brian Daubach spent seven full years in the New York
Mets' organization, and he played fewer than 20 games above
Double-A. He played for the Mets' replacement team during the
strike in 1995, and he had just over a year of major league service
entering this season.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach has not forgotten that the Mets never gave him a chance,
and the Mets have not forgotten his stint as a replacement player.
Mets catcher Todd Pratt felt insulted on Friday when he said
Daubach told him to ``save it'' during an argument. Pratt called
Daubach a ``scab.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach, the Boston Red Sox' first baseman who beat the Mets
with a two-run double in the ninth inning Thursday, did not start
Saturday. He was inserted in the lineup only after Carl Everett,
another former Met, went out of control after being ejected in the
second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox may lose Everett for a while _ he bumped the
home-plate umpire Ronald Kulpa twice during the confrontation _ but
they did not miss him Saturday. Daubach ripped a three-run home run
off Mets ace Mike Hampton to break a tie and help the Red Sox to a
6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets rallied for two runs on four hits in the ninth inning,
but Derek Lowe fielded Melvin Mora's squibber and threw out Mora to
end the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, with the score tied at 2-2, a runner on
second and one out, Hampton intentionally walked Nomar Garciaparra,
baseball's leading hitter, to get to Daubach. On the first pitch,
Daubach lifted a fly ball into the netting above the tall
left-field wall, his 15th homer and just the second allowed by
Hampton in his last seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (9-6) worked seven innings, allowing six runs (five
earned) on eight hits and two walks. Ramon Martinez pitched six
solid innings to earn the victory for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The game concluded an eventful three-game series that featured
three homers by Mike Piazza _ including a bases-empty shot in the
ninth inning Saturday _ a near brawl on Friday, an ejection of
Dennis Cook on Friday and Everett Saturday, and two Red Sox
victories. The Mets traveled to Toronto after the game to face the
Blue Jays, the second team they visit on a four-city, 11-game road
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Cook was ejected for hitting Everett on Friday, and afterward
Cook stated a fact: Everett crowds the plate. The Mets accept that,
and even admire it in a way. ``I've never seen a hitter on that
much of the plate,'' Pratt said. ``That's just more respect for
him, because he can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   The plate umpire, also noticed. During Everett's first at-bat
Saturday, leading off the second, Kulpa pointed at the dirt at the
back of the batter's box, indicating where Everett should stand.
</P>
<P>
   Everett was incensed and shouted at Kulpa, who ejected him. Five
minutes of histrionics followed: Everett slammed his helmet to the
ground, bumped chests with Kulpa, then knocked his head into
Kulpa's as he screamed in the umpire's face.
</P>
<P>
   Kulpa staggered back, and as the other umpires gathered around
him, Everett's eruption continued. He shoved aside the first-base
coach, Tommy Harper, who with manager Jimy Williams was trying to
restrain him. Everett pointed repeatedly at the back of the
batter's box, and he would not leave the home-plate area.
</P>
<P>
   Things got so wild that Mets right fielder Derek Bell, a
teammate of Everett's in Houston last year, jogged in to try to
calm Everett down. Mets manager Bobby Valentine intercepted Bell
before he got to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Everett finally retreated to the dugout, where he tossed bats
and water coolers. He has much more than an equipment fine coming
his way: for bumping an umpire _ twice _ Everett will most likely
probably be reprimanded severely.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mets played, their regular third baseman, Robin
Ventura, was in New York having a magnetic resonance imaging test
performed on his ailing right shoulder. Results were not
immediately available, but Ventura seems likely to miss at least a
few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not in the lineup, and he won't be in the lineup for a
while,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Franco played third base Saturday, and Valentine said he
``could get a lot of playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was clear on one thing: Todd Zeile will not move back
to third, where he played for the last several years. Zeile has
been contributing consistently at first base after some initial
adjustments to his new position. Since May 26, Zeile has committed
only one error, on the interference call with Chuck Knoblauch
running last week.
</P>
<P>
   He has made two standout defensive plays this series. On
Thursday, he dived to his left in the eighth inning to turn a
potential extra-base hit into an out, saving a run. Saturday, Zeile
came in to field a slow roller by Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   With Hampton sprinting to first for the throw, Zeile had no time
to transfer the ball to his hand, so he shoveled it to Hampton from
his glove for the out.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
