<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH RAIN, INKSTER FINALLY HAS SOME TIME TO KILL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ Juli Inkster's biggest decision Saturday,
like that of many parents, was what to do with her two young
daughters on a rainy Saturday afternoon in the New York
metropolitan area. Inkster, the winner of three major championships
over the past 19 months, had plenty of time on her hands because
the third round of the Japan Airlines Big Apple Classic had been
postponed by heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   Should the children continue to play with the four sons of Frank
and Lynnie Mara, with whom Inkster and her family have been staying
in Port Chester, or should they venture into Manhattan to a museum?
</P>
<P>
   The decision: Let the kids draw up a storm with acrylic paints
on glass while Inkster and the Maras _ Frank Mara is the son of the
Giants co-owner Wellington Mara _ joined in the fun. Later, Inkster
and her daughters, Hayley Carol, 10, and Cori Simpson, 6, were to
have dinner in Manhattan in Little Italy and then see the hit
musical ``Swing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and the girls are having a great time,'' said Inkster, who
marked her 40th birthday by winning the McDonald's LPGA
Championship, one of the circuit's four majors, for the second year
in a row on June 25. ``We have dinner together every night and are
getting to see some of the sights. I love having them with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The role of working mom seems to suit Inkster fine. Her
daughters sometimes accompany her to tournaments, as was the case
at the McDonald's, the sixth major she has won. ``I'm even going to
take them to the British and Swedish Opens this summer,'' said
Inkster who will be the defending champion when the U.S. Women's
Open, begins Thursday in Libertyville, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, Inkster would like to win her second Big Apple
Classic _ she was a wire-to-wire winner in 1992 _ when the
tournament resumes, weather permitting, on Sunday morning at
Wykagyl Country Club. That will be a daunting task, however,
because Inkster, at 1-over 143, trails the second-round leader,
Allison Finney, by 10 strokes. Annika Sorenstam is in second place,
one stroke behind Finney.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, Sorenstam and Karrie Webb have come to dominate women's
golf, but they have also given the LPGA keen competition at its
highest level. Webb, 25, and Sorenstam, 29, have both won four
tournaments this year. Inkster has won twice. Inkster has 24 career
titles, Sorenstam 22 and Webb 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly try to keep up with them, but I don't see myself
involved in any kind of rivalry with Annika and Karrie,'' Inkster
said. ``After all, we're from two different eras; they're in their
20s, and I'm 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but Inkster is in the top three with Webb and
Sorenstam in several statistical categories on the LPGA circuit _
scoring average, rounds under par, top-10 finishes, earnings and
the race for player of the year. In three categories _ scoring
average, rounds under par and top-10 finishes _ Inkster leads
Sorenstam while trailing Webb.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, who is outgoing, witty and not afraid to show her
emotions on the course, could hardly be more different in
personality than the cool, analytical Sorenstam, who won
back-to-back U.S. Opens in 1995 and 1996, and the equally low-key
Webb, who has captured two majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're playing together _ and I like it when Annika and
Karrie are in the field with me _ I feel I have as good a shot as
they do to win,'' said Inkster who is one of only two women (Pat
Bradley is the other) to win the modern-day career Grand Slam. ``I
think it brings out the best in me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But nowadays, with my daughters and my husband, who travels
with me to some of my tournaments, golf has become secondary,''
Inkster said. ``I still work as hard as ever and I would love to
win another Open. If anything, it's easier when I have the girls
along because they take my mind off of my golf, and I'm more
relaxed when I play. That wasn't the case when I was a young
player. We have a lot of fun together, and when I'm with them I
totally forget about golf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
