<HEADLINE>
BARAK, ARAFAT STAY UP LATE FOR THIRD MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ For only the third time since the start of the
Middle East peace talks, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat met face to face, staying up until
1 a.m. Saturday in a meeting with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat reportedly had threatened to leave the summit the night
before, but by Friday night, negotiations appeared to have resumed
_ or so it seemed by the few details released by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   After the Jewish Sabbath began at sundown Friday, the three
leaders gathered for a traditional Sabbath meal at Barak's
invitation. They sat at a large table; the meal began with a
blessing and a song that was a ``blessing for the angels of
peace,'' National Security Council spokesman P.J. Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, the three men met, joined only by translators and
note takers, officials said. It was the second three-way meeting of
the talks. Earlier in the week, Arafat and Barak also had met
without Clinton present.
</P>
<P>
   While officials kept to their self-imposed news blackout,
sources within the negotiation teams told Reuters that the talks
Saturday were supposed to focus on economic elements of a potential
accord.
</P>
<P>
   But any proposal _ indeed, any peace agreement _ would almost
certainly have to be presented before Wednesday, when Clinton is
scheduled to depart for the Group of Eight economic summit in
Japan. White House officials have said they would not expect the
Mideast leaders to remain at Camp David after the US president
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   But Gadi Baltiansky, a spokesman for Barak, told Israeli radio
he could see the talks extending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any problem from our point of view, if there is a
need to stay here another three or four days so that there will be
a deal,'' Baltiansky said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
