<HEADER>
A3248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS0716-COX     07-15 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rhome doesn't rebuild QBs in a day
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Jerry Rhome has a hideous jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   He pulls the basketball deliberately around past his ear, way
back, and lets fly _ falling back _ from directly above his head.
</P>
<P>
   It ain't pretty, but the shot's history is like a window into
the style of the Falcons' new quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   Rhome, a hoops nut, is 57, slow off the dribble, short (about
5-feet-10), and can't jump a lick.
</P>
<P>
   So . . . ``I found myself playing with players all the time,''
he said. ``Players love to stuff coaches. I tried to develop a shot
that'd be harder to block. I saw a few guys (i.e. former Seattle
forward Jack Sikma) shoot the ball further back, and I said,
`There's a thought.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There's vintage Rhome, always looking for an edge, a way to
compensate or overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The guy's itinerent, coaching with Seattle, Washington, San
Diego, Dallas, Arizona, Minnesota, Houston and St. Louis since
1976.
</P>
<P>
   But he gets results. See former students Jim Zorn, Dave Krieg,
Joe Theismann, Mark Rypien, Doug Williams, Troy Aikman, Steve
Beuerlein, Warren Moon and Kurt Warner for proof.
</P>
<P>
   Think a howitzer arm is all you need to be a good NFL
quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler thought that way until he ran into Rhome in '91,
after the Bucs released him, and Arizona picked him up.
</P>
<P>
   Rhome began changing Chandler's mind the next offseason,
challenging him to basketball, golf, billiards, poker and . . .
passing games.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the bullheaded QB was cooing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for `Rock,' I'd probably be in a cheese line,''
Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes you understand why defenses do the things they do,''
Chandler said. ``He's a great teacher. It's one thing to say, `Look
to that receiver first, that one second, and that one third.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He teaches you to get around the first two steps by reading
coverages. That helps you make quicker decisions, makes you more
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhome explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget that when you look at film, you're 100 feet
tall,'' he said. ``When you're playing, you're 6-2 or whatever.
Watching film, you're looking down, you can stop it, rewind it,
slow it down; there's no pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But . . . on the field, it's like being behind trees with that
pass rush. You got to have a security blanket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blanket is to key the defense, key certain defenders, key
certain areas to know what the defense is doing so you know before
you start doing it what you're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early '60s, before the explosion of TV, fans learned of
an undersized Tulsa quarterback because his name kept appearing in
newspaper agate next to 300, 400, 500 yards of passing offense
after every game.
</P>
<P>
   Rhome set 17 NCAA passing records, and was runner-up in '64 to
Navy's Roger Staubach in Heisman Trophy voting.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves met Rhome up close.
</P>
<P>
   In '65, they were rookie roommates with the Cowboys _ one a high
draft choice, Reeves an undrafted college quarterback becoming a
running back.
</P>
<P>
   Both got by on brains.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely accurate,'' Reeves said. ``He didn't have the
strongest arm, wasn't blessed with a lot of physical ability, but
made up for it with mental ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler is ecstatic to have back his Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve Danny Kanell is smiling, too.
</P>
<P>
   After joining the team last year, he was dreadful in the
preseason while re-learning an offense that had evolved since he
played for Reeves as a rookie with the Giants in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Some Falcons officials recently theorized privately that part of
the reason was that former quarterbacks coach Steve DeBerg _ whom
Reeves said was fired in part for lack of professionalism _ didn't
work well, or at all, with Kanell.
</P>
<P>
   After playing for the Falcons in '98, at age 44, DeBerg wanted
to play again in '99.
</P>
<P>
   The team instead signed Kanell, who took DeBerg's preferred
position _ in uniform behind Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just different. I don't want to say anything bad about
anybody,'' Kanell said. ``I really like (Rhome's) personality; I
think he's going to mold well with the guys we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanell is learning quickly, when with Rhome do as Rhome does.
</P>
<P>
   ``His strengths are . . . the finer points of being a
quarterback, reading defenses, when to try to fit a ball in and
when not to. Decision-making is his strong suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
