<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hang, cover
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIANCON, France _ Lance Armstrong was in a relaxed mood as he
stepped off the podium Saturday to commemorate his fifth straight
day in the famed yellow jersey of the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   And why not.
</P>
<P>
   With the biggest test of the Tour behind him _ he and the rest
of the ever-shrinking main pack had just finished a 154-mile trek
through the southern Alps _ it appears that his lead over Germany's
Jan Ullrich was a stable one with a week left of racing before the
finish at the Champs Elysees in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong still was without a stage victory, finishing seventh
in Saturday's stage 14 from Draguigan to Briancon, the highest city
in France. With none of the overall contenders ahead of him,
Armstrong was content to allow Colombian Santiago Botero to claim
this intense mountain stage.
</P>
<P>
   Botero, who waved both hands skyward, then clinched his chest in
celebration, crossed the finish line in 7 hours, 56 minutes, 13
seconds. Armstrong finished 2:51 behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's overall time of 61 hours, 2 minutes, 33 seconds
still was 4:55 better than Ullrich, the 1997 Tour champion. The
German finished with the same time as Armstrong on Saturday,
although he crossed the finish line two places behind him. Joseba
Boleki, a Spaniard riding for the French team Festina, was third
overall, 5:52 behind Armstrong. Two French riders _ Christophe
Moreau and Richard Virenque _ occupied the fourth and fifth spots,
6:51 and 8:26 in back of Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was in such an upbeat mood that he joked with members
of the European press. His relationship with the reporters,
especially the French ones, until Saturday had been strained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I look bad?'' Armstrong replied, when asked if he was
tired after the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously, it was a long day, a hard day. There was a lot of
wind, but that's nothing new to this Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard day for everybody. It was a long time to be on a
bike. Probably too long.''
</P>
<P>
   The group of riders started at 9:30 a.m. and did not get to
Briancon until after 5. Temperatures on this picture-perfect day
were more crisp than cold, as they had been in the two previous
mountain stages. Instead of rain, fog and wintry conditions, the
cyclists were greeted with blue skies and temperatures near 60.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong rode at an almost casual pace, with his U.S. Postal
Service teammates, including Austinite Kevin Livingston, closely
guarding their leader at the front of the peloton, or main group.
By the final climb, Armstrong had left his teammates to join the
group chasing Botero. But he did not press to catch the Colombian.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's strategy allowed Botero to accomplish what he called
his biggest feat as a cyclist. He is the first Colombian to win a
stage in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombia is experiencing a very serious crisis right now,''
said Botero, the lone rider from his country still in the Tour.
``I'm happy to have brought a positive note to this crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Armstrong could be the first overall Tour champion
not to have won a stage on the way to Paris since American Greg
LeMond won in 1990. Armstrong won four last year _ the prologue,
two individual time trials and the first mountain stage. He has
finished second four times this Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to keep the jersey,'' Armstrong said. ``When
there's a breakaway, and the riders are 20 or 30 minutes behind, it
doesn't effect the overall standings. It's easier to stay together
as a team if we all ride together.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gorski, the general manager of Team Postal, said ``it would
have made no sense for Lance to have tried to win today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventh place absolutely is wonderful,'' Gorski said. ``It's
exactly where he needed to be. Why should he have expended energy
today to try to win the stage, when he'll need the energy tomorrow.
Stage wins are irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
