<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-IRVIN-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ``PLAYMAKER'' EXPOUNDS ON RETIREMENT AND MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He had just retired, and now former Cowboys receiver Michael
Irvin took off his shoes, put up his feet and relaxed on a couch in
the green room at the Fox Sports studios in the Las Colinas area of
Irving, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   As he loosened the tie on his mustard suit ensemble and leaned
his head back, Irvin quipped to his interviewer, ``Man, you are
going to have to talk to me like one of those doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   A whirlwind day, which marked the end of Irvin's illustrious and
controversial 12-year football career, finally was starting to wind
down.
</P>
<P>
   And Irvin, whose final four years were nothing like his first
eight on or off the field, was ready to let go.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly affable and ubiquitous, Irvin had grown reserved and
mistrusting following a 1996 felony drug conviction. He still could
be outgoing and engaging at times, but he was a hermit compared
with his larger-than-life image during the height of the Cowboys'
run to Super Bowl titles in 1992, 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin said the threat of a 20-year prison term if he violated
his four years of probation caused the change. So did the fears of
being at the mercy of others, like the inventors of fraudulent rape
charges. As a result, Irvin felt confined in his own mental prison
the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Irvin was not able to find the solace on the field as he
did in the past. A bad relationship with former Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey the past two years had the team's all-time leading receiver
contemplating retirement even before the neck injury that forced
him from the game was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Following his retirement announcement Wednesday, ``The
Playmaker'' expounded on these and other issues to
``Star-Telegram'' staff writer Clarence E. Hill Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This a bittersweet day because you didn't want to leave the
game. But this is a good time in your life for another reason. You
fulfilled the terms of your four-year probation last week and now
you are a free man again. In many ways, it's a new beginning for
you.
</P>
<P>
   A: It feels great to be off probation. I got that monkey off my
back. That probation was a monkey. I'm looking forward to starting
fresh. Let's see what I can make out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the hardest part for you?
</P>
<P>
   A: The toughest part was knowing that I wasn't going to be able
to control a great deal of things. There are many issues and things
I worry about that could have went down that I had no control over,
and I was subject to doing 20 years over. I worried about that
every day. There's nothing more frightening than knowing that
something could happen today that could send you to prison for 20
years. I promise you it was scary. So I'm glad it's done.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many people would find it hard to believe that the Michael
Irvin who defied the establishment by wearing a fur coat in the
courtroom was scared about anything. Specifically, what frightened
you the most?
</P>
<P>
   A: I worried about some nut out there in the world slipping
something into my drink, and I'm taking all those NFL drug tests. I
was worried about somebody saying I did something to them or
setting them up. And I had no grounds to fight back. I worried from
that standpoint. It was just scary.
</P>
<P>
   You'd sit around and things would pop up and you were like, ``I
wasn't there. I don't know anything about that.'' It's then that
you realize just how fragile this probation thing can be. You
realize how one little thing can mean 20 years for you. You start
saying, ``I'm going to watch what I do and watch where I go.'' But
then you realize it ain't just me. I can do all those things and it
still might not work out for me. That's scary. You can't control
all of that. I had to develop the attitude that no matter what
happened, if I was around it or anywhere near it, I was guilty.
That's scary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you cope?
</P>
<P>
   A: Honestly, I did a hell of a lot better job the last four
years than I did before or I wouldn't be in this situation. First
of all, I definitely tried to watch where I was and who I was with.
In all seriousness, I would joke when I was leaving places with my
wife and my boys. If I was leaving around 10 or 11 at night, I
would yell out, ``Excuse me, but would somebody make a note that
I'm leaving the restaurant at 11 p.m.'' People would start
laughing, thinking that's just Michael being Michael. And I would
say, ``We can laugh but somebody will make a note because I said
it.'' It brought that kind of reality for me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You had to learn then what the NFL is trying to teach the
younger players in light of the Ray Lewis murder trial about
watching who you hang out with. What advice do you have for them in
avoiding what happened to you?
</P>
<P>
   A: First of all, they need to stay out of trouble and do the
right thing in the first place. But they also need to watch who
they hang with. And that's a hard thing on a young
African-American, a young brother. ... You grew up with a lot of
those people. As a man you don't want to feel like you are turning
your back on people that helped you, or people that you grew up
with and people that came from the same situation you came from. It
really is a fine line you have to walk. I was scared to go back
home and deal with some people because I knew the situation that
could happen. So I just chose not to go back home, instead of
telling people I couldn't hang out with them. I couldn't put myself
in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You were on top of the world before all this. Well, you
certainly owned Dallas. After the conviction, you lost everything,
money, image and friends. You have to have some regrets?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure, I'd be lying if didn't. It would be great if it never
happened. But it's still great. I don't call it regrets, though.
It's during those moments that you find out so much. We always
yearn to know what's real in our life, who's real in our life and
who loves and why they love us. I found out a lot about those
people. I lost a great deal with what I went through. I lost a lot
emotionally. I lost a lot financially. I lost a great deal.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm blessed that my wife Saudi didn't go anywhere, she sees
greater things. I'm blessed that way. That's a blessing because I
found out who's there for real. You go through your life now with
people who you know love you. I'm sorry to the people I hurt. I
have said it before, I said it a 100 times. You can never say it
enough. I don't know if people will ever forget it. They shouldn't.
It is my reality. But it is behind me. Thank God I'm here and have
something to look forward to and start over.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What you did was wrong. However, some people did things that
perhaps were worse. Former Rams cornerback Darryl Henley is in
prison now for drug trafficking. Former Chiefs running back Bam
Morris is awaiting trial on a similar charge, as is former Cowboys
running Sherman Williams. Former Cowboys linebacker Thomas
Henderson admitted to using drugs in the Super Bowl. Yet you were
considered the poster child for today's bad-boy athletes. Was that
fair?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, I'm the bad boy. That's how people look at me. But the
reality is those guys haven't carried the weight I carried, with
Super Bowls, publicity and the things I've accomplished. They
haven't benefited the way I benefited from those things. When I got
suspended, a letter came from Mr. (Paul) Tagliabue, the NFL
commissioner, saying the regular suspensions would have been this.
But since I played for the Cowboys and me being who I am I got to
get this greater suspension. I didn't understand it then, but I
understand it now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The past two years were tough on you on the field. You were
the subject of trade talks before last season and even went into
training camp with the threat of the Cowboys possibly cutting you
if you didn't accept the role Chan Gailey had planned. How did that
experience affect your love for the game and your decision to
retire?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know, part of me still wants to play. It would be nice to
play with a new coach. But the way things went on with me the last
couple of years made it easier for me to leave the game. Let me say
it this way: I'm a guy built on loyalty. My game is played on
loyalty. I give loyalty to the guys I played with and the guys I
played for. When I go on the field I give them all I got and they
give me back loyalty. Once I receive back less than what I gave,
when we are talking about loyalty, it takes away from what I give
you on the football field. That's the best way I can put it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What type of team do you the think the Cowboys will have
without you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think they will be fine. They are fast team. The object was
to improve speed on offense and they did that. I'll put Joey
Galloway and Rocket Ismail in a two-man race against anybody in the
league. The Cowboys are going to be fine. Dave Campo was a great
hire. And I'm going to be rooting for them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Beyond playing the game, what will you miss the most?
</P>
<P>
   A: Playing with Emmitt (Smith) and Troy (Aikman). There's
nothing like those two guys. We had such an appreciation and love
for one another. I don't think we understand how special we were
together. But what we did and what kind of team we three were
together, that was a blessing. It was special.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
