<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3257 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-LEWIS-BOTHA-NYT &LR;      07-15 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-BOTHA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS, DEFEATING BOTHA, RETAINS TITLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With a brutal left-right, left-right combination,
Lennox Lewis retained his World Boxing Council and International
Boxing Federation heavyweight titles Saturday night with a
second-round knockout of Frans Botha.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is 37-1-1 with 29 knockouts. Botha is 40-3-1 with 24
knockouts but has been stopped three times _ by Michael Moorer,
Mike Tyson and now Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by music from the movie ``Rocky,'' Botha arrived in
the ring wrapped in what appeared to be a white buffalo skin,
befitting his ``White Buffalo'' nickname. When he disrobed, the
skin was unceremoniously dumped on the concrete floor below the
steps to his corner where American and South African flags waved.
</P>
<P>
   More than four minutes later, Lewis, without a robe but preceded
by a flagbearer with the Union Jack, slowly paraded to the ring
under a veil of smoke and orange spotlights.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the cautious first round, Lewis staggered Botha
with an overhand right to his blond goatee. The South African, who
now lives in Newport Beach, Calif., quickly regained his footing
but kept moving backward, more intent on defense than on throwing
any serious punches.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, that left-right, left-right combination by Lewis
put Botha through the ropes in Lewis' corner. Botha crawled back
into the ring but the referee, Larry O'Connell, waved his arms
after 2 minutes 39 seconds of the round.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell, incidentally, was the judge who scored the debatable
draw between Lewis and Evander Holyfield early last year at Madison
Square Garden in New York City. When he was announced as the
referee Saturday night at the London Arena, he was booed by the
estimated crowd of 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very special to come back home and show the people how
much I've improved,'' said Lewis, alluding to his first fight in
London since being knocked out by Oliver McCall in 1994. ``It was a
good stoppage by the referee. When the referee asked him to come
forward, he was still wobbly.''
</P>
<P>
   Before and after Saturday night's title fight, Mike Tyson hung
on the horizon with the charm of an approaching thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewis was asked after Saturday night's knockout if he had a
message for Tyson, the champion said, ``Tell Mike to either put up
or shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was reportedly in Phoenix, his latest home in a long line
of homes from Brooklyn to upstate New York correctional addresses
to Catskill, N.Y., to New Jersey to Ohio to an Indiana prison to
Connecticut to Las Vegas to Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Lewis has a mandatory IBF title defense scheduled
against David Tua of New Zealand in November (possibly in Toronto),
Lewis has acknowledged that Tyson might be a future opponent.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Frank Bruno, once Britain's heavyweight pride who
is still more popular than Lewis, to warn Lewis that he ``better
watch out'' for the former heavyweight champion, who leveled Lou
Savarese in 38 seconds three weeks ago in Glasgow. And that
provoked Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this guy talking about?'' Lewis has been saying.
``This is the same geezer who turned into a statue in the ring
against Tyson. And he's telling me to watch out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not go in there and fight Tyson the way he did and go
in looking the way he did beforehand, when he kept making signs of
the cross. I don't think that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson dethroned Bruno as the WBC heavyweight champion in Bruno's
first defense of that title, in 1996. The Jamaica-born Bruno had
won the WBC title from Oliver McCall and in 1994 Lewis, then an
undefeated heavyweight on the rise, stopped Bruno in the seventh
round at Wembley.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter where or when Lewis fights Tyson, it is doubtful
the bout would be anywhere in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is more persona non grata than ever in Britain after two
farcical appearances _ a second-round knockout of the incompetent
Julius Francis in London on Jan. 29, and the ridiculously quick
knockout of Savarese when Tyson pushed the referee to the canvas
and later snarled on television that he wanted to rip out Lewis'
heart and eat the champion's children.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Lewis, still a bachelor at 34, has no children.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Tyson's talk about wanting to fight Lewis, he also
acknowledged that he was not ready for a title bout, that he needed
two or three more fights to sharpen his punches. His next opponent
is expected to be Andrew Golota, the Polish heavyweight with a
history of below-the-belt punches _ the perfect lighted match to
toss into the Tyson powder keg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
