<HEADER>
A3258 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0716-COX     07-15 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Voter apathy growing
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service Voters are more disengaged in the
<TEXT>
presidential race this year than at any time in recent history,
according to a recent survey of American attitudes towards
politics. Good economic times and a sense that there is little
difference between Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush
has lulled voters into ``a rather pleasant sleep,'' pollster Andrew
Kohut of the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press said
Friday.
<P>
   The poll found that only 46 percent of registered voters said
they have thought a lot about the election, down from 55 percent in
1996 and 63 percent in the same period in 1992. Low interest was
especially found in young and middle-age voters. Flagging voter
interest could result in record low voter turnout this fall, Kohut
said.
</P>
<P>
   NETWORKS IFFY ON COVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's farewell address to his fellow Democrats at
next month's party convention in Los Angeles might not be broadcast
by the major TV networks. NBC News last week released a plan that
calls for only two and a half hours of coverage for each convention
on its last two nights. NBC plans to air Clinton's Aug. 14
scheduled address on sister station MSNBC. Meanwhile, ABC is
planning to televise a preseason football game on the night a
two-term president who survived impeachment bids adieu to his
party. CBS this week is expected to announce its coverage plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech is expected to be carried on PBS, CNN, MSNBC,
Fox News and C-Span.
</P>
<P>
   NADER AND VENTURA MEET
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader and Jesse Ventura got together Friday to commiserate
about how tough it is to get money, recognition and ballot space
for a third party. Nader, the Green Party presidential candidate,
and Ventura, the Minnesota governor, met for nearly an hour in the
governor's office in St. Paul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear what happens whenever a third-party movement
begins to gain strength. The two major parties come together and do
whatever they can to squash that third party,'' said Ventura, who
now carries the banner of the Independence Party. They talked about
getting better ballot access for third parties and lowering the
cutoff from 15 percent to 5 percent support for allowing candidates
into national debates.
</P>
<P>
   GOP TO HONOR TEAMSTER
</P>
<P>
   Republicans plan to hold a reception honoring Teamsters
president James P. Hoffa on July 31, the first night of their
party's Philadelphia convention. The announcement Thursday by Jim
Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee,
underlined the Republicans' desire to win support from the
1.4-million-member Teamsters union, which Gore has heavily courted.
Nicholson said this would be the first time in at least 20 years
that the Republicans have held a convention reception for a union
president.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
