<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS0716-COX     07-15 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer wonderland
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Only one matter is certain.
</P>
<P>
   The team that opens training camp Monday in Wichita Falls has
had a radical face lift. These aren't the Cowboys that sputtered to
an 8-8 record in 1999 and bowed out of the playoffs after a week.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to keep up with the free-spending Washington Redskins,
the Cowboys quietly made some heady moves of their own this spring.
They have welcomed a new coach, a high-profile reserve quarterback,
two linebackers who might start immediately, a tight end with Super
Bowl experience, one of the NFL's fastest wide receivers and three
rookie cornerbacks who hope to be more than camp fodder.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Cowboys are deeper at positions that gave
them fits last season. Owner Jerry Jones hasn't made this many
off-season moves during his 12 years in Dallas. He reasoned that
the Cowboys needed an overhaul before their once-powerful engine
died of natural causes.
</P>
<P>
   Without these changes, there is no way Dallas would contend with
the hated Redskins, whose talent pool makes them the favorites to
win the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   How good are the Cowboys? No one knows for sure, but the goal is
to improve on last season's 8-8 record and be one game better than
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   HERE ARE 10 QUESTIONS THEY HOPE TO ANSWER DURING CAMP:
</P>
<P>
   Is Dave Campo the right man to be head coach?
</P>
<P>
   He already has been endorsed by the players, which gives him an
edge over his predecessor. Campo, who turns 53 on Tuesday, has been
a loyal assistant since 1989, the year Jones bought the team. The
former defensive coordinator has been given credit for much of the
team's success during the Super Bowl years.
</P>
<P>
   Some have questioned whether Campo will be a ``puppet'' for
Jones, an idea that makes both men bristle. Jones, as owner and
general manager, has a right to be involved in every personnel
matter, and Campo understands this.
</P>
<P>
   Campo is not an egomaniac _ remember Jimmy Johnson? _ and does
not command attention or credit. After 11 years as a respected
assistant, he deserves a chance to be the boss. It's up to Jones to
give him some breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   Will an offense that ranked 16th in the NFL last season improve?
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Cowboys, particularly quarterback Troy
Aikman, will be more comfortable this year. Aikman has had a good
relationship with new offensive coordinator Jack Reilly and new
team adviser Ernie Zampese, who ran the offense from 1994 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman struggled for two years in Chan Gailey's offensive
system. Reilly and Zampese will run an offense that helped Dallas
win three Super Bowls. That's when Emmitt Smith ran between the
offensive tackles, Aikman's timing passes were on the money and the
offensive line relied on man-on-man blocking.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's zone blocking and dump-off passes did not exploit the
Cowboys' strengths. If Aikman believes he has five good years left,
this is the time to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Who will anchor the defense?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys hope it's defensive end Greg Ellis, whose '99 season
ended when he broke his leg in December. He has progressed quicker
than expected, though. He was scheduled to begin running in July
but was running in minicamp in May.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis is a borderline All-Pro who has become the most consistent
defensive lineman in Dallas. The Cowboys did not have enough depth
to replace him when he got hurt seven months ago, one reason they
faded down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Another player the Cowboys are banking on is veteran Leon Lett,
who improved his bench-press from 405 pounds to 500 pounds in the
off-season. With Alonzo Spellman and Chad Hennings back, the
defensive line is one of the team's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone replace Deion Sanders?
</P>
<P>
   Ryan McNeil, please take a bow. No one expects the eight-year
pro to match Prime Time's overall game, but McNeil is no slouch. He
was the No. 1 pick of the Detroit Lions in the 1993 draft and also
spent time in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil and veteran Kevin Smith are beyond their prime years, so
the Cowboys selected three cornerbacks in the draft. Dwayne
Goodrich, Kareem Larrimore and Mario Edwards will get plenty of
camp work.
</P>
<P>
   At safety, George Teague and Darren Woodson provide a talented
safety blanket when the cornerbacks get beat.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Cowboys have a proven place-kicker in camp?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. Richie Cunningham was cut during the '99 season
after getting off to a bad start and will not be invited back.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Hoffman has an uncanny knack for finding
high-quality kickers few have heard of.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Chris Boniol?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will have some rookies try out for the job, but it
will not be a surprise if they sign someone cut by another team.
</P>
<P>
   You never know when ancient Eddie Murray will get an emergency
call.
</P>
<P>
   What do the Cowboys expect from Dat Nguyen?
</P>
<P>
   More than most people realize. Nguyen, who bench-presses an
incredible 500 pounds, will be the starting linebacker when camp
opens Monday. Whether he keeps the job remains to be seen. The
Cowboys will miss Randall Godfrey, who tested the free-agent waters
and went to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas quietly signed a pair of linebackers from the Tennessee
Titans this spring. Joe Bowden, a nine-year pro from Oklahoma, and
Barron Wortham, a seven-year pro from Texas-El Paso, have talent
and Super Bowl experience.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is expected to supplant Darren Hambrick at strong-side
linebacker. As for Wortham, he will be pressed to play if the
undersized Nguyen cannot withstand the pounding.
</P>
<P>
   Which newcomer will be the biggest surprise?
</P>
<P>
   Remember this name: Jackie Harris. The former Tennessee Titan
was outstanding in the Super Bowl. He is a good blocker who will
also play in two-tight end sets. That should enable veteran David
LaFleur to become more involved in the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, LaFleur has been a disappointment since he
became the team's top draft choice in 1997. To be fair, he has not
been used the way former Cowboy Jay Novacek was during his heyday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will revert to their old offensive playbook, which
features more work for the tight ends. In Harris, the Cowboys have
a good-hands receiver who is capable of starting if LaFleur
flounders.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Cowboys miss Michael Irvin?
</P>
<P>
   Do the Bulls miss Michael Jordan? Of course. No matter what
people think of him, Irvin was immensely popular among his
teammates. Few, if any, have worked harder in training camp, and
Irvin often motivated others to work harder.
</P>
<P>
   Before Irvin suffered his neck injury last season in
Philadelphia, he still was a productive receiver, capable of
catching more than 80 passes per season. He was Aikman's favorite
target because he ran precise routes. Irvin, bigger and stronger
than most of the players who covered him, rarely was pushed around
at the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the locker room, no player was more upbeat and respected
than this future Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   Is Joey Galloway as good as advertised?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Galloway has never played for a quarterback with Aikman's
credentials, and it will not be a surprise if he catches 90 passes.
He already has been tabbed the team's No. 1 receiver, a label Irvin
had for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway had a terrible season last year, stemming from a bitter
contract dispute in Seattle. In the previous four years, he
averaged 65 catches and nine touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway is another reason the Cowboys let go of Sanders.
Galloway has scored four touchdowns on punt returns and has a
career average of 10 yards per return. With Rocket Ismail as the
No. 2 passing target, Dallas should have one of the fastest tandems
of receivers in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Is Randall Cunningham worth the gamble?
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time in Aikman's career that he has had a
backup quarterback with first-team ability. Cunningham, 37, has
been such a good player for most of his career, last year's
collapse in Minnesota was a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas offers Cunningham a fresh start with eager teammates.
Longtime Cowboy Jason Garrett, who has signed with the Giants, was
a popular and steady reserve, but he lacks Cunningham's arm
strength and athletic ability. If Aikman goes down, Dallas has
someone who has tasted success a starter. His mission: to prove
last year's confidence breakdown was a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
