<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3260 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-POINTS-HNS     07-15 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POINTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NASCAR drivers could benefit from F1, CART, IRL formulas
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Defending Winston Cup champion Dale Jarrett should walk into the
NASCAR offices immediately and insist the points system be changed
to the one used by CART.
</P>
<P>
   If that were the case, Jarrett would be out in front of the
points standings after 18 races instead of ranking third behind
Bobby Labonte and Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart, Rusty Wallace and Jeff Burton also could climb up
a few notches if Winston Cup was using any other points system of a
major racing series _ be it CART, the IRL or Formula One.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the drivers who would benefit from a change,
they are stuck with a NASCAR points system that is drastically
different from the other three.
</P>
<P>
   Other racing series use fewer points per race and place more of
an emphasis on winning and finishing near the front.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's system is based on consistency and awards points to all
43 drivers who make the field. Formula One gives points for only
the first six finishing spots and CART distributes points for the
first 12 spots.
</P>
<P>
   In F1, there is a 40 percent difference between winning and
finishing second (10 points to six). In CART and the IRL, it's a 20
percent drop unless the second-place driver wins the pole and leads
the most laps. Then it is a 10 percent difference.
</P>
<P>
   But in NASCAR, it is possible for the winner and the
second-place driver to earn the same amount of points in a race.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a winner of a Winston Cup race earns a minimum of
180 points _ 175 for the victory and five bonus points for leading
a lap. The second-place finisher earns 170 points, but that driver
can receive five bonus points for leading a lap and five more for
leading the most laps.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean both drivers would earn 180 points. That
scenario happened in the Pepsi 400 at Daytona Beach two weeks ago
when Burton won and Jarrett was the runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   The most points a Winston Cup winner can receive is 185, which
is only 8 percent more than the driver who finishes second and 10.8
percent more than third place.
</P>
<P>
   The good part of the NASCAR points system is that a driver isn't
penalized as much for a poor finish. However, that also makes it
more difficult for contending drivers to catch up to the leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is consistency,'' Labonte said. ``Somebody could come
up and win five races, but right now, I would take the one win I
have and a lot of second-place finishes over five wins and a lot of
DNFs (did not finish).''
</P>
<P>
   For the last seven years, the leader at the halfway point of the
Winston Cup season has gone on to win the championship.
</P>
<P>
   The driver in front at midseason knows as long as he finishes in
the top 10 every week, it is unlikely anyone will catch him for the
points lead. But finishing eighth in an F1 or CART event while the
guy chasing you wins the race probably is going to be costly.
</P>
<P>
   The points leader in Winston Cup can afford to drive less
aggressively than the leader in other racing series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start racing for points instead of racing to win,'' said
Burton. ``I don't like that. I don't like racing for points. I
don't think anyone does.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, Labonte's teammate at Joe Gibbs Racing, has run as well
as anyone over the last six weeks. Stewart has three victories in
the last six races, climbing from ninth to fifth in the points
standings.
</P>
<P>
   However, had NASCAR been using any other points system, Stewart
would be nearer the top _ fourth in both the CART and IRL systems
and second in F1, only two points behind Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   The most points a driver can make up in one race is 151, but
Stewart still is 215 points behind Labonte. In the other three
systems, he would be within the points he could earn in one race.
</P>
<P>
   The most consistent top-five finisher this season has been
Jarrett, who has finished in one of the top-five spots 10 times. If
NASCAR was using the CART points system, Jarrett would be seven
points ahead of Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   But three drivers in the top 10 should be glad NASCAR doesn't
adopt one of the other ways of distributing points. Ward Burton, in
fourth place, would move down at least four spots in the other
systems because he has only three finishes in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who is only 45 points behind Labonte, would move down
in the other three point systems, which wouldn't reward him as much
for the eight times he has finished sixth through 10th.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
