<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CAMPO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 29 YEARS, CAMP CAMPO FINALLY ARRIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dave Campo has waited 29 years for this moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys' first-year head coach, in his first year as
head coach at any level, celebrates his 53rd birthday Tuesday, the
same day the Cowboys begin two-a-day workouts in their third summer
of training camp in Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   All players are due to be in camp and checked into their
dormitory rooms at Midwestern State University by Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Campo is more than just a catchy name for a blend of
something old and something new: old ideals brought back for a new
start under Campo, a member of the Cowboys' coaching staff since
1989 who has worked under Jimmy Johnson, Barry Switzer and Chan
Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen firsthand what it took for the Cowboys to win three
Super Bowls in the 1990s, Campo is bringing back ``a family
atmosphere,'' along with crisper practices, an emphasis on fewer
penalties and a new-look coaching staff that is committed to
teaching players what needs to be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who are coming off an 8-8 season in which they were
eliminated in the first round of the playoffs for the second
consecutive year, have returned to a basic offensive philosophy
that allowed Troy Aikman to flourish in the '90s, and have updated
it to include many of the packages used by the St. Louis Rams to
win a Super Bowl last season.
</P>
<P>
   You can't begin to talk about Camp Campo without talking about
the return of former Cowboys quarterback coach Jack Reilly as
offensive coordinator and of former Cowboys offensive coordinator
Ernie Zampese as offensive consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Or the addition of Wes Chandler (wide receivers) and Andre
Patterson (defensive tackles) to the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Or the promotion of Mike Zimmer (defensive coordinator) and Bill
Bates (secondary).
</P>
<P>
   Campo believes that this is the Cowboys' best collection of
``teaching'' assistants since the '89 season, when Jerry Jones
bought the team and brought in Johnson from the University of
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't throw the ball out there anymore; you have to
coach,'' Campo said. ``One of the things that we felt gave us an
advantage in 1989 (leading up to the Super Bowl years) was that we
had a bunch of teachers on the staff. This staff that we have now
can really teach, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on teaching comes along at an appropriate time for
the Cowboys, who, Campo said, ``are becoming a young team again,''
particularly at cornerback, linebacker, defensive end, wide
receiver and fullback, and in the kicking game.
</P>
<P>
   To maximize the learning process for both young and old players,
Campo has cut out much of the fat from the workout schedule. Four
months of voluntary, twice-a-week workouts at Valley Ranch during
the off-season were replaced by two minicamps and two quarterback
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Each practice also has been tightened up, which will carry over
to Camp Campo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be a quick-strike, fast-break type of
offense, then we've got to get up on the line of scrimmage and get
going,'' Campo explained.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Cowboys are returning to an offense that uses more
personnel packages, motions and shifts than were used in the Gailey
offense, an up-tempo philosophy is deemed necessary to give Aikman
enough time at the line of scrimmage to read the defense. Campo has
even added a 40-second play clock to practice.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage Campo has over his predecessors, particularly
Gailey, is that he hasn't had to prove himself to veteran players.
Campo knows them. They know Campo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave may be only 5-foot-6, but he's probably the feistiest guy
on the field,'' said strong safety Darren Woodson, a five-time Pro
Bowl selection.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Campo is eager to get started is an understatement.
He spent the first 29 years of his career as an assistant,
including 18 years at the high-school level and stints with 11
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a player, I would like to play for Dave Campo,''
owner Jerry Jones said. ``His style is very comfortable and
enthusiastic, yet firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp Campo begins Monday, although it actually takes the field
for the first time at 9 a.m. Tuesday, followed by a 4 p.m. workout.
Each session lasts about two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Discipline will be a big part of Camp Campo. The Cowboys
finished last season as the NFL's most penalized team with 125
penalties for 1,109 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage I have is that I do know the people here,''
Campo said. ``And I think I already have had a certain amount of
respect within the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The working relationships between Campo and Jones and between
Campo and Reilly are clearly defined and shouldn't pose a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to call plays,'' Campo said. ``I'm going to
manage the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As for working with Jones, who serves as owner and general
manager, Campo said: ``Jerry wants to win a Super Bowl. And I do,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo and his wife, Kay, have six children. With the Cowboys in
training camp, the Campos have about 80 additions to their family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at a football team like a family,'' Campo said. ``You
teach your players just like you teach your kids at home _ same way
_ through repetition.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
