<HEADLINE>
WILL OWNER'S SPENDING SPREE PAY OFF FOR REDSKINS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It apparently wasn't enough for the Washington Redskins to win
the NFC East last season. They have gone out and bought their way
into the role of conference favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Daniel Snyder, who reminds NFL observers of a young Jerry
Jones, seems intent on beating the Cowboys' owner at his own game
by putting his money where his mouth is and buying marquee players
through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, despite a $62.172 million NFL salary cap, were
able to land cornerback Deion Sanders, defensive end Bruce Smith,
safety Mark Carrier and quarterback Jeff George by signing them to
long-term, cap-friendly deals with large signing bonuses spread
over the length of their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The signing bonuses for Sanders, Smith, Carrier and George alone
total $17.25 million, including $8 million for Sanders, who was
waived by the Cowboys because of salary-cap reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, meanwhile, made room under their salary cap by
releasing veteran running back/return man Brian Mitchell and
restructuring the contracts of defensive tackle Dana Stubblefield
and safety Sam Shade.
</P>
<P>
   Going into this weekend, the Redskins were expected to pay close
to $20 million more in signing bonuses to sign their top two draft
picks _ Penn State linebacker LaVar Arrington and Alabama offensive
tackle Chris Samuels. They were the second and third draft
selections overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins have budgeted $5 million as a signing bonus for
defending NFC rushing champion Stephen Davis, but that might not be
enough. Davis' agent, Steve Weinberg, wants a long-term deal with
considerably more than $5 million up front before his client will
report for training camp this week.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has received the team's ``franchise player'' tag after
turning down the Redskins' five-year, $31 million offer in
February. Still, Davis has made it known that he will refuse a
one-year deal, including the $3.5 million tender a running back
with the ``franchise player'' label will be paid under NFL rules
for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, life has become much more complicated for the
Redskins, who hadn't made the playoffs since 1992 before winning
the NFC East last season with a 10-6 record. They lost to Tampa
Bay, 14-13, on the road in the divisional playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The heat is on Norv Turner, although that is nothing new. The
former Cowboys offensive coordinator was on the hot seat last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive losses to Buffalo and Philadelphia, followed by a
Dec. 5 loss at Detroit, drew whispers of the Redskins blowing their
division lead over Dallas and the New York Giants. But the Redskins
finished strong, winning three of their last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Turner is expected to get the Redskins into the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   While Turner runs the offense, which will have the accurate Brad
Johnson at quarterback with veteran George in reserve, the
Redskins' defense has been turned over to Ray Rhodes, who was fired
after one season as head coach in Green Bay. Washington ranked 30th
on defense in the NFL last season.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders, Smith and Carrier are expected to improve that area
with their collective talent, experience and leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders will team with second-year man Champ Bailey to give the
Redskins one of the NFL's best cornerback tandems, while
40-year-old Darrell Green enters his 18th NFL season as probably
the best non-starting cornerback in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, Smith and Green will share the cover of the Redskins'
2000 media guide, although Green has had to be digitally inserted
into the layout because he missed the photo shoot in order to be
with his ailing father in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Green received his own pile of money from Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-time Pro Bowl selection was signed this off-season to
a five-year, $10 million contract that included a $2 million
signing bonus, or roughly twice as much as Green was to make under
the terms of his existing contract.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time to find out if all that money pays off for Snyder
and the Redskins. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
