<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO GIVE TRAINING CAMPS THE BOOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, yes. Wichita Falls, Texas, beckons on the northern horizon.
A city once famous for red draws and the swimming pool party in
``The Last Picture Show'' now also hosts the biggest waste of time
in professional sports _ an NFL training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys are coming back Monday. Wichita Falls is
proud. Everybody else is, well, resigned, which has nothing to do
with the cultural aspects of Wichita Falls. It's ``any'' training
camp anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a league that has been so progressive in all other areas,
training camp is the one thing that was never updated, never
changed,'' Daryl Johnston said Friday, while also noting that it's
times like these that make him a happy recent retiree from the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of training camp goes back to at least the '50s,
when players had to work a second job in the off-season to make
ends meet,'' Johnston added. ``They came to training camp to get
into football-playing physical condition. They needed six weeks and
a bunch of games. But today's players are ready to play, basically
right now. Yet the league is still in the 50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on, what else, money. Training camp is, of course, set
up around the exhibition season _ a minimum of four preseason
games, and for the Cowboys, usually five. This summer is no
exception with a trip to Japan mixed in.
</P>
<P>
   The home exhibitions have become revenue sources the owners are
not willing to give up. Therefore, as the Cowboys report Monday,
they are still seven weeks from opening the regular season. The
veteran players privately gripe like crazy at this concept
(Johnston is much more outspoken now that's he's retired), but from
summer to summer, nothing changes. Players have long advocated
adding two regular-season games to give the owners their revenue,
while also trimming the six weeks of training camp back to three.
But it's always the same ol' same ol'.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has six weeks of spring training, including some 30
exhibitions, but at least there's validity in this schedule, based
on a pitching staff needing the time. But due to the off-season
workout programs, plus the minicamps and quarterback schools, it's
like Johnston said _ football players are almost physically ready
the first day they step into a training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks of contact drills would be about right, then play an
exhibition game,'' he noted. ``After that, go easy for a week, play
a second game, then open the season. Everything else is a waste of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there's the heat factor. Wichita Falls is
boiling, but so was Austin. Following the lead of Jimmy Johnson in
1990, this will be the 11th consecutive summer the Cowboys have
trained in the oven that is a Texas summer. The pleasant days of
Thousand Oaks, Calif., long-time training camp home for the
Cowboys, are a distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   The switch to Austin coincided with the Cowboys rise to dynasty
status in the '90s. Johnson preached constantly that the two were
connected. Johnston might have been one of Jimmy's favorite
players, but he couldn't disagree more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the truth about Austin and Wichita Falls, and the heat
that's involved,'' Daryl said. ``As a player, you are at your best
in physical conditioning the day you report to training camp. As a
player, you are at your worst in physical conditioning the day
training camp is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat beats you down, and beats you up. You spend the first
four weeks of the regular season trying to get back to the fitness
level you had on the first day of training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston recalled the summer of '92 when he broke a bone in his
hand the first week of training camp. ``I missed the next three
weeks of practice in Austin, and went on to have the best season I
ever had. I never felt better or stronger. Even when we were
winning Super Bowls, some of our worst games, and some of our
losses, came early in the season at Texas Stadium when it was hot.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons, I always thought, is we were still dragging
from the heat in Austin. My disagreement with Jimmy would be we had
the best players _ that's why we won in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   This will also be the training camp when a new head coach takes
over, and Dave Campo is a believer, somewhat, in the Jimmy Johnson
philosophy of pushing hard on the practice field. ``Within
reason,'' Johnston said, ``that might be a good idea. Dave won't
overdo it, I'm sure, but we were always a physical offensive team,
and under Chan (Gailey) in Wichita Falls that really changed. It
wasn't, however, just the heat or the fear of injury. Chan's
offense was different from what we'd had. Not as physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back now to the old offense, it makes sense that there
needs to be more hitting, but again, it has to be within reason.
Dave knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   From force of habit, Johnston said he's been watching the
temperature in Wichita Falls for several weeks. ``The triple-digits
are back,'' he said, and then added, laughing, ``I plan on visiting
camp, so I need to know what to wear.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl also noted he won't be hard to miss on the sidelines in
Wichita Falls: ``I'll be the guy carrying a six-pack on my
shoulder, and smiling a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Give it a couple of weeks in Wichita Falls and many of his old
pals will be wishing they had joined Johnston in retirement. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
