<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL ENJOYING THE CALM BEFORE THE STORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody's enjoying the backyard barbecue. The sun is shining.
The kids are in the swimming pool, splashing around and having a
wonderful time. The burgers are almost done. It's a perfect day.
</P>
<P>
   But there are storm clouds on the horizon, threatening to blow
in and ruin the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with major-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Like the folks at the barbecue, everyone's having a wonderful
time.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is about what it was before the 1994 strike because
of the combination of megastars such as Mark McGwire, Ken Griffey
Jr., Barry Bonds, Randy Johnson and Pedro Martinez, palatial new
ballparks and compelling pennant races.
</P>
<P>
   The many corporatesponsors at the All-Star Game indicate the
game finally is learning how to market itself at the national
level.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the industry is healthy and thriving.
</P>
<P>
   But the dark, ominous storm clouds are gathering.
</P>
<P>
   This storm has a name. It's called economic disparity.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of medium-market (or medium payroll, anyway) teams such
as the Oakland Athletics and Chicago White Sox is a good story.
It's also an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   The chasm between the team with the largest payroll and the club
with the smallest is greater than it has ever been. Not only does
the gap between the haves and have-nots ruin competitive balance,
it also threatens to ruin the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that revenue sharing, salary restraint,
the way we do business with each other, all of that has to be
changed,'' commissioner Bud Selig said last week. ``The fact of the
matter is that the disparity thing is so serious; wherever I go,
whether it's Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Minneapolis, San Diego,
Milwaukee, Seattle, people are concerned. They're concerned that
their team doesn't have a realistic chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest example of the problem happened just the other day
when the Reds traded their best pitcher, Denny Neagle, to the
Yankees for a handful of prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The minor-leaguers included some of the best in the Yankees'
system, but all things being equal, a team would prefer the
production over the potential. Things, though, aren't equal.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle can be a free agent at the end of the season. The Reds, a
medium-market, Midwest franchise, offered him a three-year, $18
million contract that he turned down. So they traded him to the
Yankees, who almost surely will give him the deal he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the juggernaut rolls on. After the Neagle trade, along
with the David Justice deal a couple of weeks before, the Yankees _
the first team with a payroll to top $100 million _ have to be
favored to win the World Series for the third consecutive season
and for the fourth time in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds, meanwhile, are left with a hole in the rotation and
the hope that the prospects will pan out.
</P>
<P>
   And the Reds are a viable franchise with a new stadium on the
horizon. What chance do clubs like the Minnesota Twins and Montreal
Expos have?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is none.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that baseball is well aware of the problem, and
is trying to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   The ``blue-ribbon'' economic study committee recommended some
good, common-sense proposals in its report at the owners meetings
in New York on Friday. The committee suggested the sport adopt a
vast increase in revenue sharing, and consider allowing weak
franchises to move. It did not say the sport needs a salary cap,
words that could signal the start of a potentially devastating
labor war.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that there's still a long battle ahead before
the recommendations are adopted.
</P>
<P>
   The committee proposed a 50 percent luxury tax on payrolls above
$84 million, a measure that would cost the Yankees about $15
million. Owner George Steinbrenner won't be happy about that, and
neither will the union, which vehemently is opposed to any measure
that would serve as a drag on salaries.
</P>
<P>
   What the union always fails to recognize, though, is that while
sharing the wealth might prevent the Yankees from spending so much,
it would give clubs such as the Twins the financial wherewithal to
boost payroll. The overall amount spent on player salaries would
remain about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, something has to be done. The committee's
recommendations might not be the final answer, but they're at least
a good starting point.
BASEBALL'S NO. 1 SECRET
</P>
<P>
   A couple of writers at the All-Star Game were lamenting the fact
that it's hard to do a story on Expos outfielder Vladimir Guerrero
because of his limited grasp of English. A guy who's fluent in
Guerrero's native tongue joined in the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not that good in Spanish, either,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero, a native of the Dominican Republic, doesn't have
anything against the media. He also doesn't have much to say to his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go in the clubhouse you would see he doesn't talk
much,'' Expos second baseman Jose Vidro said. ``He doesn't even
talk to his teammates. He's always listening to his music.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Guerrero is a snob who thinks he's better than
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a shy guy,'' Vidro said.
</P>
<P>
   The language barrier, the shyness, the fact he plays in
Montreal, combine to make Guerrero the Unknown Superstar.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe not unknown. But he's certainly not as recognized as
he should be. A lack of attention and notoriety can be the only
reason he wasn't elected to start in the All-Star Game by a
landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero batted .324 with 38 home runs and 109 RBI in 1998, his
first full season in the majors. Last year he hit .316 with 42 home
runs and 131 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   He's on pace to better all those numbers this year. After going
2-for-4 with a home run in the first game after the All-Star break,
Guerrero was hitting .371 with 24 homers and 78 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Those are MVP numbers, superstar numbers, numbers that could get
better because he's still young and he's still improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has a lot to learn,'' said Vidro, himself an
underrated star. ``There are some things that are going to get
better and better. He's only 24, and he's done a lot in his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   So what if the average fan doesn't realize how good he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the pitchers know about him,'' Vidro said. TRADE GRADE
MUST WAIT
</P>
<P>
   Reds GM Jim Bowden called the deal of Denny Neagle to the
Yankees for four prospects a ``high-risk, high-reward trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential reward, of course, is if third baseman Drew
Henson, outfielder Jackson Melian, left-hander Ed Yarnall and
right-hander Brian Reith develop into front-line major-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   The risk _ in addition to trading their best pitcher _ is that
Henson might give up baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Henson has a ton of talent, both on the diamond and the football
field. He's the quarterback for the Michigan Wolverines. He's
currently playing in the minors, but his priority for the next
couple of years is football. Then, he'll pick one sport.
</P>
<P>
   If it's not baseball, the reward will be significantly less. A
TRADE THAT WORKED
</P>
<P>
   Brian Giles could count on cashing a postseason check every
season when he played for the Cleveland Indians. He played in three
Division Series, two Championship Series and one World Series in
his three seasons in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Since being traded to Pittsburgh, he can count on beginning the
off-season in early October. A good season for the Pirates is a
.500 record, not a postseason appearance.
</P>
<P>
   However, the trade was the best thing to happen to Giles because
it gave him a chance to display his talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cleveland I was getting a label as a fourth outfielder or
platoon player,'' he said. ``That can be a tough label to shake
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, in his first chance as a regular, Giles hit .315
with 39 home runs and 115 RBI. This year he's an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I could put up some numbers at the big-league level if
I was given the opportunity to play every day, but it's tough when
you're not playing every day to get into a routine,'' he said.
``You feel like you have to swing the bat well every time you play
to get a start the next night. You put too much pressure on
yourself, and you can't be the player you think you're capable of
doing.'' CAL STILL A PLAYER
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that future Hall of Famer Cal Ripken, on the disabled
list with recurrent pain in his lower back and leg, apparently the
result of a disk fragment left behind from September surgery, would
announce his retirement on Thursday proved false.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken denied that he is close to retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to put the uniform back on and see what happens,'' he
said. ``I want to play as much of the second half as I possibly
can.'' CROW GLADLY EATEN
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Blue Jays starter David Wells, never shy about speaking
his mind, ripped the organization for trading Shawn Green for Raul
Mondesi in the off-season. He ripped it again in spring training
for failing to trade for a veteran pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Blue Jays tied for first in the AL East with the
Yankees, Wells acknowledged he made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I ate my words,'' he said. ``I looked very foolish,
but everyone makes mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes like the one the Yankees made when they traded Wells to
the Blue Jays before the '99 season. Since then, Clemens is 20-16
with a 4.51 earned-run average. Wells is 32-12 with a 4.32 ERA for
the Jays. Wells has pitched 360 innings to Clemens' 282 1/3. IN
SUPPORT OF JUAN
</P>
<P>
   Even though Juan Gonzalez hasn't contributed as much as hoped
for, and even though he might be traded because he refuses to
consider signing a long-term contract, Detroit Tigers reliever Todd
Jones said no one in the clubhouse is bitter toward their teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no animosity toward him,'' Jones said. ``We just want
him to be happy. He's a good guy. He's been great with us. He's
been a perfect teammate. He's very conscientious. He's very
sensitive, and he's very concerned about the guys on the team. He
tries to keep all of the other stuff out of the clubhouse.'' AROUND
THE NL
</P>
<P>
   Florida Marlins All-Star pitcher Ryan Dempster suggested that
the team's unexpected success this season goes beyond the young
talent maturing. Attitude also is a reason they are above .500. ``I
think we're hungry,'' Dempster said. ``When you get beat up year
after year, that's a tough thing to go through. When the experience
starts to catch up with the talent, you really get hungry for wins
and to prove to people that we're for real. Guys really have their
roles down. It's just going to continue to grow and improve on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets' starting pitching has been at least as good
as Atlanta's, but New York needs help in the bullpen and is fearful
of the possibility of the Braves getting Rangers closer John
Wetteland. ``If they do that, we're in trouble,'' a club official
told the ``Bergen Record''.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Astros manager Larry Dierker could soon pay for the
team's sorry performance with his job. Dierker appeared to safe a
few weeks ago because he's owed $1.5 million over the next two
years and owner Drayton McLane isn't inclined to pay people not to
work, but with dissatisfaction with the manager growing in the
clubhouse the club is expected to reassign him within the
organization in hopes he'll quit.
</P>
<P>
   Reds manager Jack McKeon could find himself in the unemployment
line before Dierker. The Reds gave up on the season when they
traded Neagle, so it makes sense to bring in the manager who'll be
working with the team next year. It won't be McKeon, who is in the
last year of his contract. Bob Boone could be the new manager by
this time next week.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Kile was 21-30 with a 5.84 ERA in his two seasons in
Colorado. He was 11-5 with a 4.51 ERA and an All-Star in the first
half for the Cardinals. However, he refuses to blame the thin air
in Denver for his problems. ``It really doesn't matter where you
pitch,'' he said. ``You just have to make quality pitches. In
Colorado, I just didn't make many quality pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Reds reliever Danny Graves had one of his worst games of the
season after finding out he'd made the All-Star team last Sunday.
He hit a batter with the bases loaded, then threw the ball away
after fielding a grounder. ``The happy emotions just took over in
my body, and I had no idea what was going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies' team record for drawing intentional walks is 14,
set by Larry Walker in his MVP season of 1997. First baseman Todd
Helton has already been intentionally walked 13 times. AROUND THE
AL
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim Angels outfielder Darin Erstad had 144 hits in the first
half, 123 away from George Sisler's single-season record of 257,
set in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Royals first baseman Mike Sweeney thought he had a
good chance to make the All-Star team, but with the number of
quality players at his position in the league, and with the fact
that the club already had one representative in elected starter
Jermaine Dye, he wasn't sure. He wasn't worried, however. ``I kind
of thought of it as a win-win situation,'' he said. ``I was hoping
to be here because I thought I'd performed well and had a chance of
being selected, but at the same time I made alternate plans. If I
didn't make the team I was going to go fishing up in the Ozarks.
Either I had 2 1/2 days to relax and go fishing and spend time with
God, or I was going to come to Atlanta and have a dream come
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Tigers pitcher Hideo Nomo, heretofore not noted for having much
of a sense of humor, recently won the human sausage race at County
Stadium in Milwaukee. Nomo, wearing the Italian sausage costume,
beat three other competitors in the race from the left-field corner
to home plate. ``He had to get his running in,'' manager Phil
Garner said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays catcher Darrin Fletcher celebrated his 1,000th career
game last Sunday at Montreal with his second career stolen base.
His only other stolen base came on July 18, 1997, also at Olympic
Stadium while playing for the Expos. ``That's kind of like Halley's
comet,'' he said. ``I'm surprised they even counted it as a stolen
base and not indifference, but I'll take it. One for every 500
games isn't bad; this is my American League stolen base.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Mariners pitcher Aaron Sele said to gauge the strength
of the AL West, all anyone has to do is look at the last-place
team. ``That's a team that's loaded with great offense,'' he said
of the Rangers, his former squad. ``Luis Alicea is having a
spectacular year, and that's your leadoff guy. The first six guys
are strong, and then they've got guys contributing at the bottom.
And that's your last-place team.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was happy to make the All-Star team, White Sox
second baseman Ray Durham couldn't understand why Frank Thomas
didn't join him. ``I felt that he should have been here,'' Durham
said. ``The players on our team, the players on other teams felt he
should have been here. He was a little upset, and I was a little
upset. You could see he was a little upset, and I think he had
every right to be upset. He's having one of the best seasons of his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins haven't traded second baseman Todd Walker yet because
GM Terry Ryan wants value in return. The problem is, the Twins have
made it clear Walker has no value to them. The best bet is they'll
trade Walker to the first team that offers something better than a
bucket of used balls, perhaps the San Diego Padres. THE WEEK AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   The early part of the week features the so-what portion of the
interleague schedule, with series such as Orioles-Marlins, Red
Sox-Expos, Twins-Cardinals and Royals-Cubs. The best of the lot
appears to be the Mariners at the Diamondbacks, which at least is a
battle of divisional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The important series come next weekend, with the Mets visiting
Atlanta and the Rangers visiting Seattle's Safeco Field for the
first time. THE LAST WORD
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely two tiers of players at these things. The
ones who know they'll be an All-Star again. And the ones who can
only hope.'' Tigers reliever Todd Jones, a first-time All-Star nn
</P>
</TEXT>
