<HEADLINE>
KELLIE KUEHNE COULD BE NEXT QUEEN OF AMERICAN GOLF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The LPGA Tour's best player, Karrie Webb, hails from Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   Its second-best player, Annika Sorenstam, arrived from Sweden,
and a glance at the tour's top 20 money leaders this season shows
that half come from foreign soil.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the United States' best player, Juli Inkster, says
``we need some youngsters, good American youngsters to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA suffers from a lack of young, home-grown stars and, in
particular, one who can elevate the tour's popularity as Nancy
Lopez did during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no better candidate exists than Dallas' Kelli Kuehne, a
5-foot-2 bundle of energy with the never-ending smile. Kuehne, 23,
possesses the charisma, talent and girl-next-door looks to become
the heiress to Lopez. Her battle against diabetes only increases
her allure.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is Nancy Lopez-like,'' said Tammie Green, a seven-time
winner on the LPGA Tour. ``She wants to be a superstar and
understands everything that goes along with being one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne, who has one tour victory, will compete this week in the
U.S. Women's Open at Merit Club in Libertyville, Ill. She emerged
as the rage of the 1999 Open at Old Waverly Golf Club in West
Point, Miss., after firing a first-round 64 en route to a
third-place finish to Inkster.
</P>
<P>
   ``People kind of put my name in that void because we haven't had
a great American player in several years,'' said Kuehne, who ranks
43rd on the LPGA money list with $131,252 this year. ``It's no
secret that we've had some good golf players, but none of them have
has been the dominant force like Tiger \RWoods\S is on \Rthe
men's\S tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in some regards that it's absolutely very important to
me because That's what I want to do, but I think it's going to be
very difficult with the talent and as many great players as we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, replacing Lopez could be even more challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it: There will never be another Nancy Lopez,'' said
Inkster, 39, who has six major tour victories to her credit.
``She's the ultimate, but as Kelli gets older _ along with the
other young players _ I think they will mature and understand that
we really need them to take this tour to the next level. I think
they can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who sponsor Kuehne agree with Inkster's assessment. She
might not be a superstar but Kuehne is getting superstar
endorsement money, reportedly more than $6 million over four years
from a group of sponsors that includes Nike, Top-Flite and Hain
Foods. She recently changed management companies to Gaylord Sports,
dropping International Management Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Kelli has the opportunity to make a statement for
American women's golf and be a person that a lot of people can look
up to,'' said Kuehne's father, Ernie. ``People have been referring
to Nancy Lopez as the queen of ladies' golf and Kelli as the
up-and-coming princess. That's a title she can live up to, and
American golf desperately needs someone like Kelli to step up and
take the spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   THE KUEHNE FILE
</P>
<P>
   Born: May 11, 1977
</P>
<P>
   Resides: Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Victories: 1 (1999 LPGA Corning Classic)
</P>
<P>
   Career-low round: 64 (1999 U.S. Women's Open)
</P>
<P>
   Best 2000 finish: T-2nd (LGPA Corning Classic)
</P>
<P>
   2000 money list: 43 ($131,252.00)
</P>
<P>
   Highlights/personal: Six top-20 finishes through 13 2000 starts.
... Six top-10 finishes in '99. .... Turned professional in
November '96 during the middle of her sophomore season at the
University of Texas. ... Two-time U.S. Women's Amateur champion
(1995-96). ... U.S. Junior Girls champion (1994). ... Wears an
insulin pump on course to battle diabetes. ... National
spokesperson for Juvenile Diabetes Foundation. ... Her husband, Jay
Humphrey, is an offensive lineman for the NFL's Vikings and stands
14 inches taller than the 5-foot-2 Kuehne. They met at the
University of Texas...Brothers Trip and Hank are accomplished
players. ... Trip was the runner-up at the 1994 U.S. Amateur and a
member of Oklahoma State's 1995 national championship team. ...
Hank was the 1998 U.S. Amateur champion.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Women's Open
</P>
<P>
   When: Thursday through July 23
</P>
<P>
   Where: Merit Club, Libertyville, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Length: 6,516 yards
</P>
<P>
   Par: 36-36_72
</P>
<P>
   Format: 72 holes (18 daily) stroke play
</P>
<P>
   Purse: $2,750,000
</P>
<P>
   Winner's share: $495,000
</P>
<P>
   Last year: Juli Inkster shot a 16-under-par 272 to defeat Sherri
Turner by five strokes, erasing memories of the championship that
slipped away in 1992. Inkster fired a final-round 71 on the
6,433-yard course at Old Waverly Golf Club, in West Point, Miss.
Kelli Kuehne, 22, finished third at 279. It was the highest Women's
Open finish for all three contestants.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   Thursday-Friday: 1-5 p.m. (ESPN)
</P>
