<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3268 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-FLA-TOBACCO-JURY-2TAK     07-15 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOBACCO-JURY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUROR SAYS A `SENSE OF MISSION' LED TO HUGE TOBACCO DAMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., this story has been added to NYT Page 1, replacing
MIDEAST-TALKS which goes inside) 
 By RICK BRAGG with SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was the lies, the jury's foreman said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a period of 50 years, these tobacco companies denied the
dangers of their product,'' said Leighton A. Finegan, the foreman
of a six-member jury here that punished the tobacco industry with a
$144.8 billion punitive damage judgment, the largest damage award
in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``They belittled or denied causation of the health effects of
smoking and addiction, and had the gall to challenge public health
authorities,'' and even used fabricated science to dispute the
risk, Finegan said in an interview on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Finegan, 44, who went into the trial believing that a person
smoked cigarettes as a choice, found among his fellow jurors a
reasoned and unanimous conviction to punish the tobacco industry.
The point, he said, was not whether people had the choice to smoke
or not to smoke, but that the companies knew they were selling a
defective product and denied that it was defective.
</P>
<P>
   Settlements with the states that had challenged the industry had
not sent that strong message, but the award of punitive damages to
about 500,000 sick Florida smokers _ though certain to be appealed
_ would, the jury hoped.
</P>
<P>
   It had to come in a way, Finegan said, that would break through
the wall of denial and invulnerability that had surrounded the
industry for a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a sense of mission,'' said Finegan. ``And we did not
want to ignore the tremendous devastation that the product has
caused. The number had to match that. It had to be significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was fair. It would bring to the forefront, for
the first time in the history of this country, the issues
surrounding this product and the millions of lives that have been
affected by this. And it would put the companies on notice _ not
just the tobacco companies, all companies _ concerning fraud or
misrepresentation of the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   But even more grating than the lies, as the panel began
deliberations after two long years and 157 witnesses in the
class-action suit, was the arrogance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To minimize the deaths of so many people,'' exclaimed Finegan,
an assistant elementary school principal. ``We have seen the deaths
of 400,000 people a year for 50 years. And they stand up in court
and say that if we give a huge verdict it's a death warrant for the
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   To all six jurors, it seemed as if the five largest tobacco
makers in the country ``thumbed their noses at the system,'' even
suggesting that one smoker's throat cancer was caused by wood dust,
said Finegan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel they are above reproach,'' he said. ``They committed
fraud. They lied to the American public. They devastated millions
of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was insulting,'' the foreman said. ``It's just the tobacco
industry's mentality, that they are beyond challenge. No one has
ever challenged them and won.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury, as most juries are, was a cross section of real
people, who had their lives rearranged by the sheer length and
importance of this trial. The jury included, besides Finegan, a
welder, a telephone technician, a postal worker, a bank teller, and
another school employee.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors were asked to consider sums of money they could not
have imagined. When the punitive phase of the case ended and the
judge, Robert Kaye of Miami-Dade Circuit Court, sent them to the
jury room to consider the punishment, they did not just pull a
number out of the air or settle on the more than $150 billion that
the smokers' chief lawyer, Stanley M. Rosenblatt, demanded.
</P>
<P>
   They had heard witnesses for both sides testify about what the
companies could pay. Lawyers for the companies had said the
cigarette makers could afford to pay $150 million to $375 million,
but would be put out of business if the jury granted anything
approaching the requested award. The jury chose not to believe
that.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In the jury room, in the less than five hours of deliberations,
the jurors each named a figure, ranging from $100 billion to $200
billion. The members of the jury averaged those figures and came to
$145 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Then, they looked at the market share of each of the five
companies and two institutes that had given false information about
smoking, and using that and other financial information, broke down
the total: Philip Morris, the country's largest cigarette maker,
$73.96 billion; R.J. Reynolds, $36.28 billion; Brown &AMP; Williamson,
$17.59 billion; Lorrilard Tobacco, $16.25 billion; Liggett Group,
$790 million; the Council for Tobacco Research, $1.195 million; and
the Tobacco Institute, $278,389.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict was announced on Friday afternoon, ``I felt a
great sense of relief that what we did was right and justified
according to the evidence presented,'' Finegan said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he and the other the jurors _ Gary Chwast,
Jacqueline Brinson, John Mestre, James Strowbridge, and Delvia
Ferreyra _ are probably among the best educated people in the
country on the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Finegan still has the notice he received on July 8, 1998,
informing him to report for jury duty.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant principal at an elementary school in the Kendall
area, south of Miami, he was a former teacher of social studies and
American history, who had lectured students _ from his heart, not
just the book _ on civic responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would just be a short thing,'' he said. ``I would
serve for a month or two and that would be it. I would complete my
civic duty, and I would have something to take back to the school
and tell the kids about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have a greater insight into the legal process, and I
could bring a wealth of information back. Never for one moment did
I think this would be two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial took over his life and the lives of the other jurors,
he said. It was not just the time it took them away from their
families. They saw their futures rearranged by it.
</P>
<P>
   They gave up promotions because of it, he said. Finegan, who has
a wife, Marice, and a 3-year-old son, had helped start a magnet
school in Miami-Dade, but had to give up his job there because the
trial consumed so much of his time.
</P>
<P>
   It all began when the lawyers asked him, during jury selection,
to state his feelings about smoking. Finegan, who immigrated to the
United States from Jamaica in 1988, said he had no strong feelings
about smoking, and had always felt that if person smoked, it was
through their own free will.
</P>
<P>
   Then came months of information, scientific data and testimony
from people who had had throats and lungs surgically removed, and
evidence that showed the addictive nature of the product and how it
was made to be addictive.
</P>
<P>
   One woman testified by videotape. She had died as the trial
dragged on, and a tape was shown after her death.
</P>
<P>
   The industry first said it was not as bad as it was being made
to appear, but the jury ruled, in July 1999, that the tobacco
industry manufactured a deadly product, and that it had deceived
the public for years. In April, the jury ordered the companies to
pay $12.7 million in compensatory damages to the smokers. In the
punitive stage of the trial, the stage just concluded, sick smokers
first asked for $196 billion in damages. But their lead lawyer,
Rosenblatt, would eventually suggest an award of $154 billion to
the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the trial went on and Finegan was gone so much
from work, someone moved into his office at the school. He said he
began to feel out of place, marginal. He was a part-time worker in
a full-time job.
</P>
<P>
   There was a big window in the jury room, he said. Sometimes he
and the others would just sit in front of it and watch people walk
by _ people going about their lives without such grave
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw people going about their daily routines,'' he said.
``Sometimes we felt like we weren't going anywhere. We were
stationary.''
</P>
<P>
   They saw their families at night, but much of a person's worth,
he said, is in how they do their job, and they were not at their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have your goals and aspirations being achieved,'' he
said. The other members of the jury spoke about it, too, he said.
``Someone else is carrying on your job,'' he said. ``It devalued my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Finegan could not talk about his life's focus, that trial, with
anyone but the other five jurors. ``There was a movie that came out
called `The Insider,' about the tobacco industry. We were told not
to watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors sat beside each other so long they became friends,
baking birthday cakes and exchanging Christmas presents. ``We got
pretty close,'' he said. ``We got to know each other's
temperaments, personalities. We celebrated each other's birthdays,
knew each other's jobs.'' They shared pictures of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they had an awesome responsibility before them, he
said, ``we felt somewhat inconsequential.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, literally, came judgment day.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, or perhaps not oddly at all, the six members of the jury
did not scatter after the verdict was read. They went to a cafe in
Coconut Grove, together. They promised to keep in touch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
