<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-HALL-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVRATILOVA'S JOURNEY ENDS AT HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ The spooky bushes that used to swallow Martina
Navratilova's wayward lobs had been cleared away, and the wall that
absorbed the backhands she belted with her grandmother's heavy wood
racket was gone.
</P>
<P>
   But almost everything else was the same. So when the 43-year-old
Navratilova stepped on the courts tucked away in the countryside of
the Czech Republic just this past month, it was as if she tripped
the door on a time capsule containing the first shreds of evidence
to her improbable journey.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the vulnerable lefty who had the courage to flee a
communist country, the fearlessness to face scrutiny by coming out
and a drive that changed the physical image of the female athlete
was standing on a manicured lawn at the Tennis Museum and Hall of
Fame on Saturday as an inductee from the class of 2000. Before she
served and volleyed her way to 18 Grand Slam singles titles, before
she supplied the contrast that turned her rivalry with Chris Evert
into folklore, there was a bare beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have to fix the courts in the spring,'' Navratilova
said. ``That was our membership dues. We'd spend about 20 hours
pulling the weeds and putting the clay on, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and father met through me. When my father would take
the clay to the court in the wheelbarrow, I would get in the
wheelbarrow and he'd wheel me down. I was about 3 years old then.
He liked me because I was smiling and so happy _ of course I was
happy because he gave me a ride _ but that's how my parents met. So
tennis not only brought my parents together, but then my parents
being together brought me to tennis. It's a big circle.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, that circle included her fellow inductees. There was
Judge Robert Kelleher, who grew tired of the payments being made
under the table to players and fought for the approval of Open
tennis in 1968. There was also Malcolm Anderson, who came off a
cattle ranch in Australia to become a force on his country's Davis
Cup team and was the first unseeded player to win the United States
National singles title, in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Through longevity and circumstance, all three are linked. In
1974, Navratilova played mixed doubles with Anderson. In 1981 she
became a U.S. citizen in the same Los Angeles federal court over
which Kelleher presided. With Billie Jean King's former husband,
Larry, as her lawyer, Navratilova went through naturalization with
50 others from all backgrounds. The six-year wait after her
defection was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no decision,'' Navratilova said before the induction
ceremony. ``If I wanted to play tennis, I had to leave the country.
The difficult part was doing it. I was 19, young and didn't think
about the consequences to do it. I had to make the choice. And what
I regret the most is that I had to make that choice and that I can
never have those years back with my sister, with my parents, with
my grandmother. If I wanted to play tennis, I had to do it. Once I
got out, I knew I couldn't go back.''
</P>
<P>
   She just pushed forward with some help along the way. The same
year she became a citizen, she also had an epiphany induced by
Nancy Lieberman-Cline. If she wanted to find an edge, she'd have to
do what no other woman had done at the time: live in the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going to French Open the first year,'' said
Lieberman-Cline, who attended the ceremony Saturday. ``And I was
thinking when we got back to the hotel, and then I asked Martina,
`When are you going to practice?' And she said, `Well, I just did.'
I went, `You got to be kidding me. You call that practice? You hit
the ball for 15 minutes, you talk to Billie Jean, you wave to
someone else, you hit an overhead and then we went back to the
hotel. No wonder you don't win all the time. Your practice habits
stink.'''
</P>
<P>
   With prodding from Lieberman-Cline, Navratilova began to carve
out a fit physique never seen on a female tennis player before. A
month or so later, Dr. Renee Richards began sculpting Navratilova's
game as her coach. As Navratilova developed her game, the riveting
rivalry between herself and Evert evolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful to be one half of the greatest rivalry in
sports,'' Navratilova said. ``You may have team rivalries, but as
for players, I can think of Ali and Frazier, but how many times did
they fight? Three? We had 80 battles in singles. We made each other
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Navratilova's impact on the game still resonates _ fitness is
not an option for players anymore _ but what has separated her from
so many other athletes today is her attention to activism. Although
her honesty about her homosexuality has cost her millions of
dollars in endorsements, her conviction is unwavering as she
continues to speak out on homosexual issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important,'' Navratilova said. ``And I think every piece
of legislation is important. Until there is equal protection and
equal rights, I'll keep speaking out. I don't want it to be an
issue, but it is because we don't have the equal rights. It's
something I couldn't even talk about until I became a citizen. It
was a disqualifier to getting my citizenship. It shouldn't be that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   She is serious when she speaks. But she also prompted more
laughs than anything else Saturday. When she addressed the crowd,
she said, ``It's nice to be able to talk about yourself without
feeling guilty or without having to pay somebody to listen to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   When she thanked everyone who had helped her in her career, she
also added a thanks to all the ``doctors who held me together,
homeopathic people, osteopaths, massage therapists, and I'd like to
thank my dogs for keeping me company throughout my career, even all
the girlfriends who suffered through all the matches in the stands
_ wherever they are.''
</P>
<P>
   She was surrounded on Saturday by those who have always stood by
her, her doubles partner, Pam Shriver; Lieberman-Cline; Richards;
and her mother, Jana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy,'' Jana said. ``To be here, it's such a long way
from where she started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
