<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUSD-ETHICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUSD SEEKS TO CREATE NEW OFFICE OF ETHICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID R. BAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Despite an annual price tag of $250,000 or more,
the Los Angeles Unified School District wants to create an ethics
office to teach its employees right from wrong after years of
embarrassing administrative scandals.
</P>
<P>
   District officials want an ethics officer who will train the
school system's 70,000 employees how to avoid compromising
positions and conflicts of interest. The ethics officer also would
sift through complaints of ethical violations and determine which
ones should be investigated by the district's chief inspector.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the investigations we do here are ethical problems,
and ethical problems can lead to criminal problems,'' said
Inspector General Don Mullinax, who originally pitched the idea to
school board members.
</P>
<P>
   The idea comes in spite of efforts to trim the immense
district's central staff and split Los Angeles Unified into 11
miniature districts with some autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   As advertised, the ethics position would pay between $77,200 and
$95,600 each year. Ads call for ``an individual of admirable
character, integrity, and significant experience.'' Applications
are due by Friday, July 21.
</P>
<P>
   The officer may also have a support staff of five people whose
total salaries could top $250,000. The office could include
analysts, who typically earn between $40,000 and $50,000 a year, as
well as clerical staff, with salaries around $30,000, district
personnel director Jon Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   School district officials said they don't mind adding another
officer and support staff, so long as the officer produces results
and the staff isn't too large.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is someone who is vigilant about conflicts of
interest, about revolving doors - those kinds of issues,'' board
member David Tokofsky said. ``As long as next week someone doesn't
come back to us and say we need ethics officers for all 11
districts and one downtown, I'm not worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics question why the district needs such an officer at all,
arguing the money would be better spent in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have yet to be convinced that the ethics issues are so
complicated that they can't be handled by a written policy,'' said
Jon Coupal, president of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the position seemed more a response to past
ethical lapses at the district than the current situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like closing the barn door after the horses are
already gone,'' Coupal said.
</P>
<P>
   While they are rarely found at suburban or rural districts,
ethics officers are common features of America's largest school
systems, according to the Council of Great City Schools, an
organization representing big, urban districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of ensuring the integrity of the system for the
sake of the public,'' said Michael Casserly, the council's
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Caprice Young said major corporations such as her
former employer, IBM, regularly hire ethics officers. She said the
position could help efforts to restructure the district and its
departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I want to do is build a multibillion-dollar
project, and have it shot because the people don't understand
ethics,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax said he was amazed to find no ethics officer when he
arrived at the district last year. Such huge and complex
organizations as Los Angeles Unified - where the annual budget now
tops $8 billion - usually need and have such officers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any lack of work for such an officer, Mullinax
said. Questions of nepotism and cronyism have long dogged Los
Angeles Unified. The district's fraud-reporting hotline logs about
100 tips each month, Mullinax said.
</P>
<P>
   His office has uncovered instances of contractors offering
employees gift certificates to popular stores in return for their
business. Many workers seem oblivious to the conflict accepting
such an offer could cause, Mullinax said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say, 'You mean we shouldn't take that gift
certificate?''' he said. ``If the employees have never been told
something's not ethical, they don't know what's unethical.''
</P>
<P>
   His office is now working on a new, more detailed ethics policy
for the district, which recently ditched a proposed ethics policy
drafted by a consultant because it was too vague.
</P>
<P>
   And he wants the ethics officer to create and run a training
program to show employees the guidelines they must follow for
spending the public's money. Mullinax has already conducted about
40 training sessions at schools and offices but says he can't do
enough to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, every second, you're tempted to make an ethical
decision, right or wrong,'' Mullinax said. ``Do I let this person
buy me lunch? Do I take home the company car?''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
