<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MANAGERS MAKE THEIR PITCHES FOR PITCHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers are looking for a No.2 or No.3
starting pitcher. So is Arizona. And Colorado. However, San
Francisco likely will stay intact.
</P>
<P>
   If no one in the National League West makes a move, Arizona
remains the odds-on favorite to win the division, but a trade
changes the complexion of it. The phones of all general managers
are busy as they try to acquire the pitcher needed to push them to
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Ismael Valdes, Baltimore's Scott Erickson and
Houston's Jose Lima don't particularly excite many general managers
for a trading-deadline deal. If Philadelphia decides to move Curt
Schilling, or Baltimore says Mike Mussina can be had, or Montreal
makes Dustin Hermanson available, then the scenario could become
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say these next (two weeks) will determine whether
we'll participate or go the other way,'' Colorado general manager
Dan O'Dowd said.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks were among the many teams scouting Andy Ashby
before he was traded by Philadelphia to Atlanta, and they've also
charted Pittsburgh's Francisco Cordova and has talked to Seattle
about John Halama and Brett Tomko.
</P>
<P>
   But like everyone else, Arizona general manager Joe Garagiola
Jr. doesn't think it's a smart move to rent a pitcher for two
months for a couple of prospects who can come back and bite you for
years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be a lot of names thrown around the next
few weeks,'' Garagiola Jr. said. ``Off of the conversations that I
have already had, right now there are some very, very unrealistic
price tags attached to some of those names. If we get to July 31
not having done anything, I don't think this is a time to make some
panic move.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said he's talking to other
teams, but none of the available starting pitchers are reason to
get excited.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Giants don't plan to make a move because the
market isn't worthy of such a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to trade for the sake of trading, because we
have enough talent here,'' Giants general manager Brian Sabean
said. ``I'd be reluctant to make a trade that wouldn't help us
short term and long term. I don't know if I'd want to get involved
with somebody else's free agent and give up the ranch.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle's niche: Before the Reds traded left-hander Denny Neagle
to the Yankees for four minor-leaguers, they offered him a
three-year, $18 million deal. Not only didn't he like the deal,
there was never a counteroffer made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, deals like this are very difficult, because you're
trading your No. 1 starter,'' Cincinnati general manager Jim Bowden
said. ``Obviously you're hurting your chance of winning now. ... I
know this deal is going to be unpopular for the present. ... We're
concerned about how fans are going to react, the media are going to
react and how players are going to react.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said the Reds couldn't afford to sign Neagle to a bigger
deal because they're in a small market, though that didn't stop
Minnesota from signing Brad Radke to a huge deal.
</P>
<P>
   More altitude fodder: Every year it's the same thing. Colorado
pounds the ball in the altitude at Coors Field and the Rockies
stumble on the road. Entering Saturday, they were 28-11 at home and
17-31 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the team batting average is .358 at home and .238 on
the road. In 48 games on the road, they have 22 homers while
opponents have 55. ``Our lack of power really shows up on the
road,'' O'Dowd said.
</P>
<P>
   Green with remorse: When Toronto traded Shawn Green for Raul
Mondesi, Blue Jays pitcher David Wells popped off about what a huge
mistake the deal was for Toronto. But having lived with Mondesi for
half the season and seeing him in right field, Wells changed his
mind about how Toronto fared in the swap of right fielders with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I ate my words,'' Wells said. ``I thought we had a
good team last year. To make a deal like we did, I didn't
understand it. But once these guys came to camp, I realized how
good they were. I looked foolish. I made a mistake. Now, when I see
Raul Mondesi out in right field every day, it's a blessing in
disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   Green entered Saturday hitting .290 with 13 homers, 60 RBI, 15
stolen bases and four errors. Mondesi was hitting .282 with 23
homers, 64 RBI, 21 stolen bases and six errors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
