<HEADER>
A3364 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LAD     07-15 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN LIKELY TO MAKE HIS NEXT START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Upon further examination, Kevin Brown's strained
right shoulder muscle should not keep him from making his next
start and pitching coach Claude Osteen has been absolved of any
wrong doing regarding the history of the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who left his Friday start against the Angels with
stiffness in his right shoulder, was examined by Dodgers team
physician Dr. Frank Jobe. The strain is of the muscles in the back
of the shoulder near the rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he probably won't miss a start,'' Jobe said. ``He
doesn't have any pain, but he does have stiffness. The reason it's
significant for him is he usually doesn't have any stiffness after
a start like most pitchers. He's already a lot better than he was
(Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   Jobe said no MRI was needed because there is no clicking or
catching in the shoulder. Jobe added that the stiffness Brown
experienced in San Diego during his July 6 start may not be related
to this injury.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's scheduled to pitch Wednesday against Colorado, and it's
likely he'll make that start. Brown will be evaluated on a daily
basis, and he will ice his shoulder after throwing until he feels
fine, Jobe said. Brown typically doesn't ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It think it's definitely related (to San Diego) because I
didn't feel anything until then, so it seems too coincidental for
it not to be related, in my mind,'' Brown said. ``I'm satisfied. It
just spasmed up. It should be able to get worked out in the next
couple of days, and we should know something better when I throw on
the side (Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, manager Davey Johnson cleared up what became a
misunderstanding after Brown left Friday's game with the shoulder
soreness. Brown told team medical personnel about his shoulder
feeling strange after the start in San Diego, but because he didn't
get treatment it wasn't included in the daily medical report given
to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Brown didn't tell Osteen about it until after he left the game
against Anaheim and was being examined by trainers. Johnson
initially thought Osteen learned of Brown's discomfort after the
San Diego start.
</P>
<P>
   However, it took Brown longer than usual to get loose to pitch
in Tuesday's All-Star Game, and Johnson said he probably would have
given word to Atlanta manager Bobby Cox about the situation had he
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset about it (Friday) night thinking Claude knew ahead
of time, but he just found out,'' Johnson said. ``I always want to
know, then I can ask the player what it is. If it's something
that's a little different, you can do something. ... (Osteen) is in
the clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Green feeling blue: For the first two months of the season,
right fielder Shawn Green was lauded for his contributions. His
presence was instrumental in a potent offense. However, things
aren't going so well now.
</P>
<P>
   Green went 0 for 3 Saturday and was 1 for 11 in the three-game
series with Anaheim. Couple that with Green's 6-for-50 slump
heading into the All-Star break, and he's 7 for 61 (.115) and his
average is .287.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll work my way out of it, but it's not fun,'' Green said.
``It's not fun struggling. This is worse than the past couple of
years. Any time anyone is struggling, it's confidence. Anybody that
says differently is lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching quandary: Todd Hundley is hopeful he'll return to the
lineup Monday against Pittsburgh. Chad Kreuter returns today after
serving his eight-game suspension for his part in the May 16 fight
at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time right-hander Mike Judd is recalled from Triple-A
Albuquerque for Tuesday's start against the Pirates, Hundley should
be fine, Kreuter's problems will be a thing of the past and Paul
LoDuca is likely headed back to the minors despite playing well.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Johnson said second baseman Mark Grudzielanek is
doing better and is expected to come to Dodger Stadium today after
missing the last six games with viral infection. Grudzielanek is
hoping to play either Monday or Tuesday.... Lefty Carlos Perez
begins serving his five-game suspension today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
