<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3433 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-TEENS-SEX-KAN &LR;      07-15 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-SEX-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S SEX TALK WITH TEENS, ABOUT AIDS AND DEATH, SEEMS TO BE
WORKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teen-agers say ``the talk'' is finally changing their attitudes
about sex.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the talk of morals and the sanctity of marriage
that parents pushed for eons. That was the talk that didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The latest edition is not about love and virtue. This talk is
about AIDS and death.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems to be working.
</P>
<P>
   The national Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
announced last week that new surveys show rates of sexual
intercourse among American high school students have declined for
the first time in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1991 and 1999, the percentage of students ages 14 to 18
who had engaged in intercourse dropped from 54.1 to 49.9, the study
showed. And among teens who are sexually active, condom use is
rising.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the survey means that nearly half of American high school
students have engaged in sexual intercourse. And some teens are
questioning the accuracy of the survey, saying they think the rate
of sexual intercourse among their peers is much higher.
</P>
<P>
   But the report of declining sexual intercourse was heralded as
great news by many teens, youth experts, health officials and
parents. They say it proves the value of early sex education in
schools and parental ``talks'' at home.
</P>
<P>
   And it raises this question:
</P>
<P>
   How could this generation fight off the roaming hands of a pop
culture and mass media seemingly obsessed with sex? Movies,
magazines, music, TV _ everywhere teens look, somebody is in bed
and, apparently, having a great time.
</P>
<P>
   The survey didn't ask why, but Kansas City area teens were quick
with their answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is totally aware from the time they are 9 years old
that you can get AIDS and die,'' said Carrie Moreland, 17, who will
soon begin her senior year at Notre Dame de Sion High School. ``To
most kids, that means something.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about morality ... it's not that we're saving
ourselves for marriage. That has nothing to do with it. It's about
staying alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say this generation is the most informed yet about
sex-related health risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are really trying to scare us, and it must be
working,'' said Justin Morasch, 17, who will be a senior at
Archbishop O'Hara High School.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Ponton, professor of adolescent psychiatry at the
University of California at San Francisco, said the decline shows
that it takes years of sex education to alter teen behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have been hearing about AIDS since elementary
school,'' said Ponton, whose new book is The Sex Lives of
Teenagers: Revealing the Secret World of Adolescent Boys and Girls.
``They know it's out there and they know they can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Janice Ellis, the new president of Kansas City's
Partnership for Children and founder of Reach for the Stars, a
nationally recognized teen pregnancy prevention program, said:
``AIDS is a pretty good deterrent. Death puts a chill into sex.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Campaign for the Prevention of Teen Pregnancy
expands on the trend. Its surveys show that most teens _ eight out
of 10 girls and six out of 10 boys _ who have been sexually active
wish they had waited until they were older.
</P>
<P>
   Teen pregnancy rates also have been dropping, although the rates
in the United States far exceed those of other developed countries.
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer Prize winner Laura Sessions Stepp said teens still
could be putting themselves at risk by engaging in sexual acts that
stop short of intercourse. She said teens are seduced by the mass
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls in late elementary grades look at magazines and they
start wearing slinky slip dresses and 3-inch heels,'' said Stepp,
who wrote Our Last Best Shot: Guiding Our Children Through Early
Adolescence. ``Movies, TV _ these images bombard kids at a very
early age.''
</P>
<P>
   If teens are resisting media influence because of AIDS, it has
taken a while. The epidemic is now in its third decade.
</P>
<P>
   But other reasons for a decrease in the number of sexually
active teens may reach even further into America's social
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents of today's teen-agers grew up witnessing the sexual
revolution, which had its heyday in the late 1960s through the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual mores changed. A growing tolerance of divorce, birth
control, abortion and premarital sex swept the country.
</P>
<P>
   Taboos were lifted. Sex was no longer dirty. Pregnant teens were
no longer secretly taken away in the night to go visit their aunt
in Florida. Movie and television dialogue made sexual references
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that because of those things, parents today
are much more comfortable in talking to their kids about sex than
generations before them,'' said Ponton, who has written several
books on teen behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most teens interviewed for this article said their
parents had talked to them about the risks of sexual activity. Love
and waiting for that right someone is typically part of the spiel,
but today's talk is usually more about the harsh realities of AIDS,
sexually transmitted diseases and youthful dreams shattered by
unwanted pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Morasch said his parents sat him down and gave him the talk
right before his freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them _ they double-teamed me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, parents said they did not get the same talk from
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was taboo back then,'' said Chris Yasso, president of the
Lee's Summit Area Council of PTAs.
</P>
<P>
   Not all parents talk with their children now, she said, but
today there is sex education in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids now learn about sex in the classroom instead of the
hallway or the locker room, where a lot of us learned it,'' Yasso
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Moreland, Carrie Moreland's mother, remembered a day that
illustrates the value of enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in high school, a good friend of mine feared she was
pregnant because she had French-kissed a boy,'' Moreland said. ``My
daughter and her friends are so much better informed about sex and
STDs (sexually transmitted diseases) than we ever were.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Lett of Kansas City said his teens received the talk early
on, and he sees the irony of the decline: It comes at a time when
teens are most casual about discussing sex.
</P>
<P>
   He often comes home to a group of teens visiting his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say things I would never say around my parents,'' Lett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Moreland thinks feminism also gets some credit. Girls are
no longer meek and deferential to boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's girls view their body as their own, and that is
something set in motion a long time ago ... before they were
born,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ponton agrees that feminism has greatly changed what used to be
a predator-prey role in teen-age sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a power balance now in the way boys and girls relate
to each other,'' Ponton said. ``Girls are much more willing now to
control situations and relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Lett, 17, who will be a senior at Grandview High
School, is five months into a relationship with her boyfriend.
Friends are always surprised to learn that she and her boyfriend
are not having sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' they ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' she answers.
</P>
<P>
   But she does know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see kids who get drunk and have sex,'' she said. ``They
don't think anything bad can happen to them. I'm just not that
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't want to have sex. It's just I'm a little
scared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
