<HEADLINE>
ETHERTON STOPS SHEFFIELD AT KEY MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a game of many twists and turns Saturday, the
biggest may have been one of the few times in the weekend
interleague Freeway Series that Dodgers' slugger Gary Sheffield
didn't turn on one of the Angels pitchers' serves.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield slugged four home runs in the three games at Dodger
Stadium, including his 31st of the season in the third inning
Saturday against Angels rookie right-hander Seth Etherton.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the fifth inning, with the Angels ahead by a run, and
the tying run on third base with only one out, Etherton retired
Sheffield on one pitch --- a popup to second. Etherton eventually
got out of the inning and came away with his fourth win in a row,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how good he is,'' Etherton said of Sheffield, who's
slugged six homers in 15 at-bats against the Angels this season.
``He's quite a hitter. I was fortunate to get him to pop it up. I
made a pitcher's pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Etherton, who's 4-1 in seven starts, said he got Sheffield on a
curveball, down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he saw it good,'' Etherton said, ``and he just missed
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Young and not so wild
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia'' says the work of Etherton is all
a part of the club's emphasis on good, young pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these guys . . . Etherton, (Brian) Cooper, (Jarrod)
Washburn, (Scott) Schoeneweis . . . it's their makeup, their poise
that's so impressive,'' Scioscia said of his kiddie korp mound
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys simply go out and make their pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   And, on Etherton, the former pitching star at USC, Scioscia
said: ``He has ice water in his veins.''
</P>
<P>
   No stopping Sheffield
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia explained that he and his staff ``had a couple of plans
in mind'' for pitching to Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it didn't work out so well,'' he said. ``But,
fortunately, we were able to hold the rest of the lineup in
check.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Even with Sheffield's 4 for 9 in the series, the Dodgers
didn't do much at the plate in the three games, a mere .189 (18 for
95). But, minus Sheffield's output, the Dodgers hit only .163 (14
for 86). And, of the Dodgers' eight RBI, Sheffield had five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time when we see him,'' Scioscia said, ``we'll try the
one-bounce cricket pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Roll out the skipper
</P>
<P>
   During the series Scioscia made only three appearances on the
field at Dodger Stadium, where he played for 13 years and caught
more games (1,395) than anyone in Dodgers history, Brooklyn and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them were after the Angels' two wins, Friday night and
Saturday, and the other was in the bottom of the seventh inning
Saturday, when he came out to argue with second base umpire Greg
Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and the Dodgers' F.P. Santangelo on first, Alex
Cora hit a grounder to the right of shortstop Benji Gil, who was
able to get the force at second. But Santangelo upended second
baseman Adam Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a roll,'' Scioscia said. ``I wanted to get the
(umpire's) interpretation. If it's a clean slide, no problem. F.P.
is a tough player, a clean player. But even if it's an
unintentional roll it's still a roll. You're not supposed to roll
into the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   So, was Scioscia satisfied with Gibson's explanation?
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a roll,'' Scioscia reiterated.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   More Erstad
</P>
<P>
   Angels left fielder Darin Erstad, with more two hits Saturday,
has 149 hits for the season, one more than he had all last season.
</P>
<P>
   After going hitless in four at-bats in the first game of the
series with the Dodgers, Erstad was 5 for 11 in the next two.
</P>
</TEXT>
