<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COW-ART-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVE TO BRING COW ART TO KC LEAVES CRITICS UNMOVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALICE THORSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might be a whole herd, it might be a single stray, but it's a
safe bet that some life-size fiberglass cows are coming to a
street, park or shopping district near you.
</P>
<P>
   Influenced by last summer's hugely popular ``Cows on Parade''
installation of 322 decorated cows in Chicago, a local group has
just about corralled the project for Kansas City, which would have
300 cows. Although enthusiasm is running high in some quarters, for
others the idea of duplicating the Chicago effort represents the
civic equivalent of cattle rustling.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion is heating up and could be boiling Monday, when local
organizers bring the project before the 12-member Municipal Art
Commission. Commission member Richard Nadeau recently labeled the
effort ``herd instinct, without critical thinking and judgment.''
Supporters argue that the project would be a popular hit and that
proceeds from it would support worthy causes.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's event attracted global media attention and, according
to Nathan Mason, curator of special projects for the Chicago
Department of Cultural Affairs, raised $200 million for the city,
primarily in tourist dollars. At the end of the outdoor display,
which was paid for with corporate sponsorship, the decorated cows
were auctioned, raising $3.5 million for charity.
</P>
<P>
   An installation of 500 decorated cows now is on display in New
York City. Other cities are looking at ``creature shows'' ranging
from 1,000 fiberglass bulls in Los Altos, Calif., to fiberglass
moose in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Chicago project caught the attention of Karen
Holland, an advisory member of the Municipal Art Commission.
Holland, who also is chairwoman of the Missouri Arts Council,
spearheaded the volunteer effort to get a similar herd of bovines
for Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, she and a group of supporters approached the
Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art about being a beneficiary of the
project, and the museum agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Kemper, the Kansas City version of ``Cows on
Parade'' would benefit the American Royal and the Kansas City Zoo.
On June 20, the three organizations signed a contract with the West
Hartford, Conn.-based CowParade Holdings Corp. to ``bring the cows
home,'' in the words of Dan Keegan, director of the Kemper Museum.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, representatives of the Kemper, the zoo and the
American Royal will ask the Municipal Art Commission for permission
to install the cows on city property from May to August 2001. The
cows would be placed throughout the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming presentation spurred Nadeau, an opponent of the
project, to fire off a letter to Mayor Kay Barnes and to circulate
it to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a franchise project _ commercial art, not public
art,'' Nadeau argued in his July 6 letter.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues Nadeau raised was the copycat overtones of
reproducing the Chicago venture.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan said the core group agonized over the question of doing
cows in initial meetings about Kansas City's community project.
</P>
<P>
   They considered different animals _ New Orleans did fish,
Cincinnati did pigs _ and other objects, and even explored the idea
of doing beef cows instead of the dairy cows used in Chicago. But
the costs were prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking at figures like a half-million dollars to get
a designer and make a prototype,'' Keegan said. (Under the
contract, CowParade Holdings Corp. will provide Kansas City with
fabricated cow forms.)
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Keegan said, the group ``couldn't come up with an
object that said `Kansas City' better than a cow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the original cow town,'' he said. ``It is the fact that
has established this community. It's nothing to apologize for; it's
something to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City ``Cows on Parade'' largely would follow the
blueprint used in Chicago, enlisting nearly 300 artists to decorate
fabricated fiberglass cow forms. Local corporations would be
invited to sponsor cows and have their names listed on accompanying
plaques for $5,000 each, for a potential corporate outlay of $1.5
million. Of each $5,000, $1,000 would go to pay the artists and
most of the rest would go to cover expenses.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the outdoor display, the cows would be auctioned,
with the proceeds benefiting educational programs at the Kemper,
the American Royal and the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   No taxpayer dollars would be spent on the project, Keegan said.
Out of the $5,000 per cow paid by corporate and individual
sponsors, CowParade will cover shipping, placement, maintenance,
upkeep, marketing and publicity, and liability, as well as the
artists' fees.
</P>
<P>
   According to Keegan, CowParade would put out an open call for
artists to submit designs, which would be reviewed by a committee
of local arts professionals and community representatives. The
committee also would invite ``significant national and regional
artists'' to submit designs, Keegan said.
</P>
<P>
   Project guidelines prohibit pornography, corporate logos or
signs in the designs of the cows. CowParade retains the copyrights
to the designs as part of the overall exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of using decorated fiberglass cows to enliven city
streets began in Switzerland, with a 1998 parade of 800 cows in
Zurich. This summer, there are CowParade displays in New York City;
West Orange, N.J.; and Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers are not proving as enthusiastic about the project as
Chicagoans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's really art,'' said Tom Eccles, director of
the Public Art Fund, a nonprofit organization that organizes public
art projects in New York. ``It has the potential to be an
incredible setback if you're trying to present serious but engaging
contemporary art in public spaces,'' Eccles said in a recent
telephone interview. ``It certainly hasn't caught on with the
artistic community of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   A story in the July 12 New York Times asked: ``Isn't it time to
put those fiberglass visitors out to pasture?''
</P>
<P>
   ``So now New York is copying Chicago, a cow town, and
Switzerland, a cow country,'' writer Sarah Boxer observed in an
article that did not once use the word ``art'' in its review of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer noted that several designs, including a ``Moonica Lewinsky
cow,'' were rejected by the New York organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boxer characterized the cows as ``a public moosance,''
Keegan thinks Kansas Citians will be enthusiastic about the bovine
invasion here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that this is going to go,'' he said in a
recent interview. ``It's a great project. The community is truly
behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Keegan recently contacted Janet Simpson, executive director of
the Kansas City Artists Coalition, about having the coalition
represented on the CowParade selection panel.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Star, Simpson was supportive of the
project. ``From the coalition's point of view, we're very happy any
time a project is committed to paying artists for their work,'' she
said. ``We're also very happy that the selection process will be
open and all artists will be invited to submit a proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolphin gallery owner John O'Brien, a prime mover in the
development of the Crossroads Art District and a staunch advocate
of local artists, said he thinks it is disrespectful to artists to
ask them to paint cows.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, O'Brien mused about the $1.5 million
corporate sponsorship of the cows and what it could mean for the
local art scene if used to promote Kansas City art and assist
Kansas City artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word is getting out that Kansas City is viable,'' he observed.
``There are artists doing unique things, creative things. Why step
back and do something that's been done? That's old hat. We're not
old hat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
