r s BC-GREENE-OLYMPICS-KAN &LR;      07-15 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENE-OLYMPICS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENE MAKES UP FOR LOST TIME, REALIZES OLYMPIC DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POSNANSKI  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Maurice Greene's dream was too powerful.
Everything went wrong for him Saturday at the U.S Track and Field
Trials. He stumbled out of the gate. He fell way behind. A stiff
wind blew in his face. The other sprinters tried to play mind
games. Psych him out.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene has dreamed all his life of the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene is going to the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the Olympic team,'' Greene sang as he danced. ``I made
the Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene made the U.S. Olympic Team on Saturday when he won the
100-meter dash. It wasn't the race he dreamed about. Greene has
studied his race so thoroughly that he has planned every one of the
451/2 steps he takes. He had planned to come here, win, break his
own world record, run the perfect race.
</P>
<P>
   The stumble ended his dream of the perfect race. But this race
showed what kind of heart beats inside Maurice Greene. When he
stumbled out of the blocks, everyone in the stadium gasped. This
the Olympic Trials, a place where dreams are shattered in an
instant. St. Louis' Jeff Hartwig had been an Olympic favorite in
the pole vault, but this week he had trouble with his contact
lenses and was not able to clear the lowest height. His dream died.
</P>
<P>
   And it looked that way for Greene as he fell behind. The
100-meter dash, runners say, is too short to make up a mistake. But
Maurice Greene started gaining. There's no runner in the world who
makes up ground quite like Maurice Greene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't panic,'' he said. ``I just stayed with it. I just
kept thinking, over and over, `Keep running.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He could not let the dream die. The dream of being the world's
fastest man has been pounding inside him ever since he was a child
in Kansas City, Kan. His parents used to watch him outside the
window, just running back and forth across the yard. When they
asked him what he was doing, he said simply, ``Practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   His older brother, Ernest, was always faster. Maurice at first
dreamed only of catching his brother. When he caught Ernest, that's
when he started thinking about the world. In 1995, he beat the
great sprinter Carl Lewis for the first time. He thought he would
make the Olympic team in 1996. He wasn't quite ready. He ended
those trials in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to let that happen again,'' Greene said
Saturday. ``There was no way. When I stumbled out of the gate, I
just knew I would catch up. I knew I was going to make the Olympic
team. There was no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He did catch up. He ran by. And then, with the breathtaking
finish _ nobody in the world can finish like Maurice Greene _ he
won. He did not know how to react. In the past, Greene has finished
races with style. He has stuck out his tongue. He has pumped his
fists. He has mugged for the camera.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he simply raised his hand in the air. With one
finger.
</P>
<P>
   That's how he always expected to finish in his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not shocked, of course,'' Greene said. ``I expected this.
But I still have to let it sink in. I'm going to the Olympic Games.
Those are pretty powerful words. I'm going to the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene finished at 10.01 seconds, which is relatively slow by
his standards. Greene has run under 10 seconds a record 27 times.
He ran a 9.93 on Friday. But then, this wasn't about time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to make the Olympic team, that's all,'' Greene
said. ``There was no other goal. I made it. This is my first
step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
