<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3439 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN--WILLiAMS-HNS &LR;      07-15 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN--WILLiAMS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Saints' Williams set to make up for awkward rookie year
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THIBODAUX, La. _ When his rookie season came to a merciful close,
Saints running back Ricky Williams could not wait to escape New
Orleans and seek sanctuary in Austin, where he went to college and
is accepted for what he is _ a big kid with a large trophy and a
huge bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is loved and respected in Austin, where he's just as
comfortable in a dormitory room as a million-dollar mansion. He can
blend in with the University of Texas crowd and doesn't have the
enormous responsibility of trying to carry the weight of an entire
region on his broad shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very positive atmosphere for me,'' Williams said
Saturday after the Saints' first practice of training camp at
Nicholls State. ``They didn't try to label me. I didn't have to
worry about people calling me a bum or a crybaby. That happened
almost everywhere I went except Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, Williams often was viewed as a nonconformist who
was as popular as rap music, as unpredictable as the weather and as
ornery as an agitated alligator. After former coach Mike Ditka
traded everything but Bourbon Street to get him, Williams was under
incredible pressure to produce in almost superhuman fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media put him on a pedestal,'' said first-year coach Jim
Haslett, who was hired to replace Ditka. ``It's tough on a
22-year-old rookie when he's expected to be the savior.''
</P>
<P>
   The expectations of the fans and media were unrealistic and
unfair. After winning the Heisman Trophy and setting the NCAA
Division I career rushing record during his senior year, Williams
was supposed to be a football Moses who would help the Saints march
to the promised land.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, Williams got lost. Moses became
football's Master P. Rather than sign with a legitimate sports
agent _ and they all wanted to sign him _ he chose No Limit Sports,
founded by Percy Miller, an NBA wannabe and music impresario who
became famous as Master P.
</P>
<P>
   After the Saints traded eight draft choices, including two No. 1
picks, to acquire him, Williams signed what is perhaps the worst
contract in NFL history for a player of his stature. He also posed
in a wedding dress for the cover of ESPN the Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, which was plagued by injuries, he rushed for only
884 yards and scored two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sport driven by results, and I didn't have results,''
Williams said. ``At the (Indianapolis scouting) combine before I
was drafted, (former Oilers running back) Alonzo Highsmith told me
not to play hurt because I'd be judged by how I played when I was
injured, not that I was playing with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not that kind of player. My No. 1 priority is to the
team, not myself. I think you have to make some sacrifices. I
sacrificed people questioning my talent to try to help the team
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was ridiculed and criticized as an uncooperative,
injury-prone malcontent who went out of his way to irritate the
media by limiting interviews to once a week, conducting interview
sessions with his helmet on, sleeping in his locker and on the
floor, and giving one- and two-word answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sleep in the locker room,'' Williams said. ``A lot of
that stuff was fabricated. I have to understand that I'm in the
spotlight, and people are going to exaggerate things about me. I
have to make sure to take extra steps to be normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're winning, it's easy to stay positive, but when
things start going bad, you have to look for someone to blame.
Everything just becomes negative.''
</P>
<P>
   When Williams finally sat still for a lengthy interview, he made
the biggest mistake of his career _ he said what he thought about
his coaches, teammates, New Orleans and Saints fans. It was
difficult to find anyone who wasn't insulted by his comments in
Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of the guys were offended,'' Williams said.
``At this level, we're all men. They'd come to me and ask about it.
I think a lot of guys understood that I was speaking out of
frustration. As a tough competitor, things are going to come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did wrong was that I should have gone to the players
and talked to them about it instead of having them read about it.
But that's in the past, and we're all ready to move on. I think
they respect me as a football player, so I don't think it should be
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Words won't earn Williams respect from his teammates. Actions
will.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing about Ricky is that he should be a man about it,''
said quarterback Jeff Blake, who is in his first season as the
starter after leaving Cincinnati as a free agent. ``A man's
responsible for his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky has an aura about him. When I first met Michael Jordan,
I could feel his aura. Joe Montana was the same way. Players like
that give off a vibe that makes you want to be part of it. Ricky
has that capability, but he has to humble himself and realize it's
not all about him. It's about your team, your family, your loved
ones and your friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you do for people, the more God will bless you. The
more you give, the more you receive.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds offensive tackle Kyle Turley, ``He just has to get out
there and do his job like the rest of us, and if we win, everything
will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Sports Illustrated controversy, Williams fired his
agent and hired Leigh Steinberg, the premier agent in the NFL. One
of Steinberg's specialties is damage control. He has his work cut
out trying to help Williams change his image.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just told me to work hard, but that's never been a problem
for me,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, Williams returned to the University of Texas
to work on his degree in elementary education, which he's two
semesters shy of earning. He sought out Earl Campbell for advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me you've got to learn to accept things that come
along in this game, and the better you do it, the better things
will come out in the long run,'' Williams said. ``Last year, I was
in a different world, and they (New Orleans fans) didn't receive me
the way I'd been received in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college, you're looked at as a kid, and I was one of their
kids in everyday life. In the NFL, they expect you to do things a
certain way, and if you don't, they're going to criticize you.
People thought I was cocky and full of myself, but I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have taken it personally last year because they didn't
know me from Jack. But now I try to not take it personally because
I understand it's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams also vacationed in Europe in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was neat because things move slower over there, and people
didn't recognize me,'' he said. ``I had a good time relaxing and
just being myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was able to be himself at both practices Saturday. His
mother, Sandy Williams, came to camp from her home in Austin. She
wore his No. 34 jersey, signed autographs for fans and talked with
the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know she was here, but that's great,'' Haslett said.
``We emphasized to the players and coaches that we want to build a
family-type atmosphere, and their families are welcome at camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Ricky doesn't have to be a superstar. It's great
that we have good people who can take the emphasis off him and
allow him to concentrate on football.''
</P>
<P>
   Under new offensive coordinator Mike McCarthy, who was
quarterbacks coach at Green Bay, the Saints are installing the West
Coast offense. If Williams stays healthy, the coaches say he can
rush for 1,200 yards and catch 45 passes. It's the first time
coaches have wanted him to be an integral part of the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any reason I can't be an every-down player,''
Williams said. ``I'm very optimistic about the system and the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said I wasn't a good football player last season
because I didn't produce. This season, I don't want attention, but
I understand why I get it. I just want to play football. I'm just
another piece of the puzzle trying to help us win.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
