<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SEEING STORM WARNINGS AFTER LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With his expansive knowledge of the movie
industry, Dodgers managing general partner and CEO Bob Daly
certainly should appreciate the latest film about nature's fury,
``The Perfect Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Daly in his infancy running the Dodgers, he may be on
the precipice of experiencing another not-so-pleasant storm. For
the third straight year, that's the direction the Dodgers are
heading.
</P>
<P>
   After falling to the Angels 6-2 Saturday at Dodger Stadium to
conclude their three-game series, the Dodgers are in jeopardy of
falling to .500 for the first time since April 8 if they don't beat
Pittsburgh today.
</P>
<P>
   Even the scorching bat of Gary Sheffield can't overcome the
other problems the Dodgers are experiencing. Sheffield hit his
major-league-leading 31st homer in the third inning, but it was one
of only three hits the Dodgers managed off Angels starter Seth
Etherton (4-1) in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers (45-44) remained six games behind Arizona in the
National League West, though they're in fourth place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long way to go to catch up, and it's not like we're
chasing one team,'' said Sheffield, who hit four homers in the
three-game series. ``That's the bad part about this whole
situation. If we were playing just as well as those teams in front
of us (it would be different), but we're not. It seems like we're
going the other way and they're going forward. It makes it that
much more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   While Etherton showed composure and control in winning his
fourth straight start, Dodgers right-hander Chan Ho Park (9-7) lost
his third straight. He walked seven for the third time this season
and leads the National League with 78 walks. Each of the three runs
he allowed in his five innings reached base because of walks.
</P>
<P>
   Park, needed greatly if the Dodgers are to make any kind of move
toward the postseason, has followed his five-game winning streak by
failing to win in his past five starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got to the usually reliable Dodgers bullpen to extend
their lead to 5-2 in the sixth inning when Bengie Molina drove in
two runs with a single to right off reliever Antonio Osuna.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone by Sheffield, Angels third baseman Troy Glaus
homered for the third straight game. His solo shot in the eighth
off Matt Herges was his 28th, and gave the Angels a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you're on the road, to win two of three against a
good ballclub, you have to be pleased,'' Angels manager and former
Dodgers catcher Mike Scioscia said. ``It's a good feeling, but
there's no more satisfaction beating this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will in San Diego today to conclude their interleague
schedule with a three-game series against the Padres, and they go
feeling good about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But at Chavez Ravine, questions linger about what the next two
months will be like, not to mention the future of the Dodgers.
Their hope is the return of Mark Grudzielanek and Todd Hundley,
both expected back early in the week, changes their downward
spiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you lose, things are not good,'' Dodgers first
baseman Eric Karros said. ``Am I feeling tense? Are certain guys
feeling tense? I don't know about that. I approach the game the
same every day. It's not like all of a sudden I'm going to take it
to a new level. I play as hard as I can every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does everybody want to win and would we like a better
situation? Sure. But it's not because it's a lack of effort or a
lack of desire. ... You'd like to have some stability, but the
bottom line is if you're not winning, you're not winning. I don't
think anybody wants to languish around .500, but change for the
sake of change, I don't know if that's the answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
