<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EITZMANN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EITZMANN HOPES TO BE QUICK STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Like thousands of rookies before him, Patriots
tight end Chris Eitzmann had a predictable first impression of pro
football: These guys are fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect,'' said Eitzmann after his first
few days with the team. ``I was expecting it to be a lot tougher
than college, of course, but everyone's so quick and fast. They're
a lot faster than they were at Harvard . . . obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Eitzmann was the captain of the 1999 Harvard team, a rare honor
for a tight end, and he has grown _ in many ways _ since arriving
in Cambridge as a 190-pound freshman. Now he is up to 250 pounds,
is football tough _ discard all Ivy League stereotypes _ and comes
to the Patriots as a quick tight end who can catch.
</P>
<P>
   Tight ends in pro football are divided into two categories: the
slower types known for blocking, and the quicker players who can
escape linebackers at the line of scrimmage and free themselves for
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Eitzmann has been practicing with the blocking tight ends, but
his Harvard resume shows speed and receiving ability, with 19
catches last season and 45 for his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a 4.6 (in the 40-yard dash) a few weeks back,'' said
Eitzmann, ``and I was proud of that. I'd definitely say speed is
one of my strengths. When I came to Harvard, I weighed 190 pounds
and I was never known as one of the biggest or strongest guys, even
in high school. And the tight ends don't catch a lot of passes in
Harvard's offense, so by the time I got to my senior year, I
thought I had developed into a pretty good blocker.''
</P>
<P>
   Eitzmann has already overcome obstacles. He is from the small
town of Hardy, Neb. _ yes, he was Harvard's first captain from
Nebraska _ and was so highly regarded at Chester-Hubbell-Byron High
School (``a regional school for three small farming towns'') that
Nebraska coach Tom Osborne tried to recruit him.
</P>
<P>
   Few Nebraska boys turn down an invitation to play for the
Cornhuskers. But that is exactly what Eitzmann did, and the
Lincoln, Neb., newspaper headlined his shocking decision in words
Eitzmann still remembers: ``Eitzmann turns down Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people came up to me and gave me their opinion,''
Eitzmann said. ``They'd say, `How could you turn down Nebraska? You
just turned down every Nebraska boy's dream.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Eitzmann has no regrets about the decision (``I'm 100
percent sure I made the right choice'') and the folks back home in
Nebraska are with him. ``Now they say, `Chris, you made the right
decision.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The only flicker of doubt in Eitzmann's mind came on draft day
in April, when Eitzmann saw player after player selected from
high-profile football programs. ``I was watching that and I was
thinking, `I wonder if I'd have been drafted if I went to
Nebraska.' But that was it . . . the only time. I know I made the
right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the draft, the Patriots signed some promising
non-draftees, including a few from the area. Eitzmann met with
agent Brad Blank at Mike Boyle's gym in Winchester, where a few of
Blank's players work out.
</P>
<P>
   Blank, his Boston-based agent, feels Eitzmann has long-term
potential because he went to Harvard, instead of a football factory
where the hours are long and the football days longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got upside potential that a player from one of
the football factories doesn't have,'' said Blank. ``Compared to
guys who've gone to those kind of schools, where football is a
year-round thing, Chris hasn't played a lot of football. We all
know how Harvard approaches football. If he sticks with the
Patriots in some capacity, the upside for Chris is a lot better
than a guy who's been going nonstop football the last five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Ben Coates gone, the chances of a rookie free agent
tight end making the Patriots are slim. Eitzmann majored in
psychology and has done summer work at a Boston investment banking
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Might he follow in the footsteps of Nebraska's famed investment
billionaire Warren Buffett if football doesn't work out? Well,
acknowledged Eitzmann, he has not met Buffett, and has not
approached Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway Inc. firm in Omaha. Like
many just out of college, Eitzmann said, ``I don't know what I'd do
. . . maybe go back to the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2,500-acre farm has been in the family since 1900 and it'll
soon be time to harvest the soybeans and corn. But Eitzmann is
hoping to be in New England for the fall, sticking with the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard . . . we go from 7 in the morning to 6 at night,''
said Eitzmann. The veterans will be taking the field for the first
time Monday, so it gets harder.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the time has been spent on the mental side of pro
football, learning the offense. ``I might have a little edge on the
other guys when it comes to that, but it's still tough,'' said
Eitzmann.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
