<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO--Astros-Tigers-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' bullpen melts down against Tigers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DETROIT _ When it comes to using his bullpen, Astros manager Larry
Dierker calls it a guessing game.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, there were no right answers. Dierker kept sending
pitchers to the mound _ and the Detroit Tigers kept sending runners
across home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' bullpen suffered a total breakdown during a
seven-run seventh inning as the Tigers rallied for an 11-6 victory
before a sellout crowd of 39,189 at Comerica Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole inning was a disaster,'' Dierker said after watching
the Tigers tag four Astros relievers for five hits, two walks and
two sacrifice flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relief pitching was terrible. Maybe it would have been
better if I had picked different guys. It's been hard to get anyone
into a role, because it's good game, bad game for almost everybody
down there (in the bullpen).
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm guessing sometimes. Most of the times, I'm
guessing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The question Saturday was which reliever to employ. The possible
answers:
</P>
<P>
   A.) Yorkis Perez; B.) Marc Valdes; C.) Doug Henry; D.) Jose
Cabrera.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, it was none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   The first six Tigers reached and scored in the seventh. By the
time the inning was over, the Tigers had sent 10 batters to the
plate and had turned a 5-4 deficit into an 11-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Tigers climb back from a 4-1 deficit to get
within a run, Dierker decided to remove starter Jose Lima after
sixth innings. His plan was for Perez to face Bobby Higginson, a
lefthanded hitter, and then bring Henry in to face the Tigers'
mostly righthanded-hitting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan didn't work,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson doubled to left-center off Perez, sliding in just
ahead of Moises Alou's throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higgy made it happen,'' Detroit manager Phil Garner said. ``He
made himself get to second.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry (1-3) faced only three batters, allowing two walks and a
single.
</P>
<P>
   He walked Dean Palmer, and Deivi Cruz followed with a single
that tied the score at 5. After a walk to Juan Encarnacion, Valdes
entered and immediately surrendered a two-run bloop single to
former Astro Brad Ausmus.
</P>
<P>
   Damion Easley's RBI single, two sacrifice flies and a
run-scoring triple by Luis Polonia completed the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen has blown 15 of 26 save opportunities this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be leading the world in blown saves,'' Henry said.
``We've got to find a way to fight out of this. We just can't sit
here and say, `Here we go again.'''
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros weren't thinking that, the Tigers were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't concerned. I never felt like we were going to lose
the ballgame,'' Higginson said. ``Not with their bullpen and the
way we've been swinging. They really don't have much of a bullpen.
It was like they were out there saying, `When are we going to give
it up?'''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he decided to take Lima, who had made only 84
pitches, out of the game after the Tigers began to hit the
righthander hard in the fifth and sixth innings. Lima allowed four
runs and 10 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every hitter that came up was hitting the ball the last
two innings (off him),'' Dierker said. ``I felt like he was just on
the edge of the same sort of disaster that befell the bullpen
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) at least he was throwing strikes. Throw strikes and
you've got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima did not second-guess Dierker's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't go any further,'' Lima said. ``I was making some
pretty quality pitches out there, but they were hitting them. It
seems like everything I throw is being hit. It's like I'm telling
them what pitch is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers took the lead in the second when Palmer doubled and
scored on Ausmus' single.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros answered with four in the fourth off Tigers starter
Willie Blair, highlighted by Tony Eusebio's two-run homer over the
420-foot mark in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio is only the third opposing player to hit a ball to the
deepest part of Comerica Park. Alou, who had two or more hits for
the fifth straight game to raise his average to .367, had an RBI
single, and Richard Hidalgo added a sacrifice fly, but Alou was
doubled off base by Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Eusebio homered. Hidalgo hit his team-leading
25th home run in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you score this many runs you're supposed to win,'' Dierker
said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
