<HEADER>
A3447 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-REAX-BOS &LR;      07-15 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-REAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMMATES TRY TO DEFLECT ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pitcher Rod Beck, who is on the disabled list, was in the Red
Sox clubhouse when Carl Everett finally made his way back there
after his second-inning ejection Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he was a little ragged,'' Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   Beck, a 10-year veteran, has some knowledge of Everett's
reputation for anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into that,'' he said. ``It doesn't
pertain to this, to tell you the truth. He's here now. For the most
part since he's been here, everybody knows he's outspoken, but
since he's been here he's been a pretty solid citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll give him the benefit of the doubt. We're his teammates.
We're behind him. What else are you going to do? I would hope if I
went off like that, teammates would be behind me. Sometimes, your
emotions get the better of you.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long season. If you play enough years, you're going to
have an incident or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck believed the umpires may have discussed Everett's
positioning in the batter's box after the game Friday night, when
Mets lefthander Dennis Cook pointed out to plate umpire Marty
Foster where Everett was standing.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 6.03 in the Official Playing Rules states: ``No part of the
batter's foot is to be closer than 6 inches from the side of home
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules are rules,'' Beck said. ``It's pretty cut and dry. It
says 6 inches. I can't throw 6 inches in front of the rubber. That
doesn't mean I haven't done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Sox players kept their distance from Everett during his
outburst, except for Jose Offerman, who joined coaches Tommy Harper
and Wendell Kim in their attempts to restrain the player. Batting
coach Jim Rice, perhaps the one person in a Sox uniform physically
qualified to handle a player of Everett's strength, sat on the
dugout steps.
</P>
<P>
   Harper, who two weeks ago in Chicago pulled a cursing Everett
away from Globe columnist Dan Shaughnessy in the visiting clubhouse
at Comiskey Park, did not want to address Everett's behavior. He
did, however, understand why Everett had become angry when plate
umpire Ronald Kulpa made an issue of how close Everett was standing
to home plate, twice drawing a line in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was standing in the same spot last night; he's been hitting
from the same spot all year,'' Harper said. ``You can't have a
different batter's box game to game. The other part, you'll have to
ask Carl.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Everett finally was hauled into the Sox dugout, veteran
Bret Saberhagen made an effort to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   The presumption is that Saberhagen was attempting to calm him.
``No, I was trying to get him to go back on the field,'' Saberhagen
said sarcastically. ``That was something between him and me. Write
what you guys want to write. I have no comment on Carl. It's
unfortunate what happened, that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Ace pitcher Pedro Martinez also attempted to deflect attention
away from Everett, even though the club is likely to lose its
leading home run hitter and RBI man for at least five games,
pending a decision by Frank Robinson, the major league official in
charge of on-field discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't make a big deal about it, guys,'' Martinez said to
reporters. ``Come on, guys, pick us up. Write about the game. It
doesn't matter. Don't just write the negative stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield, the team's player representative, agreed. ``A guy
got thrown out. Big deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Mike Stanley, whose word carries considerable weight in
the Sox clubhouse, said Everett has not been a negative influence
on the team. ``He hasn't been loud or boisterous in the clubhouse.
Most of his snaps have been against himself, when he hits himself
in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett has a habit of being one of the last players to arrive
in the clubhouse, well after the time stipulated by manager Jimy
Williams. ``That might be between him and Jimy,'' Stanley said,
``but it's not something disrupting the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Eckersley, the former Sox reliever who was with Oakland
in the 1990 playoffs when Roger Clemens had his notorious meltdown
with umpire Terry Cooney, worked Saturday on the Sox radio
broadcast. Eckersley said this incident couldn't compare because so
much more was at stake when Clemens lost it.
</P>
<P>
   He also said displays such as Everett's have been commonplace
for years. ``But nowadays, with so much TV, you see a lot of guys
looking (stupid).''
</P>
<P>
   The worst he's seen for losing composure? ``Frank Robby,''
Eckersley said, ``and he's the guy giving out the suspensions. I
don't want to single out Frank, but he was tough. When he got
(angry) at an umpire, you knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what I was surprised at? Derek Bell coming in,''
Eckersley said, referring to the Mets outfielder's attempt to
intervene. ``What was that? That looks weak . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing when a guy on another team gets hurt and you're
worried about your buddy, but that's not cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who contended the Mets were behind the umpires'
decision to make an issue of where Everett stood in the box, was
asked if he had concerns about Everett's temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not really, This is the first time somebody's done
something like drawing a line in the batter's box. He just reacted,
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if Everett's reaction was justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to talk to Carl,'' he said. ``You certainly don't
like to see a player ejected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
