<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3448 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS &LR;      07-15 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Woods would love to complete sweep at St. Andrews
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Arnold Palmer never did it. Neither did Sam
Snead, Tom Watson, Byron Nelson or Billy Casper.
</P>
<P>
   This week, where the game of golf began so many centuries ago,
Tiger Woods gets the chance to do what only a foursome of people
have done before _ win all of golf's modern grand-slam tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   And since he hasn't even reached his 25th birthday yet, it could
be a crowning moment for Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that I've always wanted to do,'' Woods said.
``And to be able to have the chance to do it at the home course
where golf all started, that's what anyone would want. It would be
great to complete the Slam at St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that it's happened this year, to have two of the
greatest sites you can ever play on _ Pebble Beach in the U.S. Open
and to hopefully complete the Slam at St. Andrews, that's what you
always want. And for me to be in that position, I'm very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   No, just very, very good. Woods is trying to join Gene Sarazen,
Ben Hogan, Gary Player and Jack Nicklaus as the only people who
have won all four of golf's modern majors _ the Masters, U.S. Open,
British Open and PGA. Nobody has won them in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Jones, of course, won the Grand Slam in one year _ 1930 _
when it consisted of the U.S. and British Opens and Amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, not everybody is conceding Woods will complete the
Slam in fairy-tale fashion at St. Andrews' famed Old Course. He is
a value wager at 5-2 in the British bookie parlors.
</P>
<P>
   But many others seem sure Woods' game is tailor-fitted to the
wide expanses of St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tiger Woods doesn't win the Open, there should be a
stewards' inquiry,'' said Sir Michael Bonallack, the recently
retired secretary of the Royal &AMP; Ancient Golf Club of St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   This is no horse race. And would they have reason to suspect
hanky-panky when Secretariat is 31 lengths ahead of the field?
</P>
<P>
   Woods set the tone for things when he arrived in Ireland on
Monday. He was coming off his worst showing in months, finishing
well down the list at the Advil Western Open on Sunday and then
traveling all night to get to Ireland on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of hours later, he was teeing off in the first round of
a two-day charity pro-am. All he did that day was break the course
record with a 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any problem with the way I struck the ball in
Chicago,'' Woods said. ``The problem was that I putted horribly. I
putted so badly, it's a joke. But I putted pretty bad before the
U.S. Open, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And we all know how that came out. Woods stomped the field by 15
shots at Pebble Beach and now, after a suitable rest period, we
suspect Woods is ready for another feast. He typically chows down
on records and fellow touring pros whenever the big tournaments
present themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been too busy taking it easy,'' Woods said, using a
suitable oxymoron to explain his time since Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   There was time spent celebrating, and, yes, the champagne does
taste better when you drink it out of the U.S. Open trophy. And,
now that he has come to the U.K., he's not about to let anything
get in the way of getting ready for the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, OK. Maybe he will let one thing get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm over here to enjoy the fishing,'' Woods said. ``That's the
best thing about coming over here early for the Open Championship.
You can take some time for fishing and play a few of the wonderful
courses over here.''
</P>
<P>
   None of which is more wonderful than the Old Course, of course.
His appearance this year at the British Open is causing almost as
much of a stir as the flap between Mark James and Nick Faldo, who
have warred about the contents of James' book Into the Bear Pit for
the past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament organizers at Loch Lomond were aghast when Woods'
appearance at the Limerick Golf Club on Monday drew extensive
coverage while the pro-am for the Loch Lomond, which is a premier
event on the European Tour, drew nary a mention in the British
papers.
</P>
<P>
   During the charity pro-am event, a chance to play with Woods and
Mark O'Meara at the pair's home course in Orlando, Fla., was
auctioned off for slightly more than one million pounds. That is
close to $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   One tabloid said Woods playing at the rather nondescript
Limerick Club was ``like the Pope dropping in to give a sermon at
your local church.''
</P>
<P>
   And competitors who are readying themselves for the British Open
are showing their respect for Woods in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never had someone as dominant as Tiger, not in my
career anyway,'' said Colin Montgomerie. ``This is all very new,
this complete dominance by one player. And we all know that we've
got a battle on our hands with his ambition and his will. If that
stays with him, we've got a battle on our hands every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not every week. Fortunately, for the rest of golfdom,
Woods plays fewer than half the events on the PGA Tour schedule.
</P>
<P>
   When you win virtually all of them you tee up in, you can take
off whenever you want. It's one of the perks of the job.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, by the way, already has won one award from Woods
leading up to this major _ most melodramatic performance. It was
Montgomerie who has said that, were he to win his first major at
St. Andrews, he likely ``would retire from the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've won a major at St. Andrews, where else is there to
go but down?'' he said. ``I might rather retire and be done with
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie wasn't more than half-serious when he said that. But
he has the mood pegged pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger has set this incredible standard, and everybody's trying
to emulate him,'' Faldo said. ``Golf is going to improve. It has
to. It's going to take a few years, but he's going to drive these
kids to a new level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God I'm retiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, so that's the word that the Brits use for what we call
Tigeritis _ the avoidance of tournaments in which Woods is playing.
</P>
<P>
   With the passing of players like Faldo, Fred Couples, Greg
Norman and others who are well into their 40s, it will be left to
the youngsters like Spain's Sergio Garcia, Australia's Aaron
Baddeley and Adam Scott and perhaps a new crop of American
collegians such as Matt Kuchar, Charles Howell or the University of
Houston's Andy Sanders to try to draw a bead on Woods.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean others in their prime won't have their
moments. Phil Mickelson, Ernie Els, Jesper Parnevik, David Duval
and others have plenty of golf ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, there is only Tiger when it comes to talking about
the golf's reigning superstar for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate the fact that he has a chance to complete the
career Slam before his 25th birthday, consider that Nicklaus didn't
do it until after he had turned 26.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Woods hasn't done it yet. But you get the feeling by
the end of next weekend, he will be in the history books with the
current Fab Four. One thing is certain: Woods is not in any way,
shape or form worried about anybody else on the golf course this
week other than himself. He was asked recently if there was
anything that intimidated him. His response?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe stepping into the ring with Mike Tyson,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad for the others at the British Open that Tyson won't be
inside these ropes this week.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
