<HEADER>
A3449 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-HALLOFFAM     07-15 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-HALLOFFAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVRATILOVA INDUCTED INTO HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ She got slam-dunked by a basketball player. It
hurt, but it eventually made the difference on her own kind of
court. A pivotal difference, you might say.
</P>
<P>
   Martina Navratilova is describing her epiphany as a tennis
player: ``I was almost 26. It was 1981. I'd already won Wimbledon
twice, but this year I got beat in the semifinals (by another
Czech, Hana Mandlikova), and I thought I was a failure. So did my
friend and coach, Nancy Lieberman.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, an all-timer of college and pro basketball, told
Navratilova, ``You're wasting your talent, not working hard, and
you're getting older. It's disgraceful. You could be the best ever
if you'd shape up. But it'll soon be too late.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy was absolutely right,'' said Martina, who overcame her
love affair with the International House of Pancakes and other
diversions and became quite possibly the best ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was late to really start with a new outlook. But Nancy sold
me on total commitment to the game. I went to the gym and started
working out seriously. She worked me harder than I ever imagined.
I'd been irresponsible, but I changed, thanks to her burning me.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, a spare, finely-tuned Navratilova was
fast-breakingly ferocious and unstoppable, a one-woman assault wave
who Saturday washed up at the edge of Narragansett Bay long enough
to accept sporting canonization at the International Tennis Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Completing the Class of 2000, two other saints, Aussie Mal
Anderson and Judge Robert Kelleher, marched into the Casino and
onto God's own sod: the grass court where Dick Sears won the
initial US Championship in 1881. Anderson, a successor to Sears as
the US champ in 1957 (the first to win the title unseeded), helped
his homeland win two Davis Cups, widely separated, in 1957 and
1973.
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher ``should be thanked by every professional tennis player
living,'' lauded his presenter, Billie Jean King. ``When the judge
was president of the US Tennis Association, he gave the big push
needed to make open tennis a reality in 1968. Instead of peanuts we
were getting under the table as amateurs, it was prize money on top
of the table, and the game took off. Thanks, Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martina was the event's drawing card, the attraction _
``Martina the Magnificent,'' her presenter, Dr. Renee Richards,
declared to enthusiastic applause from the nearly 4,000 admirers
who filled the venerable amphitheater despite the threat of rain on
a somber, wind-chilled afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As her mother, Jana Navratilova, beamed from a nearby chair,
Martina recalled her small-town days in Revnice, a leafy village
outside Prague. She was the romantic catalyst in bringing her
divorced mom together with her beloved stepfather, Mirek Navratil.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would fill a wheelbarrow with clay to take to the courts at
the small club,'' Martina said. ``He gave me rides on the
wheelbarrow when I was 3. Then when I was older, he took me onto
the court to show me the game. My mom and I both fell for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play at the club, kids paid their dues by doing 20 hours of
work _ weed-pulling, rolling, watering, lining the courts. My
grandmother and my mother made me eat carrot salad all the time _
good for the eyesight, they said.''
</P>
<P>
   Also nearby was Martina's angel, Jan Kodes, a Wimbledon and
French Open champ and Hall of Famer himself. ``Jan had standing in
Czechoslovakia,'' Navratilova said, ``and he talked the tennis
federation into letting me go to the US Open in 1975'' _ where she
defected. ``They weren't going to let me out of the country again;
I was too independent. But Jan was persuasive, thank God. And at
risk to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My one regret is that I had to make that choice. I didn't want
to leave my home and family, but it was the only way I could
develop as a player and person.''
</P>
<P>
   Kodes smiled at the memory. ``Did you see the Martina exhibit in
the Hall?'' he asked. ``Those nine silver Wimbledon plates, one for
each championship. She should give a dinner party.'' Serving carrot
salad?
</P>
<P>
   Kodes had other fond memories. ``Do you remember that wonderful
party in Revnice?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Very well. That was 1990. Czechoslovakia was liberated at last,
six months after the ``Velvet Revolution'' trashed Communism, and
Martina was making her first trip to her transformed homeland, now
a free country. She had appeared in Prague in 1986, a member of the
US Federation Cup team, but it was an uneasy visit.
</P>
<P>
   Shadowed by secret police, she was considered a ``non-person,''
a criminal though protected by her 1981 US citizenship. Her friends
were chary about making contact. But in 1990 she was joyously
received at a bash at the little tennis club where it all began.
Music resounded from a four-piece band. Wine and beer cascaded, so
much so that the Globe correspondent was even singing in Czech.
</P>
<P>
   Martina danced with everybody, sang, and made a speech.
Everybody wept. ``It was the first time in 15 years that the
family, my parents, my sister (Jana), and I were all together,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   A spirited woman of charities and causes, she also declared, ``I
will continue speaking out on behalf of gays and lesbians until we
have equal access and protection under the law. Vermont is a start,
but it's a small state. I couldn't be open until I got my
citizenship. They would have refused a lesbian naturalization.''
</P>
<P>
   She saluted all her coaches present _ Richards, Lieberman, King,
Craig Kardon, and numerous others, including George Parma, a Czech,
the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``They suffered with me, and they have my thanks. My thanks to
all my old girlfriends, wherever they are. They suffered, too,''
she said, chuckling. Martina also cited Pam Shriver, with whom she
shared 20 major doubles titles, a record, and made a 1984 Grand
Slam. ``One of our records they'll never break, Pam, is the 109
straight wins, 1984-85,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can she not be called the greatest?'' Shriver asked.
``Unimaginable numbers _ 167 singles, 165 doubles titles _ and the
fact that for 20 straight years she was in the top four, most of
the time No. 1 or 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam remembered Martina's first US Open singles triumph in 1983,
on her 11th try. ``I hugged her and congratulated her. `It's been a
long wait for a great player,' '' Shriver said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what she said? `Bitch! If you hadn't beaten me in the
1978 semis, I'd have done it a lot sooner.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 2334EDT &QL; 
