u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-IVERSON-     07-15 1653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-IVERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVERSON USING LITTLE EFFORT TO DODGE 76ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixers president Pat Croce was at the team's free agent camp
Friday morning and saw many familiar faces. He didn't see the one
he hoped to see, however: Allen Iverson's.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson wasn't required to be at the camp and, in fact, many
veterans don't bother with such summer inconveniences. But only a
week earlier, Croce and Magic Johnson met with Iverson in Virginia
and told him it might be a good idea if he showed. A few veterans
did show Friday. Iverson did not.
</P>
<P>
   As marquee free agents continue to come and go, and be wined and
dined, the Philadelphia Story, Summer 2000, is developing into a
soap opera. At its core are Iverson, the talented but perpetually
tardy point guard, and longtime coach Larry Brown, who happens to
believe players should be on time and work hard at practice.
</P>
<P>
   You think Rick Pitino and Antoine Walker are at each other?
They're Torvill and Dean compared with these two.
</P>
<P>
   Things have been simmering and boiled over last week. Iverson
said he thought it would be ``very hard '' to go through another
season with Brown. The coach fired back, telling reporters, ``I
wonder what your relationship would be with any employee you might
have who doesn't choose to come to work on time, or who doesn't
choose to come to work at all, who doesn't choose to do the things
everybody else in the organization does, and then says he's upset
with the way he's being treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. The generally upbeat Croce has had to play the role of
mediator and said he is, at best, ``cautiously optimistic'' about
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be a stimulator,'' Croce said. ``What Larry says
is very valid. He has developed a system and a precedent that
works. Allen has a way of doing things his way. All I can say is
I'm hoping. I'm hoping.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sixers assistant John Calipari, a certified Brownophile,
had a front row view of the relationship last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be coached, taught, and learn that it's all
about team, then you'll love to play for Larry Brown. He's the best
I've ever seen,'' said Calipari. ``Allen Iverson is one of the
finest offensive players in the league. He's an average defensive
player who doesn't put a premium on it. If he ever did commit to
the game, he could be a great one.''
</P>
<P>
   Croce said one positive sign is Iverson is working out this
summer. That's apparently a first. Said Croce, ``He told me I'd be
surprised when training camp began. I said, `Surprised?' He said,
`You'll see. Just wait.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean he will be on time? Does that mean he will
follow the team's directions? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Calipari, ``It's not easy when someone is asking you to do
things that you'd rather not do. And asking you to do those things
every day. Therein lies the issue. Allen doesn't want to deal with
it and Larry ain't gonna change. The light bulb just hasn't gone on
yet for Allen.''
</P>
<P>
   And Brown?
</P>
<P>
   ``His chronological age (59) is not important. He's younger than
I am,'' said the 41-year-old Calipari. ``He comes every day with
high energy. The only thing different from 20 years ago is that his
hair is a little shorter and a little grayer. That's it. He has
been great for Allen Iverson. I was there. But Allen has to realize
that, too. He has to be committed like Larry is.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been players over the years that loathed practice but
showed up when the games began. Croce said while Iverson might be
one of those lads, he needs to be more.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not enough,'' Croce said. ``We are a team. We have to
practice as a team. That's the way Larry Brown sees it and that's
the way it has to be. Larry has this saying: perfect practice makes
perfect. He's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Could the Sixers trade Iverson? Sure they could. He's still a
base-year player, meaning Philly could only get back player(s)
making less than Iverson's $10.125 million salary. Brown sounds at
times as if he'd take Scooter Barry even-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it works out for them, I really do,'' Calipari said.
``But if they offered him up and I was on another team, I'd take
the chance. There are five organizations right now who need a big
change. Allen has a big heart. And he fills the building.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is, what building will he fill next season?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let games begin
</P>
<P>
   The second Shaw's Summer League opens Monday afternoon at
UMass-Boston with some interesting names and faces scheduled to be
in attendance. Ten teams have committed and there are some familiar
lads on the rosters: Tyus Edney (Washington), Damon Jones (New
Jersey), Wayne Turner (Indiana), Dontae Jones (Indiana), Randell
Jackson (New York), and Scoonie Penn (Atlanta). The Celtics had an
intriguing name on their roster, Bobby Hurley. The former Kings
guard, who last played in 1997-98, was a late scratch. ``He's
rehabbing and he's still not in shape,'' Celtics general manager
Chris Wallace said. ``It would have been a perfect opportunity for
him.'' Hurley may try to land in someone's veterans camp this fall.
Also on hand will be Kris Clack, last year's No. 2 pick (55th
overall). Only one Celtic from last year's team is scheduled to
compete: Tony Battie. The team had hoped to have Adrian Griffin,
but he isn't ready after late-spring ankle surgery . . . Hornets
backup center Brad Miller says the Celtics are one of a handful of
teams who've shown some interest, but the Hornets have the upper
hand in their dealings with the ex-Purdue big man. Charlotte can
match any offer up to the NBA average salary, about $4 million a
season. Most teams pursuing Miller have the $2.25 million exception
available. Miller, who went undrafted, earned $385,000 last season,
so he's due for a big raise. The Hornets, meanwhile, have yet to
present an offer to Eddie Jones, who has been courted by Miami,
Orlando, and Chicago. Charlotte has a history of not paying its key
guys (see Larry Johnson, Alonzo Mourning, Glen Rice, Vlade Divac),
so the Jones situation will be interesting. The Hornets also, in
retrospect, blew a chance to have an additional exception available
this summer. Charlotte could have gone into the summer with a $2.1
million slot, which represents half of the salary of the late Bobby
Phills. But the Hornets wasted it on Dale Ellis, who was unwanted
and unhappy in Milwaukee and did next to nothing for the Hornets .
. . Speaking of injury exceptions, the Nets may have one for Kerry
Kittles of nearly $4 million and, given Kittles's uncertain future,
may use it to get Ron Mercer. Jersey needs someone who can shoot
the ball. The Celtics had a chance to use half of Greg Minor's
salary ($1.4 million last year) as an injury exception, but decided
against it. The question is why? You can always apply for an
exception, but that doesn't mean you have to use it. That figure
might have enabled them to bring in a veteran to help in the locker
room. ``We just felt it wasn't necessary,'' Wallace said. There
still is no firm word on Minor's future. This is the last year of
his contract and, given that he was still walking with a cane last
spring, it doesn't look promising . . . Pitino says he has no
interest in the Delaware opening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rookie reruns
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were delighted and surprised to see Vin Baker for
workouts with their summer league team in California. Baker, who
has had back-to-back bummer years for the Sonics, is practicing
with the team, lifting weights, and doing conditioning drills. He
told the Seattle Times, ``That's one of the reasons I came down
here. It's just like being a rookie again. Just to walk in the gym
with those guys who have to work extra hard to make it in the
league. That's my whole mentality right now. Don't focus on
anything else. Just focus on what got me here. Busting my butt like
I did out of the University of Hartford. Just starting all over
again.'' Baker is a member of the 2000 Olympic Team . . . ESPN.com
asked visitors to vote on which key member of the Celtics needed to
be replaced for the team to succeed. Four options were given:
Antoine Walker, Vitaly Potapenko (we don't know how he got in
there), Kenny Anderson or Pitino. The winner: Anderson with 34
percent of the more than 2,700 votes. Potapenko was next with 28.4
percent while Walker (18.9) and Pitino (18.4) were basically
deadlocked . . . As Detlef Schrempf contemplates retirement _ he
turns 38 in January _ he may soon get an offer from Greek
powerhouse Panathinaikos. Since Schrempf has German citizenship,
he's not viewed as a foreigner in Europe . . . Croce said he was
very concerned about losing Brown to North Carolina when he took a
call from Carolina kingmaker Dean Smith. ``I didn't know what he
was calling about because I didn't know that Roy (Williams) had
turned the job down,'' Croce said. ``But I knew Larry had this
dream and I'm not a guy who busts up another guy's dream.'' . . .
Free agent center/forward Adonal Foyle, also of interest to the
Celtics, has been working out daily at the Golden State Warriors
practice facility and plans to attend Pete Newell's Big Man Camp.
The Warriors are thin up front and have told Foyle they want him
back. Foyle told the San Francisco Chronicle, ``I'm not afraid to
hide the fact that at first I didn't think they would offer me a
contract. What the Warriors are doing now, I like that. This is a
very interesting place to play. I'd love to be a part of it.'' One
reason Foyle is happier: the presence of Dave Cowens . . . Reports
out of California indicate Jerry West is going to resign. West says
he is under contract through September and is off to Alaska to do
some fishing. Indications seem to point to a departure from the
only professional organization he has ever known. West always said
he wanted to go out on top. He's there now.
</P>
</TEXT>
