<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG SADDLED WITH TOUGH CONDITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIANCON, France _ The people riding in the lifts high above the
ski areas in the southern Alps had a great view of the racers
heading north in the Tour de France. The sightseers could view the
majestic mountains, some of them covered with snow, the puffy
clouds in the bright blue sky, and the long line of cyclists on the
roads below.
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of fans lining the route, from the man wearing a
Texas flag like a cape running next to the riders to the campers on
the mountainside, seemed to be having a fun summer day.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong had an entirely different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long day, it was a hard day,'' said Armstrong. ``It
was a hard day for everybody. That's a long time to be on your
bike.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost eight hours, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   But sore or not, the defending champion held on to the overall
leader's yellow jersey that he has worn since Tuesday, as he
finished the 14th stage in seventh place, 2 minutes 51 seconds
behind winner Santiago Botero of Colombia. Botero rode the 155
miles, the longest stage of the Tour, in 7:56:13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel so good the first half and I don't know why,''
said Armstrong, who still has a lead of 4:55 over German Jan
Ullrich entering the last week of the race. Maybe it was the three
mountains the cyclists had to pedal up and down. The first two were
designated ``first category'' and the final one was the highest
category in the Tour, as it was a 7.2 percent grade for 14
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong obviously felt better in the second half, as he took
off on the last climb with nine riders. There was no way the group
was going to catch Botero, but they put on a show of their own as
Armstrong and Italian rival Marco Pantani kept trading places for
the lead in the pack.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the two traded words, and they looked more like
friends than rivals. But Armstrong just shrugged when asked what
the exchange was all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today he was really flying, and I told him that,'' he said.
``I was working hard to stay with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who is more than 10 minutes ahead of Pantani, could
afford to be gallant, and said he didn't care if it seemed like he
was motivating his competitor. Pantani finished third, just two
seconds in front of Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be motivating (but) it's the gentlemanly thing to do,
to say, `Hey, you're strong,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also seems not to care whether he's won a stage as
long as he's in the overall lead. Last year he won four stages in
the Tour, but if he doesn't win one this week, he'll become the
first person since Greg Lemond in 1990 to win the Tour without
winning one of the days' races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is to keep the yellow jersey,'' said Armstrong
of his US Postal Service team. ``So if there's a breakaway that
doesn't affect the overall standings, it's OK. If 10 guys who are
10 minutes back take off, we let them go.''
</P>
<P>
   Botero, 27, called Saturday's victory ``the biggest win of my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombia is experiencing a very serious political crisis, so
I'm happy to have brought a positive note to the country,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Botero is just the fifth Colombian to win a Tour stage.
</P>
<P>
   The racers will leave Briancon, just 20 miles from the Italian
border, Sunday as they cover three more mountains and head farther
north into the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Which is little comfort to Armstrong, even though he holds the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be difficult because today was so long and hard,'' he
said. ``It'd be nice to ride 74 kilometers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How different is riding in the Tour de France than watching it
on television?
</P>
<P>
   A lot, testified Steve Pucci, of West Newbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``On TV, you don't get all the feel of the crowds, the terrain,
all the idiots like us,'' Pucci said  &UR; yesterday &LR;  as he took a break
from pedaling up the Col de Vars.
</P>
<P>
   Pucci has a personal attachment to the Tour as friend and former
teammate and coach of Tyler Hamilton, of Marblehead, Mass., who is
in 33d place overall. Pucci, 51, has been in France for the past
week with other members of the Newbury-based CCB team, riding parts
of the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour riders and Hamilton rooters included 55-year-old Graham
Jones, of North Andover, Mass., a former professional racer in
Belgium, and Walter Deuellian, the race director of the Mount
Washington (N.H.) Hillclimb (which Hamilton won in '99 and '97).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
