<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-CAMPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH IS ON: IT'S TIME FOR CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Topics as varied as criminal activity, injury comebacks,
coaching changes, high-profile veterans and rookies, and serious
life issues the league's Armanis face will be among the reasons to
pay close attention as training camps open. Here are 25 people to
watch this season:
</P>
<P>
   1. Ray Lewis: Acquitted on murder charges, Lewis's highly
publicized trial will make him the curiosity factor in the league.
Steps are being taken to keep the Ravens linebacker shielded from
the media and public while he attempts to get his life back to
normal. He made an unannounced visit to the rookie symposium last
week in San Diego to warn players to be careful whom they associate
with and where they go after football hours. He could have a huge
impact on the lives of other NFL stars. But we thought that when
Rae Carruth was charged with murder, and things are still going on
around the NFL that have created a black eye for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   2. Daniel Snyder: The .com owner has created the following
situation: boom or bust. Not afraid to spend money, Snyder has
rankled some of his fellow owners, much like George Steinbrenner
used to, with his flamboyance and fiscal approach. His highly-paid
Redskins will be under a microscope, as will the staff,
particularly coach Norv Turner.
</P>
<P>
   3. Kurt Warner: The reigning NFL and Super Bowl MVP. How will he
respond when the entire league goes gunning for him? If Warner
survives, his legacy will grow.
</P>
<P>
   4. Al Groh: Anyone who replaces Bill Parcells is on the ultimate
hot seat, never mind that he is coaching in the nation's largest
media center. It helps that the system and some of the Jets
coaching staff is intact. It's the same philosophy. This is
different than the situation Pete Carroll inherited, because
Carroll had to bring in a new coaching staff and introduce his
philosophy to a team that had gone to the Super Bowl. Groh inherits
an 8-8 team.
</P>
<P>
   5. Bill Belichick: He'll receive a little more attention than
the usual first-time coach because of the odd circumstances
surrounding his hiring by the Patriots. He basically turned his
back on Parcells and the Jets, walking away from that highly
visible head job. Belichick must overcome the team's depleted
talent pool and motivate his younger players.
</P>
<P>
   6. Keyshawn Johnson: One of the best offensive players in the
game, it'll be curious to see the impact of his subtraction from
the Jets and his addition to the Tampa Bay attack. The Bucs are
considered a Super Bowl team, and they feel Johnson makes the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   7. Wade Phillips: The Bills coach's decision to bench Doug
Flutie before a playoff game, then losing to the Titans, and his
subsequent decision to start Rob Johnson, will have its
ramifications. Phillips is second-guessed more in the rest of the
country than he is in Buffalo, and he must hope the Bills'
performance this season validates his judgments.
</P>
<P>
   8. Courtney Brown: He's the No. 1 pick in the draft (of the
Browns) and all will see whether Brown can be the next Bruce Smith
or Reggie White. There'll always be debate whether Brown or Penn
State teammate LaVar Arrington was worthy of the No. 1 pick. It may
not be settled after one season.
</P>
<P>
   9. Deion Sanders: One of the most interesting and exciting
players in the game. He's changed teams again, going from Dallas to
Washington at big money (seven years, $56 million). He's had injury
issues the past couple of years, but when healthy can dominate in
the secondary and as a punt returner.
</P>
<P>
   10. Paul Tagliabue: There's no commissioner who has the business
side of his sport so controlled. His teams are making a fortune,
there's stadium expansion everywhere, and the revenue-sharing
concept has been a bonanza. But all the money in the world can't
correct the growing perception that the players are troubled people
committing crimes and running amok. The NFL has done a lot to
educate its players, but it is having trouble keeping up. It seems
there's a new tragedy every month. It's not Tagliabue's fault, but
the commissioner has to pull something brilliant out of his bag of
tricks. It's also a league that must loosen up before its followers
concur with Vince McMahon's assessment of the NFL as the ``No Fun
League.''
</P>
<P>
   11. Gene Upshaw: Despite the many gains made by the union the
past few years, there's still no balance of power between the
players' association and the league. Upshaw, the union president,
has gotten tough with corrupt agents who are stealing money from
clients and those violating the rules in structuring contracts. But
the teams are in charge. Contracts, for the most part, are a sham.
Long-term deals, where only the bonus is guaranteed, often include
such things as voidable years, escalators, and unmakeable
incentives, all to lessen the salary cap hit. Team executives bully
agents and players, telling them to be quiet about injuries and not
to reveal the sacred details of the contracts. Some of this stuff
is laughed at in the unions of the major leagues, NHL, and NBA.
</P>
<P>
   12. Terrell Davis: The best running back in the NFL returns
after missing all of last season with a knee injury. This bodes
well for the Broncos, who, coming off back-to-back Super Bowls, had
a down year without Davis and John Elway and an injured Shannon
Sharpe, who has since signed with the Ravens. The Broncos still
have a good core, are a year wiser and better with quarterback
Brian Griese, and have what many other teams don't: veteran
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   13. Jamal Anderson: Anderson's season-ending injury crippled the
Falcons, who became the biggest disappointment of the 1999 season a
year after making the Super Bowl. The Falcons could be a factor
again if Anderson comes back 100 percent, which he isn't yet, and
several free agent moves pan out.
</P>
<P>
   14. Bill Parcells: He's shopping for the groceries. The fun will
be watching whether his controversial trading of Johnson for two
No. 1s works out. We'll see how good a personnel man he really is.
If his drafted players become stars, he can add another rung to his
lofty ladder of successes.
</P>
<P>
   15. Ron Dayne: Don't be surprised if he's a star. A big, tough,
bruising runner who has made good impressions on the field in New
York, and with the Giants has an offense that's perfectly suited
for him. One of the fun things every year is to follow the Heisman
Trophy winner's transition into the NFL. Some never make it.
</P>
<P>
   16. Mike Martz: He's in one of these no-win situations, taking
over for the coach (Dick Vermeil) that won the Super Bowl. Sounds
familiar. Martz was the brain behind the Rams' high-powered
offense. He has done some tweaking with the coaching staff and the
roster. Obviously, the league is gunning for St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   17. Dennis Miller: He will either be really funny or really
annoying on ``Monday Night Football.'' It's great there's at least
an attempt to loosen things up in the broadcast booth. Too bad the
rest of the league is so boring.
</P>
<P>
   18. Sebastian Janikowski: The drafting of the former Florida
State kicker (early in the first round) was already controversial;
he's had two brushes with the law amid talk of deportation, which
apparently won't happen. Nonetheless, Janikowski's strong leg,
off-field problems, and the fact he's wearing the black and silver
of the Oakland Raiders make him someone you want to keep an eye on.
</P>
<P>
   19. Ryan Leaf: It'll be interesting if he finally gets to play
for the Chargers this season. For all of his obnoxious behavior,
could he still be a great quarterback? The Colts made the right
choice going with Peyton Manning over Leaf three years ago, just as
the Patriots did when they opted for Drew Bledsoe over Rick Mirer.
Is Leaf another Mirer? Or will Leaf emerge as a pretty good player?
</P>
<P>
   20. Shaun King: Tampa Bay has a killer defense and excellent
offensive personnel. But it's up to King to deliver the ball. The
rookie quarterback struggled at times last year, but a scout who
regularly covers the Bucs said he thinks King will be a very good
NFL quarterback and surprise his critics.
</P>
<P>
   21. Vinny Testaverde: Losing him destroyed the Jets' season last
year. If he returns in top form, with protection, and with Curtis
Martin behind him, Testaverde _ who is approaching the season as if
it's his last _ could make things exciting in New York again. One
problem: No Keyshawn to come up with tough catches over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   22. Ben Coates: The former Patriots tight end will surface in
some team's training camp. He's in the best shape in years and he's
trying to prove wrong those who feel he's all done.
</P>
<P>
   23. Shannon Sharpe: Another great pass-catcher that the game
missed last year. Sharpe returns with what should be a high-powered
offense in Baltimore, a team that could be very tough and a big
postseason factor.
</P>
<P>
   24. Akili Smith: For all the odd things the Bengals do, they
have built a pretty exciting offense and Smith will be the trigger
man, tossing it to Peter Warrick and Ron Dugans and, if he's
around, Corey Dillon out of the backfield. He should be the most
exciting of all the young QBs in the league.
</P>
<P>
   25. Drew Bledsoe: Just because he's the main guy with the local
team. Bledsoe always piques our interest. The Patriots had better
come up with more options than just Terry Glenn, whom teams are
going to swarm now that Shawn Jefferson and Coates are gone.
</P>
<P>
   Others to watch: Dallas owner Jerry Jones because he's always
exciting; Minnesota receiver Randy Moss; Tim Couch, Year 2; Glenn,
because he's so vital to the Patriots' offensive success; Colts
running back Edgerrin James, who will have to contend with teams
keying on him; Former Lions running back Barry Sanders, who may
wind up back in the league if the Lions can work out compensation;
Damon Huard-Jay Fiedler replacing Dan Marino; Ravens cornerback
Chris McAlister, who may emerge as an outstanding player; Tennessee
running back Eddie George, who has been so tough and so good; Bruce
Smith _ does he have anything left? And if he returns, the Rev.
Reggie White.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston's bargain hunters
</P>
<P>
   How are Belichick and Dan Duquette one in the same? They like
reclamation projects and they tell you nothing. Belichick will have
a few of them on his team, including running back Raymont Harris,
special teams player and receiver Aaron Bailey, cornerback Antonio
Langham, linebacker Chad Cascadden, and whatever reject is picked
up between now and the end of camp. Harris and Langham could have
the biggest impact if they return to their respective high points .
. . Many months later, there has not been a proper explanation as
to why strength and conditioning coach Johnny Parker was fired by
Belichick. Larry Kennan, who heads the NFL Coaches Association,
swears he's never heard a legitimate reason. ``I speak to Johnny a
lot and that still hits him hard,'' said Kennan. ``It came out of
the blue. Johnny was told several times that he had a job for life
with the Patriots.''. . . Kennan will look into how the Patriots
structured contracts for some of the assistants. Some of them have
a clause that if they're fired and they have time remaining on
their deals, the team is only liable for half the amount. Kennan
said he would balk at such a clause . . . Patriots e-commerce
manager Anthony Jardim reports sales of merchandise over the
Internet have increased 400 percent over the previous 12 months.
Every cent of the proceeds goes to the Patriots Charitable
Foundation. The auction site _ accessible via www.patriots.com or
www.proteamauctions.com _ offers fans and collectors of Patriots
memorabilia the chance to bid on and compete for authentic Patriots
merchandise (both new and game-used) along with autographed
authentic memorabilia. This week, the Patriots were offering a trip
for two to the Hall of Fame Game in Canton, Ohio, and the induction
ceremony and other Hall of Fame events when the Patriots play the
San Francisco 49ers to kick off the 2000 exhibition season. This
package includes two round-trip tickets, leaving July 28 and
returning Aug. 1 . . . Ray Lucas's agent, Felix Diaz, spilled the
beans last week to the Record (N.J.) indicating the Jets may trade
Lucas. Diaz told the newspaper that if it came down to a trade,
Parcells would try and send Lucas to a good situation. The Jets
have a healthy Testaverde and rookie first-round pick Chad
Pennington to go along with punter/QB Tom Tupa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He received the message
</P>
<P>
   When Vincent Brisby accepted his pay cut (with incentives to
earn $2.6 million), agent Michael George understood it was either
this way or the highway. Brisby saved the Patriots $750,000 on the
cap, saved himself a job at a high rate of pay, and enabled the
team to sign Adrian Klemm and Bruce Armstrong as well as the other
draft picks. The Patriots did well signing Klemm, forcing the
second-rounder to take on a fifth year so the team could soften its
salary cap hit. They also placed a few ``not likely to be earned''
incentives in their contracts to the lower-round rookies in lieu of
a bigger signing bonus, which caused a few of them to balk.
Contrary to reports, this did not anger the union. It did alert the
agents the team was doing this. ``It was well within their rights
to do so,'' said NFLPA spokesman Carl Francis. ``We weren't angry,
we were just making our agents aware of what was happening. I'm
sure some of the incentives are reachable if the guys play.''
Respected agent Ralph Cindrich, who represents Klemm, actually
thought the team showed a lot of class by signing Klemm now, even
though he won't be able to play throughout training camp after knee
surgery. ``I give them credit for looking past that and negotiating
a good deal for Adrian,'' said Cindrich of the five-year, $3.34
million deal with a $1.225 million signing bonus. This contract
concept was suggested by Bob Kraft many months ago at an owners
meeting. Jones followed, and now other teams are joining the ranks
. . . There is some concern about Lions coach Bobby Ross's health.
The 63-year-old has experienced blood clots in his legs this
offseason, and while they appear to be under control, He is still
experiencing them. Ross, however, isn't about to slow down. ``I'm
63, but I feel very good,'' said Ross. ``I don't feel any different
than I did at 45.'' Ross, who has two years remaining on his
five-year deal, knows he will not have Barry Sanders. Sanders has
finally returned the $1.83 million portion of his $11 million
signing bonus owed the Lions and has also sent checks to both of
his agents, Lamont Sith and David Ware, for their commissions on
the deal . . . Former Patriots vice president of personnel Bobby
Grier is settling into his new job in Houston and will be closing
on a house there shortly . . . Veteran defensive end Leslie O'Neal
will soon decide whether he'll retire or take the massive slash in
salary he accepted from the Chiefs this offseason. O'Neal went from
$3 million to $440,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bengals' strife
</P>
<P>
   There's never a dull moment covering Bengals football. Nobody
wants to go there and once they're in, they beg to leave. The
Dillon and Carl Pickens sagas are priceless. The latest is the
Bengals, who have been accused of holding Pickens hostage _
refusing to release him after several trade possibilities fell
through _ want the receiver in camp. Pickens would rather eat
soybean the rest of his life. Meanwhile, agent Marvin Demoff has
accused the Bengals of no longer negotiating a deal. The Bengals
last offered Dillon five years at $21 million, but Dillon plans to
hold out until he gets his price or until he's dealt . . . The XFL
has announced a team in Las Vegas. And now there should be no
question as to whether the games will be scripted or serious. Vegas
will list odds, which it can only do if it knows the games are
legitimate . . . Wide receiver Sean Morey has been medically
cleared to participate in the Patriots camp after battling the
effects of a seasonlong ankle injury in Barcelona. Morey made quite
an impression on NFL Europe coaches, often playing at far less than
100 percent and still looking like one of the most talented players
there . . . Patriots rookie running back J.R. Redmond's groin
injury is healing ahead of schedule and he's now awaiting clearance
to get on the field once he's signed . . . Former Holy Cross coach
Peter Vaas, who now coaches Berlin in NFL Europe, returned to his
New Hampshire home June 26 but then flew back to Hamburg last
Saturday to help coach the Notre Dame alumni to a 14-10 win over
the Hamburg Blue Devils . . . Interest in the Patriots this
offseason has been as low as it's been since the pre-Parcells era.
The true test will be Monday when camp opens and fans are allowed
to watch the two-a-days at Foxboro Stadium. By the way, the camp is
free, unlike that of the Redskins, who will charge $10 a head and
$10 for parking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
