<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-BRITISHOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE BRITISH OPEN, BUT IS IT WORTH IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To go or not to go is a question that has dogged PGA Tour
players for years. We're talking the British Open, of course, that
most glorious major championship with its variety of weather and
just as many opinions about how much an American pro should
sacrifice in an effort to gain a spot.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Faxon, for one, is shelling out thousands of dollars just
for the chance to get into next week's field at St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Andrade, while he ``commends Brad for going,'' is of a
different mind-set, opting not to go through the rigors of
qualifying. He did it in 1989 and '90, but hasn't since, playing
only when exempt (five times since 1992).
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over and shot 6 under (in qualifying) for two days and
went home,'' said Andrade. Faxon and Andrade pointed out that
accommodations must be made for qualifying, which could be outside
of London, in addition to reservations for the British Open site.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go over there to qualify without thinking of getting
into the Open,'' said Faxon. ``You have to get rooms. It's eight or
nine days; two weeks away from the PGA Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Andrade had an apartment booked for the week, but when
he didn't qualify, he was able to hand off his accommodations to
Ian Baker-Finch and recoup some money. That helped, said Andrade,
``because it's not like they make it convenient for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The qualifying process is something the PGA Tour's Policy Board
has discussed and one of the player directors _ Hal Sutton _ said
he is sensitive to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play unless I'm exempt,'' said Sutton, who is in the
St. Andrews field after finishing T-10 at Carnoustie last year. For
the previous 10 British Opens, however, Sutton didn't bother to
qualify and he sympathizes with players who don't want to, either.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton would like to see a PGA Tour stop in early July _ say the
Western Open _ be a British Open qualifier, with perhaps the top 20
players not otherwise exempt earning spots.
</P>
<P>
   While he would favor such a plan and indicated ``it could
happen,'' Sutton emphasized it's still just being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to qualify for the British Open usually requires passing
up at least two PGA Tour events, and most players can't afford to
do that, not with their name well down the money list.
</P>
<P>
   Legitimate concerns, though Faxon doesn't adhere to them. ``It's
the British Open,'' so he's at a course in England Sunday and
Monday _ London Links _ trying to nail down a spot. If he misses,
he'll come home Tuesday and head to the B.C. Open in Endicott,
N.Y., where he is the defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pleasure before business
</P>
<P>
   The growing trend for those who do have spots in the British
Open is to go over a week early, play the legendary layouts of
Ireland, and take part in some nightlife. ``We're going to go over
and play golf every day and have a lot of fun at night,'' said
Dudley Hart, who had a trip planned with Tim Herron, Jeff Sluman,
and some other friends. He rattled off some of the itinerary _
Royal County Down, Royal Dublin, Portmarnock, Old Head _ and
realized golf writers were salivating. ``It's a tough life,'' said
Hart, laughing, ``but we've gotta do it.'' Herron, listening to the
list, wasn't so sure. ``I think I'll be too tired for the British
Open,'' he said . . . Tiger Woods is another who went over early
and played in a charity event in Limerick, Ireland, with Mark
O'Meara, Stuart Appleby, and David Duval. Woods shot 64-68 to win
the JP McManus Pro-Am because Appleby (63-68) was disqualified for
using an illegal laser gauge . . . Steve Elkington and Sutton have
personal reasons for choosing a more traditional routine, showing
up on site a few days before the event. Elkington has a severe
sinus problem and said it really kicks up this time of year.
Sutton? ``With three little girls, I try to spend as much time at
home as I can.'' . . . Elkington had favorable first impressions of
two Rhode Island products _ Dana Quigley and Rhode Island CC _
during the CVS Charity Classic. He praised Quigley's game,
particularly his driving, and said, ``Now I know why he's doing so
well on the Senior Tour.'' As for RICC, ``it's my new favorite
course,'' because the short, classic layout puts a premium on the
wedge game and ``we just don't play courses like that anymore.''
Elkington and playing partner Craig Stadler were unanimous about
Quigley's passion for golf. ``I have never, ever in my life seen
anybody who loves golf as much as that guy,'' said Stadler, a
reference to the fact that Quigley has played more than 100
tournaments in a row without taking a week off. What's the most in
a row for them? ``Three,'' said Elkington, to a round of laughter.
Said Stadler: ``I played seven or eight, way back when I was too
dumb to realize.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tabloid diversions
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with the British Open comes the British tabloids. A
nauseating thought to many players, many of whom know that a
central theme will be last year's Ryder Cup Matches at The Country
Club in Brookline _ in particular the infamous celebration on the
17th green by the Americans. Because he made the dramatic 40-foot
putt that capped an improbable rally against Jose Maria Olazabal
and virtually assured victory, Justin Leonard figures to draw some
attention and said last week that he ``expects the worst and hopes
for the best, but I can't help that and I'm not going to be too
concerned with it.'' Davis Love, who played with Leonard in the CVS
Charity Classic, couldn't sit still any longer. ``Real golf fans
know what happened,'' he said. ``We played good for one day, they
played good for two. People need to go back and remember what they
thought of Saturday night. Everybody was happy. We didn't have any
complaints, they didn't have any complaints. Then, all of a sudden
Sunday, there was one incident that we have apologized for that
really didn't affect the outsome of the match _ even the players
involved knew that. And to think it changed that much from Saturday
night to Sunday is pretty amazing. What changed is we won the first
six matches and they got beat. It's a lot of sour grapes led by
their captain.'' . . . ``Their captain,'' of course, is Mark James,
who happens to be entered in the British Open. If only the pairings
people had a sense of humor, just imagine the possibilities _ James
flanked by Tom Lehman and Nick Faldo, both of whom caught the wrath
of the captain in his book . . . Saying most of the principals
involved have made peace, and that fans and writers are the ones
still stirring the pot, Leonard shook his head in disbelief. ``It's
amazing to me how personal people take things. Even people who had
nothing to do with the event. These people need to get out and read
something other than the sports page.'' . . . You don't think Woods
has any competition? Apparently you've never heard of Nedbank, as
in the large South African banking institution. It seems the powers
who run that business enjoy spending piles of cash because they
have sweetened the pot to $4.06 million for this year's Sun City
event in South Africa, which will run opposite Woods's Williams
World Challenge. Both are non-sanctioned events that attract
marquee names, but as good as these guys are, they can't be at both
tournaments, so let the decisions begin. On the one hand you have
Woods; on the other, a chance for a first-place prize of $2 million
. . . Who has the most top-10 finishes on the PGA Tour this year?
That's easy, Woods. But who is next? If you said Steve Flesch
(nine), give yourself a pat on the back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tough competition
</P>
<P>
   It never should have happened, but the USGA elected to run its
Women's Open opposite the British Open. That's a shame for the
women, for arguably their biggest tournament of the season will get
overshadowed by Woods's run for a second straight major. The women
will be teeing it up at the Merit Club in Chicago . . . The good
news for Kim Williams: She got into this weekend's LPGA Big Apple
Classic as an alternate and grabbed a share of the first-round lead
with a 4-under 67. The bad news: She had to face more questions
about a 1994 shooting that left a bullet lodged in her right
shoulder. She was an innocent bystander in a Youngstown, Ohio,
drugstore that night, and the incident set her career back a few
years. The bullet was removed the next year, but Williams has been
plagued by one injury after another, culminated by back surgery in
late 1998 that limited her to just eight tournaments last season.
``I'd rather (people say), `The girl that won the tournament: Did
you know she got shot? Rather than, `Oh, that's the girl that got
shot,' '' said Williams, whose best finish in 11 years on Tour is
T-2.
</P>
<P>
   . . . Arthur Cicconi, the only head professional in the 24 years
of Presidents GC in Quincy, has submitted his resignation,
effective at the end of this year. He's one of the really great
people in the profession and his tireless work turned the Norfolk
County Classic into a well-respected event, which should be
commended . . . The trucks and field workers have been in place for
months, but a ceremonial ground-breaking was held Thursday for the
TPC of Boston facility in Norton. Officials from FleetBoston
Financial, the PGA Tour, and Connell Limited Partnership took part,
along with Norton town officials. It marked the official start of
construction for the golf course, which is scheduled to open in
2002, designed by the Arnold Palmer Course Design Co. Some 100
corporate memberships have been sold, said Brian Connor, director
of marketing, and just 10 remain in the charter category . . .
Entries are still being accepted for the New England Junior Open
Championship (July 24-28) at Ponkapoag GC in Canton. There are four
divisions for boys, two for girls, and the entry fee is $20. Call
the pro shop for information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
