<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF THE BLUE, SCIOSCIA SITTING PRETTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The last local intercounty, interleague series of
the season is over, leaving Southern California baseball fans with
the question of whom you'd rather be right now.
</P>
<P>
   a) Davey Johnson or b) Mike Scioscia?
</P>
<P>
   a) The manager with the $1.5 million-a-year salary or b) the
manager getting by on Mickey Mouse money?
</P>
<P>
   a) The custodian of Dodgers tradition or b) the trustee of
Angels, uh, history?
</P>
<P>
   The answer has to be b), b), b). Scioscia, Scioscia, Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   As they headed out of the All-Star break, the relative states of
the Dodgers and Angels could be summed up with these images:
Johnson under siege, the world coming down around his ears, and
Scioscia loose and playful, seemingly confident that any call he
made would be the right one.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia and the Angels left Dodger Stadium with two victories
in three games, including a 6-2 win in front of 42,726 grumbling
Dodgers fans Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, who began the day five games behind the Seattle
Mariners in the American League West, improved to 49-42. The
Dodgers, six games behind the Arizona Diamondbacks, dropped to
45-44. But the gap between them was bigger than that.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Dodgers turned the Southern California freeway
map upside down the past three days. On the I-5, south is now up,
north is now down.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dodgers manager's office, Johnson stood with hands on
hips and faced the music again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't hit, you look flat. And when you don't pitch,
you look worse,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through a little tough time. We've got a couple of
guys down (Todd Hundley, injured; Mark Grudzielanek, sick; Chad
Kreuter, suspended). It's dog-days time. We're going to get
healthier in the next couple of days. But right now I don't have a
lot of help on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not an excuse, just a fact. Johnson knows that if he
doesn't find a way to coax more out of his $90 million roster this
season, he won't have a next season to try again.
</P>
<P>
   In the Angels manager's office, Scioscia leaned back in a chair
and appeared, 91 games into his rookie season as a major-league
manager, to be completely at ease and pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do that over,'' he said, interrupting his own interview
at one point. ``I just burped into a microphone.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about the only thing that went wrong for Scioscia in a
series that could only have been better for him if the Angels had
survived the 10th inning Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Do managers have hot streaks as hitters do? Scioscia seems to be
on one.
</P>
<P>
   He calls in left fielder Darin Erstad to form a five-man infield
after the Dodgers put a runner at third with none out in the 10th
in that first game. The ensuing ground ball goes right to Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   He moves Erstad to center field in the eighth inning Friday
night after Garret Anderson is injured. Erstad makes a diving catch
to stall a Dodgers rally.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning of that game, he lets pitcher Kent
Bottenfield bat with two out and the Angels down a run. Bottenfield
singles to set up a two-run Erstad homer.
</P>
<P>
   The most heartening thing for the Angels staff was that even
before Scioscia signaled for the five-man infield, Erstad was
running in, spotting the situation, knowing his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's in sequence,'' hitting coach Mickey Hatcher said.
``That's what Mike's got going here.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia came to Dodger Stadium for the first time since he was
a Dodger. Friday night, the video board replayed his 1988 playoff
homer off Dwight Gooden, and followed that with a shot of Scioscia
in the Angels dugout, and the crowd gave him an appreciative
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   By the seventh inning Saturday, he was drawing boos when he
argued with an umpire over a play at second base. The moment seemed
to certify, for anyone who wasn't sure yet, that Scioscia is an
Angel now.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Johnson, he's the lucky one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-00 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
