<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-ECONOMICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMITTEE'S PITCH IS A CHANGEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By GORDON EDES 
c.2000 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A baseball fan does not have to possess a long memory to
understand the significance of the report on baseball's economics
released by a panel of experts Friday, one that recommended
significantly increased revenue sharing and a luxury tax with a
much sharper bite than the one that currently exists as a way to
close the economic disparity among teams.
</P>
<P>
   It is an explicit reminder that the ugly season will soon be
upon us, one in which baseball's owners and players try to hash out
a new collective bargaining agreement against a backdrop of three
decades of work stoppages and acrimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on past experience, it is real clear that we will have
another strike or lockout,'' said Roger I. Abrams, a Major League
Baseball salary arbitrator and the dean of the Northeastern
University School of Law. ``They've never reached an agreement
without one. Sometimes, parties get hooked on that as the way they
conduct their relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   The players' union is expected to exercise its option to extend
the current collective bargaining agreement through the 2001
season. But soon, lawyers for both sides will begin what has been a
torturous dance, one that resulted in the unthinkable in 1994, a
work stoppage that resulted in the cancellation of the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire, for one, is already on record that he will quit
before he participates in another work stoppage. Most reasoned
voices on both sides understand that it would be suicidal to shut
down the game yet again.
</P>
<P>
   Is it inevitable? Abrams, author of the new book, ``The Money
Pitch: Baseball Free Agency and Salary Arbitration,'' thinks not,
but cautions that while the owners and union have made some strides
in creating a better atmosphere of trust, there is much to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope now that there will be more enlightened
leadership from Bud Selig, who is well respected by his
colleagues,'' Abrams said. ``But in the fairly near future, they
have to begin the process of dialogue before positions become
hardened. That's why I'm troubled that the union was not involved
in the preparation of this study.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-man group, appointed by the commissioner's office and
given access to the sport's financial data, did not come out in
favor of a salary cap, which is anathema to the union, nor did it
propose changes to rules governing free agency or salary
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The committee recommended a 50 percent luxury tax on payrolls
above $84 million; proposed sharing of 40 percent to 50 percent of
local revenues after ballpark expenses; and recommended that new
national broadcasting, licensing, and Internet revenue be
distributed unequally to assist low-revenue clubs, provided that
they meet a minimum payroll of $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not pretend to believe these changes will be easy or
universally popular,'' former Senate majority leader George
Mitchell, one of the panelists, said Friday. ``We do believe them
to be a solution to the alarming disparities between baseball's
haves and have-nots.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the panel were former Federal Reserve Board chairman
Paul Volcker, Yale president Richard Levin, and political
commentator George Will.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an illustrious group,'' Abrams said. ``How can George
Will not be right? But George Mitchell may wish he was back in
Belfast before this is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell helped to broker a peace agreement in Northern Ireland
before this assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discussion seems to be in the correct direction,'' said
Abrams, who had not yet seen a copy of the full report. ``But one
would think they also would have to look at local TV revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what kind of deal George (Steinbrenner) is going to
get in his new Yankees/Nets/Devils cable consortium? It could be
worth $100 million a year, then all bets are off.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams noted how the Yankees recently crossed the $100 million
threshold for payrolls. ``That was a very significant event.
</P>
<P>
   ``What baseball needs is to develop confidence in one another as
partners,'' he said. ``There has to be a building of trust and
communication. The owners, the union, the players all have to
realize they are partners in an extraordinary enterprise, one that
is not really a big business but is very important to many of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The sides are not yet at that point, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't see it yet, I don't see it yet, but there are a lot
of people willing to help foster that dialogue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So what are his prospects?
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette smirked the other day when asked how close Japanese
righthander Tomo Ohka was to the Red Sox. ``About 45 miles,'' he
said. Without explaining why Ohka has been passed over while Paxton
Crawford was called up from Pawtucket to the big club, Duquette
said: ``Ohka's gotten the experience he has needed to get another
chance at the big leagues. He pitched well for us in September.''
Duquette was asked if there are prospects he absolutely would not
include in a deal. ``As you get closer and closer to the trading
deadline, you've got to make a decision where your ball club is. To
me, it doesn't make a lot of sense to give up young players you
could have for the next five or six years for a player you might
have for just a couple of months. But if you have a chance to make
the playoffs with one or two players, you have to consider all your
options.'' Brian Rose, who is back in Pawtucket and almost
certainly could benefit from a change of scenery, looms as a likely
player to be dealt before the deadline, especially if he strings
together some good starts for the PawSox. ``I like Brian Rose,''
said one major league scout. In the last five years, the pitcher
who dominated the International League more than any other was
Rose. Ohka and (Sunny) Kim are a lot like Rose, without the
pinpoint command. They're not going to succeed without that
control. Ohka and Kim to me are going to be long (relievers) or
fourth or fifth starters in the big leagues.'' . . . Duquette on
Tony Blanco, the 18-year-old third baseman from the Dominican
Republic off to a sensational start in the Gulf Coast League:
``Tony Blanco's got all the tools to be a big-time player.'' . . .
Sean Berry, the former Expo who signed a minor league deal with the
Sox and is currently with Pawtucket, said he'll leave if he doesn't
get a callup this week. Berry, who was released earlier this
season, said he was giving it 15 days . . . One major league
executive was caustic in his criticism of Reds GM Jim Bowden, who
last week traded his ace, Denny Neagle, to the Yankees for several
prospects. Bowden said the Reds were forced to make the move
because they couldn't risk letting Neagle go as a free agent after
the season, and was afraid the Reds couldn't afford the lefthander,
who is making $4.75 million. The Yankees already have begun
negotiations with Neagle, who figures to command a salary in the
Brad Radke range (four years, $36 million). Bowden is pleading cost
effectiveness after laying out a bundle to sign Ken Griffey in the
offseason. The Reds received some of the Yankees' top prospects in
return, including third baseman Drew Henson, pitcher Eddie Yarnall,
and outfielder Jackson Melian. ``I can't believe the trade is as
one-sided in Cincinnati's favor as it looks,'' the executive said.
``I have a pretty good feeling that the Yankees knew Henson (who
also plays quarterback for Michigan) isn't going to play baseball,
or isn't going to play just baseball. Yarnall, who had a chance to
be in the Yankees' rotation and didn't pitch well, has fallen out
of favor with a lot of people. Melian, the kid from Venezuela, is a
good player, but his parents were killed in a car accident a couple
of years ago and that has understandably affected him. They're
talented players, all three guys, but they all have some quirky
issues. And Bowden? He's got more bluster than anybody since P.T.
Barnum.'' . . . Talks are intensifying between Interbrew, owner of
the Toronto Blue Jays, and Rogers Communications, a cable network
power with plenty of dough. Toronto insiders are confident a deal
will be made, and if so, the Blue Jays are already contemplating
taking a run at free agent-to-be Chipper Jones, with current third
baseman Tony Batista moving to short if the Jays can land Chipper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Power plays have failed
</P>
<P>
   Both the Cubs and Sammy Sosa appear to be big losers in the
team's bid to trade him and the slugger's carping for a contract
extension when he still has a year left. ``I don't think Sammy is a
winning player, he's a sideshow,'' said one big-league official.
``The best thing the Yankees did in the last month was not making a
deal for either Sosa or Juan Gonzalez. The Yankees are not a New
York Post-type of team. They're totally businesslike,
go-about-their-work kind of guys who hang together and get the job
done. Gonzalez or Sosa might have ruined that. Sammy could have
been a Vladi Guerrero, but he stopped working on three-fifths of
his game. Good luck, him finding a team that will give him $17
million a year for four years.'' . . . Rumors abound in Cleveland
that the Indians might entertain offers for Manny Ramirez, who also
is eligible for free agency. The Indians freed up big money by
trading David Justice to the Yankees, and some clubs don't expect
the Indians to pick up the option they hold on Kenny Lofton for
next season, which would seem to give them even a bigger war chest
to re-sign Ramirez. But this will be a monster free agent market
this winter, and the Indians could decide to go in another
direction (Mike Mussina? Mike Hampton?) . . . Ben Mondor's PawSox
are treating the Aug. 1 exhibition between the US national team and
the Taiwan national team as more than just a baseball game. With GM
Lu Schwechheimer working closely with the Taiwanese consulate and
ambassador, the game is being transformed into a cultural festival,
much like what a fan might expect at an Olympic event. There are
60,000 native Taiwanese who live in the Greater Boston area,
Schwechheimer estimates, and there will be nearly an hourlong
pregame ceremony showcasing both Taiwanese and US cultures. The US
national team is not likely to be the same club that represents the
United States in the Olympics, since the selection committee will
be able to select professionals that are not on a team's 40-man
roster, but some players will make the cut. There are tickets
remaining for the 7:05 p.m. game ($10 box seats, $6 general
admission). One of the goals Mondor and his staff had when it
renovated McCoy Stadium was to attract world-class events, and this
is their first shot at one . . . Peter Gammons, who revolutionized
the coverage of baseball in the '70s and is widely known as ``The
Commissioner'' today, has been nominated for next year's Spink
Award by the Baseball Writers Association of America. Two other
worthies were nominated for the award, given annually at the Hall
of Fame induction ceremonies for career contributions to the game:
Ross Newhan, national baseball writer of the Los Angeles Times, and
Joe Falls, the longtime columnist for the Detroit News who had a
national audience for years in The Sporting News. The membership
will vote at the World Series. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He could be just a rental
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are willing to move righthander Darren Dreifort, but
he's eligible for free agency after the season . . . The Red Sox
are not on Curt Schilling's teams to which he would accept a trade,
according to published reports. His list reportedly includes the
Yankees, Braves, Mets, Diamondbacks, Cardinals, and Indians. He
apparently would also consider a trade to Toronto because of his
connection to Jim Fregosi, who was his manager when the Phillies
went to the World Series in 1993 . . . Despite the shocking
collapse of the Indians, there are no plans for the team to
jettison manager Charlie Manuel. The team's ridiculous run of
injuries _ it has gone through 26 pitchers _ makes it unfair to pin
anything on Manuel. His own bouts of bad health _ he has had two
surgeries on his colon, one in February and one in May, also robbed
him of a real chance to establish himself as a clubhouse presence.
But there is no question tensions are mounting on the Tribe. The
brothers Alomar, Sandy and Robbie, reportedly got in a shouting
match last Sunday after a game in which Robbie Alomar was hit by a
pitch and complained that Steve Karsay's retaliatory gesture _ he
hit Eddie Taubensee of the Reds with a pitch that just brushed his
jersey _ was insufficient . . . Al Martin, who made headlines this
spring when he was accused of being married to two women, could be
had in a trade with the Padres, but that has little to do with his
domestic difficulties, more to do with his inability to hit lefties
(5 for 60, .083 at the break) . . . Duquette will be competing with
Pat Gillick of the Mariners in his efforts to obtain another
hitter. Names still floating around include Ron Gant, Rondell White
(he just went on the DL), John Jaha (so did he), Bobby Higginson,
and Jeromy Burnitz. Pitchers that will draw interest before the
trading deadline include Esteban Loiaza (Rangers), Ismael Valdes
(Cubs), Hideo Nomo (Tigers), and Scott Erickson (Orioles) . . . Tim
Raines plans to play four games for independent Somerset in the
Atlantic League to prepare for a tryout with the US Olympic team.
Raines, 41, retired in March after 21 seasons in the majors, in
part because of his ongoing battle with lupus . . . Amin Fatah, the
Red Sox press parking attendant and unofficial president of the
Somalia branch of the Sox fan club, is adamant the Sox will win the
AL East. Sports Illustrated, interestingly, hasn't backed off its
preseason prediction the Sox will win it all. Wrote SI's Tom
Verducci in this week's issue: ``Neither (James) Baldwin, bless his
anonymous mug, nor anyone else is about to outduel the great
Martinez in October.''
</P>
