<HEADLINE>
AN EVERETT BLOWOUT IN SOX WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The autumn winds have yet to howl. But that October feeling fell
on Fenway Park Saturday as the Red Sox and New York Mets ended a
raucous weekend series in a swirl of conflict, intrigue, and
intensity worthy of a fall classic.
</P>
<P>
   There was Hurricane Carl Everett turning tornadic, head-bumping
plate umpire Ronald Kulpa and getting tossed, most likely to await
a hefty suspension. There was manager Jimy Williams accusing the
Mets of conspiring to incite Everett's eruption. And there were
enough off-field charges and countercharges to fill a docket on
``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there was a baseball game that turned on a dramatic
three-run home run by an accidental hero, Brian Daubach, who came
off the Boston bench for Everett after his second-inning ejection.
</P>
<P>
   With their 6-4 victory, the Red Sox clinched a 2-1 advantage in
the weekend showdown, winning their first series at home in eight
tries since May 10. And though the outcome was more joyous for Sox
fans than the disastrous 1986 World Series with the Mets, the
experience put the participants in an October state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like playoff baseball the last three days,'' said
Daubach, whose two-out, two-strike double in the bottom of the
ninth Thursday won the series opener. ``It was two good teams, two
intense teams, and three good ballgames. I think if we get to play
them in October, it would be a heck of a dogfight.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, barring other complications, Everett might be back in
the lineup. But first the Sox slugger faces a penalty that could
equal the five-day suspension that Atlanta manager Bobby Cox
recently drew for bumping an umpire.
</P>
<P>
   In an outburst that may represent the worst on-field behavior by
a Sox player since Roger Clemens was ejected from a 1990 playoff
game in Oakland, Everett exploded after Kulpa twice warned him he
was violating the boundaries of the batter's box by straddling the
line closest to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, with his rear foot across the chalk line, stands as
close to the plate as almost any batter in the big leagues. Mets
reliever Dennis Cook had complained the night before, after hitting
Everett in the left shoulder, that Everett was out of the batter's
box.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Everett protested when Kulpa informed him after the
first pitch from Mets ace Mike Hampton that he was standing too
close. Yet Everett maintained his composure and waved Williams back
to the dugout when the manager headed for the scene.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kulpa had drawn a line in the dirt to indicate how
close Everett could approach the plate. And Everett had erased the
line to Kulpa's consternation.
</P>
<P>
   Four pitches later, with the count 2-2, Kulpa again warned
Everett and drew another line, sending the hitter into a frenzy.
Everett apparently said something unacceptable to Kulpa, who
ejected him. The two then went toe to toe, jawing, and Everett
appeared to make contact twice with Kulpa. First, the bill of
Everett's batting helmet appeared to strike Kulpa's face. Then
Everett banged his head into the umpire's nose, forcing Kulpa to
backpedal in apparent pain.
</P>
<P>
   For minutes, Everett stormed about the field. Before he
disappeared into the runway to the clubhouse, several Sox players
and coaches tried to restrain or calm him, all to little or no
avail. First base coach Tommy Harper first stood between Everett
and the umpire. Third base coach Wendell Kim joined Harper. And
Williams was always a few steps away.
</P>
<P>
   Still, reinforcements were needed. Jose Offerman rushed out of
the dugout. Then Mets right fielder Derek Bell, Everett's boyhood
friend from Tampa and former teammate in Houston, ran in to try to
calm Everett. But Bell was intercepted by Mets manager Bobby
Valentine and could only watch as the Sox tried to shepherd Everett
off the field.
</P>
<P>
   In his last angry acts before departing, Everett hurled a bat
from the dugout onto the field, knocked over a water cooler, and
exchanged words with at least one teammate, Bret Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Everett's other teammates kept their distance during the
episode. And many declined to discuss specifics afterward. ``It's
out of the control of my hands,'' said catcher Jason Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   Everett would not discuss the episode after the game. ``No man,
I'm not talking,'' he said as he left the clubhouse with his baby
in his arms to attend postgame Family Day activities on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were the umpires talking.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams was. And he was livid at the Mets, whom he accused
of precipitating the furor by complaining to the umpires before the
game. ``That was set up before the game ever started,'' he said.
``It had to be the opposing team calling the umpires. That's the
only way it could happen. I know it came from the other side.
There's no doubt in my mind. I don't even have to ask anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams suggested the Mets may have dropped a dime on Everett
``in retaliation'' for the Sox manager twice asking the umpires
Friday night to check if Cook was doctoring the ball. That had sent
Cook into a similar rage. He was ejected for hitting Everett and
complained he should not be penalized because Everett was crowding
the plate and beyond the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets controlled the game early. Sox starter Ramon Martinez
faltered in the first inning, yielding two-out walks to Edgardo
Alfonzo and Mike Piazza. Todd Zeile then exploited Martinez's
wildness by doubling to the right-field gap, scoring both runners.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez (7-5) regained his control and put himself in
position to end a personal three-game winless streak. Before Rheal
Cormier relieved him in the seventh, Martinez walked no more Mets
and struck out three.
</P>
<P>
   He dodged potential trouble in the third after Alfonzo doubled
by striking out Piazza to end the inning. And after Piazza doubled
in the sixth, Martinez stranded him at third by inducing Zeile to
ground out and Matt Franco to hit an inning-ending fly ball to Troy
O'Leary in left.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hampton (9-6) stifled the Sox on one hit, a
first-inning double by Jeff Frye, through the first four innings.
Hampton, who entered with a 7-1 record and 1.87 ERA in his previous
12 starts, kept 11 straight Sox off the bases after Frye's hit,
then began his undoing by plunking Daubach to lead off the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   A batter later, Izzy Alcantara singled to center. Manny
Alexander singled home Daubach, Darren Lewis followed with a ground
ball to third that Matt Franco fired into the Sox dugout, allowing
Alcantara to score.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox struck Hampton's death blow in the sixth. Frye
singled to open the inning. After Varitek grounded out, Hampton
intentionally walked Nomar Garciaparra, who ended his brief
flirtation with the .400 mark by going hitless in three at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The logic was sound. Walk the major leagues' leading hitter so
Hampton, a lefty, could face the lefthanded Daubach, a former Met.
But Daubach, who relishes every measure of revenge he can exact
against his ex-team, had extra incentive, after his former friend,
Mets catcher Todd Pratt, was quoted in a New York paper as
denigrating Daubach as a ``scab'' for serving as a replacement
player for the Mets during spring training in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach, who declined after the game to discuss Pratt's
comments, offered his rebuttal on Hampton's first pitch, lifting it
into the screen above the left-field scoreboard. ``I thought it was
going to be off the wall,'' Daubach said, ``but luckily it
carried.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Red Sox won the series, though they may have
lost Everett. Yet Williams considered the series one to remember,
maybe even in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was some rivalry for three games,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
