<SLUG> BC-BBO-ONBALL-EVERETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS OF CONTROL CROSSED THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jimy Williams is right. Carl Everett was set up Saturday by the
New York Mets, just as Williams set up Dennis Cook the night
before.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets almost certainly called the umpires' attention to
Everett standing too close to the plate, even though he has set up
in the same spot all season, just as Williams the night before had
the umpires checking Mets reliever Dennis Cook to see whether he
was defacing the ball with his thumbnail.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Friday), we got in someone's head,'' Sox pitcher Rod Beck
said. ``Today, (the Mets) got in someone's head. Except it's going
to cost our guy a few games.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook was ejected from Friday night's game, but that was the end
of it. Everett was ejected Saturday, but that will only be the
beginning. Everett, who made contact with plate umpire Ronald Kulpa
twice, the second time head-butting him with such force that the
rookie ump's head snapped back, will pay for his rage with a
suspension that will be a minimum of five games, and could possibly
be double that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be five a bump,'' Beck said. ``He got him with the
beak of the helmet, and then he head-butted the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: No Sox player in uniform has snapped like
this since Roger Clemens, dressed for combat in eye black and Ninja
turtle shoelaces, was ejected from Game 4 of the 1990 American
League playoffs in Oakland by Terry Cooney. Clemens, who charged
from the mound and pushed aside umpire Jim Evans in his attempt to
get at Cooney, served a five-game suspension at the start of the
following season and was fined $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   This, too, is certain: Everett, whose meltdown occurred in the
hours between a morning pickup game involving Sox players and their
kids and a postgame team barbecue attended by CEO John Harrington,
crossed a line, as surely as he violated the line drawn in the
batter's box by Kulpa.
</P>
<P>
   His loss of control was so complete that his boyhood friend from
Tampa, Mets outfielder Derek Bell, ran in from right field to try
and calm him down, an extraordinary act by an opposition player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him since I was a kid and (was) trying to make sure
he didn't get into serious, serious, serious trouble,'' Bell told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Had Bell seen him this angry before? ``Yeah, I grew up with
him,'' he said. ``I've seen him since he was 8 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez, among others, urged reporters
not to focus on Everett's actions. ``Don't make a big deal about
it, guys,'' Martinez said after the game, clapping his hands.
``Come on, guys, pick us up. Write about the game. Let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   But like it or not, by his actions, which were beamed across the
country by Fox, Everett has resurrected his history of explosive
behavior. It's not by accident that Bell was worried Everett might
go too far.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, while playing for the Florida Marlins' Triple A team in
Edmonton, Everett was suspended for a dugout confrontation with
manager Sal Rende, in which he shouted expletives at Rende and had
to be restrained by three coaches. He was suspended for the team's
final trip of the season and that winter was traded by the Marlins
to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, according to a Marlins uniformed official,
Everett was involved in another ugly incident on a commercial
flight carrying the team. Everett became upset because someone had
placed a briefcase on his clothing, the official said, and began
cursing passengers loudly. A coach had to intervene on that
occasion, too.
</P>
<P>
   Did his behavior have anything to do with his subsequent trade.
``Yeah,'' the Marlins official said. ``He just couldn't handle a
lot of situations, both on and off the field. He was so
inconsistent, in both his play and his behavior. You didn't know
from one day to the next what you're going to get out of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's played lights out the last couple of years in
Houston, so I thought maybe he has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins official was asked whether people were concerned by
the intensity of Everett's rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has that aura about him,'' the official said. ``You're not
sure what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Everett was banned from winter ball for an incident in
Venezuela in which he had a run-in with an umpire, then went into
the stands after fans he claimed threw beer at him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, while playing for the Mets, Everett was ejected from a
game against the Marlins in Miami after making an obscene gesture
at plate umpire Larry Poncino. Poncino, one of the umpires who lost
his job in last summer's labor dispute, said that he and Everett
had exchanged words after Everett gestured about a strike call that
Poncino had made in a previous at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `This is the big leagues, and we don't do that
BS,' '' Poncino said.
</P>
<P>
   Everett responded by stepping out of the box, Poncino told him
to step back in, but after Everett popped up, more trouble ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he's running across the field, he flips me the bird,''
Poncino said from his home in Tucson. ``I said, `Keep on going.' He
made a beeline at me, how he didn't bump me, I don't know. He
threatened to kick my ass, and he threw Bobby Valentine (the Mets'
manager) to the ground. The guy went totally nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Poncino said he recalled Everett being suspended two games and
fined after that incident.
</P>
<P>
   Everett had not had an incident since coming to Boston until two
weeks ago in Chicago, when he exploded at Globe columnist Dan
Shaughnessy, hurling curses at both the newspaperman and team
publicist Glenn Wilburn before coach Tommy Harper pulled him into
the trainer's room. Everett was upset, he said, because he thought
Shaughnessy had written that Everett and second baseman Jeff Frye
had been fighting. Shaughnessy merely had written the two had had
an animated conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Saturday. ``This is embarrassing, uncalled for,'' Fox
broadcaster Joe Buck told the nation as Sox coaches Tommy Harper
and Wendell Kim, along with teammate Jose Offerman, fought to
contain Everett. ``He is right now out of control. One hundred
percent out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Jimy Williams was asked if he was worried about
Everett's temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he should be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
