<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-SAILNOTES-COUTTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUTTS VISIT FLOATS THEIR BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russell Coutts, the 37-year-old New Zealander who twice
skippered his country to America's Cup wins, will appear at the
Pleon Yacht Club in Marblehead Tuesday night to talk with sailors
in the youth program.
</P>
<P>
   Pleon, the 113-year-old club once hailed as ``the parent of the
junior yachting movement,'' admits all sailors for membership up to
the age of 20. The club is run and staffed entirely by teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts, one of the most decorated sailors in the world, has been
competing in various regattas in the United States and eagerly
agreed to speak with the young sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, Coutts skippered Team New Zealand to its second
consecutive America's Cup win, in Auckland, and in 1995 he led TNZ
to become the second non-American team to win the Cup. Australia
took the oldest trophy in sports away from the New York Yacht Club
in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Coutts was preparing for the 1984 Los Angeles
Olympics, in which he won the gold medal in Finn (singlehanded)
Class. A decade later, after amassing an impressive streak of wins
on various boats, he became two-time champion of the World
Match-Racing Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts took over as skipper of TNZ after the Kiwis placed second
behind Italy in the 1992 America's Cup Challenger trials, and in
the 1995 Cup races in San Diego, he skippered his team to an
overwhelming win with a 37-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an honor for us to have a sailor the caliber of
Coutts to address the program,'' said Bob Campbell, a Pleon alumnus
and veteran America's Cup racer. ``The kids are all excited about
meeting him and hearing what he has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to young sailors, Coutts is Michael Jordan or Pete
Sampras. The year before Coutts successfully defended the Cup in
Auckland, he became the Etchells Class world champion.
</P>
<P>
   But to many, Coutts may well be remembered for a simple but huge
gesture on the eve of New Zealand's America's Cup triumph last
February. Having won four straight races with laughable ease over
Italy's Prada, TNZ had just one race to win for a sweep. About the
only question remaining was whether Coutts would stay at the helm
or turn it over to 22-year-old understudy Dean Barker.
</P>
<P>
   Including 1995, Coutts had won nine straight America's Cup races
and a 10th would have set a Cup record.
</P>
<P>
   But on the morning of the race, Coutts offered the helm to
Barker, who leaped at the chance and, swallowing his nervousness,
gave Prada the same sort of thumping Coutts had.
</P>
<P>
   During the final series, Coutts spoke of his approach to racing.
Sometimes described as ``spaced out'' by his crew, Coutts says he
merely focuses and visualizes several moves ahead in a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people think I'm deaf,'' Coutts said, ``but it's
just that I get so focused on what I'm doing I tune out a lot of
other things that might be distractions. I like to do a lot of
thinking, visualizing.''
</P>
<P>
   At Pleon, Coutts will be speaking to a bastion of sailing
history that sparkles with the names of such world-class performers
as Ted Hood, George O'Day, Dave Curtis, Robbie Doyle, J.B. Braun,
Jud Smith, Geoff Mason, and Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it the Pleon Club took shape on a summer afternoon in
1887, when Arthur Wood and a friend were looking out at the sea,
watching sailboat races, a game played mostly by adults.
</P>
<P>
   Wood then founded Pleon for junior sailors and over the next 40
years nurtured it into the independent club it is. Two former Pleon
sailors, Hood, who skippered Courageous to an America's Cup victory
in 1974, and the late O'Day, an Olympic gold medalist who designed
some of the best one-design classes in the world, wrote about their
feelings for the club.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hood, the famous boat builder and sailmaker who still races
out of the New York Yacht Club in Newport, R.I.: ``Pleon is a
unique institution. It provides something for everyone, no matter
what their ability . . . from recreational sailing to advanced
(race) tactics and club management.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Day, whose designs included Rhodes 19, Widgeon, Javelin, and
the O'Day Daysailor, said of the club: ``Pleon is where it all
started. From its programs have come the sailors who have won the
America's Cup, Olympic and Pan American Games, and every major US
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleon gave me more than racing skills; it gave me a life and
love of creating and building boats.''
</P>
<P>
   Coutts's appearance at Pleon befits a theme he often has spoken
about. ``Kids have to have an early love for the sport if they're
going to do it,'' says Coutts, who will sail for a Swiss Cup
syndicate in 2003. ``Adults have to know when to help them and when
to get out of the way and let their love for sailing take its own
course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
