<HEADER>
A3476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUINS-B     07-15 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WHAT IT'S WORTH, SINDEN WILL WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're looking for a quick resolution regarding the Bruins'
large crop of restricted (Group 2) free agents, don't hold your
breath. There's a good chance several, if not most, of the club's
unsigned players will still be without contracts as training camp
draws near.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was obvious the tide around the league had turned
significantly, with teams taking a much tougher stance financially
than in the past. It took longer for restricted free agents to come
to terms and involved much more haggling.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Anson Carter acknowledges he has a much different
view of his worth than the Bruins, which will likely lead to a
standoff and perhaps a trade. Carter decided against filing for
arbitration, setting the stage for a holdout. That same stance a
year ago proved disastrous for goalie Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins say they're in it for the long haul and management
doesn't expect an easy August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a waiting game for both sides,'' said
president/general manager Harry Sinden. ``There have been hardly
any Group 2 free agents signed. Everyone is much more cautious.
Almost every team has gone way beyond their budgets and their
owners are saying, `Stop it,' so they're a little more cautious and
they're not jumping into the fray.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said whether a player elects to take the team to
arbitration doesn't alter the Bruins' view of his worth. He said
the philosophy the team uses for formulating its offers is based on
what it projects the player would be awarded in arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, I took a much firmer line,'' said Sinden. ``I'd
say, `I don't care where you should be, this is what you're
getting.' But (the media) beat me up so much on that. From a
(public relations) standpoint and from a player's perspective, you
have to go in with the numbers that come up, just as if an
arbitrator was deciding it. The only difference, of course, is that
an arbitrator isn't deciding it and what you may see is the number
the arbitrator would give. (The players) don't always see it that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations with center Joe Thornton won't be easy, but
it's Carter who stands to be the most difficult, even more
difficult than the contract impasse in 1998 that resulted in
Carter's holdout until November. Even Sinden acknowledged that
Carter would be the toughest to re-sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea here is to not get him cheap and I would hope they
wouldn't want to take advantage of the situation and get
overpaid,'' said Sinden. ``That's really what it's all about. We
tried to do it now by bringing up the (players of comparable
ability) just like the arbitrator would and saying, `This is where
he fits.' We can usually show the agent and the player. They have
access to the same data we do.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the situation murkier is that Carter was limited to
59 games last season because of injury. Complicating it further is
the Bruins' dismal performance, which resulted in them missing the
playoffs for the second time in four years. Sinden said he doesn't
expect any of his free agents to concede leverage despite the
club's misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was always a huge factor in contract negotiations, what
kind of a year the team had,'' said Sinden. ``If you were on a
losing team, you never had a chance. They don't seem to figure
that's a factor anymore. They never figure they had anything to do
with the team losing. I'm not saying I'd be different. I'd say, `We
were terrible except for me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buying some time
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about the Paul Coffey signing, but at the very
least it provides the Bruins a necessary buffer zone that will
allow defensemen such as Jonathan Girard and Nick Boynton more time
to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``That played a big part in it,'' said Sinden. ``Following the
draft we had three defensemen that we knew could play for us.
That's all. We had three possibles and probables in Girard,
Boynton, and Brandon Smith. Since then, we have six who can play
for us definitely and we have another five, including Girard,
Boynton, and Smith, who are possible and probable. We've got some
depth now on our defense and we do think we have enough people to
fill out our roster on the NHL level.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cup's schedule is full
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the year Scott Gomez of the Devils, who was one of the
best feel-good stories of last season, took the Stanley Cup home to
his native Alaska last week. Gomez, the first Latino to play in the
NHL, had big plans, including having the Cup mushed by dogsled,
raised 200 feet by an Anchorage Fire Department ladder, and taking
it to a children's hospital ward . . . For awhile, it appeared Rob
Ray had played his last game for the Buffalo Sabres after the club
declined to pick up an $800,000 option on his contract. However,
for a reduced rate, the Sabres decided to re-sign Ray, who ranks
11th on the league's all-time penalty minutes list. Initially, Ray
was upset the team didn't pick up the option but he cooled down as
the sides continued talking. Ray played only slightly more than
four minutes per game last year . . . Forward Dany Heatley, the No.
2 overall choice by the Atlanta Thrashers in last month's draft,
has decided to stay at the University of Wisconsin. Heatley, who
was the rookie of the year in the WCHA last season, paid his own
way to visit the Thrashers and tour their facilities . . . The last
time Dave Andreychuk played for the Sabres, Lindy Ruff was his
teammate. Now, Andreychuk, who just re-signed with Buffalo, has
Ruff as his coach . . . Former Bruin Marc Potvin has been named the
head coach of the Springfield Falcons, the American Hockey League
affiliate of the Phoenix Coyotes. The 33-year-old Potvin, who
played 33 regular-season games for the Bruins from 1994-96, last
year served as head coach and director of hockey operations for the
Mississippi Sea Wolves of the East Coast League . . . Steve
Staios's stay in New Jersey wasn't long. The former Bruin was
acquired by the Devils June 12 for a ninth-round draft pick. Last
week, he was sent back to the Thrashers for future draft picks.
Staios, who plays defense and forward, was hampered by injuries
last year and limited to 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Really, how do you feel?
</P>
<P>
   When one reporter asked Sinden if he had any interest in signing
free agent Vladimir Malakhov, who last week wound up with the
Rangers, Sinden minced no words. ``No,'' he said. ``Very little.''
Malakhov, remember, was the player who was out of the Montreal
Canadiens' lineup because of a knee injury but was well enough to
ski with his family. The Habs traded him to New Jersey, where he
went on to play well and win the Stanley Cup . . . In case you
missed it, the Coyotes signed Bruins right wing Landon Wilson to a
one-year deal plus an option. They're hoping he can do what he
couldn't in Boston _ stick in the NHL. ``I think Landon has a real
good opportunity to be a good NHL player,'' said Coyotes GM Bobby
Smith. ``He has played very well at times but it just wasn't
working out for him in Boston and it was time for a change of
scenery for him.'' . . . 53 days to training camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
