<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-15 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTIGLIONE HAS NO AIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time someone finally said it: Joe Castiglione is the latest
in a distinguished line of broadcasters to be the official ``Voice
of the Boston Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, not really,'' comes the predictable protest from a modest
man. ``It's different today, with the proliferation of media.
There's NESN, there's over-the-air TV, and there's radio. It's not
like the old days. To call one person that would be misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Good try, Joe, but it doesn't wash. With all due respect to Sean
McDonough, Bob Kurtz, Jerry Remy, and your partner, Jerry Trupiano,
the No. 1 radio man will always be the person most associated with
a team's broadcast image. Radio is the baseball broadcast medium.
It is radio that accompanies you on the front porch, in the
kitchen, in the backyard, on the beach, and, most importantly, in
the car. Historically, radio calls resonate far more than TV calls
do. The No. 1 radio voice is, for better or worse, the essential
link between any major league baseball team and its fans, and in
this town that voice belongs to Joe Castiglione.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the voice. It's not a classic doomsday broadcaster voice; we
can all agree on that. It's a voice ripe for parody. It's not Ned
Martin's voice, or Ken Coleman's voice, or Bob Wilson's voice, or
even Trupiano's enviable voice. It is comparatively thin and reedy
and nasally, and when Castiglione goes into the high register to
describe a great play every dog in Berkshire County springs to
attention. So nobody's perfect, all right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't have Mel Allen's pipes,'' he acknowledges,
citing a boyhood hero. ``But I think it's a voice that wears well.
It's not big and booming, but there is wearability. I think over
180 games, counting exhibitions and, perhaps, postseason play,
people need to look at you as a friend who calls the ballgame, not
as a commercial announcer.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no signature home run call. ``Bob Starr said it best,''
laughs Castiglione. ``All the good ones are taken.'' He doesn't
quote Tennyson, a la Ned Martin. He doesn't invent imaginary
catchers of foul balls, the way Ernie Harwell does. He doesn't do
the overtly ``We'' thing, either, although he has always cared
deeply (The ever-wry Starr once observed in the wake of a
game-winning homer by New York's Mel Hall that ``My partner looks
as if he's just been harpooned'').
</P>
<P>
   What Joe Castiglione does is tell you what happened, and I mean
precisely what happened. My longtime colleague Jack Craig once
pointed out something to the effect that if a ground ball had three
hops, Joe Castig will tell you it had three, not two or four. I
like that. After all, isn't using words to paint a clear picture of
the game what radio play-by-play broadcasting is all about?
</P>
<P>
   The second big thing Joe Castig brings to a broadcast is vast
empirical knowledge. He seems to know everything worth knowing
about the career of every player who steps up to the plate or takes
the mound. And he knows how to dole out the information without
being either smug or repetitive. ``I've always been blessed with
good recall,'' he says. ``But I do have a system. I start a file
card on every player the first time around. I still do them all in
longhand because it helps the recall process.''
</P>
<P>
   He buttresses this system with the expected pregame schmoozing
around the batting cage and in the dining room with fellow
broadcasters and scouts who, as all baseball media people know, are
the greatest sources imaginable. If there is a new tidbit to be
unearthed, be assured that Red Sox radio listeners will immediately
be apprised.
</P>
<P>
   If life is good for Joe Castiglione, now in his 18th year as a
Red Sox broadcaster and seventh as the No. 1 man (even though he
rejects the title as overly pretentious), it's because it's well
deserved. His dues were paid in duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   How about coming here in 1983 from Cleveland, taking a pay cut,
and then spending the entire season living at the Susse Chalet in
Newton while his family was back home because the Castigliones were
unable to sell their house? ``Twenty-six dollars a night,'' he
recalls. ``But the worst part was packing my trunk and taking it to
the basement each time we went on a road trip so I wouldn't be
charged for the room while I was away.'' Christian charity
precludes him being asked what he made that season, but the rumor
is that he would have been better off going on welfare and donating
his services to the radio station.
</P>
<P>
   The early critics were pretty vicious. He was crucified over the
voice thing, of course, and when they weren't going after him for
his sound they were attacking him for just about every thought that
popped out of his head. It didn't help any that he was replacing
Jon Miller, who while thoroughly unappreciated by management, was
the darling of the critics. ``I got ripped a lot that first year,''
Castiglione says, ``and it hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   What got him through it all was the support he received from
Coleman and Johnny Pesky, who was recuperating from a mysterious
allergy attack that year and who spent a lot of time in the
broadcast booth. The booth has always been a refuge for him, from
that time to the present. ``From Kenny to Bob Starr to Trup, I've
never had a cross word up there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The late Bob Starr was an intriguing mentor. ``I learned a lot
from him,'' says Castiglione. ``He had a detachment. I used to take
it all to heart. Losses really bothered me. But Bob had a saying.
`It's not my life and it's not my wife,' he would remind me. That's
really helped me the past seven or eight years. I love what I'm
doing, and I care about the Red Sox, but it's still a game.''
</P>
<P>
   As he nears the end of his second decade here, Castiglione is in
an ideal broadcasting groove. He's got the institutional memory so
vital to a broadcaster in a tradition-oriented town such as Boston.
He has established his personal credibility. He will never be
caught off-guard. He is poised to deliver the goods for, well,
however long they will have him. He is doing what makes him happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still get psyched to go to the ballpark every day,'' he
insists.
</P>
<P>
   It shows.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
