<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USTRIALS-FAVORHAMILTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAVOR-HAMILTON RENEWS PRIORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ At 36, Regina Jacobs is running better than ever.
At 31, so is Suzy Favor-Hamilton, which should make for an electric
duel in Sunday afternoon's 1,500-meter final.
</P>
<P>
   Both women credit their growth to experience, but of very
different kinds. For Jacobs, the changes over the years have been
technical: more iron, better diet, refinements in running form. For
Favor-Hamilton, the growth has been born first of misfortune, then
of outright tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injury, first of all, woke me up and made me realize I may
not have a second chance,'' said Favor-Hamilton of the left
Achilles' tendon she tore in February 1999 at an indoor 1,500-meter
race in Boston, where her winning time of 1:58.92 still tied the
American record. ``I knew I had so much to give that I hadn't even
stepped into yet. And my brother's death really changed my life. I
realized I may not be here tomorrow. I have to do things now. I
can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting is what everyone had been doing since her days at the
University of Wisconsin, where the gorgeous 14-time All-American
was the biggest star ever, winning 23 Big 10 titles and nine NCAA
crowns, a record that still stands. Although she made the Olympic
teams in both 1992 and 1996, her career since graduation has seldom
lived up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '92 when I just came out of college, I had a lot of
endorsements, a lot of modeling opportunities, and I was pretty
much doing all of them,'' said Favor-Hamilton. ``I kind of lost
sight of the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   That picture came painfully back into focus last September with
the suicide of her 37-year-old brother, Dan, who suffered from
manic depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why it takes a death to sometimes change
people,'' she said. ``In my case, it's made a positive of
everything. The feeling I had after he died, I'm never going to let
that feeling leave me. I felt hurt and upset, but it also made me
feel I could conquer the world, that I'm ready to do great
things.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things the married Suzy Hamilton did after the
death was return Favor to her name, in honor of Dan. Another was to
fly to Ireland for physical therapy with the renowned Gerard
Hartmann, in a desperate attempt to salvage her career. After 10
days of treatment so painful she cried every day, squirming to get
away from the hot wand Hartmann applied to break up the scar
tissue, Favor-Hamilton was running again.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the entire 1999 season, Favor-Hamilton came back
to run her first 1,500 meters April 30, breaking a 15-year-old meet
record with her time of 4 minutes 5.13 seconds. She has run
consistently well ever since, including a spectacular effort last
month at the Prefontaine Classic, when she took a strong early lead
only to be nipped at the wire by Romania's Gabriela Szabo, ranked
No. 1 in the world last year at the distance. Favor-Hamilton's
time, 4:00.79, ranks as the second best in the world this year,
setting the scene for a fight to the wire Sunday with Jacobs, a
strong medal contender in Sydney whose personal best for the
distance, 4:00.35, was set just last year.
</P>
<P>
   The two women are not friendly, perhaps in part a residue of the
early success Favor-Hamilton achieved in the marketplace, not on
the track. ``It seems like there's just kind of always a tension,''
said Favor-Hamilton. ``You feel it. Maybe it's more from her. I'm
just out there doing what I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jacobs: ``I think we're very different. The common thing we
share is we both want to win and we're in the same race, so
naturally that would breed a huge rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, it's one Favor-Hamilton is finally ready for. Both women
dominated their heats here, with Jacobs leading the field in
4:06.16 and Favor-Hamilton in 4:10.29. But more than that,
Favor-Hamilton knows the time is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I could wait, I could wait, I have another
year,'' she said, reflecting on her brother's death. ``I don't feel
like that now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
