<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-MORALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORALES VOWS TO IMPROVE TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ While his second-half spark wasn't enough for the
Revolution to overcome the MetroStars, newcomer Jose Luis Morales
promises his play _ and the team _ will get better soon.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, the first Spaniard to play in Major League Soccer,
arrived in the United States Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half Saturday, he darted onto the field and was
impressive throughout his stint.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo liked what he saw. ``You can
see that he's not 100 percent yet,'' he said. ``He's going to be an
impact player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, it felt pretty good out there when I got on the
field,'' said Morales, through an interpreter, referring to the
fact he hasn't played a game in almost two weeks. ``It was a little
different with us losing, 1-0, when I came out, so it was tough to
get used to the first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two games from now, I'll have no trouble adjusting to the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The team will get better with more practice time together, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, who scored 51 goals in his seven-year professional
career in Spain, said he'll train during practices. ``You can get
the rhythm a bit and after a couple of games, I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales doesn't speak English, so he can't tell his teammates
much right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everybody's name but I can't say it in English to get
their attention,'' Morales said. ``You don't know all the other
players, they don't know about me. In a regular game, your team
knows how you play and you know how they play, as well as where
they give you the ball. You get to know each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning Saturday's 2-0 loss, Morales said: ``We're unlucky;
we gave up a goal in the first five minutes and we clearly had more
opportunities than they did, and if we hadn't given up that goal,
we would have had a better result.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no specific way to score goals. It's just a bad
stretch for the team. It seems unbelievable the goals that we've
missed so far. Once we get a couple of them to go in, though,
they'll all start to go in for us.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question Morales will enjoy playing in the United
States. ``They criticize you for your play there, while here, they
come to have a good time and to see good plays and to cheer you
on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he knows better days are ahead. ``I'm very happy, I'm very
content to be a Revolution player,'' Morales said. ``I'm going to
try to work as hard as I can to help my teammates on and off the
field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
