<HEADER>
A3484 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-METROS     07-15 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-METROSTARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION DOOMED BY MENTAL MISTAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The Revolution lost again Saturday _ a 2-0 defeat
to the MetroStars marked their sixth straight game without a
victory _ but they gained some compensation with the brief, but
dynamic, debut of Jose Luis Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Of the last 18 MLS points, the Revolution have earned only 1.
They surrendered their Eastern Division lead last month and now
trail the MetroStars by 12 points. They appear to be following the
pattern started in 1997, when they set a league record with a
nine-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   This game began on the wrong foot for the Revolution, as Brian
Dunseth was outmaneuvered by Alex Comas, who gave the MetroStars
the lead in the third minute.
</P>
<P>
   Comas was isolated on Dunseth as Daniel Hernandez lofted a
45-yard free kick. Comas shook off Dunseth just inside the penalty
area, spun to his left, controlled the ball, and jabbed a shot into
the right side of the net as Juergen Sommer advanced.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Revolution seemed desperate. They struggled with
balancing a sense of panic with the calmness necessary to recover.
And only after Morales entered, less than 48 hours after his
arrival from Spain, did the Revolution display enough cohesion and
subtlety to unbalance a confident and hard-charging MetroStars
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was not to give up an easy goal, not make mistakes,''
Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo said. ``I always say the game is
90 minutes, and when the referee blows the whistle the game is on.
We made a mental mistake and they took advantage of it, and after
that we were chasing the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we also played well after that. But we seem to need an
open net to finish. Everyone strikes the ball well and into the
corner of the net in practice. In the game, the goal seems to
shrink and the goalkeepers seem to get bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars seemed more dangerous offensively with Colombian
strikers Comas and Adolfo ``El Tren'' Valencia and a fluent
midfield game. They set the tone with hard tackling in midfield and
the Revolution needed much of the first half to adjust to the pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take responsibility for the first goal,'' Dunseth said. ``I
went up to get my head on the ball, but instead of clearing it I
knocked it down in front of his path.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we weren't physical enough with them. We need to be
tougher mentally. We need to be kicking people all over the field,
so any time they have the ball we at least have a body on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommer, replacing Jeff Causey in goal, had little chance to stop
the first goal but made an impressive save on Mark Chung in the
50th minute. Morales, who replaced Dunseth (groin strain) after
halftime, was effective from his first touch on. In the 53d minute,
Morales and Mauricio Ramos combined to set up Wolde Harris, but
Harris's left-footed shot went high after he had rounded goalkeeper
Mike Ammann.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball took a hop on me and I took my eye off it, but no
excuses,'' Harris said. ``But those are goals that will make or
break you. Those chances stayed in the back of our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars clinched the victory in the 62d minute on an
excellent play by Petter Villegas, who made a fantastic dummy,
allowing him to glide past Mauricio Wright and then play a
give-and-go with Valencia. Villegas was on the verge of being
offside as he finished into an open net, and the Revolution
protested.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, though, went on the offensive and seemed capable
of breaking through, especially after the MetroStars' Billy Walsh
was ejected for a foul on Jamar Beasley in the 78th minute. Beasley
suffered a neck injury and was taken to Norwood Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Columbus (a 4-1 loss Wednesday) we didn't show up to
play,'' Clavijo said. ``This time we did show up to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
