<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-15 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-METS-BELL-BOS &LR;      07-15 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-BELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL TRIED TO NOTCH AN ASSIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were boyhood chums growing up in Tampa, realized their
life-long ambitions of playing in the big leagues, and were
teammates in Houston in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Within the span of eight days last December, they were traded _
Carl Everett to the Red Sox and Derek Bell to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Everett is, said Bell, ``like my little brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Bell tried his darnedest to intervene on Everett's
behalf when the Red Sox outfielder pulled a nutty after being
ejected in the second inning by plate umpire Ronald Kulpa over
where he should be standing in the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   While Red Sox manager Jimy Williams and coaches Wendell Kim and
Tommy Harper did their best to keep Everett away from Kulpa, whom
he had already bumped and head-butted, Bell came running in from
right field to lend a helping hand.
</P>
<P>
   He's convinced if he got there sooner, Everett would have gone
to the dugout a lot quieter than he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a little brother to me,'' said Bell, ``so I'm pretty
much the closest person besides his wife who can calm him down.
I've known him since I was a kid and (was) trying to make sure he
didn't get into serious, serious, serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went in there to tell him to get his ass in the dugout
before I grab him, pick him up, and take him over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell was intercepted by Mets manager Bobby Valentine, who later
said, despite the Everett-Bell relationship, he wasn't too excited
about Bell's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he had to get involved,'' said Valentine. ``I
know he was trying to calm him down, but I didn't think that was
his place. They played together and know each other well, but he
shouldn't have gotten that close.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell said although Valentine kept him at arm's length from
Everett, he was able to get his message across.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to him all the time,'' he said. ``I told him,
`Let's go, don't have me grab you.' He knows I don't pay attention
to his attitude. I just wanted to say a few things to him to calm
him down. If I had known he was going to go off like that, I would
have tried to get there sooner. As soon as I got up there, he
calmed down and went into the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows that he can get as mad as he wants to, but he knows
that I'll also tell him things (suspension) that will happen if he
keeps it up. He's one of the best outfielders in the league, has a
long-term deal, and I'm very proud of him. I told him, `Don't let
me down, get in the dugout.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That he did, but then he banged his fist against the bat rack,
threw a bat onto the field, and knocked the water coolers off the
top step of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the first time Valentine had seen Everett take
things to the edge.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when Everett was a member of the Mets, he was ejected
in a game against the Marlins and went jaw-to-jaw with plate umpire
Larry Poncino. When Valentine came out to restore the peace,
Everett flung him to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The game story in the New York Daily News quoted Valentine as
saying: ``He threw me down like a Beanie Baby.'' When asked about
the incident Saturday, all Valentine would say was, ``I'd rather
not talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' Mike Hampton, who was on the mound when Everett was
tossed, said he wasn't surprised by the outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not really,'' he said. ``I played with him two years (in
Houston, 1998 and '99). I know how he gets sometimes. When he
believes in something, he lets you know about it. He loves the
game. He has a passion for it. Sometimes, he just goes too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets catcher Mike Piazza offered his view on what transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kulpa) asked him to get back into the batter's box and he
lost it. He just freaked out. He was upset. As far as I could see,
his foot was very close to the plate, on the line or over the line,
and the umpire said they had looked at it and they were going to
enforce it and obviously they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he brought it to Kulpa's attention, Piazza said, ``I
didn't say a thing. As soon as he got in the box, the umpire said,
`Carl, you've got to get in the batter's box, you have to move back
a bit.' Then they started arguing a bit, Everett moved up a bit,
drew a line, and said to (Kulpa), `This is the line and as long as
my foot is on the line, I'm OK.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They said a few more words and then when he was really getting
upset, I was out of there. He was not in a good mood. I didn't want
to get in the cross-fire. It's an unfortunate incident. Any time
you bump an umpire, that's not good. You can't do that. It's
unfortunate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
